<SLUG> BC-BIRMINGHAM-BALLET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EDWARD II': A GRAPHIC PRODUCTION FROM BIRMINGHAM ROYAL BALLET 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's not often that publicity announcements warn that
a ballet is not family entertainment. Yet some of those heralding
David Bintley's ``Edward II'' did note that this production
``presents graphic sexual images and is not appropriate for
children.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Birmingham Royal Ballet made its New York debut with
the two-act work at the City Center on Thursday night, one learned
the reason for such a warning. ``Edward II'' is filled with sex and
violence. Yet to anyone who might accuse the British company of
mere sensationalism, Bintley, its director, might point out that
his sources are medieval history and classic drama. And although
his choreography is sometimes disconcertingly uneven, ``Edward II''
is a serious effort.
</P>
<P>
   Bintley has been inspired by historical accounts of the reign of
this monarch, who died in 1327, and by ``Edward II,'' Christopher
Marlowe's still-enthralling play of 1592. Both in real life and in
Marlowe's tragedy, Edward, though married and a father, displayed
an inordinate passion for his friend Piers Gaveston. Isabella,
Edward's queen, and the English barons grew dismayed by Edward's
behavior. A civil war erupted. Gaveston was executed. So,
eventually, was Edward, after suffering gruesome sodomistic
tortures.
</P>
<P>
   Bintley does not underplay the unsavory incidents. Yet he
provides them with dramatic point. ``Edward II'' never resembles a
kinky porn show.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a sign of how venturesome the Birmingham Royal Ballet
can be. Since the '40s, the Royal Ballet in London has often had a
second company of some kind. Often it served as a training ground
for young dancers. At other times it was a touring group. Earlier
incarnations of the organization occasionally visited America.
</P>
<P>
   When it moved to the British city of Birmingham in 1990, the
second company became totally independent of London's Royal Ballet.
It has developed its own repertory, featuring provocative new works
like ``Edward II'' as well as revivals of such major 20th-century
ballets as Leonide Massine's ``Choreartium'' and Ninette de Valois'
``Job,'' which thrilled me when I saw them in England a few years
ago and which would surely thrill New York audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The Birmingham dancers made an impressive debut, for all are
blessed with a strong sense of conviction. Bintley set ``Edward
II'' to a commissioned score by John McCabe, which, as played by
the Royal Ballet Sinfonia conducted by Paul Murphy, helped
emphasize the story's dramatic tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Bintley was most inventive in scenes for the leading characters.
Robert Parker's Gaveston was a bounding scamp. The obviously
infatuated Edward of Wolfgang Stollwitzer could not keep his eyes
or hands off him. No wonder Monica Zamora, as an innocent-seeming
Queen Isabella, was so bewildered by these men.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the first act came a potentially overwrought yet
mesmerizing incident when, after Gaveston's execution, Stollwitzer
clutched a bag supposedly containing Gaveston's severed head while
a distraught Zamora tried to cling to him. Here was a truly macabre
romantic triangle.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, throughout the ballet, group sequences were weak.
Although Joseph Cipolla, a former member of Dance Theater of
Harlem, was a believably surly Mortimer, most of the other barons
were spoilsports who just kept marching monotonously. And, to make
``Edward II'' last an entire evening, Bintley has padded his
two-and-a-half-hour production with extraneous choreography,
including appearances by fairground entertainers presenting a show
that serves as a heavy-handedly allegorical counterpart to what is
basically a realistic plot.
</P>
<P>
   The second act has several dull stretches, especially an
interminable court ball. And some of the battle scenes involve
little more than running around on a smoky stage. The designs for
the second act are also odd. Peter J. Davison's sets for both acts
make ingenious use of shifting walls and curtains. But whereas
Jasper Conran's costumes for the first act are essentially
medieval, some of those for the second inexplicably suggest the
early 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the weak ensemble sequences, Bintley again
choreographically enlivens his leading characters in the second
act. Jonathan Payn was charming as Hugh Despenser, Edward's new
male favorite. As hostile forces trap Edward, Stollwitzer's monarch
grew horrifyingly demented, and when he bent to ask for mercy his
cringing was pitiable.
</P>
<P>
   With his studded wristband and codpiece, Toby Norman-Wright, as
Lightborn, the executioner, appeared to be en route to a leather
club. But this fellow was genuinely sinister. The torture scene was
horrifying without being unduly protracted. Even more effective was
the moment when Norman-Wright cradled the king in his arms like an
ominously gentle angel of death.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting character development was that of Zamora.
Her frail and naive Isabella of the first act submitted to
Mortimer's wiles. But, gradually, as the ballet proceeded, she
found strength to stand proudly as a stern warrior.
</P>
<P>
   Such thoughtful interpretations made one curious to see these
dancers in a variety of roles. And, later in the engagement, which
runs through Oct. 1, there will be a program called ``Jazz
Triple,'' featuring three one-act jazz ballets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
