</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-595&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELIEFS: UNDERLINING WHAT CHRISTIANITY AND JUDAISM SHARE 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there were a religious equivalent to low-level environmental
pollution, a major offender might be the well-meaning but
platitudinous statements by religious leaders about interfaith
understanding.
</P>
<P>
   But the statement ``Dabru Emet,'' published in The New York
Times on Sept. 10 as an advertisement, is not one of them. Its
Hebrew title comes from the biblical phrase ``Speak the truth to
one another.'' It is only 10 paragraphs, and every paragraph has
been carefully forged.
</P>
<P>
   The opening sentence speaks of ``a dramatic and unprecedented
shift in Jewish and Christian relations.'' In the decades since the
Holocaust, after nearly two millenniums of dismissing or
denigrating Judaism, church after church has publicly expressed
remorse and pledged to acknowledge in its preaching and teaching
``God's enduring covenant with the Jewish people'' and ``the
contribution of Judaism to world civilization and to Christian
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These changes merit a thoughtful Jewish response,'' the second
paragraph said. ``It is time for Jews to learn about the efforts of
Christians to honor Judaism.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed were eight brief statements about how Jews might
now view the relationship of Judaism and Christianity. The first
said that both faiths worship the God of Abraham, Isaac and Jacob,
and that ``through Christianity, hundreds of millions of people
have entered into relationship with the God of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Other paragraphs addressed Jewish and Christian concerns about
the authority of the Bible, the land of Israel, the moral
principles of Torah, and justice and peace.
</P>
<P>
   One paragraph advised that ``the humanly irreconcilable
difference between Jews and Christians will not be settled until
God redeems the entire world as promised in Scripture''; meanwhile,
Scripture-based polemics, political pressures or proselytizing will
be destructive and futile.
</P>
<P>
   The next paragraph claimed that an improved relationship between
Jews and Christians will not weaken Jewish practice, accelerate the
``religious assimilation that Jews rightly fear'' or encourage
intermarriage, conversion to Christianity or a false blending of
faiths.
</P>
<P>
   A crucial paragraph dealt with the Holocaust. ``Nazism was not a
Christian phenomenon,'' it stated, but it added that ``without the
long history of Christian anti-Judaism and Christian violence
against Jews, Nazi ideology could not have taken hold nor could it
have been carried out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many Christians participated in, or were sympathetic to,
Nazi atrocities against Jews,'' the paragraph continued. ``Other
Christians did not protest sufficiently against these atrocities.
But Nazism itself was not an inevitable outcome of Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   The paragraph also expressed gratitude for Christians who had
risked themselves to save Jews and for those who have struggled for
an unequivocal repudiation of any contempt for Jews and Judaism in
Christian teaching or practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dabru Emet'' was signed by more than 150 rabbis and Jewish
scholars. They came from all branches of Judaism _ Reform,
Conservative, Orthodox and Reconstructionist _ although they did
not claim to speak for anyone but themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Four Jewish scholars of different viewpoints _ Dr. Tikva
Frymer-Kensky of the University of Chicago Divinity School, Dr.
David Novak of the University of Toronto, Dr. Peter W. Ochs of the
University of Virginia and Dr. Michael A. Signer of the University
of Notre Dame _ met for over a year (indeed, some conversations
went back five years) to hammer out the wording.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As evidence that the drafters were tangling with substantial
matters, one observer recalled ``hot and heavy arguments,'' and
people ``storming out of the room'' and then cheerfully getting
back to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this Presbyterian, the crafting of this document was
nothing short of miraculous'' said the observer, the Rev.
Christopher Leighton, executive director of the Institute for
Christian and Jewish Studies in Baltimore, where the drafters met.
</P>
<P>
   As Novak recalled, ``It was a question not only of getting four
Jews to agree but four theologians as well.'' Many of the stumbling
points, of course, had less to do with differences between Jews and
Christians than differences among different strands of Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   But evidence that the statement is substantial has also been
supplied by the criticism it has garnered. Rabbi A. James Rudin,
senior interreligious adviser of the American Jewish Committee,
complained that the paragraph on the Holocaust fell short in
emphasizing Christian responsibility and the need for churches to
continue re-examining their histories.
</P>
<P>
   The drafters surely knew that no single paragraph on the
Holocaust would be beyond criticism. (One Jewish historian who
signed the statement reportedly hesitated because he found the
language about the Holocaust and Nazism overstated in the other
direction.)
</P>
<P>
   The essential point, Novak said in a telephone conversation
Friday, was that Nazism was not an inevitable product of
Christianity. ``If you look upon Christians as potential Nazis by
the very fact of their Christianity, you cannot really have a
relationship,'' he said, unless you ask them to renounce their
faith.
</P>
<P>
   That this paragraph should be the focus of criticism was
inevitable and understandable.
</P>
<P>
   But that could obscure some other very substantial aspects of
the statement. For one thing, it implicitly criticized the Jewish
community for being uninformed about or indifferent to major
developments in Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   By underlining points of intersection between Judaism and
Christianity while affirming an ``irreconcilable difference,'' the
statement suggested that Jews would understand that difference only
as they plumbed their own tradition and not simply because they
rejected the other tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dabru Emet'' implicitly challenged Jews who, as Novak had
written, ``seem to think not being a Christian is all they need to
do to retain a Jewish identity.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement is one of several efforts to widen the
Jewish-Christian encounter from a focus on community protection to
one on theology. Its drafters were convinced that understanding
what the two faiths have in common and what differentiates them
would lead Jews to a renewed commitment to be fully Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have assumed that ``Dabru Emet'' was written in
response to Pope John Paul II's trip to Israel. A few have
suspected it of being released to ride on the coattails of Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, the Democratic vice presidential candidate. Not
so, in either case. The statement has been years in germination,
and it was released two weeks ago because of the approaching Jewish
holy days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're insisting that Jews speak theologically in public,''
Novak said. ``And if theology can't be discussed from pulpits,
where can it be?''
</P>
</TEXT>
