<HEADLINE>
U.S. SWIM COACH QUICK TO APOLOGIZE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Richard Quick's drug rant didn't irritate
the Netherlands' Inge de Bruijn as much as his timing. The head
U.S. women's Olympic coach didn't bring up the issue of ``dirty''
swimmers until after de Bruijn had beaten Quick's club swimmers
Jenny Thompson and Dara Torres in the 100 freestyle and 100
butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   So while Quick insisted he was pointing to no particular
swimmer, the insinuation seemed clear to de Bruijn. She called
Quick out Friday after leading all semifinalists (including Torres)
in the 50-meter freestyle with an astonishing world-record swim of
24.13 seconds. Her previous best was 24.48.
</P>
<P>
   De Bruijn and Quick stood on the deck of the warmdown pool and
cleared the air for five minutes. DeBruijn said Quick apologized to
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for him as a great coach to apologize like that,''
said de Bruijn, who broke eight world records in the five months
leading up to these Games. ``After I set all those world records,
(people) accused me of things. I didn't think that's fair. I think
I handled it well. It was not easy at all. I don't think (the
doping) question is fair to be asked of anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 0003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
