<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-SOFTMONEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS TO BAN SOFT MONEY IN NEW YORK SENATE RACE COLLAPSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD J. LEVY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Negotiations over an agreement to ban soft money in
the New York Senate race collapsed on Friday after Hillary Rodham
Clinton offered a plan that was initially embraced by Rep. Rick
Lazio _ until he learned that it contained more restrictions on him
than on her.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, Lazio denounced Clinton as the ``queen of dirty
money'' and said she was clinging to legalistic excuses to avoid a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted that Lazio's aides had engaged in some sleight
of hand in the bargaining over an agreement. She based this
assertion on what appeared to be her interpretation of an 18-word
clause in a letter that her campaign received from the Lazio
campaign on Thursday. Lazio's aides said they were baffled and
infuriated by her reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   It was a remarkable shift during the day from apparent good will
to vitriol between candidates who have argued for weeks over soft
money, the largely unregulated contributions that have eroded a
system of limits on federal elections imposed after Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Lazio has sought to put Clinton on the
defensive over soft money because she has benefited from at least
$5 million in commercials financed by soft money she collected in
conjunction with Democratic allies.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who has not raised soft money, asserts that he has
championed a ban because it will restore the public's faith in
elections. A campaign committee can accept donations of up to
$1,000 per person for the general election. On Friday morning,
Clinton took the stage at a breakfast meeting in Rye, N.Y., and
announced that even though her candidacy might suffer financially
if she renounced soft money, she would immediately do so as long as
Lazio followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's make it simple, effective, enforceable and fair,'' she
said. ``Today I will urge the political parties supporting me not
to buy any more soft-money issue ads on TV or radio as long as the
parties and other groups helping my opponent don't buy any more of
those ads either. All it will take to do this is one word from Mr.
Lazio: OK So how about it, Mr. Lazio? OK?''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio had wanted a written agreement drafted by lawyers, and
monitored by two leading proponents of campaign finance reform,
Sen. John McCain of Arizona and Sen. Russell Feingold of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio immediately agreed to this more informal one, and his
aides sent a letter to the Clinton campaign, outlining what they
understood to be the agreement: no soft-money spending by political
parties on behalf of either candidate and no spending by outside
political groups, either.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning upstate, Lazio declared victory, announcing what he
said was an historic change in campaign finance practices. Around
the same time, though, Clinton's aides issued a statement saying
there was no deal, accusing the Lazio campaign of ``double talk.''
</P>
<P>
   The stumbling block was spending by outside political groups,
which is technically not soft money because it is not collected by
political parties. It turns out that Clinton wanted to ban
soft-money spending for both candidates; however, outside political
groups could help her but not him. Her aides pointed to her
statement at the breakfast, noting that a close parsing of the
language revealed the distinction.
</P>
<P>
   When the Lazio campaign responded that such a rule was unfair,
the Clinton campaign said that the Lazio campaign had actually
agreed on Thursday to the same thing. The Clinton campaign pointed
to the 18-word clause in the letter that it had received from the
Lazio campaign during the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides had been discussing how each candidate would be
required to obtain signatures from outside groups pledging to not
spend money in the race. In the letter, the Lazio campaign said
that to speed up putting an agreement in place, ``we have dropped
our precondition that you attain the signatures of the outside
interest groups supporting your campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the clause demonstrated that the Lazio campaign no
longer would require the groups supporting her to stay out of the
race. By saying on Friday that such groups would have to refrain,
the Lazio campaign had ``reimposed a condition they had taken off
the table,'' she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio campaign called her interpretation nonsense,
maintaining that it was merely letting the Clinton campaign know
that if necessary, it could obtain some of the formal pledges after
the agreement was in force.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and her aides have long expressed concern that
conservative political groups would spend heavily to defeat her,
though until now, they have mostly used her as a fund-raising
vehicle while spending relatively little.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that these groups were closely tied to the Lazio
campaign and as a result should be barred from spending in the
race. The groups supporting her, such as the National Abortion
Rights and Action League and various unions, were more independent,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a big difference having an organization that is a
longstanding institution that makes independent decisions, and an
organization with your supporters on the board that calls the shots
where the money goes, which is what he has,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters in Elmira Friday night, Lazio ridiculed
Clinton. ``I twice voted for campaign finance reform in the House,
and we issued the pledge,'' he said, referring to his call for an
agreement. ``Now today, we see more evasion, more ducking, more
distortion of the truth. Let me tell you, there is not going be any
coronation this November of the queen of dirty money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 0010EDT &QL; 
