<SLUG> BC-WASHPOST-PUBLISHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAHAM STEPS DOWN AS WASHINGTON POST PUBLISHER
</HEADLINE>
 By FELICITY BARRINGER  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
  Donald E. Graham announced on Friday that he was stepping down
after 21 years as publisher of The Washington Post to concentrate
on steering its parent company, of which he is chairman and chief
executive, as it continues to expand its new-media ventures.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The publisher's job will be taken by his longtime associate,
Boisfeuillet Jones Jr., the first publisher from outside the
Meyer-Graham family in 30 years. Jones had been associate publisher
and president of the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Alan G. Spoon resigned as president and chief
operating officer of the Washington Post Co. to join a venture
capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   The latest changing of the guard, while not expected to bring
any change in direction for the newspaper, was still a symbolic
moment: for 61 of the last 67 years, the publisher's job has been
held by a member of Graham's family.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Meyer, his grandfather, bought it in 1933. Since then,
the only nonfamily publisher was James Sweeterman, who ran the
newspaper for six years after Graham's father died in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's mother, Katharine Graham, one of a tiny group of major
newspaper publishers who have won Pulitzer Prizes in their own
right, took over in 1969 and presided over the newspaper's greatest
modern triumph, the coverage of the Watergate scandal, which ended
with the resignation of President Richard Nixon. After 10 years,
she turned the job over to her son in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   In his tenure as publisher, during which The Post's major
competitor, The Washington Star, closed, Graham focused on
broadening the newspaper's coverage and circulation in the
ever-expanding suburbs, as well as building on The Post's
reputation for enterprising national and international reporting.
</P>
<P>
   When Ben Bradlee, the flamboyant and hard-driving editor who
oversaw the Watergate coverage, resigned, Graham replaced him with
Leonard Downie Jr., who was equally hard-driving but less
flamboyant _ a journalist who grew up at The Post, and was best
known for his local investigative coverage and his stint as
metropolitan editor.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's strategy of making the most of the newspaper's
near-monopoly position in its region paid off for years; until
three years ago, when it was supplanted by Newsday. The Post had
the greatest household penetration of any large newspaper in the
country. But like most other newspapers, it has suffered an erosion
of daily circulation _ which was stemmed in the last year or so _
and a sharper drop in Sunday circulation.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, Jones _ who was two years behind Graham at
school in Washington and worked with him on The Harvard Crimson _
served as the newspaper's lawyer and later as its president.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, in an interview, said: ``The point is to have a good
publisher. Everyone here knows that Bo's basically running the
paper the last few years. He's doing the job; he ought to have the
title.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
