<SLUG> BC-OLY-BKW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. BREEZES AS FRANCE EDGES BRAZIL
</HEADLINE>
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Katie Smith scored 14 points and was one of
six Team USA players in double figures as the United States rolled
past New Zealand, 93-42, Friday at the Dome in Olympic Park.
</P>
<P>
   In what became the most exciting day of the women's tournament,
the Americans reasserted their dominance while upstart France
continued its surprising bid for a medal. The Frenchwomen knocked
off Brazil in overtime, 73-70, to move to 4-0 in their Olympic
debut.
</P>
<P>
   Isabelle Fijalkowski scored 18 points on 6-of-7 shooting and
Yannick Souvre also had 18 points, dropping in six 3-pointers. The
French players gathered in a circle near midcourt after the game,
held hands and jumped up and down while singing.
</P>
<P>
   France's final preliminary round game is against Australia,
which is also 4-0 and along with Russia is considered the one of
the few teams to have a shot at upsetting the United States. Even
if France loses that game, it will finish second in the six-team
pool and head to the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   With one game remaining before the medal round begins, the
United States women moved to 4-0 in Group B and are a virtual
certainty to be seeded first among the final eight qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
   Leading, 47-17, at halftime and turning 22 turnovers into 26
points, the Americans solidified their dominance after a grueling
victory Wednesday over Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, used primarily as a defensive specialist, made 6 of 11
shots and led the Americans in scoring for the second time in the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In the other game, South Korea knocked off Russia, 75-73, in
another overtime thriller. Lee Jong Ae's 12-foot jumper with 2.8
seconds left in overtime _ just her second field goal of the game _
gave South Korea the victory and kept alive its hopes for a
quarterfinal berth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
