<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8716 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-AMICHAI-ART-2TAK     09-23 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-AMICHAI-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEHUDA AMICHAI, POET WHO TURNED ISRAEL'S EXPERIENCE INTO VERSE,
DIES AT 76 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT26 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) (Eds: Sample poems are included at the end of
article. Poetry quotations appearing here in bold should be set in
italics.) 
 By MEL GUSSOW  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yehuda Amichai, the Israeli poet who distilled his experience _
and his nation's _ into highly metaphorical verse written in Hebrew
and translated into more than 25 languages, died Friday in
Jerusalem. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
   He died of a rare form of lymphoma, said Stanley Moss, a poet
and close friend.
</P>
<P>
   In his poetry Amichai often wrote about love and loss and, in
recent years, about aging and mortality, all of it linked by his
gift for poeticizing the particular: the localized object or image
in everyday life. From his point of view, the role of a poet was
``to name each thing, each feeling, each experience, plainly and
accurately, without pretense.''
</P>
<P>
   In Amichai's verse, said the critic Robert Alter, ``There is a
tension between personal experience and the violent pressures of
history.'' Alter continued. ``Writing about himself, he is also
writing about Everyman.''
</P>
<P>
   Amichai's work derived from his own background as a young man
fleeing from Nazi Germany to Palestine in the 1930s, as a soldier
who fought in the British Army in 1948 and in the Israeli armed
forces, and as a husband and father and lover articulating his
feelings and dreams.
</P>
<P>
   He was firmly rooted in contemporary Israel and aware of the
politics that surrounded him, but he often treated it by
indirection and had been known to write love poetry in time of war.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing ``The Selected Poetry of Yehuda Amichai'' in The New
York Times Book Review in 1986, Edward Hirsch said, ``Amichai is an
essentially autobiographical poet with the rare ability to
characterize the complex fate of the modern Israeli, the private
individual inevitably affected by the public realm of war, politics
and religion.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that Amichai was like one of Emerson's ``representative
men,'' updated and living in Jerusalem, a prophet who ``speaks in
the guise of an ordinary Jewish citizen concerned with his people
and his place.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hebrew and in translation, Amichai's work is remarkably
accessible, imaginative, unburdened by artificiality and often
almost conversational. As a result, he was that exception: a poet
who is read by a wide public and not just by academics and other
poets. His books sold about 15,000 copies on average in Israel,
comparable to best-seller status in larger countries. Still, in the
manner of a poet, for many years he had to support himself by
teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Amichai's celebrity in Israel followed him down the street.
Walking in Jerusalem, his home for many years, he would be
recognized and accorded the attention that in the United States
might be reserved for a movie star or athlete.
</P>
<P>
   In a profile of Amichai in The New York Times Magazine in 1986,
Alter said about the poet's work, ``His Hebrew is often rich in
soundplay, wordplay, allusion and other traits of virtuosity that
are not readily evident in translation, and his language is a
shifting mixture of colloquial and literary.''
</P>
<P>
   Alter said that Amichai saw no contradiction in a poet's also
being a man of action. and that a symbolic tie between the two can
be discovered in his use of poetic metaphor as a ``weapon in the
hand-to-hand struggle with reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Amichai said he believed that metaphor ``is the great human
revolution, at least on a par with the invention of the wheel.''
Words were his arsenal, as in his ``Poem of My Time'':
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Is there in this land a stone that was never thrown
</P>
<P>
   And never built and never overturned
</P>
<P>
   And never uncovered and never discovered
</P>
<P>
   And never screamed from a wall and never discarded by the
builders
</P>
<P>
   And never closed on top of a grave and never lay under lovers
</P>
<P>
   And never turned into a cornerstone?  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Lawrence Joseph &UR; , &LR;  published in The Paris
Review, Amichai said, ``A poet's state of mind is seeing the world
with a kind of double exposure, seeing undertones and overtones,
seeing the world as it is.'' Irony was an essential element in his
poetry, a way, he said, of ``always trying to see another side.'''
That was how he lived, he said, ``focusing, refocusing and
juxtaposing different shifting and changing perspectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing his process, he said he combined ``different,
sometimes competing, language and forms.'' Before he began writing,
he said he thought about the shape the poem would take ``almost
visually, like a piece of sculpture _ I can touch it.'' Then he
would fill it in ``with my subjects, from the entire world of my
subjects.'' Freely mixing techniques and forms, he wrote poetry
that ranged from terse four-line images to sonnets to the epic
``Travels of a Latter Day Benjamin of Tudela.''
</P>
<P>
   For him, time was the most important dimension in his writing:
``Time is entirely relative, relational. The phrase I like to use
to describe my sense of time _ a play on  &UR; comparative literature  &LR; _
is &UR; comparative time &LR; . Time, for me, is imaginatively comparative
and continuous; I have an almost physical sense of memory recall. .
. . It's easy for me to shortcut back to my childhood, my
adolescence, my wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Yehuda Amichai was born in Wurzburg, Germany, on May 3, 1924.
The Amichais were an Orthodox Jewish family living in a mostly
Catholic environment. After immigrating with his parents to
Palestine in 1936, he lived in Jerusalem. After his high school
graduation, he was drafted into the British army and served four
years with the Palestinian brigade during World War II. Stationed
in Egypt, he accidentally came across an anthology of modern
British poetry that included poems by Dylan Thomas, T.S. Eliot and
W.H. Auden. Their work had a great impact on him. As he said, ``I
think that was when I began to think seriously about writing
poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   After the war &UR; , &LR;  Amichai taught school in Israel and, in 1948,
joined the Haganah underground. He fought in the Israeli-Arab wars
of 1948, 1956 and 1973. His adult life was caught up in Israel's
struggle to survive and endure and the images of war appear
frequently in his work. In his poem ``Seven Laments for the War
Dead'' he wrote that everything is written in three languages:
``Hebrew, Arabic and Death.''
</P>
<P>
   While teaching, he also studied the Bible and literature at
Hebrew University and wrote poetry. In 1951 he showed some of his
poems to a professor who submitted one to a magazine. It was
accepted. Then he won first prize in a poetry competition. His
first book of poetry, ``Now and in Other Days'' was published in
1955. The book was attacked by some Israeli critics, partly because
of his use of colloquial language, but gradually it became a
success, and soon his career as a poet had begun.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1950s after a trip to the United States, Amichai
wrote two essays, one about hearing Auden read his poetry at the
92nd Street Y in New York. Later, he and Auden became friends.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Amichai began writing short stories, publishing a volume in
1959. Other books followed in Hebrew, but it was not until 1968
that his work was published in English, beginning with his first
novel ``Not of This Time, Not of This Place.''
</P>
<P>
   Amichai's breakthrough with English readers came in the late
1970s with two volumes translated by the author and Ted Hughes. It
was Hughes, he said, ``who put me into orbit.'' With Hughes'
encouragement, Amichai was invited to read his poetry at the
Spoleto arts festival, and soon found himself in the company of
Auden, Pound and others, ``reading with poets whom I had admired
for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon the admiration was mutual, as Amichai's work became
recognized throughout the world. Although he often taught and gave
poetry readings in the United States, he remained an active Israeli
citizen who never ignored the politics of his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to acknowledge political realities,'' he said in the
interview in The Paris Review. ``There's an old Jewish saying, `If
you meet the devil, take him with you into the synagogue.' Try to
take the evil of politics into yourself, to influence it
imaginatively, to give it human shape. This is my attitude toward
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   For Amichai, all poetry was political: ``This is because real
poems deal with a human response to reality, and politics is part
of reality, history in the making. Even if a poet writes about
sitting in a glass house drinking tea, it reflects politics.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his many books of poetry and his short stories,
Amichai published a volume of plays, two novels and three books for
children. A new book of verse, ``Opened Closed Opened,'' was
recently published by Harcourt Brace. In it, he said, ``God is
change and Death is his prophet.''
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife Chana, two sons, Roni and David, and
a daughter Emanuela, all of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1960s Amichai lived in the Yemin Moshe district of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Gods Come and Go, Prayers Remain Forever,'' a poem written
in 1994, he wrote:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tombstones crumble, words come and go, words are forgotten,
</P>
<P>
   The lips that uttered them turned to dust,
</P>
<P>
   Tongues die like people, other tongues come to life,
</P>
<P>
   Gods in the sky change, gods come and go,
</P>
<P>
   Prayers remain forever.  &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Metaphor as a Weapon in `a Struggle With Reality' &QC;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; God takes pity on kindergarten children,
</P>
<P>
   Less on schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   On grown-ups, He won't take pity anymore.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves them alone.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime they have to crawl on all fours
</P>
<P>
   In the blazing sand,
</P>
<P>
   To get to the first aid station
</P>
<P>
   Dripping blood.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe He will take pity and cast His shadow
</P>
<P>
   On those who truly love
</P>
<P>
   As a tree on someone sleeping on the bench
</P>
<P>
   On a boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we too will spend on them
</P>
<P>
   The last coins of favor
</P>
<P>
   Mother bequeathed us,
</P>
<P>
   So their bliss will protect us
</P>
<P>
   Now and in other days. &LR;  _ From ``God Takes Pity on Kindergarten
Children'' (``Now and in Other Days,'' 1956)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In the place where I never was
</P>
<P>
   I never shall be.
</P>
<P>
   The place where I was, as if
</P>
<P>
   I never was there. Human beings wander away
</P>
<P>
   From the place of their birth
</P>
<P>
   And far from the words their own
</P>
<P>
   Mouth uttered,
</P>
<P>
   No more within the promises
</P>
<P>
   That were promised.
</P>
<P>
   And they eat standing up, and die sitting,
</P>
<P>
   And remember lying.
</P>
<P>
   And what I shall never return
</P>
<P>
   To see, I must love for ever.
</P>
<P>
   Only a stranger will return to my place. But I shall
</P>
<P>
   Inscribe the things again, like Moses,
</P>
<P>
   After breaking the first tablets. &LR;  _ From ``The Place Where I
Never Was'' (``Poems, 1948-1952'')
</P>
<P>
   &UR; I was born in 1924. If I were a violin my age
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't be very good. As a wine I would be splendid
</P>
<P>
   Or altogether sour. As a dog I would be dead. As a book
</P>
<P>
   I would begin to be expensive or thrown out by now.
</P>
<P>
   As a forest I would be young, as a machine ridiculous,
</P>
<P>
   And as a human being I'm very tired.
</P>
<P>
   I was born in 1924. When I think about humanity
</P>
<P>
   I just think about those born in my year.
</P>
<P>
   Their mothers gave birth with my mother,
</P>
<P>
   Wherever they were, in hospitals or in dark flats.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, my birthday, I would like
</P>
<P>
   To say a great prayer for you,
</P>
<P>
   Whose load of hopes and disappointments
</P>
<P>
   Pulls your life downward,
</P>
<P>
   Whose deeds diminish
</P>
<P>
   And whose gods increase,
</P>
<P>
   You are all brothers of my hope and companions of my despair.
</P>
<P>
   May you find the right rest,
</P>
<P>
   The living in their life, the dead in their death.
</P>
<P>
   He who remembers his childhood better
</P>
<P>
   Than others is the winner,
</P>
<P>
   If there are any winners at all. &LR;  _ From ``1924'' (``An Hour of
Grace,'' 1983)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
