<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8721 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-WOMPOLO-COLUMN-LA     09-23 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WOMPOLO-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INDESCRIBABLE MOMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ The horn blared and the coach of the United
States women's water polo team, Guy Baker, Friday night almost
leaped into the pool in his frenzied exhilaration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's indescribable how I feel,'' he said. ``No matter what
happens, we're going to win a medal now. It's just unbelievable how
far we've come.''
</P>
<P>
   His gals, showing once again their toughness, their resolve,
their durability and, most of all, their courage, had defied all
pre- Olympic expectations and earned themselves an opportunity to
win a gold medal by beating the Netherlands 6-5 in what was an
aquatic version of one of those fierce NBA playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   The teams competed furiously the entire 28 minutes, holding,
grabbing, bumping, mauling, jostling and even elbowing in a game
that wasn't decided until the final seconds when team captain Julie
Swail and Maureen O'Toole teamed up to smother a Netherlands shot
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans will face Australia, which beat them earlier in
the week 7-6, tonight for the championship. If this one is as
intense and entertaining as Friday night's drama, then the 17,000
people expected to show up at Sydney International Aquatic Centre
will be in for a riveting evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Australia obviously will be the favorite, but I promise we'll
show up,'' said a smiling Baker after his team's latest heroics.
``We're a team that never quits, and gets stronger as the game goes
on. I think you saw that tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   What the intimate gathering at the Ryke Aquatic Centre saw was
the Americans bolt to a 2-0 edge on two early O'Toole goals and
then fall behind 5-3 at one point in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   What the intimate gathering saw was Coralie Simmons and Robin
Beauregard, both former UCLA All-Americans, score goals to tie up
matters at 5-5 in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   What the intimate gathering saw was Heather Moody score what
turned out to be the game-winner at the 6:09 mark of the fourth
period and then have to retire to the sidelines after getting
elbowed in the nose by a Dutch player.
</P>
<P>
   What the intimate gathering saw was the American goalkeeper,
Bernice Orwig, make an incredible stop on a point-blank shot by the
Netherlands' Carla Quint in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just focused on the ball and I had to stop it because of
what happened to Heather,'' said Orwig, who played at USC. ``We had
to win this game for her after she got hurt. No way we were going
to let it slip through our grasp.''
</P>
<P>
   Moody remained in the Americans' locker room afterward and was
unavailable to the press.
</P>
<P>
   Her status tonight is uncertain, although Guy Baker said, ``If
there is any way she can play, she will.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans showed stellar resourcefulness in this one,
although it seemed they were in serious trouble when they fell
behind by those two goals.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Dutch have been the most dominant force in the
sport the past 12 years, winning eight world championships. Eight
of their players on the current team have performed in more than
100 international matches, compared to only three for their Yankee
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   No way they would squander such an advantage, especially when a
gold-medal match with Australia was a little more than 14 minutes
away.
</P>
<P>
   But Baker's women have extraordinary grit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never got down or got worried when we fell behind,'' said
Simmons, who wound up with two goals. ``We had made a few defensive
mistakes and we just tightened up. I don't think they scored on us
the last two quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just seemed to play better when we are in tough,'' said
O'Toole. ``We did the same against Hungary in Sicily when we
qualified for the Olympics. This team just never stops fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   In beating the Netherlands for the second time in this
tournament, the U.S. team now has a 4-1-1 record that also includes
victories over Russia and Kazakhstan and a tie with Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we and the Australians are two very evenly matched
teams,'' said Baker. ``They've got a lot of talented players and so
do we. It seems like every time we play them, it goes right down to
the final horn.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what, Maureen O'Toole will hear the horn for the final
time tonight, culminating a 22-year career in storybook fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't ask for a better way to go out,'' said O'Toole,
whose team did its pre-Olympic training in Los Alamitos. ``My dream
was always to play in the Olympics and to win a gold medal. I'm
halfway there. Hopefully, I'll achieve both goals on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans figure to be underdogs. But they weren't exactly
the favorites against the Dutch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are starting to find out we have a pretty good
team,'' said Baker.
</P>
<P>
   No kidding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
