<HEADER>
A8728 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-POLITICS-COLUMN-SFCHR     09-23 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GORE'S PERSONAL TOUCH DRAWS VOTERS IN  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Actor Harry Hamlin, in jeans and a sport coat, was quietly
sitting in a Southern California health center this week, because
he wanted to hear Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, Geoff Patnoe, 28, a former Republican strategist
who works in the technology industry, stood along a rope line in a
park in Sunnyvale, because he wanted to see Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was running across California this week, from
Hollywood to Silicon Valley, in search of dollars and votes. There
were two big, fancy fund-raisers, crowds of campaign workers, and
political reporters to record it.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the real people who showed that even in a state as
big as California _, &LR;  with more than a dozen media markets, where
everything seems to run on television, &LR;  _ sometimes the candidate
himself makes the sale.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case a stone's throw from Hollywood, where Hamlin
showed up quietly, to see Gore face to face.
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin isn't exactly a regular guy. He starred in ``L.A. Law,''
was once People Magazine's ``Sexiest Man Alive,'' and has taken
some challenging roles, like the gay lover in the controversial
``Making Love,'' a film about coming out. His wife, Lisa Rinna, who
was the husband-stealing vixen of ``Melrose Place,'' once posed for
a Playboy centerfold while pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   So the couple have a stake in the fact that Gore and his running
mate, Joe Lieberman, have been recently charging that Hollywood has
been irresponsible in marketing adult products to kids recently _
even as the Democratic nominees were picking up money in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamlin, watching Gore talk to seniors and health care
professionals at a town hall meeting, seemed impressed. Instead of
chafing at Gore's Hollywood stance, he said he had to give him some
credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain factions in Hollywood that have made profits
by selling the worst part of what we do to the wrong audience _ an
audience of children,'' Hamlin said. ``They see a way to make a big
buck there; they've exploited that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have small children, and it's very important to me that the
kind of programming, the kind of films marketed to them, is
appropriate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, he said, ``my 21/2-year-old daughter is not even
allowed to see Disney movies. (They) have catastrophes in them, and
parents die, and there are witches and monsters, a lot of negative
stuff,'' he said. ``For a 21/2-year-old ... to be exposed to that
kind of trauma on the screen, I think, is inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin said he doesn't think Disney is inappropriately marketing
to kids; it ``really is a parental issue.'' But he gave Gore a
thumbs up for raising the issue, and said he hoped ``there could be
regulations put in place by marketers,'' to assist parents choosing
their kids' entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Half the state away, there was another unlikely supporter in
Gore's camp.
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley, that was Patnoe, a Republican, a tech
communications worker and former GOP strategist who has given money
to George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Patnoe showed up at Lakewood Park in Sunnyvale to ``check out''
the vice president at this week's rally. He stood along the rope
line, next to a guy who held a newer version of a Palm Pilot-like
device.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president came up and grabbed it. ``Wow, is this the
new Handspring Visor?'' asked Gore excitedly, referring to another
version of the handheld gizmo that's become a tec &LR; chie must-have.
``Is it a Beta version? Has it shipped yet?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He commented how he had a Palm V, but he bought two
Handsprings for his daughters,'' Patnoe said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Patnoe, who once worked for Gov. Pete Wilson, said he was
taken aback. ``I'm a big fan of Bush Senior,'' he said. ``But I
thought, `There's no way that Bush Jr. could have a discussion like
that with someone.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But for Patnoe, the clincher came a moment later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore looked me in the face and asked me for my vote,'' he
said. ``I have never been asked directly by a presidential
candidate like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This will shock most of my friends, because I am going to vote
for Al Gore,'' he said. ``Retail politics does work.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's as simple as that: up close and personal still
works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
