<DOCNO> NYT20000923.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8730 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-OIL-RESERVE-SFCHRON &LR;      09-23 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-RESERVE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CLINTON TO TAP U.S. OIL RESERVE  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     and MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One day after Vice President Al Gore called for
tapping the Strategic Petroleum Reserve to reduce oil prices,
President Clinton moved to release 30 million barrels of crude oil
from the 570-million-barrel stockpile.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson announced the decision Friday,
marking the first time since the Persian Gulf War in 1991 that the
reserve is to be tapped _ and the first time ever for nonmilitary
purposes since the stockpile was created more than a
quarter-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the right time to do this,'' Richardson said at a news
conference, describing the move as an effort to ease supplies of
home heating oil, which the Energy Department estimates will cost
30 percent more this winter than last.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure that American families keep warm this
winter and get their heating oil,'' Richardson said. ``Portland,
Maine, will be in the 50s next week, so will Minneapolis, and it
snowed in the Rockies yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, campaigning hard in the battleground states of the
Midwest, urged Clinton Thursday to release 5 million barrels from
the reserve in six or seven installments.
</P>
<P>
   Gore reiterated his call Friday, saying releases from the
reserve would ``help the middle-class families of this country get
some lower gasoline prices and lower home-heating oil prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson quickly denied any political motivation. ``This is
not political,'' Richardson said. ``The president wants to help the
American people get heating oil.''
</P>
<P>
   The Strategic Petroleum Reserve consists of crude oil stored in
salt domes in Louisiana. It was created as an emergency supply in
1973 after a series of oil shocks disrupted economies around the
world. It has been tapped only once before, by President George
Bush to maintain supplies during the Gulf War against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush, himself a former
Texas oil man, condemned the move, saying the reserve ``is meant
for a national emergency, a national war, a major disruption of
supply. The Strategic Petroleum should not be used as a short-term
political fix for somebody whose administration has been asleep at
the switch.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Petroleum Institute, representing the U.S. oil
industry, refused to comment Friday, referring reporters to a
sharply critical statement issued Thursday after Gore's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country's current situation has been a long time coming,
and it cannot be remedied overnight,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices, which reached nearly $38 a barrel in recent days,
fell $1.38 Friday to $32.68. But most economists believe the
political impact of the oil release will be far greater than its
economic consequences.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore called for several releases of 5 million barrels
each, Clinton, in effect, authorized six releases. It would take
114 such installments to deplete the nation's reserves.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, economists believe the additional 30
million barrels will probably translate into just paltry savings,
if any, for the average consumer. Drivers will probably notice no
difference at the pump, while users of home heating oil might see a
short-term drop in price, according to industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh  &LR; Refinery Capacity an Issue
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the new oil could reach homes in 40 to 50 days, just
in time to bring prices down for winter _ and election day. But
first the crude oil must be refined, and most of the nation's
refineries, particularly those on the Gulf Coast, are running close
to 100 percent capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having more crude isn't going to help me make more (heating
oil) right now,'' Bill Greehey, chairman and chief executive of
Valero Energy Corp., a refining company based in San Antonio, told
the Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   However, the mere threat of using the nation's reserve to
influence the market could lead to lower energy bills as sellers
try to unload their inventory before an anticipated price drop. By
the time markets closed Thursday, the day Gore announced his
support for the plan, the price of oil dropped 3 percent to $34.20
a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe Clinton's decision to tap the oil reserve
could prompt OPEC ministers, who will meet next week in Venezuela,
to place more oil on the market.
</P>
<P>
   But an OPEC backlash is also possible. A tiny cut in supply from
the oil-producing nations would more than eliminate any benefit
from using the domestic reserves, something Gore himself recognized
when he spoke against such a policy in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they (OPEC) would have to do is cut back a little bit on
supply, and they'd wipe out any impact from releasing oil from that
reserve,'' Gore said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices began moving sharply up last spring after remaining
in the low $20 range for the previous two years _ a level
economists say was depressed by the Asian financial crisis, when
world demand fell sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Prices have been rising as a result of many factors, including
the long economic expansion in the United States that has boosted
demand, now combined with higher economic growth overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The long period of depressed oil prices also induced higher
consumption, reflected in such things as the popularity of larger
vehicles. Half of all vehicles now sold in the United States are
sport utility vehicles, light trucks and vans, which consume more
gas than the average car.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the policy's actual effect on oil prices, its
political ramifications could be significant in a presidential race
where the outcome of a few swing states could determine the victor.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, with 21 electoral votes and a 40-year record of voting
for the winning presidential candidate, the price of heating oil is
big news. For example, a front-page headline in Thursday's
Cleveland Plain Dealer warned of a proposed utility rate hike that
would cost the average consumer $70 more per month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it a crisis today, but it is critical in the
short term,'' Ohio Gov. Bob Taft said of the high cost of natural
gas. Still, Taft, a Republican, stood at Bush's side this week in
Cleveland when he attacked Gore's proposal as politically motivated
and ``bad public policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Heating oil is most widely used in the Northeast, including New
York, where Hillary Clinton is battling for a Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Polls have consistently given Bush an edge over Gore when voters
are asked which candidate is better able to address the high cost
of gasoline. Gore's new line of attack allows him to polish his
image as a populist crusader standing up for the little guy, while
reminding voters that both Bush and his running mate, Dick Cheney,
have worked for big oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am president,'' Gore said this week, ``I am going to
stand up to big oil and demand fairer gasoline prices for families
and an end to unfair profiteering.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's opponents call his plan politically motivated and
economically undisciplined.
</P>
<P>
   They point to an internal memo written by Secretary of Treasury
Lawrence Summers, reported in the Wall Street Journal this week,
that argued it would be ``a major and substantial policy mistake''
to use the reserve beyond a limited test. Summers pointed out that
his view is shared by Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan
Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the plan note that only once, during the Persian
Gulf War in 1990-91, has the nation found it necessary to use the
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Strategic Petroleum Reserve was established by Congress to
address supply disruptions. It was not intended, and should never
be used, to manipulate prices,'' the American Petroleum Institute
said in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
