<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRUDZIELANEK STILL THINKS ABOUT SHORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ His glove is at second, but Mark Grudzielanek's
heart belongs at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek said he understood why the Dodgers moved him from
shortstop this year and is all right with it, but as his first full
season at second winds to a close, he hasn't given up on the
possibility of returning to short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm at second,'' Grudzielanek said. ``Next year,
you never know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm done with shortstop for the rest of my
career. I love that position. You play it as long as I did, that's
going to feel like home.
</P>
<P>
   ``But A.C. is doing a good job and I see him being here for a
while. He's very solid and one of the better defensive shortstops
in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A.C.'' is Alex Cora, the 24-year-old shortstop the Dodgers
were so high on in the offseason, they asked Grudzielanek to switch
from short _ where he had always started during his five-year
career _ to second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accepted it,'' Grudzielanek said. ``I understood it and
tried to make the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Cora failed to win the job out of spring training, the
Dodgers left Grudzielanek at second and opened the season with
veteran Kevin Elster at short.
</P>
<P>
   Cora has been the Dodgers primary starting shortstop since being
recalled a second time this season on May 31. He's batting .244,
with only 12 errors in 101 games.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek said he has slowly become comfortable at second,
but the move has also coincided with an offensive drop.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Grudzielanek hit .326 _ the highest average ever for
a Dodgers shortstop and the highest in the NL in 63 years. This
season he is batting .281, although his seven home runs and 48 RBI
are almost identical to last year's totals (seven, 46).
</P>
<P>
   ``The move was definitely on my mind, but I don't want to make
excuses for my poor offensive output this year,'' he said. ``I
never really put a good streak together.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Sheffield out for year? Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said it
was possible Gary Sheffield's bad back could force him to miss the
last eight games, but the outfielder said he expects to return.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield did not play again Friday and has played only one of
the last six games while battling a lumbar sprain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be back out there,'' Sheffield said. ``I've been doing
some strengthening exercises, but every time I get ready to swing a
bat, I feel that sharp pain again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, it's not to a point where I can't swing a bat and go
out there and play. But I don't want to risk further injury. That's
the only thing I'm really concerned about.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Outfielder F.P. Santangelo, out since Aug. 23
with a torn ulnar ligament in his left thumb, was activated.
Johnson said he could be used as a pinch-runner. . . . Believe it
or not: Padres first baseman Ryan Klesko stole his 23rd base of the
season. He'd stolen a total of 26 bases in his six-plus previous
seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
