<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8735 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     09-23 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERVINS MUST PAY TO SHARE GOLD JOY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Sherry Ervin traveled halfway around the
globe so she could watch her son compete in the Olympics on a
giant-screen television in a place packed with strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand: Ervin made it inside the Sydney
International Aquatic Centre Friday when her 19-year-old son
Anthony tied for the gold medal with U.S. teammate Gary Hall Jr. in
the 50-meter freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Ervin was one of the lucky ones, as it were. She corralled one
of the 17,500 tickets to the penultimate finals session of the
eight- day competition.
</P>
<P>
   Trust her, procuring an NBA Finals Game 6 seat on the floor
couldn't have been any harder. The Valencia mom was so grateful for
the seat, she didn't blink at the price _ $275 Australian (about
$173 in U.S. currency).
</P>
<P>
   To sire an Olympian, you see, is to realize quickly that
parental pride is its own reward. Everything else _ airfare,
lodging, food, tickets to your child's events, hugs for your child
after his race _ will cost you extra.
</P>
<P>
   Extra money. Extra time. Extra tissues.
</P>
<P>
   Ervin was one of the lucky ones, as it were. Her airfare and
lodging were picked up by Budweiser, a branch of Anheuser-Busch.
Otherwise, she wouldn't have been able to afford to join her
husband Jack and the couple's eldest son Jackie at the Games
(youngest son Derrick stayed home).
</P>
<P>
   What parents of Olympic hopefuls don't know can hurt their
pocketbooks. It's sort of shabby but true:
</P>
<P>
   You can drive your kid to practice twice a day, six days a week,
for 11 months a year for eight to 10 years; you can stop at every
Motel 6 from Apple Valley to Yuba on the age-group swimming
express; you can dress up ground beef in a hundred ways to keep
your kid in swimsuits and caps; you can be there to wipe away
rivers of tears and shoo away fears. And if Junior grows up to
become one of the fortunate few to compete in the Olympics, you'll
be in the same boat as Maude and Ed from Milwaukee when it comes to
securing a decent vantage point.
</P>
<P>
   Ervin is pretty sure she would have seen more of the 50 final
had she stayed home and planted herself in a booth at a San
Fernando Valley sports bar. For starters, she was as far away from
the blocks as you could be and still go deaf from the chants of
``Aussie! Aussie! Aussie! Oi! Oi! Oi!''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Ervin stands 6-foot-2, but from where Sherry and Jack
sat, he looked ethereal, like a finger of steam rising from the
deck. And they were so high, she almost could use the flags hanging
from the rafters to wipe the sweat off her brow.
</P>
<P>
   No matter.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry and Jack Ervin were among the lucky ones, as it were.
Their son was the first one off the blocks and Sherry flew to her
feet, her reaction time just slightly slower than Anthony's.
</P>
<P>
   The race lasted under 22 seconds but long enough for her to yell
herself hoarse cheering. Even though the field was swimming toward
the Ervins, they were too far away to make out many details.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to look at the replays to see the race,'' Sherry Ervin
would later say, or rather, croak.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, watching the race unfold over and over and
over, from all different angles, would be a pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Ervin, 19, touched the wall, Sherry stared at the
giant scoreboards on either side of her to see his reaction. When
she saw the image of Ervin hug the image of Hall, with whom he had
trained this summer in Phoenix, the tears started to queue in the
corners of her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really was picture perfect,'' Ervin said throatily.
</P>
<P>
   A German gentleman was seated behind her and at some point he
grabbed Sherry Ervin's shoulder and shouted above the din, ``It was
worth the price of the ticket just to see your reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Ervin couldn't see her son's face during the awards
ceremony to gauge what he was feeling, though she could guess.
``All we could see was the top of his head,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The co-gold medalists were shepherded to a group interview
session after the awards ceremony and then to drug testing. More
interviews ensued, then a long overdue warmdown, more interviews, a
deep-tissue massage and a live network TV appearance.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly three hours after his race before the Ervins
finally got to give their son a congratulatory hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I loved him,'' Sherry Ervin said, ``and then I
started crying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 0050EDT &QL; 
