<SLUG> BC-TRUMAN-BUILDING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE DEPARTMENT BUILDING DEDICATED TO HARRY S. TRUMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Kevin Murphy  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   WASHINGTON _ President Harry S. Truman's
contribution to world peace and diplomacy fills American history
books. On Friday, it was set in stone.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Under a bright afternoon sun, President Clinton unveiled a
17-foot-long granite marker that names the headquarters of the
State Department as the Harry S. Truman Building.
</P>
<P>
   The honor, to recognize the foreign policies of Missouri's most
famous son, was long overdue, said U.S. Rep. Ike Skelton of
Lexington, Mo., who spoke at the ceremony Friday. He called Truman
``undoubtedly one of the most illustrious occupants of the Oval
Office.''
</P>
<P>
   Truman brought an end to World War II by dropping the atomic
bomb, led America during the Korean War, created the Marshall Plan
and NATO to rebuild and protect Europe, and saw the start of the
Cold War with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a doer, whose plain words and bold actions mended a
broken world, saved freedom, and embodied the principles of our
nation at its best,'' Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright said
at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   But Truman, the 33rd president, was also one of the more
unassuming chief executives. So what would he think of having his
name emblazoned across the State Department headquarters?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he would be honored,'' said John Truman, a grandnephew
of Truman's.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have been very proud and humbled by the step you are
taking today to memorialize his good name,'' Truman said.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-foot-high black granite marker was stationed in a bed of
pale yellow chrysanthemums in front of the eight-story State
Department complex, where about 8,000 people work. Part of the
building was finished in 1939 and the other section in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great day for the State Department and a great day
for Missouri,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright tried to re-create the Truman era during two days of
events honoring him. At a State Department dinner Thursday night,
the menu was identical to one at a state dinner at the White House
in October 1949. On Friday, the Navy Commodores orchestra played
big band music of the 1940s era.
</P>
<P>
   Among guests at the dinner was Larry Hackman, director of the
Truman Library and Museum in Independence. The library lent a bust
of Truman that was displayed in the headquarter's lobby Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not someone who was enamored with having things named
after him, but if there was one he would have (agreed to), it would
have been the State Department building,'' Hackman said.
</P>
<P>
   Only two other federal buildings in Washington are named after
presidents. The Commerce Department bears the name of Herbert
Hoover, former Commerce secretary, and a new world trade center is
named after Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   The Executive Office Building next to the White House is going
to be named after Dwight Eisenhower of Kansas. The dedication date
is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Skelton said he was asked earlier this year by two former aides
of Truman to name the State Department headquarters after him.
Albright readily agreed and the legislation sailed through the
House and Senate with bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   ``His leadership and character, especially in the area of
foreign policy, have earned him well-deserved praise and respect
throughout the world,'' Sen. John Ashcroft, a Missouri Republican,
said in a statement to the Senate on Thursday. Ashcroft and Sen.
Kit Bond were invited to attend the ceremony Friday but said they
had other commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Truman is rated in numerous polls of historians as one of the
country's best presidents, but his foreign policies are not without
detractors, especially regarding the Cold War that lasted until 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Vietnam intruded and we saw the consequences of the Cold
War, we began to argue that his truculence really provoked the
Russians when there was a possibility for cooperation,'' said Allan
Winkler, a Miami University history professor who specializes in
the last half of the 20th century. ``His reputation has gone up and
down.''
</P>
<P>
   But Albright and others said Truman took the long view in making
decisions, such as sending aid to Europe to stave off Soviet
influence, recognizing the state of Israel in 1948, and opening the
armed forces to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Truman is largely responsible for some of the
freedoms and opportunities Americans have today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing we say, `Thanks, Mr. President,' by naming
this building for him,'' Clinton said. ``It would be a far, far
better thing if we would follow his lead and give the same set of
opportunities to our grandchildren.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
