<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SLEEPOVERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SLEEPOVERS AND SOFT MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Sept. 23:
</P>
<P>
   Just when Hillary Rodham Clinton has been making headway among
voters in New York, her campaign for Senate has hit a familiar
political problem. On Friday the White House released a list of
more guests who have stayed overnight there or at Camp David since
July. About a quarter of them have contributed to Hillary Clinton's
campaign for Senate in New York. At the same time, the first lady's
proposal to Rep. Rick Lazio, her Republican opponent, that both
candidates forgo all broadcast advertisements paid for with
unregulated soft money was rejected by Lazio on the grounds that it
was one-sided. The collection of soft money, of course, is at the
center of the reckless fund-raising system that has led to excesses
like the White House sleepovers.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons' use of the White House to reward contributors was
a national embarrassment, but the sleepovers themselves were never
proved to be illegal. That probably continues to be the case, but
the use of invitations to the Lincoln Bedroom as fund-raising bait
is just the kind of outdated practice that Hillary Clinton needs to
shed as she grows to political independence. Lazio is justified in
making this distasteful practice an issue in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A possible mutual agreement to ban soft money unraveled Friday
when it turned out that Hillary Clinton's proposal would have
called on Lazio to bar advertisements sponsored by groups outside
his campaign but allow supporters of Clinton's candidacy _
particularly the AFL-CIO, the Sierra Club and the National Abortion
and Reproductive Rights Action League _ to run advertisements paid
for by unrestricted donations. The first lady argued that her
proposal was more of a sacrifice for her campaign than it would be
for Lazio. Her aides also asserted that the outside groups paying
for advertisements for Lazio were sham organizations set up by the
Republican Party, whereas Clinton's groups were legitimate
organizations with large numbers of members.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's contention is not supportable. A soft-money ban
should apply equally to both campaigns. She could easily get these
well-known groups to forgo their televised ad campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Although discussions between Lazio and Clinton collapsed into
recriminations Friday night, there is still time for them to try to
work something out that would be of mutual benefit and would also
serve the public interest.
</P>
<P>
   A deal to ban soft money would also enhance Clinton's image. The
one thing that has marred her increasingly effective race is
fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 President Clinton twisted the limits on the use of soft
money, which should never have been used for campaign
advertisements, in a way that has damaged and corrupted the
political system. Using the White House and Camp David for
sleepovers has tarred the presidency and cheapened institutions
that should be above political advantage. Mrs. Clinton can go far
to separate herself from these abuses if she can accept a fair deal
on soft money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
