<DOCNO> NYT20000923.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8739 &Cx1f; kan-z
r n BC-HEASTER-BUSINESS-KAN &LR;      09-23 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-BUSINESS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE GIVES WALL STREET THE JITTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Jerry Heaster  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   While the Stock Trader's Almanac reveals
September as the worst month of the year for investors over the
past half-century, there doesn't appear to be any common factor
involved in the month's historically bad showing.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thus, in the 27 Septembers since 1950 during which the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index registered a loss, it must be assumed that
transient rather than cyclical factors were to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts of the conservative persuasion think they've
already identified the cause of this September's stock market
swoon.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, as they see it, is the increasing strength shown by
Al Gore in voter polls combined with the vice president's
relentless attacks on Big Business. Since the Labor Day weekend
kickoff of the presidential election campaign, September has become
a downer for all the major indices: Measured from their September
highs established early this month, the Dow Jones industrial
average is down 4 percent, the S&AMP;P 500 is off 4.7 percent and the
Nasdaq has plunged 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Kudlow, a Wall Street economist and policy aide in the
Reagan administration, has accused Gore of liking jobs but not the
businesses that create jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes prosperity,'' Kudlow said in a recent commentary.
``He just doesn't want anyone to get rich.'' The perceived
contradictions of Gore's message, he says, jeopardize the 18-year
bull market. Kudlow, who has taken to calling Gore the aspiring
``regulator in chief,'' says Gore's campaign theme of ``the people
against the powerful'' makes it clear a Gore presidency will be
characterized by a heavy hand on business activity.
</P>
<P>
   As polls show improving prospects not only for Gore but also for
Democrats attempting to regain a House majority, investor jitters
have intensified accordingly, says James K. Glassman, a resident
fellow at the American Enterprise Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Glassman, who is co-author of Dow 36,000, differs somewhat from
Kudlow in that he thinks the market could live with a Gore
presidency if it occurred in the context of divided-government
gridlock. Glassman, writing in The Wall Street Journal this week,
said his research showed the market had performed best since the
mid-1970s when one party controlled the White House while the other
controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   During one-party control, he said, the Dow Jones industrial
average rose an average of only 2.3 percent annually. When
political power was divided between the White House and Congress,
however, the average yearly gain was nearly 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gridlock is good,'' Glassman avers. ``It has blocked big new
federal programs, new taxes, and new agencies, departments and
regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Although nobody believes what happens in Washington is the
be-all, end-all for stock prices, Glassman says his research proves
conclusively that what happens in Washington ``has a huge effect on
stock prices.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be, of course, that Wall Streeters are worried
needlessly. Perhaps the race is closer than recent polls indicate.
Even so, politics aside, here's something else to keep in mind: The
stock market is a leading economic indicator, and the bias has been
down for six months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 0054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
