<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8744 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-LAGUARDIA-NYT &LR;      09-23 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LAGUARDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GRIDLOCK AT LA GUARDIA 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Sept. 23:
</P>
<P>
   New York City's airports are already strained beyond their
limits and crying out for more flights to enhance competition. That
is the conundrum now facing regional and federal transportation
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers complain that there are not enough conveniently
scheduled flights from New York City to places like Buffalo and
Norfolk. Congress passed a law earlier this year allowing airlines
to circumvent long-standing caps on the number of flights out of La
Guardia Airport to fly regional jets to such underserved, or new,
destinations.
</P>
<P>
   But travelers also point out that there are far too many
nightmarish delays at La Guardia. The city and the Port Authority
of New York and New Jersey, La Guardia's operator, have moved to
prevent airlines from capitalizing on the legislation and adding as
many as 600 more takeoffs and landings a day at La Guardia.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority informed airlines on Thursday that they could
not add more flights during the airport's two busiest morning and
two busiest evening hours. The authority fears that the airlines
could add up to 50 percent more daily flights to an already
overburdened system, and would like new flights to be scheduled
during off-peak hours. The airlines concede that the airport is
already under tremendous strain, but feel compelled to add the new
flights at prime time to keep up with the competition. They also
claim that the Port Authority has no legal right to ban flights
approved by the Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   One alternative reportedly being considered by the Port
Authority is a restructuring of fees paid by airlines to reflect
the higher value placed on rush-hour flights. Such a step is worthy
of further study, and could be a means of holding airlines to the
same pricing principles they impose on passengers _ you pay more
for the most convenient flights.
</P>
<P>
   At some airports around the nation, the airlines themselves are
reacting to passengers' ire at recent gridlock by reducing the
number of flights. That is more easily done at hubs already
controlled by one airline, where cutting back does not translate
into a meaningful drop in market share.
</P>
<P>
   At La Guardia, an airport not dominated by any one airline, it
will take the prodding of regulators to both rationalize the
scheduling of existing service and accommodate truly needed new
routes. Whether the Port Authority should be that regulator is not
clear, but it should be applauded for intervening to state the
obvious. Something has to give.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
