<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8747 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-FUNDRAISING-EMAI     09-23 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-FUNDRAISING-EMAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE E-MAILS CONFIRM GORE AIDES TREATED COFFEES AS
FUND-RAISERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Retrieved White House e-mail messages turned over
Friday to federal and congressional investigators show that Vice
President Al Gore's senior aides routinely characterized White
House coffee sessions as fund-raising events in early 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While none of the e-mail messages indicate that the vice
president himself was involved in any of the electronic
conversations, the aides' descriptions of the coffees seem to be at
odds with Gore's comments in an April 18 interview this year with
federal investigators. The vice president said the 103 coffee
gatherings with campaign donors held at the White House before the
1996 election had not been ``fund-raising tools.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's remarks in the four-hour interview had led a senior
Justice Department prosecutor, Robert Conrad Jr., to recommend that
Attorney General Janet Reno appoint a special counsel to
investigate the truthfulness of Gore's remarks, but last month,
Reno declined to appoint a special counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail messages had been subpoenaed by a congressional
committee and the Justice Department investigating allegations of
campaign finance abuses and other matters in the Clinton
administration. Their release Friday came after months of
complaining by members of Congress that the White House was trying
to withhold them.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans quickly seized on the contents as evidence that the
vice president and the White House had not been truthful in earlier
explanations of the purpose of the coffees, and an event at a
Buddhist Temple in Hacienda Heights, Calif., before the 1996
election. And the committee chairman, Rep. Dan Burton of Indiana,
said he would made hold hearings on the newly released
correspondence next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign countered that the e-mail messages were
consistent with earlier explanations of the nature of the coffees
and contained nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Skelton, Gore's political director, asked an aide to the
vice president in an e-mail note dated April 23, 1996: ``These are
F.R. coffees, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked Friday night whether the abbreviation stood for
fund-raising, a White House aide said it could also mean
``finance-related,'' a phrase the vice president himself once used
to describe his appearance at a luncheon at a Buddhist temple in
Los Angeles in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
   On May 8, 1996, Skelton described in an e-mail message the
expectations that the White House had for people invited to coffees
with President Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Skelton wrote to an aide, ``but keep in mind that these
people must be justifiable on the basis of what they give us down
the line. What is the consequence of our meeting with one person
other than that person feeling good?''
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail messages released by the White House are among a
cache of nearly 150,000 messages that the White House failed to
properly archive from 1996 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans have criticized White House officials
for failing to immediately inform them that they could not retrieve
the messages, a problem the White House attributed to a computer
error in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was not revealed to congressional committees
investigating the issue until early this year. Since April,
technicians have methodically retrieved the lost e-mail
correspondence from a computer database.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kennedy, a spokesman for Gore, said Friday night that the
e-mail messages contain information that had already been provided
three years earlier to several congressional investigative
committees, including the House panel led by Burton.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing significant here in response to Dan Burton's
25 subpoenas,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said that in the April interview with federal
investigators, the vice president acknowledged that White House
coffee guests were often solicited to contribute to the Democratic
Party after attending one of the events.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president testified seven times in April that
attendees would likely be asked at a later date to financially
support the DNC, and that is completely consistent with these
e-mails,'' Kennedy said. ``There is nothing in any of this material
that sheds any new light on old arguments, all of which have been
fully investigated for years now.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, the communications director for Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas, said the e-mail notes are ``another piece of
evidence that calls into question the vice president's credibility
when he says he did not know that a fund-raising event was a
fund-raising event.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, on Friday Burton vowed to make the newly released
e-mail messages an issue at a hearing scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   When Reno decided not to seek the appointment of a special
counsel to investigate Gore, she said, ``I have concluded that
there is no reasonable possibility that further investigation could
develop evidence that would support the filing of charges for
making a willful false statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton said: ``At the time the attorney general made this
statement, did she have these e-mails? Many of them come from the
vice president's office and deal directly with the White House
fund-raising coffees and the Hsi Lai Temple fund-raiser.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House first released the documents this afternoon to
The Associated Press, not long after White House aides released a
lengthy list of recent overnight guests at the White House and Camp
David. In 1997, the White House routinely released campaign
documents late on Friday afternoon so it would be published in
Saturday newspapers when readership is often thought to be
lightest. Aides refused to say whether the simultaneous release of
the material was intended to minimize its impact.
</P>
<P>
   Some messages deal with Gore's luncheon at the Hsi Lai Temple.
But many of those notes are excerpts of memorandums that had been
previously turned over to congressional investigators and made
public. Several e-mail messages again demonstrate that Gore aides
may have been confused about two fund-raisers that had been
originally scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Currently, we are committed in San Jose and L.A. for
fund-raising events,'' one staff e-mail note said about the trip.
</P>
<P>
   But the schedule for Gore prepared nearly three weeks before the
temple luncheon did not mention a fund-raising event at a Los
Angeles area restaurant. After arriving in Los Angeles at 11 a.m.,
Gore was scheduled to proceed to the Hsi Lai Temple event, which
was described at the time as a Democratic National Committee
``Asian Pacific American Leadership Council Luncheon.''
</P>
<P>
   Another e-mail note recommended that Gore bring $20 with him to
the temple so he could make a donation of his own. ``The VP will
need to have some cash on hand,'' a message said, ``to offer as an
offering at the Buddhist temple in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   James Wilson, the chief counsel of the House Committee on
Government Reform, said Friday night that he was ``particularly
frustrated'' by the cache of e-mail messages that the committee
received this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is new information and new leads that need to be
investigated,'' Wilson said. ``The White House covered this up for
over three years and that is simply not acceptable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
