<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-U.S. (Washington) _ The Clinton administration is not
hiding its desire to see the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic, unseated. It is also holding large amphibious exercises
with Croatia to show the military muscle behind the money it has
given to the Serbian opposition. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT18 was sent 9-21 to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-ADOPTION-COSTS (Undated) _ As more affluent, childless New
Yorkers increasingly turn to costly private adoptions, often
circling the globe for an orphan to bring home, there are other
people willing to adopt the city kids that few seem to want.
Economics has something to do with their choices. None of them can
afford the expense of a private adoption, which can easily run up
to $20,000. And adoptions from the foster care system are
subsidized, offering up to $1,200 a month per child, if one
requires special medical care. By Somini Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By Peter
Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROLLS-ROYCE (Munich, Germany) _ As director of Project
Rolls-Royce at the German automaker Bayerische Motoren Werke AG,
Karl-Heinz Kalbfell is planning to introduce an entirely new line
of Britain's most prestigious name in cars. But thanks to a
stalemate between BMW and Volkswagen AG, which both wanted to buy
Rolls-Royce two years ago, he has to wait until 2003, when
Volkswagen will relinquish control over the celebrated name. Until
BMW acquires the name, Kalbfell is not supposed to even pose in
front of current Rolls-Royce models, much less promote them in any
way. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-TIMEWARNER-EUROPE (Paric) _ Time Warner and America Online
have proposed remedies _ including dissolving an alliance with
German media conglomerate Bertelsmann _ to allay concerns of
European antitrust regulators about their proposed $165 billion
merger. But the remedies have failed to sway opponents of the deal
in the music and Internet industries and among consumer
organizations, making it unlikely the regulators will accept them
without substantive change. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   ALLSTATE-AGENTS (Undated) _ The Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission determined this week that when the Allstate Insurance
Corp. forced more than 6,000 agents to sign away their rights to
sue the company to keep their jobs, it violated federal law. By
Greg Winter.
