<HEADER>
A8753 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-BOOMERS-$ADV24     09-23 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-BOOMERS-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS INDEXES FALL, SOME MUSINGS ON THE DOWNSIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 24)  
 By   JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the last week of the third quarter begins, the three major
stock indexes are down for the year. If they finish the quarter
this way, it will be the first time since 1990 that all three have
been down at this time of the year. So let's think some bearish
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   One of the threats to the stock market is the retirement of the
baby boomers. As they leave the work force, will they also choose
less risk, moving money from stocks into bonds?
</P>
<P>
   Paddy Jilek, the director of U.S. economics at Credit Suisse
First Boston, thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges that the life-expectancy data shows that people
who are retiring at 65 can now expect to live to 75 or 80. That
makes it difficult to say when retirees' investment horizons will
shorten enough to make them demand investments that are less risky
than stocks. Still, he said, ``eventually the baby boomers will
become risk averse like every retiree, and that means, ther things
being equal, the stock market could struggle over a 10-year
period.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first baby boomers, the age of 65 doesn't come for 10
years. So what's the worry?
</P>
<P>
   Jilek thinks that the previous generation, which is reaching 65
now, is ready to begin making the portfolio shift to less risky
assets like bonds. And he argues that this group, which dates from
1935 _ 10 years before the beginning of the baby boom generation _
was the pace setter at two other crucial points for markets.
</P>
<P>
   One was the surge in home buying that he believes reached its
inflection point around 1965, while many baby boomers were still in
grade school. Before then, housing prices had been falling,
relative to the Consumer Price Index. Afterward, housing prices
began to rise in real terms.
</P>
<P>
   The second key point was at the beginning of the 1980s. That,
Jilek argued, was when this older group began the accumulation of
financial assets to help pay for college educations for their
children and eventual retirement for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   If this group is leading the way again, investors may have more
to worry about now than they are aware of. ``A sprinkle now, a
drizzle soon, and a torrent in 15 year's time,'' Jilek wrote in a
recent report on this issue. ``It's the sprinkle that marks the
inflection point relative to asset prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Jilek thinks that there is another threat to the stock market _
one that means it may not be able to match the wonderful returns of
the last half of the 1990s. If it coincides with the shift of risk
preference by those born in 1935 who are now retiring, it could
aggravate the portfolio shift away from equities, putting downward
pressure on stocks.
</P>
<P>
   That threat, he says, is from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   In his report, Jilek argued that foreign demand for U.S. stocks
played a crucial role in the second half of the 1990s _ and that a
switch in sentiment could hurt. In 1999, according to Federal
Reserve data, foreign investment funds bought a net $98.1 billion
of U.S. stocks. That number has taken off this year, despite the
poor performance of the major stock indexes. Net purchases surged
to $176.4 billion in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. stock has also been gobbled up in the form of foreign
acquisitions of U.S. companies. There were about $153 billion in
cross-border deals in 1999, almost double the $78 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   So with the stock market in a position it has not seen for a
decade, think of influences that go beyond corporate earnings,
whose growth appears to be slowing, and whether the Federal Reserve
is finished raising interest rates for this cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it is not a factor tomorrow, Jilek said, it would be
wise to be a little more cautious about the potential for stocks in
the years ahead. ``I think it is an issue you really need to keep
in mind,'' he added. ``It's there all the time and can be a pretty
powerful force.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
