<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-MITSUBISHI-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CASE OF THE PHANTOM SALES LOGGED BY MITSUBISHI MANAGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Ore., Fla., Ga., Japan)   (For release Sunday, Sept. 24)  
 By MARCIA RUFF    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In recent years, it has sometimes seemed that if it wasn't for
bad news, there would be little news at all for Mitsubishi. For
several years, the company was dogged by complaints of sexual
harassment in its Normal, Ill., assembly plant.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the president of the Japanese parent company resigned
over illegal payments to gangsters. His successor, Katsuhiko
Kawasoe, announced his resignation this month after the company was
embarrassed by reports that it had concealed customer complaints
for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Things were looking up, though, for the U.S. sales operation,
Mitsubishi Motor Sales of America, which broke even in 1998 for the
first time in a decade. Profits have risen since then, with sales
expected to reach 300,000 this year, up from 190,515 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But then last week, Automotive News, the industry's leading
trade publication, published an article that said the company had
falsified sales records and possibly jeopardized customer
warranties.
</P>
<P>
   The article portrayed deception unfolding like scenes from
``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' David Mamet's play about desperate, amoral
salesmen. In late-night sessions at regional headquarters in
Orlando, Fla., regional sales managers entered false sales data,
seeking to inflate their total to meet corporate objectives and
outsell other regions, the article said. The managers entered names
like Patty O. Furniture, Bud Weiser and Supa Mann as the buyers of
cars on dealers' lots. Automotive News quoted an unidentified
source as saying that thousands of cars had been ``sold'' this way.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers never knew about the fake sales until a legitimate buyer
wanted the car _ and the dealer would find it listed on the
computerized inventory as sold, Automotive News reported. The
region would then ``back out'' the false sale and enter information
about the real buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi concedes that false sales were entered, but said the
numbers were in the hundreds, not the thousands. The company said
it began an investigation after a sales manager in Atlanta reported
the falsifications in May. Memos went out condemning the practice,
and regional sales managers were barred from entering sales data.
</P>
<P>
   The article also raised the issue of whether the legitimate
buyers might lose warranty coverage if their cars had been reported
as sold at an earlier date. Automotive News reported that the
warranty clock started with the false sale, not the actual sale.
But a Mitsubishi spokesman, Kim Custer, said the warranties start
from the date of delivery to the customer. In the normal course of
business, information about an actual sale would overwrite any
false data.
</P>
<P>
   Defending the integrity of the company's sales totals, Custer
said any cars sold falsely ultimately went out the door as
legitimate sales. To maintain the accuracy of its database, the
company periodically asks auditors to compare its records with
title registrations, which represent actual ales. For 1999,
Mitsubishi said the auditor found a 5 percent discrepancy, which it
said was within the norm for its automotive clients.
</P>
<P>
   Overzealous sales reporting has a long history in the business.
Art Spinella of CNW Marketing/Research, in Bandon, Ore., said,
``Falsifying sales records has been going on for years and years
and years, and has been done in a whole raft of ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it is done for bragging rights. Cadillac lost face two
years ago when it claimed sales leadership for 1998 over its
archrival, Lincoln, only to back down a few weeks later when
independent figures showed that Cadillac had come up short.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the falsifications are done for money. If a dealership
or salesman is a few units short of reaching a target for a bonus,
the temptation is great to fudge the sale of a few cars, which
would then be sold for real the next month.
</P>
<P>
   From a customer's perspective, the risk of having a warranty
jeopardized this way is low. It is wise, however, to double-check
the date of delivery on your car's records when you buy it and when
you bring it in for the first service. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 0139EDT &QL; 
