<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8756 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CARS-MITSUBISHI-MONTE     09-23 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-MITSUBISHI-MONTERO-$ADV24-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CAMEL FOR WILDERNESS EXPLORATION,   TWO HUMPS INCLUDED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo., Japan)   (For release Sunday, Sept. 24)  
 By LEONARD M. APCAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESTES PARK, Colo. _ I am at the wheel of the freshly redesigned
2001 Mitsubishi Montero, doing what most people never do in
off-road-capable sport utility vehicles: I am driving it off road.
</P>
<P>
   More precisely, I am on Old Fall River Road in Rocky Mountain
National Park. The nine-mile gravel path zigzags up a narrow
mountain valley to a treeless tundra with heartstopping views.
</P>
<P>
   There are no guardrails, and the turns are so tight that
vehicles longer than 25 feet should stay back at camp. But the
Montero, at just under 16 feet, neuvers nicely, and its
rack-and-pinion steering _ rare for a mountain goat like this _ as
well as its unusual transmission are making pretty easy work of the
terrain even at power-sapping altitudes of 8,500 to nearly 12,000
feet. With the sunroof peeled back, the pines and aspens within
reach, this is truly a ride on the edge of the wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Montero is not truly about off-road treks in the
highlands. While Mitsubishi likes to advertise its dirt-digging
prowess, the latest Montero, full of leather and luxury, has been
designed more for the Hamptons than for the Himalayas. Like just
about every vehicle in this $32,000-to-$36,000 segment, the ride
has been re-engineered to feel more like a car's than a camel's.
The appointments are more luxurious and the third row of seats,
which is standard, does a neat, four-step disappearing act into the
cargo floor.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the Montero's famously boxy look has been given a
little flair. The front fenders have new humps, and the rear flanks
have been puffed out to form beefier haunches.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it is not a handsome wrap. The large grille and
squared-off side windows don't mesh well with rounded fenders that
look like cartoonish afterthoughts. A young boy stepped forward
during my test drive and asked the name of the red truck.
``Montero?'' he said, mangling the pronunciation. ``Kind of ugly,
especially right here,'' he said, jabbing at one of the humps.
</P>
<P>
   Looks may not be the only aspect to give a buyer pause.
Mitsubishi confessed this summer to concealing complaints and
defects about its vehicles in Japan going back more than 20 years.
While I encountered no troubles with this test truck _ and none of
the defects in Japan are related to Monteros sold in this country _
Mitsubishi cars and trucks have received mixed reviews in
product-quality surveys. DaimlerChrysler has invested in the
company and installed its own operating chief to improve
Mitsubishi's fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Humps aside, the Montero stands out in two other respects, which
partly explain its strong sales since it was introduced in March.
One is its disappearing third seat. The other is its new Sportronic
automatic, a transmission that allows drivers to shift manually,
but without a clutch, through five speeds in both rear-drive or
three distinct four-wheel-drive modes, including a full-time
all-wheel-drive setting. Up and especially down the mountain roads
of north central Colorado, this was a brake-saving delight. It also
provided much better coordination between the gearbox and the
engine because the transmission, on its own, shifted often as it
hunted for the appropriate gear in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Sportronic is standard on the Montero Limited, which starts at
$35,517. A less expensive XLS, without leather and the fancy
gearbox, starts at around $32,000.
</P>
<P>
   Third-row seats are a popular SUV feature, especially for
customers who want the room and flexibility of a minivan, but don't
want to be seen driving one. The Montero's extra seat is a big
improvement over the jump seats the truck used to have, which
folded to the side when you needed them out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Among the big SUVs, the Dodge Durango has a nicely designed
third seat. G.M. put an even better one in its slightly larger
Chevrolet Tahoe and GMC Yukon, and Ford plans one for its 2002
Explorer, due out next year. Even the next generation of the
smaller GMC Envoy and Chevy Blazer will come in stretched versions
with third seats. In mid-November, Toyota will begin selling its
Sequoia, which also has a third row.
</P>
<P>
   The standard Montero third-row seat is a narrow bench that
barely holds two children and has precious little legroom. There
are two shoulder straps with the seat belts, and the side windows
pop out for ventilation. With the seat up, I was able to stow a
backpack and a few carry-ons behind it. There was also extra space
below the floor. Best of all, there was room for each of my two
children to have a row of his or her own. In all, there was seating
for seven.
</P>
<P>
   When I needed to pack up for the ride home, it was easy to fold
the seat and flop it into a compartment below the floor. That
opened up plenty of room for about 10 bags, including two big
suitcases and a set of golf clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the tight space, the air-conditioning didn't quite reach
the far-back seat. Separate automatic climate control, rear air
controls and a second blower are a $900 option.
</P>
<P>
   On the road, the Montero was pretty well behaved, and road and
wind noise were modest for a truck. It navigated hairpin turns at
40 mph with composure. The four-wheel anti-lock disc brakes were
sure. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most trucks at this price have V-8 engines under the hood, and
while the Montero's 3.5-liter, 200-horsepower V-6 will not win any
prizes for brute force, it felt surprisingly strong on the highway
and on city streets. Although the engine has been improved to
provide better pickup at lower speeds _ peak torque is 235
foot-pounds at 3,000 rpm _ it was both puzzling and humiliating to
be overtaken by a Dodge minivan as we galloped up a mountain pass.
The Montero was cranking out 5,000 rpm, but the minivan beat us to
the top. The Montero's V-6 generally limits towing capability to
1,500 pounds, compared with around 6,000 pounds for a Ford Explorer
or Expedition.
</P>
<P>
   While the Montero had plenty of smart touches, it also had its
quirks. The side mirrors are rectangles mounted vertically instead
of horizontally, the more common practice. The idea is that it will
pass more easily through tight spaces, but it also narrows the view
to the rear and makes blind spots larger.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the rear tailgate opens wide like a refrigerator door, not
up like a liftgate. This is fine in the wide-open West and made
loading very easy. But imagine trying to open the back end in a
tight space in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there were some details that were strangely missing
from a vehicle that wanted to offer every luxury and up-to-date
touch. While there were dual air bags in the dash and side bags in
the front seats, there was no shoulder strap or headrest for the
center spot in the second row.
</P>
<P>
   The Montero Limited has mirrors in the sun visors, but they are
not lighted, despite the vehicle's luxury pretensions. The rear
side windows do not open fully and the front passenger seat is not
available with power adjustments. One other flaw: The only
indicator of whether the air-conditioning is cranking is an
impossibly tiny light on the blower knob that is difficult to see
on a bright day.
</P>
<P>
   Such details may not mean a lot to other drivers. But with the
most luxurious leather version topping $36,000, the Montero
shouldn't be missing much.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 0143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
