<HEADLINE>
FISET HURTS KNEE IN CLOSE LOSS TO DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK WELCH  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ As if things aren't bad enough for the Los
Angeles Kings. Goaltender Stephane Fiset suffered a sprained left
knee midway through the first period of the Kings' 3-2 exhibiton
loss to the Anaheim Mighty Ducks in front of 11,237 at The Pond.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings already were playing without Jozef Stumpel, who has
missed training camp in a contract dispute. Then, their top player
Rob Blake resigned his captaincy, also over trying to reach a new
deal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fiset, who did not allow a goal in his first two games, left the
ice with nine minutes left after former King Dan Bylsma
inadvertenly ran into him during a scramble in front of the net.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset got to his feet and began flexing his left leg.
Eventually, he eventually skated off under his own power.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset will be reevaluted today. The Kings play tonight in
Bakersfield against San Jose. Jamie Storr is expected to start in
goal with Steve Passmore and Travis Scott also available.
</P>
<P>
   While things were downright dark in Los Angeles, it appears the
power is back on in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks won their second consecutive exhibition game after
three straight losses. But more importantly, Anaheim finally found
a way to take advantage of the man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim scored not once, but twice in an 85-second power-play
binge that turned a tie game into a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' Paul Kariya stuck in a rebound from a Steve Rucchin
shot to end the streak of power-play failures at 38 in a row.
Kariya's goal came with Anaheim holding a 4-on-3 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Murray's power-play goal midway through the second period
brought the Kings to within 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Ducks top goaltender Guy Hebert made his preseason debut Friday.
Hebert was slowed by a strained groin muscle.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Single-game tickets for the regular season go on sale
today at 10 a.m. at Staples Center and all TicketMaster outlets.
Telephone orders also can be taken through TicketMaster (213)
365-3600. Internet users can log on to www.ticketmaster.com
topurchase tickets. Tickets are available for all hoe games with
prices beginning at $19.50. Information: (888) KINGS-LA.
</P>
</TEXT>
