</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 9, it became clear to Dorenko, who knows better than
most how power works in Russia, that its latest czar had indeed
waved his hand. After his program was canceled, Dorenko desperately
tried to reach the president but could not get through, and no one
called him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no answer,'' he said. ``Which is why I think that it
was a serious answer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 1030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000923.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8771 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-GORE-MILITARY-REVIEW-     09-23 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-MILITARY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GRUNT AS PRESIDENT? HISTORY SALUTES A FEW GOOD MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Much has been made in the presidential campaign
about Vice President Al Gore's stint with the Army in Vietnam, but
one striking fact has gone largely unnoted: If elected, Gore would
be the first president in a century to have served as an enlisted
man and one of only four ever.
</P>
<P>
   The presidency, of course, has been replete with men who served
their country in uniform _ 27 of the 42 presidents _ but the
overwhelming majority did so in the officer corps.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 12 generals (Washington, Jackson, Harrison,
Taylor, Pierce, Andrew Johnson, Grant, Hayes, Garfield, Arthur,
Harrison and Eisenhower), though no admirals. And there has been a
colonel (Theodore Roosevelt), a commander (Lyndon B. Johnson) and a
lieutenant commander (Ford), a major (Truman), a captain (Reagan)
and three lieutenants (Kennedy, Nixon and Bush).
</P>
<P>
   But not since William McKinley, who was president from 1897
until his assassination in 1901, has there been a president who
served in the humbler ranks.
</P>
<P>
   McKinley enlisted as a private in the 23rd Regiment of the Ohio
Volunteer Infantry during the Civil War. (He went on to receive a
battlefield promotion to lieutenant after the Battle of Antietam
from a colonel who went on to become a general and a president,
Rutherford B. Hayes.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to McKinley, only two other presidents had served in
the enlisted ranks, according to several presidential reference
books.
</P>
<P>
   James Buchanan served in a company of dragoons _ essentially
cavalrymen _ in the defense of Baltimore during the War of 1812.
And Abraham Lincoln volunteered as a private when the Illinois
militia mobilized to fight in the Black Hawk wars in 1832. His
company promptly elected him captain, but when that unit stood
down, he re-enlisted as a private.
</P>
<P>
   As for Gore, in August 1969, he walked into a draft center in
Newark, N.J. and enlisted as a private. And a private he remained
through basic training at Fort Dix, a tour at Fort Rucker and five
months as an Army journalist in Vietnam. (He was granted an early
discharge to attend divinity school.)
</P>
<P>
   Gore, of course, was no ordinary buck private. His father was a
senator, and GIs like him were on what one Army general and Vietnam
veteran called ``a watch list,'' a sort of unwritten order to keep
them out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Charles C. Moskos, a sociologist at Northwestern University who
has long studied the military, said that the dearth of enlistees
among the presidents reflected the social and economic backgrounds
of the nation's politicians and officers, who with few exceptions
were of the educated elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical military experience is to be an enlisted man,'' he
said. ``It has not been shared by our presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign has made the most of his military record, which
starkly contrasts to the lack of service by President Clinton, but
it remains to be seen how much it will help him on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   His opponent, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, scores higher in the
polls on military matters, and in recent years people in uniform,
particularly in the officer corps, have tilted increasingly toward
the Republican Party. The tradition in which the majority usually
considered themselves independent is weakening, a trend that has
raised concerns about the increasing politicization of the
military.
</P>
<P>
   A survey last year of up and coming officers found that 64
percent identified themselves as Republicans, compared to only 8
percent who were Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   As if to underscore the point, an array of veterans, including
senior officers who served under Clinton and Gore, last week
endorsed Bush, who served as a fighter pilot in the Texas National
Guard during the Vietnam War and was, for the record, a lieutenant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 1031EDT &QL; 
