<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8775 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-VIOLENCE-POLITICS-REV     09-23 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENCE ON THE SCREEN: UNLOVELY AND INVULNERABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This is the logic of politicians when they think
about popular culture: Many of today's films and music and
videogames are vile, not like the John Wayne movies or Elvis
records they enjoyed when they were young.
</P>
<P>
   More than 80 percent of American adults tell pollsters they
think the violence in the culture contributes to violent acts by
young people.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the evidence of a relationship between culture and
actual violence is highly uncertain, it is good politics to wax
indignant about entertainment corrupting the nation's youth.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the First Amendment makes if almost impossible to
draft a law that would place meaningful restrictions on the
entertainment. Freedom of speech is sacrosanct, and any real
crackdown on entertainment would amount to an extension of
regulation from Washington, something the Republicans especially
deplore.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the entertainment industry is a big source of campaign
money for both major parties, and especially for Democrats. As of
early August, according to the Center for Responsive Politics, a
nonpartisan watchdog group, people and companies in the industry
had donated $23.7 million to candidates and parties for this year's
federal elections, 61 percent of it to Democrats. By Election Day,
the total will doubtless be much larger.
</P>
<P>
   So what is likely to come out of Congress this year is the same
thing it has produced almost every other time the evils of popular
culture have become a political issue. Whether the entertainment in
question was peep shows (turn of the 20th century) or gangster
movies (1930s) or comic books (1950s) or disco (1970s), the result
was always a lot of hot air and no consequential legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Senate Commerce Committee approved a bill that
would prohibit the broadcast of television shows with violence in
the daytime or early evening, when children could be expected to be
watching. Under the legislation, the Federal Trade Commission would
define what was violent.
</P>
<P>
   The debate gave the senators a fine opportunity to sound off.
But it is a sure bet that the bill will never become law. Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz., the Commerce Committee chairman, explained why:
``The notion of letting five unelected bureaucrats at the
commission decide what can be broadcast and when it can be
broadcast is objectionable to most free people.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for good reason: It is impossible to prospectively define
what constitutes `violent' programming in a way that will not
prohibit the transmission of `Saving Private Ryan' or `Schindler's
List,' for example. A telecast featuring murder, suicide, gang
violence and knife fighting is violent, but does anyone want the
FTC to ban the broadcast of `Romeo and Juliet'? Parents, not
bureaucrats, should decide whether children should be exposed to
Shakespeare or even, for that matter, arguably violent cartoons
about coyotes and roadrunners.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, incidentally, voted ``present.'' If he had voted against
the bill, some political opponent someday would surely have used it
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Even if by some fluke of politics the bill were to be passed and
signed by the president, the Supreme Court would almost certainly
declare it unconstitutional. Just last May, the court struck down a
law that required cable systems to limit sexually explicit channels
to late-night hours, on the ground that the law violated the basic
principle of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, when the FTC reported that the vast majority
of adult-rated films, recordings and electronic games were being
advertised to appeal to children, Vice President Al Gore and Sen.
Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, his running mate, suggested that
if the entertainment companies did not voluntarily clean up their
act, the commission should move against the industry by using its
power to prohibit false and deceptive advertising.
</P>
<P>
   That also might not pass constitutional muster, said William Van
Alstyne, a First Amendment expert at Duke University Law School.
Van Alstyne observed, for example, that children under 17 were
allowed into R-rated movies if accompanied by an adult. So
moviemakers were on firm legal and ethical ground when they aimed
ads for movies at children in the hope that they would persuade
their parents to take them.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians are not completely powerless, however. They can
hector, threaten and badger the industry, or, to use the Yiddish
word that Lieberman used last week, ``noodge'' it into doing a
better job of policing itself.
</P>
<P>
   This has sometimes worked in the past. Arm-twisting by lawmakers
led the movie studios in the 1960s to introduce the current rating
system. While not perfect, it gives parents some idea of a film's
content and gives theaters grounds for turning children away from
inappropriate movies.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein, Lynne Cheney, whose husband is the Republican
vice presidential nominee, suggested that political pressure could
induce music companies to include written lyrics with their
recordings so parents could see what their children were listening
to.
</P>
<P>
   William Bennett, the education secretary in the Bush
administration who offers himself as a guardian of American moral
values, believes the strongest weapon politicians have is their
ability to inflict public shame. In that context, the Commerce
Committee has called executives of the large movie studios to
testify on Wednesday and say publicly what, if anything, they
intend to do to limit children's exposure to violent entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, then, self-regulation by the industry is probably
the politicians' only recourse to objectionable content. But there
may be a price to even voluntary censorship _ a diminution of the
country's artistic energy.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, the film studios adopted a voluntary code of
conduct in which they agreed not to portray gangsters (James Cagney
or Edward G. Robinson) as heroic, police officers as corrupt or
loose women (Jean Harlow) as happy _ the notion being that children
would not learn from the movies that crime pays or that there is
value in promiscuity.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, ``the movies lost some of their bite,'' said
Francis G. Couvares, an authority on movie censorship who is now
dean of freshmen at Amherst College. ``The rules blunted these
electric and dynamic characters who defied social values and
limited the capacity of some great actors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 1040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000923.0053 </DOCNO>
