<DOCNO> NYT20000923.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     09-23 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR SALT LAKE CITY CHIEF, STRESS THE GAMES, NOT THE
SCANDALS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Mass.)   (Sports of the Times) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ This is Mitt Romney's first Olympic
experience, and he is having a great time, donning an official Salt
Lake Organizing Committee outfit and joining the staff for a jog up
the Sydney Harbor Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   There is time to go to events and say, what a city, what
wonderful people, but by the way, there is no way Salt Lake City
can match Sydney in national fervor or expenditure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the headline `Our Finest Hour,''' Romney said the other
day. ``I doubt that any paper would say that in the States, even in
Salt Lake City _ maybe for D-Day or landing on the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   He is enjoying these Summer Games because they are not his. He
doesn't have to worry about escaping convicts or grass fires or bus
snarls. All he has is a lingering scandal back home and concerns
about putting on modest but uplifting Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Romney, 53, is the fresh breeze imported from back East during
revelations about the inbred burghers who bought the Games. But
first, he had to give himself an education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no notion of who Juan Antonio Samaranch was,'' Romney
said. ``I had no idea what the International Olympic Committee did.
I didn't know it was located in Lausanne. I knew nothing about the
United States Olympic Committee. The only thing I read on the
sports pages were the results.''
</P>
<P>
   He walked into an organization on the eve of destruction, but
Romney does not lack for confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I specialize in turnarounds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his work for the management consulting firm Bain &AMP; Co., he
was a leader among alpha males in nearly identical dark suits and
blue shirts and red suspenders who worked long hours and shared a
secret handshake and made tons of money. You've heard of Moonies?
These guys are called Bainies. He's not exactly a naif. He saw his
father, the late George W. Romney, run into a buzz saw when he
ventured outside Michigan to try to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my business, you don't want any free publicity,'' Mitt
Romney said. ``Politics are the exact opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   He discovered that in 1994 when he ran for the Senate against a
man with an even more familiar name. ``I learned a lot from Ted
Kennedy,'' Romney said. ``He's the master. I used to say, `Wow, are
they good.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy campaign put Romney on the defensive for his Mormon
religion, his wealth, his father, his party. What else could
anybody say about him if he ran a troubled Olympic committee?
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife talked me into it,'' Romney said, referring to Ann
Romney, who grew up in Birmingham, Mich., and attended Brigham
Young University, just as he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me, `You have exactly the background.' The more I
thought about it, I realized, we're only here for one lifetime. I
was making more money than I should have. It was time to do
something different.''
</P>
<P>
   Observing his first Olympic Games, Romney has discovered he
cannot afford what these folks are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sydney is the high water mark in investment,'' Romney said,
noting that Sydney organizers have said their budget ``was $1.5
billion, American, but I've read it was really $5.6 billion, if you
add everything in. That's not something you do in the U.S. It's
politically unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here it's national pride. For us, it's city and state. I doubt
that somebody in Vermont would feel the same way about the Games,
even the people who love winter sports.''
</P>
<P>
   He says the Salt Lake City committee has rebounded since the
dreary days of February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went a whole year without new sponsors,'' Romney said.
``The scandal sent a shudder through the country.''
</P>
<P>
   One tremor came when David D'Alessandro, the chief executive of
John Hancock Financial Services, whom Romney respected from the
opposite side of Massachusetts politics, threatened to pull out as
a major sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the fact that John Hancock was visibly critical, it sent
a signal,'' Romney said. ``David's a smart guy, a nice guy. He sent
a message. But ultimately he re-upped. It was symbolically
important. I think corporate America wants to be part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started, I was like a deer in the headlights, but we
hired good people, I knocked on doors, and now we've raised $770
million from U.S. marketing. We're clearly on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Romney concedes that damage has been done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not rebuilt excitement and enthusiasm,'' he said.
``The cloudy history has many people feeling less proud of the
Games in Salt Lake City. We let our country down the way we got the
Games.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll admit, when I took over, I asked, `Should we turn back
the Games?' My personal view is that the best way to make amends is
to replace the scandal with great Games.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the Games are going to be run with a budget that cannot
match Sydney's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be like the family that says it doesn't have
money at Christmas and is going to have to get back to the old
spirit,'' Romney said. ``There are 8,000 banners around here
costing $200 each. You multiply it, and it comes to $1.6 million.
We're going to celebrate the athlete the best way we can, but we're
going to cut way back.''
</P>
<P>
   Will his Winter Games suffer because the legal cases will still
be pending during the Games?
</P>
<P>
   ``People can distinguish between athletes and managers,'' Romney
said. ``If the managers are in trouble, so be it. They will get a
fair legal hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been legal troubles in Atlanta and Sydney. The
organizers in Nagano, Japan, burned their records, an option not
available for Mitt Romney. But right now, Sydney is bustling, and
Salt Lake City is 17 time zones and 17 months away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 1056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
