<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SCANDAL-SEEKER-NY     09-23 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-SEEKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH JOURNALIST REVELS IN UNCOVERING IOC SCANDALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Well before the International Olympic
Committee became easy to mock for its excesses and before the
investigation of the Salt Lake City bribery scandal uncovered
internal corruption, Andrew Jennings symbolized a one-man, cheeky
and obsessive opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Other reporters were critical, but through three freewheeling
books written during the past decade, Jennings, a shaggy
gray-haired British journalist in the sleeveless photographer's
vest, has made sport of detailing malfeasance within the IOC. His
reporting led to a lawsuit against him by the IOC in 1994 and a
conviction by a court in Lausanne, Switzerland, for his
``distasteful'' portrait of his constant target.
</P>
<P>
   There is little objectivity to Jennings' work; his reporting
includes heavy doses of ridicule. He is convinced that Juan Antonio
Samaranch's 20 years as IOC president have shown him to be no less
an authoritarian than he was during his service in Generalissimo
Francisco Franco's fascist government in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Franco was his mentor and Samaranch hasn't changed,'' Jennings
said. ``He learned the gift-giving culture from Franco. He did
nothing about corruption until Salt Lake, because that's what
dictators do.''
</P>
<P>
   There is great glee and passion in this stance; it makes
Jennings chortle and rant, and it shapes almost everything he says.
He is elated to leaf through his new book, ``The Great Olympic
Swindle'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster), and display newly found photographs
of Samaranch in his Franco-era togs _ ``his funny clothes,''
Jennings calls them.
</P>
<P>
   He is no less amused to turn to another photo, one of Sen. John
McCain, R-Ariz, holding his head in one hand during the vague and
unprepared testimony at a hearing last year when Anita DeFrantz, an
IOC member from the United States, said that she could not remember
the organization's budget.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Jennings is reveling in essentially being right
about the IOC. Maybe not in every detail, but Jennings' books
largely foreshadowed the revelations about corruption in the
organization that came to light when the Salt Lake City bribery
scandal erupted in late 1998 and forced the IOC into reforms that
Jennings calls drivel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're third-rate clowns,'' he said of the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   On the second floor of the All Seasons Menzies Hotel, where the
news media watched the IOC's pre-Olympic session by closed-circuit
television, Jennings was interviewed more than he worked. His
yellow cell phone rang incessantly. He chatted in a coffee shop or
while reclining on a lobby couch. His voice, filled with high
spirits and cool calculation, could be heard well above most
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salt Lake was my vindication,'' he said. ``I got interviewed
even more after the scandal first broke.''
</P>
<P>
   The bull market in Jennings' loquaciousness rose here recently
because his book _ which described the alleged organized crime
connections of Gafur Rakhimov, an international boxing official
from Uzbekistan _ came out several months before the Australian
government decided this month to bar Rakhimov from entering the
country because of national security concerns. Rakhimov has denied
any links to organized crime, and Samaranch pressed the Australians
to allow Rakhimov to attend the Games, but the government stood by
its decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine my happiness when The Australian commissioned me to
write an article about it,'' he said, referring to a newspaper.
``And they gave a freelancer a front-page byline with a picture!''
</P>
<P>
   More controversy occurred when the makers of a German
documentary about the IOC's recovery from the Salt Lake City
scandal received unprecedented access. Franklin Servan-Schreiber,
an IOC spokesman, wore a miniature microphone that picked up an
embarrassing exchange involving Kevan Gosper, Australia's IOC vice
president. What Servan-Schreiber did not know was that Jennings was
hired to write the documentary. Jennings added the revelations
about Rakhimov, whose dossiers from the FBI and British and Russian
authorities are posted on Jennings' Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor Franklin,'' Jennings said, with little sympathy. ``I
didn't film it, but I played a significant role.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings is usually outraged and frequently outrageous. One
evening the week before the Games opened, he stood in the back of a
news conference held by Francois Carrard, the IOC's
director-general, and fired a question about Mohamad Hasan, the
IOC's Indonesian member being held on charges of financial
corruption by his government. Samaranch tried to persuade the
Indonesian attorney general to free Hasan, but was rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings shouted his question about Hasan, his familiar voice
creating a knowing murmur from other reporters, something he
prefers to think is borne of anticipation, not contempt for his
clamorous presence. ``A lot of us would be keen to hear how a man
so patently evil, a man detained for so much venality, is on the
IOC,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``An interesting question, Mr. Jennings,'' said Carrard, who
would probably not respond to a Jennings query about the weather.
``Next question, please?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Jennings was not going to get the answer he wanted.
He knows that his presence can be entertaining, but likes to
believe that the core of his question informs ``the boys and
girls'' of the news media, even if the response does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only ask the question to set the answer against the
truth,'' he said. ``Their only answer about Hasan is not to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Pound, who, along with Jacques Rogge, is considered a
leading candidate to become IOC president next year after Samaranch
retires, said Jennings ``writes well, but it's so unbalanced that
it eventually becomes white noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings' running theme, Pound added, ``is that every member of
the IOC is a raging crook.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound and Samaranch may be heartened by Jennings' insistence
that he has done all he can and will soon depart the IOC beat.
``I've said what I had to say,'' Jennings said. Asked what he
gained from his decade of informed scorn about the organization,
Jennings cited something he claimed Seymour Hersh, the well-known
investigative reporter, has told young reporters about the rewards
of detailing the My Lai massacre in South Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wealth! Power! Fame! Glory!'' Jennings said, his voice rising,
his face beaming.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
