<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Sept. 24, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A foot of snow fell in parts of Wyoming on Saturday as a jet
stream disturbance combined with chilly air from Canada to bring
the season's first heavy snow to the Rockies. Sunday, the
disturbance will reach the Plains, causing a cool rain in Kansas
and Oklahoma. Snow is likely early Sunday in parts of eastern
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Humid air streaming north from the Gulf of Mexico will fuel
thunderstorms from Central Texas to the lower Mississippi and
Tennessee valleys. A few of the storms will be severe with damaging
winds and hail.
</P>
<P>
   Partial sunshine and warm weather will cover the Eastern
seaboard, though a brief afternoon shower may occur in the
Northeast as a cool front approaches from the West.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, cloudy and cool weather will cover the Great Lakes
while the West Coast stays dry and warm.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: MAXI TORNADO
</P>
<P>
   A damage survey in the aftermath of the deadly tornado which
struck Xenia, Ohio, on Wednesday indicated that the twister briefly
produced winds over 200 mph. This ranked the twister an RF4S on the
Fujita Scale, with winds estimated at 207 to 260 mph. Such ``maxi''
tornadoes, which include the most powerful F5 twisters, account for
only 1 percent to 2 percent of the nearly 1,000 tornadoes that
occur each year in the United States. Maxi tornadoes that strike
highly populated areas are even less common. Yet they account for
approximately two-thirds of all twister-related deaths. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
