<HEADER>
A8792 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FRANCE-PRESIDENT-390&AMP;     09-23 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-PRESIDENT-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORTER TERM FOR PRESIDENT? THE FRENCH SAY HO HUM. 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE DALEY   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ At a rally for his own local party leaders last week,
France's Socialist prime minister, Lionel Jospin, tried to whip up
some enthusiasm for the referendum France is holding on Sunday to
decide whether to cut the president's term from seven to five
years.
</P>
<P>
   A ``yes'' vote would institute the most radical constitutional
reform in decades. Some say the measure _ though only a
sentence-long amendment to the constitution _ would be tantamount
to creating France's Sixth Republic.
</P>
<P>
   But inside a small theater in Paris where Jospin waited to
speak, the atmosphere was hardly electric. The prime minister took
his turn at the podium after five other party officials, who read
off their arguments for the change much as if they were making a
presentation in front of their social studies teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin argued that the shorter term would likely eliminate
France's awkward periods of cohabitation like the one France is
experiencing now, where the president and the prime minister belong
to different parties. This has happened three times in the last 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   A five-year term would also keep the president on his toes,
Jospin said. ``Let him come more often before the French people,''
he said. ``It is a way of making sure he is responsible to them.''
But he acknowledged that the vast majority of French citizens were
unlikely to bother to go to the polls this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, you could scour Paris for a poster on the issue and
not find one, or flip television channels for hours and not hear a
word about the vote. The one newspaper that did bother earlier this
month to print two full pages of interviews with voters indicated
that most felt that the referendum was either too complicated or
too boring to bother with.
</P>
<P>
   The low turnout is expected to help the ``no'' vote. But experts
still believe that the measure will pass. Surveys suggest that the
French _ though unmotivated by the referendum _ are overwhelmingly
in favor of shortening the presidency, bringing it into line with
other presidential terms in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that the issue lacks the excitement of a
good political battle. On this issue, Jospin and his archrival,
France's Gaullist president, Jacques Chirac, are awkward
bedfellows. And unsure who will get credit for victory, neither has
campaigned much or loosed party purse strings for advertising.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jospin's speech on Tuesday to party officials who are supposed
to bring in the vote was the prime minister's first and only
scheduled effort in support of the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac is hardly doing better. Since he dropped his longstanding
opposition to the idea and proposed the five-year term last June,
he has campaigned for the vote on fewer than a half-dozen
occasions. Earlier this month, for instance, he went to a Paris
suburb and parried with school children.
</P>
<P>
   One young boy asked if seven years did not give a president more
time to think things through. ``If five years isn't enough,''
Chirac answered, ``then you were not born for the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Chirac was actually making one of his rare appearances to
promote his view when news broke on Thursday that a former aide who
died last year had made a confession on videotape accusing the
president of taking kickbacks in the 1980s. But whether the images
of the former fund-raiser detailing how he ran a slush fund under
Chirac's instructions will affect Sunday's vote remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe it may prod voters to go to to the polls
to increase the accountability of their president, but others think
that France's already cynical voters may stay away to register
their disgust.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone who has run for the presidency since Charles de
Gaulle left politics in 1969 has promised to cut the presidential
term. But once ensconced in the Elysee Palace, the winners have all
let the matter gather dust. The former president, Francois
Mitterrand, called the seven-year terms ``an ongoing coup d'etat''
when he was running for office. Then, he served two of them.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac had always opposed the five-year term until June when he
abruptly changed his mind. But political analysts see a clever
political end run by Chirac, who is 68 years old. He plainly
intends to run again in 2002 and is likely to face a tough battle
from Jospin, 63, who though currently suffering in the polls
because of recent fuel protests has generally won extraordinarily
high approval ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current rules of the game, Chirac would be 77 at the
end of another term, which might put some voters off. By reducing
the president's term to five years, Chirac could help eliminate the
issue of his age in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin, however, found himself with little room to maneuver.
Having called for the change for years, he could hardly try to
block the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
