<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Sept. 24:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-ELECTION (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ The people of Yugoslavia
will vote on Sunday in what everyone agrees is a watershed election
for the future of President Slobodan Milosevic, who trails his main
challenger, Vojislav Kostunica, in the opinion polls. But no one
knows how Milosevic and his government will react to the vote, or
how the people of Yugoslavia will respond to that reaction. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-KOSOVO (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ With its Serb population
largely departed, and an Albanian population refusing to take part
in Sunday's Yugoslav elections, Kosovo would seem unimportant in
the overall battle for votes. Yet, in one of the ironies in which
the Balkans abound, the one part of Yugoslavia that the West
controls may supply the swing that brings victory for the incumbent
Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-REFERENDUM (Paris) _ At a rally for his own local party
leaders, France's Socialist prime minister, Lionel Jospin, tried to
whip up some enthusiasm for the referendum France is holding on
Sunday to decide whether to cut the president's term from seven to
five years. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CAVIAR (Astrakhan, Russia) _ Along the shores of the
Caspian, the world's largest inland sea, competition for resources
threatens extinction of the last great sturgeon population on
earth. After a century of supplying the world with caviar, which
today fetches as much as $2,000 a pound in Geneva, Paris and New
York, the Caspian sturgeon population, 70 percent of the world's
reserves, is being harvested at a rate that can be sustained for
only a few more years, experts and law enforcement officials say.
By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CZECH-REACTOR (Temelin, Czech Republic) _ The four cooling
towers of the Soviet-designed nuclear power station Temelin
overlook the rolling hills of the southern Czech Republic like a
gigantic castle. But for the majority of Austrians, whose country
begins just 40 miles away, this castle is haunted. As the Czech
authorities make final preparations to switch on Temelin's first
reactor, fiercely antinuclear Austria has intensified its threats
to block the Czech Republic's effort to join the European Union. By
Ladka Bauerova.
</P>
<P>
   ANGOLA-OIL (Aboard the Pride Angola, off Ambriz, Angola) _ Next
year Angola hopes to pump a million barrels of oil daily from the
ocean floor. By 2010 rigs like this one may export more crude than
Kuwait. But if the gods rained gold on Angola, the wealth has been
largely consumed by the government and its war machine, fueling
what has become the continent's longest-running civil conflict. By
Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-FUJIMORI (Lima, Peru) _ Hoping to blunt the crisis that
threatens to drive him from office, President Alberto Fujimori has
promised to dismantle the powerful National Intelligence Service.
But the spy agency has so thoroughly penetrated Peruvian government
and society, experts and diplomats say, that a complete purge of
the state's security system will be difficult to carry out, even if
Fujimori really means what he says. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CHRISTIANS (Beijing) _ Leaders of the official Protestant
church defended China's policies on religious freedom this week,
asserting that a record 15 million Chinese now worship in approved
Protestant churches and that persecution of so-called underground
Christians is rare. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-SUPERTRAINS (Kofu, Japan) _ Many of Japan's ``bullet
train'' lines, already among the world's fastest, have been losing
money for years. And yet money seemed like an annoying afterthought
in a demonstration that made it clear that this nation's eager
railroad developers are determined to push a new generation of
ultra-high-technology trains capable of traveling almost twice as
fast as today's best. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON-SMOG (Houston) _ For decades, the stench of the nearby
refineries never seemed to concern city leaders here. The hot
summer breezes often carried a brown haze over the downtown skyline
and, with it, an odor that the business elite regarded as the sweet
smell of money. ``Smell that,'' went a popular local refrain during
the 1960s. ``That's prosperity.'' But no one is bragging about the
city's bad air anymore. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   NH-IMPEACHMENT (Concord, N.H.) _ These are humbling days for the
highest court in New Hampshire, as the impeachment trial of the
court's chief justice puts it on display on live public television,
its justices stripped of their robes, baring their feelings and
foibles for all the state to see. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD-CHILDREN (Los Angeles) _ As the second round of Senate
hearings approaches on Wednesday over a Federal Trade Commission
report critical of the way some R-rated movies have been marketed
to children, the Hollywood studios are in the throes of deciding
what exactly they are going to say and how the movie industry can
repair any damage that the report might have caused. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BIO-BALLPARK (Arlington, Texas) _ For those who mock George
W. Bush as a daddy's boy who slouched through life reaping the
dividends of his name, the lovely Texas Rangers baseball stadium
here is a useful rebuttal. Yet a close look suggests that Bush got
the opportunity to be a baseball owner mostly because of his
connections. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FLA (Miami) _ A look at the race in Florida. By Richard
L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BOGEYMEN (Undated) _ They are bad. Really bad. And they are
big. Big and bad, like those nightmarish, saw-toothed meanies that
lurk beneath the bed. They are Vice President Al Gore's bogeymen _
big oil, big drug companies, big health insurers, big polluters.
They are out there, threatening America's prosperity. And like
politicians before him, Gore hopes to ride the public's trepidation
about them all the way to the White House. A political memo. By
Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   NADER-CAMPAIGN (Minneapolis) _ Ralph Nader, the Green Party
candidate for president, is getting plenty of star treatment these
days. Though he has been locked out of the presidential debates,
struggling for media attention and fading in many polls, he has
managed to attract huge and adoring crowds in the college towns and
union strongholds he has visited in recent weeks. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Democrats gain hope in Pennsylvania
race; Afoul of the law with emery boards; Choosing a legend, of the
opposing party; Passing the buck, in a fashion. By B. Drummond
Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN-HEALTHCARE (Washington) _ Forty states will soon lose
hundreds of millions of dollars of federal money that was supposed
to provide health insurance to children in low-income families,
federal and state officials say. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-RESERVES (Washington) _ Although the Clinton administration
has emphasized dwindling stocks of home heating oil as the main
reason to temporarily release 30 million barrels of crude oil from
the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, the effects on consumers are
likely to spread far beyond the small fraction of homes that are
actually heated with that fuel. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   WWII-MONUMENT (Washington) _ ``It has taken twice as long to
build this monument than it took to fight the war,'' Rep. Marcy
Kaptur said the other day as the National Capital Planning
Commission prepared to approve the National World War II Memorial,
which would be built on the Washington Mall. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
