<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8809 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NH-COURT-IMPEACH-NYT &LR;      09-23 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-COURT-IMPEACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMBLING DAYS FOR NEW HAMPSHIRE'S SUPREME COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAREY GOLDBERG   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ The court clerk choked up as he recalled his
agony of conscience. One justice called the last six months a
nightmare. Another said the court was made up of five prima donnas.
And Thursday, a former justice who resigned amid scandal discussed
the humiliation of his publicly torturous divorce.
</P>
<P>
   These are humbling days for the highest court in New Hampshire,
as the impeachment trial of the court's chief justice puts it on
display on live public television, its justices stripped of their
robes, baring their feelings and foibles for all the state to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't just about words, it's about human beings, and the
ambiguity that comes with everyone just trying to make their way
through life, and trying to remember what did they say, and what
did they do, and why did they do it?'' said Albert E. Scherr,
associate dean of the Franklin Pierce Law Center here. ``It's
almost operatic in the story lines that are playing out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Drama aside, legal authorities like Dean Scherr say the trial,
which has lasted a week and is expected to continue at least
another week, also carries broad legal and political significance.
In particular, it highlights the tension in many states, some say,
between the need to keep the courts safely removed from political
meddling and the need to keep a strong check on a court's power
when it steps out of line.
</P>
<P>
   Where this trial fits in that picture is open to interpretation:
Some New Hampshire observers see the Legislature's impeachment of
Chief Justice David Brock as payback for politically unpopular
decisions that the Supreme Court has made, particularly one that
revamped the state's system for paying for schools. Others see the
trial as a necessary housecleaning by lawmakers of a judicial
system that got too chummy with old-boy connections and too sloppy
with ethical practices.
</P>
<P>
   What is undisputable is that the trial is lifting the curtain
behind which the court operates, revealing it in all its complex
dynamics, including the isolation some justices say they feel in
their legal seclusion where the phone rarely rings, the feeling of
family they develop together and the tensions that arise around
disputes over law and proper behavior.
</P>
<P>
   When Justice John T. Broderick Jr. decided that he had to report
a colleague in an ethical violation, ``It was like a death in the
family, that's what it felt like,'' he said last week.
</P>
<P>
   It was that ethical violation that ultimately led to the current
trial: Justice W. Stephen Thayer III, who has since resigned and
been given immunity in the case by prosecutors, was in the middle
of a divorce. His wife, Judith, former chairwoman of the state
board of education, was appealing a decision in the case. Thayer's
colleagues all recused themselves from hearing it. So other judges
were needed to serve on a special panel for the Thayer divorce.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 4, according to a report by the state attorney general
and recent testimony, Thayer explosively objected to the choice of
a particular judge for that panel. In response, Brock tried to
prevent the court clerk, Howard Zibel, from calling that judge but
was too late.
</P>
<P>
   It had been known for months that Zibel had acted as a critical
whistleblower by reporting the incident in a memo to a judicial
watchdog panel; what had not been quite clear until he testified
last week was just how badly Zibel had agonized before doing so.
</P>
<P>
   He kept thinking, Zibel said, about a colleague's recent talk
describing how court clerks had handled the transport orders for
the Jewish children of Vichy France in World War II; he had lost
his great-grandparents in the Holocaust, he said, and while he was
not equating the ethical dilemma of the Vichy court clerks to his
own, still, ``I think all of that has a bearing on why I couldn't
sleep that night,'' he testified.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, he said, was that ``my obligation was to report
unprofessional conduct, and this crossed a line I couldn't abide.''
</P>
<P>
   Broderick, who also reported Thayer, described sleeplessness of
his own, and agonizing through ``a week I would not want to
relive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the choice I would make, and the court would make,
would be to ultimately end a person's professional life at age
54,'' he said, referring to Thayer. ``I would pass that cross to
anyone in this room. I didn't want it. He was my friend. He was my
colleague.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Brock, 64, stands accused on four articles of
impeachment: of making a phone call to a Superior Court judge 13
years ago seeking to influence a case; of allowing Thayer to
influence the appointment of judges in his own case; of allowing
judges to comment on cases from which they had recused themselves,
and of repeatedly lying under oath. He denies lying or seeking
undue influence, and says that while he has made mistakes, nothing
rises to the level of an impeachable crime. The court's recusal
policy has been overhauled since the case began, as has the state's
procedure for appointing justices.
</P>
<P>
   Thayer and other justices also testified that though they
sometimes commented on cases that they had recused themselves from,
they never saw a justice try to change the outcome of a case in his
own interest.
</P>
<P>
   Brock is expected to take the stand in his defense, and has been
attending every day, a snowy-haired, ruddy-faced figure accompanied
by his wife and sometimes some of their six children. Several
colleagues have said that one of Brock's daughters had been found
to have cancer just before the Thayer incident, and he could well
have been distracted and under unusual stress.
</P>
<P>
   Every justice to speak has praised Brock; Justice Sherman Horton
said that though ``the court consists of five prima donnas and
they've all got their own ideas,'' Brock ``does an excellent job of
moving the ball forward with five prima donnas, and I don't think I
could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the trial is no easy call, legal observers say.
Though some New Hampshire state representatives who backed
impeachment said they expected that their charges would not
withstand the state Senate trial, no one is confidently predicting
the verdict. The 22 senators who are hearing the case are keeping
their views to themselves, though some do sometimes betray a slight
predilection toward speeding the trial, which is inconveniently
scheduled just as campaigns are heating up.
</P>
<P>
   Broderick may have offered the saddest assessment of the
situation: ``There are no winners here. I feel badly for Justice
Thayer, for the Supreme Court of New Hampshire, for the time,
effort and money that's gone into this whole process.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
