<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8821 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-OIL24-COX     09-23 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OIL COMES GUSHING BACK AS A NATIONAL PRIORITY
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For most of the past decade, the politics and
geopolitics of oil have bubbled quietly beneath the surface of
American life, as low-cost crude fueled an unprecedented economic
boom.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, like a long-dormant well tapped by an errant drill,
oil has come gushing back as a powerful influence on the country's
economy, diplomacy and politics.
</P>
<P>
   As crude oil supplies have tightened, sending prices to their
highest level in a decade, election-year politics has merged with
consumer anxiety and international gamesmanship to create, for
policy makers, something like a perfect storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have front-page energy news for the rest of the
year,'' said Dale Steffes, executive director of the Houston Energy
Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   It was Vice President Al Gore who sent the topic vaulting from
the business section to the front page last week, when he publicly
pressed President Clinton to tap the nation's Strategic Petroleum
Reserve to help head off high prices for home heating oil in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ordered the October release of 30 million barrels from
the reserve. That's nearly twice as much as President Bush released
during the 1991 Persian Gulf war, the only other major drawdown in
the reserve's 26-year history.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the reserve is to be used to address severe supply
shortages, not as a tool for governing prices, and Gore's
presidential opponent, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, cried foul.
</P>
<P>
   The reserve ``is meant for a national emergency, a national war,
a major disruption of supply,'' Bush said Friday in Florida. ``The
Strategic Petroleum Reserve should not be used as a short-term
political fix for somebody whose administration has been asleep at
the switch.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his fellow Democrats, though, see the move as a
political triple play.
</P>
<P>
   First, it appeals to consumers in New York, where First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton is running for a U.S. Senate seat, and
elsewhere across the Northeast, where 75 percent of the nation's
heating oil consumption is concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   Second, it gives Democrats a claim to victory if oil prices
slide downward between now and election day, and political cover
should costs move upward. On Friday, crude oil for November
deliveries fell $1.32 a barrel to $32.68 on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, down about $4 a barrel from its peak last week.
</P>
<P>
   Third and perhaps most important, Gore placed the perennial
bogeyman of imported oil _ now nearly 60 percent of the oil the
country consumes _ at the center of the presidential campaign. Gore
has sought to portray Bush and running mate Dick Cheney, both
former executives in the oil business, as the ticket of large
petroleum conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the big factors involved here is whether or not
we're going to have a president who is willing to fight for people,
willing to stand up to big oil and foreign oil,'' Gore told
reporters traveling with him Friday in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1980, when President Carter portrayed the Republicans
as a party whose ``policy was dictated by the big oil companies''
as he accepted the Democratic nomination for re-election, has the
issue been given so much prominence in a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Voters replaced Carter with GOP rival Ronald Reagan that year,
and Carter's projections of an enduring energy crisis fed by
ever-spiraling oil prices faded as the cost of crude abated.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan's own successor, President Bush, sent half a million
American troops and allies to the Persian Gulf a decade later to
evict Iraqi invaders from neighboring Kuwait, a move that ushered
in 10 years of cheap oil _ and along with it, the spectacular
American growth largely credited to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Only now, in the fading months of his presidency, has Clinton
been forced to confront the prospect of a serious hike in oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
   The subject was on the front burner two weeks ago when Clinton
journeyed to the United Nations for a summit of leaders from around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   There, Clinton and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright spent
much of their time meeting privately with officials from Saudi
Arabia, the world's largest oil-producing state. Clinton pressed
for production hikes aimed at trimming crude prices below the
$28-a-barrel ceiling agreed to earlier this year by members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Saudis later agreed to pump an additional 800,000 barrels a
day into world markets.
</P>
<P>
   As OPEC oil ministers gather this week in Venezuela, the Clinton
administration intends to keep pressing for further output hikes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers is spending this
weekend meeting with his counterparts from the other wealthy
industrialized countries that make up the Group of Seven, in hopes
of uniting the G-7 behind that message on the eve of the OPEC
talks.
</P>
<P>
   The wild card for OPEC, though, could well be Iraq. Ever since
his defeat in the Gulf war, Iraqi President Saddam Hussein has been
bridling under U.N.-imposed sanctions that limit his oil exports to
2.3 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam could find this a useful time to put the shoe on the
other foot, cutting his output to further tighten global crude
supplies and ratchet prices upward.
</P>
<P>
   That ploy could only work if Saddam's OPEC partners _ the
U.S.-backed Saudis chief among them _ agree not to undercut him by
opening their own spigots to make up for his cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is hoping that the memory of U.S. action in the Gulf
war, when Iraq threatened Saudi oil fields, will weigh heavily in
the decisions that Gulf states make at the OPEC meeting in
Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   In a rich historical irony, Gore's hopes for election now partly
rest on the central legacy of Bush's father: U.S. victory in the
Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
