<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-WWII-MEMORIAL-NYT &LR;      09-23 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-MEMORIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANS FOR A WORLD WAR II MEMORIAL LURCH TOWARD APPROVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``It has taken twice as long to build this monument
than it took to fight the war,'' said Rep. Marcy Kaptur, D-Ohio,
the other day as the National Capital Planning Commission prepared
to approve the National World War II Memorial, which would be built
on the Washington Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Kaptur introduced the bill to build the memorial 13 years ago
and, with approval from Congress, presidents and commissions, most
of the hurdles had been crossed.
</P>
<P>
   It should be built, she said, before all of the war's veterans
have died.
</P>
<P>
   After a public hearing in which 100 people spoke for and against
the monument, the commission on Thursday approved it, 7-5, a
surprisingly close vote.
</P>
<P>
   The final approval is expected soon from Interior Secretary
Bruce Babbitt. His approval would set the stage for a
groundbreaking presided over by President Clinton on Veterans Day,
Nov. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., the 1996 Republican presidential
nominee, spoke in his role as chairman of the campaign to build the
memorial, urging the commission to approve the monument to the
400,000 Americans killed in World War II and the 800,000 disabled.
``I think they would agree that this is an appropriate site,'' Dole
said.
</P>
<P>
   The site is between the Washington Monument and the Lincoln
Memorial, which proponents find appropriate because it links World
War II with the heroes of the Revolutionary War and the Civil War.
Opponents say it will clutter the Mall, obstructing the views of
both memorials.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Kramer, who said that he went ashore at Utah Beach on D-Day,
told the commission, ``I am 78 years old, and I would like to see
this memorial built in my lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   He was followed by Virgil M. Davis, who said he was at Pearl
Harbor on Dec. 7, 1941, and opposed the memorial. ``My message is
to keep the Mall clear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents have vowed to go to court to try to block the
monument, which organizers hope will open in 2003. One of the
opponents, Judy Scott Feldman, co-chairwoman of the National
Coalition to Save Our Mall, said that approval was illegal because
the monument would replace the Mall's Rainbow Pool, which she said
was part of the Lincoln Memorial and therefore protected by
existing law.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial, which was designed by Friedrich St. Florian, is
expected to cost $100 million. The Rainbow Pool is to be replaced
by a slightly larger oval pool flanked by two semicircles of 56
pillars and two arches. A wall on the Lincoln Memorial side would
display 400 gold-colored stars, each one representing 1,000
Americans who died in the war.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign that Dole leads has already raised almost all of
its $140 million goal, which includes the monument's cost plus
fund-raising and administrative expenses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
