<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-HEALTHCARE-845(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
40 STATES FORFEIT U.S. AID FOR POOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The 10 states that will not forfeit federal aid are listed in
the 14th graf, beginning ``The states that have ...'') 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Forty states will soon lose hundreds of millions of
dollars of federal money that was supposed to provide health
insurance to children in low-income families, federal and state
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The money _ 45 percent of the $4.2 billion provided by Congress
_ remains unspent by the states after three years. It will be given
to the 10 states that used their full allotments of federal money
under the Children's Health Insurance Program, which was created by
Congress, with much enthusiasm and fanfare, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to be able to keep that money and use it to
provide health care to children,'' said Helene Robinson, director
of the state program in Louisiana, which expects to lose $63.7
million, or 63 percent of its federal allotment of $101.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   California and Texas account for more than half of the unspent
money _ $590 million and $446.3 million, respectively. Together
they have 29 percent of the nation's 11 million uninsured children.
</P>
<P>
   Health care for children has become a major issue in the
presidential campaign. Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic
nominee, says that Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican candidate,
has a dismal record of providing health insurance to children in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush rejects the criticism. Texas officials say 100,000 children
have enrolled in the new program since they began taking
applications in April.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bartlett, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, said Gore
``should address the problems on his own watch.'' Bartlett said
that the number of uninsured children nationwide had increased
since the Clinton administration took office, and Census Bureau
reports show that the 11-million figure is up from 9.6 million in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   States have until Sept. 30 to spend the money they were
allotted. In interviews with The New York Times, officials in 20
states gave these reasons for failing to use their full allotments:
</P>
<P>
   _ Some states took a year or more to start enrolling children.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some were reluctant to put up the state money they had to
spend to obtain the full amount of federal money available.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some states said they could not find enough eligible uninsured
children to use all their federal money.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some states inadvertently deterred enrollment by using complex
application forms and procedures.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some states complained that the federal government had
administered the program in a rigid, inflexible way that prevented
them from spending the money for children who might have benefited.
</P>
<P>
   The states that have used all of their 1998 allotments are
Alaska, Indiana, Kentucky, Maine, Massachusetts, Missouri, New
York, North Carolina, Pennsylvania and South Carolina. Those states
will have one year to spend the extra money, which reverts to the
Treasury after Sept. 30, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Defense Fund, an advocacy group, celebrated
creation of the program as a landmark in social policy. But Gregg
Haifley, deputy director of the fund's health division, said the
group was now telling states: ``Get off the dime. Spend this money
on what it's intended for. Don't let it just pile up or trickle
through your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Health Insurance Program is meant to help
children in families with too much income to qualify for Medicaid
and too little to afford private insurance. State officials said
the program had done immense good, by providing care to over 2
million children while also stimulating improvements in Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   But spending has lagged behind expectations. Donna Shalala, the
secretary of health and human services, said, ``A significant
portion of the allotments will be unspent.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado illustrates the experience of many states. It has spent
$22.7 million of its 1998 allotment of $41.8 million and expects to
lose the remaining $19.1 million, or 46 percent of its allocation.
</P>
<P>
   William N. Lindsay, president of the Child Health Policy Board
in Colorado, which supervises the program, said: ``If we enrolled
every single eligible child in Colorado, we still couldn't spend
our full allocation of federal money. Our economy is doing so well,
there are fewer eligible kids than what was estimated when the
federal government did its initial allocation of money.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Lindsay said, state spending is limited by
provisions of the Colorado constitution. To draw the full amount of
federal money, he said, ``state legislators would have to make
conscious decisions to shift resources to health care from other
areas like public education, and so far they have been unwilling to
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress provided a total of $40 billion over 10 years. States
had three years _ from Oct. 1, 1997, to Sept. 30, 2000 _ to use the
first year's installment of $4.2 billion. State and federal
officials said that $1.9 billion of that amount would be unspent at
the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   Frank C. Ullman, a health policy expert at the Urban Institute
here, said, ``It is likely that even fewer states will exhaust
their 1999 allotments,'' which remain available through September
2001.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   New York has the biggest child health program in the country. It
has used all of its federal money for 1998 and 1999 and much of its
allotment for 2000. Enrollment in New York has reached 550,000,
about one-fourth of the national total, and is growing by more than
15,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut has spent $25.5 million of its $35 million
allocation and expects to lose $9.5 million, or 27 percent of its
money.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, Edward J. Rogan, a spokesman for the Department
of Human Services, said the state had spent $78.4 million of the
$88.4 million available from the federal government.
``Unfortunately,'' Rogan said, ``that leaves a balance of $10
million. We would like to have spent the entire allotment.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government pays from 65 percent to 84 percent of the
costs of state programs to insure low-income children.
</P>
<P>
   In Louisiana, state Sen. Donald Hines, a Democrat who is also a
family physician, said: ``We were not able to take advantage of
some of the federal money, because we had difficulty coming up with
the state matching money. We had a shortfall in our budget in the
last two years. This year we made cuts in the health and hospitals
budget. I don't think we needed the entire amount of federal money
anyhow.''
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico said it would use just $5.1 million of its $62.9
million allotment, leaving $57.8 million, or 92 percent, unspent.
</P>
<P>
   J. Barry Bitzer, deputy secretary of the Human Services
Department in New Mexico, said: ``The federal law and regulations
provided New Mexico with a lot more money than we could possibly
use. We have 30,000 uninsured kids, of whom no more than 1,000 are
eligible for the new program.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida has spent $201 million of its 1998 allotment of $270
million, leaving $69 million, or 26 percent, unused.
</P>
<P>
   Justin J. Sayfie, a spokesman for Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida,
said: ``There was a lag in getting the program up and running. The
Florida Legislature didn't meet until March 1998, and Florida
started implementing the program in October 1998. We were one year
behind the curve.''
</P>
<P>
   Illinois has used $55 million of its allotment of $122.5
million, leaving $67.5 million, or 55 percent, unspent.
</P>
<P>
   Eric P. Robinson, a spokesman for the Illinois Department of
Public Aid, said: ``We are aggressively reaching out to enroll
children, but it's unrealistic to think we could have used $122
million in three years. We can't just flip a switch and achieve
full enrollment.''
</P>
<P>
   California, with an allotment of $854 million, expects to lose
$590 million, or 69 percent of its federal money.
</P>
<P>
   Diana M. Bonta, director of the California Department of Health
Services, said the program got off to a slow start under Gov. Pete
Wilson, a Republican. But, she said, since Gov. Gray Davis, a
Democrat, took office in January 1999, enrollment has increased at
a brisk pace, to 330,000 from 56,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ken August, a spokesman for the California agency, said: ``The
application form was long and confusing. It's been greatly
simplified. It was 28 pages. It's now four pages. And it's
available in 11 languages.''
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire has used $4 million of its 1998 allocation of
$11.5 million, leaving $7.5 million, or 65 percent, for
redistribution to other states. Kathleen A. Dunn, a state official
who supervises the child health program in New Hampshire, said the
federal government ``allocated more money to us than we needed to
bring this program online.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Indiana found more uninsured children than
expected, and it has spent all of its allotment of $70.5 million to
cover them.
</P>
<P>
   States may not use the new federal money to cover children
eligible for Medicaid. This has created problems for states like
Minnesota and Washington, which expanded Medicaid eligibility
before 1997 and were already covering most low-income children.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota says it has spent less than $500,000 of its $28.4
million allotment. Washington state has spent $2.2 million of its
$46.7 million allocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did something progressive, but we did it too early,'' said
Mary B. Kennedy, the Medicaid director in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia, one of the poorest states in the nation, has used
$12 million of its $23.6 million, leaving $11.6 million unspent.
The state says that its new program covers 11,600 children, but
that 14,000 youngsters still have no health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's regrettable that, for whatever reason, we didn't have our
plan approved until September of 1998,'' said Dorothy V. Yeager,
acting director of the West Virginia program. ``We lost one of the
three years we had to spend the money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
