<HEADER>
A8844 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-OIL-RESERVES-NYT &LR;      09-23 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-RESERVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELEASE OF SOME RESERVE OIL WILL ACT FAST ON MANY PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Energy Secretary Bill Richardson announced the
release of oil from the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, he said seven
times in 10 minutes that the goal was to deliver more fuel to heat
homes. But in fact, almost all of the oil will be turned into other
products, and the effects of the release will be felt by consumers
whenever they fill up at a gas station, pay for an airline ticket,
or even pay the family's bill for electricity or natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 30 million barrels that the government will lend to
refineries in the next several weeks from the Strategic Petroleum
Reserve, 85 to 90 percent will be turned into products other than
home heating oil, Energy Department officials said. Fixing a
shortage of heating oil is like confronting a shortage of brisket,
they said; you have to kill the whole steer, which will also
produce hamburger and sirloin, along with leather.
</P>
<P>
   Refineries will vary the proportions slightly, depending on
market prices for products, but in general half of each barrel of
crude oil becomes gasoline, a quarter becomes heating oil or diesel
fuel (which are nearly identical) and a tenth becomes jet fuel. The
rest goes to everything from lubricating oils to asphalt to floor
wax.
</P>
<P>
   Because of futures markets, which send price signals faster than
oil can flow physically through pipelines, consumers can expect to
see prices declining fairly soon. But because the oil that will be
released must be paid back later by oil companies, prices may
rebound later, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate effect is that ``the speculators will run,'' said
Gary N. Ross, the chief executive of Energy Group, a consulting
firm in New York. People who hold contracts today that specify that
oil will be delivered to them this winter will sell some of those
contracts because more oil will be available in the winter, and as
they sell, prices will fall, he and others said. In fact, that has
already begun to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The price of crude oil for November delivery fell by $1.32 cents
a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange on Friday, closing at
$32.68. Heating oil for delivery in October fell by 4.41 cents a
gallon, to 95.48 cents.
</P>
<P>
   In pennies per gallon, it could be heating oil that sees the
greatest effect, because stocks are so low and prices so high, but
only about 10 percent of households use heating oil or kerosene as
their primary fuel, according to the Energy Department's most
recent survey, in 1997. (That is down from 22 percent in 1978.)
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton reiterated Saturday the argument that the
intervention was aimed mainly at heating oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it stands, overall heating oil inventories are more than 20
percent lower than they were last year, 50 percent lower on the
East Coast. More than 60 percent lower in New England,'' he said.
``The overriding purpose for our action is to increase supply and
help consumers make it through the cold winter.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How big will the effect be?
</P>
<P>
   Richardson and other officials refused to predict. ``The reason
we are doing this is not for price, but to deal with disruption, to
deal with the problems of extreme shortages,'' he said. ``This is
not a price issue.''
</P>
<P>
   People closer to the industry were a little less delicate.
Philip K. Verleger Jr., of Brattle Group, an economic consulting
firm based in Cambridge, Mass., said that the sudden gush of oil
onto the market would probably push the price of crude down by $5
to $7 a barrel, which comes to 10 to 15 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   In a normal winter, a typical house uses 680 gallons of home
heating oil, according to the Energy Department. The last several
winters have been considerably warmer than usual, but given normal
temperatures, a 10-to-15-cent-a-gallon price cut, would come to $70
to $100 a household, assuming that the effect lasts all the way
through the heating season.
</P>
<P>
   It might happen that way; Richardson said that in 30 days, the
administration would decide whether to release even more oil from
the reserve, which holds about 570 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
   The average car uses about 550 gallons a year; vans, pickup
trucks and sport utilities typically use about 700 gallons, the
Energy Department says. A household that owned one of each type of
vehicle would save $100 to $150 in gasoline bills over the next six
months, depending, of course, on how far and how fast they drive.
</P>
<P>
   The price of all goods transported by trucks would also be held
down, too. And because oil and gas are sometimes substituted for
each other _ in electricity generation and various other industrial
uses _ a decline in the price of one fuel would hold down the price
of the other, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The price of natural gas is up sharply in the last few months,
but the government has no natural gas reserve to tap.
</P>
<P>
   The reduced prices cannot last forever, though. The oil is not
being sold, but borrowed, and the refiners that take it will repay
in kind, plus interest, taking oil off the market to replenish the
borrowed stocks. How much interest and how long a term depends on
negotiations between the companies and the Energy Department, but
likely repayment times are next spring and fall, when demand is
lower. Some may wait until then to buy the oil needed for
repayment, but others could arrange to buy that oil immediately
with contracts on the futures exchanges for deliveries next year.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the effect may be to drive down prices now and raise
them later.
</P>
<P>
   But the prices this winter are unknowable; even after the winter
is over, the effects of the oil swap may not be clear. Ross, of the
New York consulting firm, pointed out that two hurricanes have
recently passed through the Gulf Coast and narrowly missed areas
that produce oil and gas, and that in late 1995, Hurricane Roxanne
reduced Mexican production by 50 million barrels. The plan
announced by Richardson on Friday would dampen the impact of any
such upsets, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
