<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8871 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGO-ELECTION-715&AMP;ADD     09-23 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-ELECTION-715&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTE IN YUGOSLAVIA IS REFERENDUM ON MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ The people of Yugoslavia will vote on
Sunday in what everyone agrees is a watershed election for the
future of President Slobodan Milosevic, who trails his main
challenger, Vojislav Kostunica, in the opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   But no one knows how Milosevic and his government will react to
the vote, or how the people of Yugoslavia will respond to that
reaction. And no one believes that Milosevic will suddenly
disappear on Monday morning in a cloud of steam, like some wicked
witch of the east, leaving only his shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica himself believes that Milosevic will pick from a set
of alternatives once the size of the turnout and the electoral
results are clearer. A large turnout of 5 million people would make
the election hard to steal, because Milosevic would have to come up
with nearly a million extra votes to win outright in the first
round. If no one wins 50 percent of the vote, there will be a
runoff on Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Milosevic knows what to do,'' a hoarse Kostunica
said in an interview Saturday. ``The opposition has not broken, and
my candidacy has attracted tremendous support. In these last hours
they are hesitating, and Milosevic is going from one solution to
another. Those around him cannot tell the emperor everything _ they
cannot tell the simple truth that the emperor is naked. And that is
sometimes fatal to the emperor.''
</P>
<P>
   Kostunica is confident that the regime is shaken, and that
Milosevic cannot win in the first round if the count is fair. ``But
what the exact results will be and the consequences of two sides
claiming victory is another matter,'' he said. ``We'll do our best
to avoid any sort of violence and tension, but people will be
decisive in defending their victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Reactions to an election perceived to be stolen could be
aggressive in some cities controlled by the opposition. Whatever
happens, opposition leaders believe that the political situation in
Yugoslavia has been altered permanently after 13 years of
Milosevic's rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have won, and Serbia will never be the same after this
election,'' said Zoran Djindjic, who led the opposition's campaign.
``Milosevic will never again be able to claim that he is supported
by a majority of the people. The question is how to implement this
victory. But there is a new reality, this new majority, which will
remain regardless of what happens after Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Djindjic said, up to 75 percent of Serbs voted for
politics founded in nationalist ambitions, whether promoted by
Milosevic, Vojislav Seselj of the Serbian Radical Party or Vuk
Draskovic of the Serbian Renewal Movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, a majority of Serbs support a normal
European democracy,'' Djindjic said. Kostunica is himself a
moderate nationalist, but a democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Zarko Korac, another opposition leader, said Milosevic will not
suddenly disappear. ``He's a formidable opponent and it will be a
death of a thousand cuts,'' he said. ``This election is a serious
cut, which will delegitimize him. But it's a process.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's aides say his victory is not in doubt. His campaign
has been based on appeals to patriotism, fear of the future and a
fight against an opposition he has called traitors, NATO lackeys
and ``enemies of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ljubisa Ristic, the president of the Yugoslav United Left party
of Milosevic's wife, Mirjana Markovic, says he supported new
elections within a few months of last year's NATO bombing, and that
it has been a mistake to wait. ``But there is no question that
Milosevic will win,'' Ristic said. ``Whether in the first round or
the second round, it's just a matter of prestige.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic could decide to declare victory in the first round and
wait to see how Kostunica and his supporters react; he could say he
is ahead but enter a runoff, hoping for lower turnout; he could
challenge the results in the courts, citing voter fraud, postponing
any resolution; he could have the Federal Election Commission
declare the election a fraud and order a new election later.
</P>
<P>
   That new election could coincide with early elections for the
Serbian Parliament, where real power lies here. Or he could even
say that he accepts a loss, if he in fact loses, and then maintain
power by concentrating on running Serbia.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In any event, in voting that also takes place on Sunday,
Milosevic is expected to retain control over the federal Parliament
_ aided greatly by the boycott of this election by Montenegro's
President Milo Djukanovic. In local elections, Milosevic's
coalition is expected to win back some key towns from the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic will also succeed, most experts believe, in cutting
down the power of Seselj, an increasingly ambitious coalition
partner. Milosevic may then turn again to Draskovic, who refused to
back Kostunica and whose party has lost support.
</P>
<P>
   But given the personal nature of the system here, Milosevic is
unlikely to want to show weakness, which would diminish his control
over his party, the security forces and the country. So the most
likely outcomes are a declaration of victory or a legal maneuver
that buys time.
</P>
<P>
   International reaction will also be important, especially from
Russia, which has backed Milosevic. Russia is a member of the
Contact Group on Yugoslavia, which has jointly called for a free
and fair election. A result that Moscow does not support will do
little to help Milosevic achieve the legitimacy that these early
elections are designed to provide.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign of the regime's nervousness in the last two
days, some Western journalists, especially from television
companies like NBC, Canadian Broadcasting Co. and ARD, the German
company, have been refused permission to cover the election despite
having been granted visas and have been told to leave the country.
CNN and the BBC have correspondents here, but their requests for
visas for more personnel to cover the elections have been denied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
