u p BC-GORE-BOGEYMAN-NYT &LR;      09-23 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BOGEYMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL MEMO: GORE'S CALCULATED RISK IN TAKING ON BIG BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are bad. Really bad. Malevolent even.
</P>
<P>
   And not just bad. They are big. Big and bad, like those
nightmarish, saw-toothed meanies that lurk beneath the bed.
</P>
<P>
   They are Vice President Al Gore's bogeymen _ big oil, big drug
companies, big health insurers, big polluters. For good measure,
Gore still throws in big tobacco from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   They are out there, threatening America's prosperity. And like
politicians before him, Gore hopes to ride the public's trepidation
about them all the way to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   America has a tradition of populist politics, and in most cases
the strategy has worked best when the enemy has been given a face.
For William Jennings Bryan it was the banks. For Theodore Roosevelt
it was the railroads and other ``malefactors of great wealth.''
William Howard Taft, Woodrow Wilson and Franklin D. Roosevelt
busted the trusts. John F. Kennedy took on U.S. Steel.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been decades since a politician denounced such a
broad array of corporate targets with such pointed language. For
Gore, it is all part of the broader positioning of his campaign as
``for the people,'' and the other side _ Gov. George W. Bush and
the Republicans _ as ``for the powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never hesitated,'' Gore said in Pennsylvania on Friday,
``to take on big oil or the big pharmaceutical companies or the
HMOs or whoever was operating in a way that was not in the best
interest of the middle-class families of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most campaign messages these days, Gore's assault is rooted
in extensive polling and focus-group surveys that suggest deep
public frustration with rising prices and, in the case of health
maintenance organizations, confounding red tape. Populism has
proven most effective, historians say, in times of economic
inequality, and Gore's target audience includes those who feel they
have not shared in the good times.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's tactic is not without risk. Another important
component of his message is the taking of credit for the country's
economic health, including the 22 million jobs created in the
Clinton years. By setting his sights on central industries, Gore
may create the perception that he is fighting the very businesses
that have generated those jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the risk of being branded a hypocrite. One major
industry that Gore does not group with his litany of corporate
offenders is big entertainment, which he condemns separately in
speeches for marketing violence to children even as he solicits its
executives for hefty campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Because it has been so long since any prominent politician tried
Gore's approach, it is hard to predict how it will be received,
said Alan Brinkley, a presidential historian at Columbia
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is using it very carefully, making attacks against
specific targets and not more broadly against concentrated economic
power,'' Brinkley said. ``I don't see how he could be perceived as
antibusiness given the very centrist economic policy he's promoting
and has been identified with over time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jerry Jasinowski, the president of the National Association
of Manufacturers, said that Gore had convinced the business sector,
particularly the leaders of small companies, that he is against
private enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know in an election that things are said and done that
wouldn't happen in normal times,'' Jasinowski said. ``But words
mean something, and these words are irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Gore long ago discarded any instinct to soft-pedal his
message. This week, in speeches about oil pricing on Thursday and
Friday, he pledged to ``work toward the day when we are free
forever of the dominance of big oil and foreign oil.'' Because Bush
and his running mate, Dick Cheney, both served as executives in the
oil business, Gore said the Republican ticket was ``of big oil, for
big oil and by big oil.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gore turns his sights on managed care, he laments that
doctors' decisions are being ``overruled by some bean counter'' who
``doesn't have a right to play God.'' When the target is the
prescription drug manufacturers, he describes them as having ``so
much power and so much wealth _ by all odds the most profitable
industry in America.''
</P>
<P>
   That claim is true, according to a Fortune magazine survey that
placed pharmaceutical profits in 1999 at 18.9 percent. The industry
responds that it spends a hefty portion of profits on developing
new drugs, though studies show that a larger share is devoted to
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``While this pattern of attack may be good politics for the vice
president,'' said Alan Holmer, president of the Pharmaceutical
Research and Manufacturers of America, ``it misleads the public
about the industry that continues to develop important new
medicines.''
</P>
<P>
   Oil industry officials and analysts said this week that they
were distressed by Gore's offensive because, they maintain,
domestic petroleum pricing is primarily a product of foreign
supply. Profits are up this year, but the industry was battered
last year by plummeting prices. Oil profit rates for the first half
of this year were 6.8 percent, according to Business Week, compared
with 7 percent for all United States industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is either extremely badly informed or he's being
extremely disingenuous,'' said J. Robinson West, the chairman of
Petroleum Finance Co., which provides strategic advice to oil
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, the chief strategist for the Bush campaign, said the
primary impact of Gore's ``screechy left-wing populism'' was to
stem the flow of liberal support to Ralph Nader and the Green
Party. And he pointed out that Gore's running mate, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman of Connecticut, had received heavy campaign contributions
from the insurance and pharmaceutical industries, and that Gore's
family had profited from Occidental Petroleum mineral leases.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Fabiani, Gore's deputy campaign director, said the vice
president had credibility because he fought against price-fixing in
the oil and natural-gas industry in Congress and was an early
supporter of generic drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In good times,'' he said, ``you have economic power built up
and sometimes it builds up to excess. Now it's time to make sure
that elements of the economy that are blocking the prosperity of
others, primarily families, is brought under control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 1350EDT &QL; 
