<HEADLINE>
U.S. IS RALLYING ALLIES' SUPPORT TO AID GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ The top U.S. financial officials, fresh
from parallel plunges into world oil and currency markets, sought
to rally allies in the Group of 7 industrialized nations on
Saturday to fight what they labeled twin threats to the
record-breaking U.S. economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and Alan Greenspan, chairman
of the Federal Reserve Board, met their European, Canadian and
Japanese counterparts in Prague ahead of the annual meetings of the
World Bank and the International Monetary Fund. The officials
negotiated a joint communique expected to be released Saturday
night that will be closely scrutinized as an indicator of how far
authorities intend to extend market interventions.
</P>
<P>
   The United States joined Group of 7 counterparts Friday in a
concerted intervention in currency markets to support the tumbling
euro, Europe's single currency, catching traders off guard and
giving the euro at least a temporary boost. On the same day, U.S.
officials announced plans to dip into the nation's Strategic
Petroleum Reserves to fight the surge in oil prices as winter
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   The attempts to correct currency rates and oil prices cast the
United States, which typically argues that such markets should take
care of themselves, as an aggressive interventionist, evoking
expressions of surprise even from some generally less
market-sensitive counterparts. Many expressed satisfaction that the
action to bolster the euro had gone smoothly, though it remained
unclear how markets will react when they reopen for trading this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was surprising how well the action went,'' Germany's
finance minister, Hans Eichel, told reporters Saturday morning.
``Especially before the U.S. election, it was surprising the U.S.
even participated.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-level talks on how best to corral market prices
underscored how officials have come to view the euro's weakness and
oil's strength as major inflationary threats that pose an immediate
danger to what has been seen as an almost unprecedented streak of
global economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Although the rhetoric has been understated, the United States
participated in the defense of the 21-month-old European common
currency, led by the European Central Bank, because of what Summers
called a ``threat to the world economy.'' It was the first time
since 1998, when the United States and Japan joined forces to back
the yen in the midst of the Asian financial crisis, that the
Clinton administration had agreed to sell dollars in support of a
foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
   Summers in the past has stressed his reluctance to tap the
national oil reserve as a way to put downward pressure on oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's decision to do so sent a clear
signal that the price of oil, which has hit its highest level since
the Persian Gulf war, threatens the health of the U.S. economy and
the presidential campaign of Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   European officials on Saturday praised the U.S. action on oil
and suggested that the European Union should also adopt a unified
political response to the challenge posed by rising oil prices.
Several European nations, including Britain and France, have
sustained protests by truck drivers and other groups hurt by high
oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Prices at the pump in Europe, already far higher than those in
the United States, have risen even more dramatically because oil is
bought and sold in dollars, which have been rising in value against
the euro almost in tandem with the oil-price spike.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union should also devise a common response to the
oil-price rise, said Ernst Welteke, who heads Bundesbank, Germany's
central bank. He said the failure to adopt a common approach after
the United States took action demonstrated a weakness in political
coordination among European governments that he suggested was one
of the factors that have hurt the euro since its launch in January
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``The discrepancy between European governments' response to the
oil shock does not demonstrate that a common financial and economic
policy is being pursued within the euro zone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   France's finance minister, Laurent Fabius, pushed Group of 7
ministers to coordinate an assault on high oil prices, possibly
through a joint meeting with OPEC nations, European officials said.
But Gordon Brown, Britain's finance minister, threw cold water on
that idea Saturday. He said his counterparts had not endorsed the
idea of a joint meeting, though he said several bilateral meetings
had been arranged.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Vaclav Havel, the Czech president, invited 200
charity and pressure groups concerned about globalization to debate
the heads of the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund at
Prague Castle.
</P>
<P>
   During the two-hour session, followed by a walk through the
gardens of the sprawling historic residence of Czech rulers,
numerous environmentalists and political activists presented an
extensive list of demands to James D. Wolfensohn, president of the
World Bank, and Horst Koehler, managing director of the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Several called for the complete abolition of the two
Washington-based lending agencies, which were founded just after
World War II to finance the reconstruction of Europe and stabilize
world currencies. Both have been under heavy pressure recently to
help improve the economies of poorer nations that receive most of
their loans.
</P>
<P>
   On Prague's streets, anti-globalization protesters who have
vowed to shut down the annual meetings did not disrupt Saturday's
closed-door sessions of the Group of 7. Security around the
historic city center was tight.
</P>
<P>
   So far the protests have been muted, but thousands more are
expected to arrive in the Czech capital ahead of a planned march
for debt relief on Sunday and an attempt to disrupt the formal
ceremonies of the meetings on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
