u i BC-CZECH-REACTOR-NYT &LR;      09-23 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-REACTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRIA FIGHTS NUCLEAR PLANT NEAR CZECH BORDER  
</HEADLINE>
   By LADKA BAUEROVA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ The four cooling towers of the Temelin
nuclear power station overlook the rolling hills of the southern
Czech Republic like a gigantic castle. But for most Austrians,
whose country begins just 40 miles away, this castle is haunted.
</P>
<P>
   As the Czech authorities make final preparations to switch on
the first reactor at the Soviet-designed plant, fiercely
antinuclear Austria has intensified its threats to block the Czech
Republic's effort to join the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Austria is the only country in the world to have built a
complete nuclear power plant and then to have decided _ in a 1978
referendum _ not to put it or any other nuclear plant on line. The
country, which suffered from the radiation cloud released by the
1986 Chernobyl accident, has become a vigorous campaigner against
nuclear power, particularly in the former Communist countries whose
nuclear plants often include Soviet designs.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the Czech authorities ``arrogant'' and ``irresponsible''
for deciding to put Temelin on line, Austria's Parliament voted
unanimously on Sept. 5 not to approve the energy chapter of the
Czech Republic's application to join the European Union. A Czech
government spokesman, Libor Roucek, replied by saying that the
Austrian reaction to Temelin was ``hysterical to the point of being
embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 7, the European Parliament in Brussels passed a
nonbinding resolution urging the Czech Republic to carry out
additional studies on Temelin's environmental impact before it is
put into operation.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech government, which has already invested nearly $2.5
billion in the power plant, had refused to do more testing, arguing
that the safety features bought from Westinghouse meet American
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The only Czech leader who appeared to sympathize with the
concerns about Temelin was President Vaclav Havel, whose voice
carries much moral weight, but who wields little actual political
power. ``It would be unwise, even suicidal,'' to prevent a further
check of Temelin's safety, Havel said.
</P>
<P>
   Most members of the Czech cabinet and Temelin's director,
Frantisek Hezoucky, were critical of the Brussels vote. ``It is
irritating that the European Parliament wants to vote on a thing it
knows nothing about,'' Hezoucky said. ``The Czech delegates were
not even allowed to speak. This is a decision made about us without
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Edmund Stoiber, the premier of the German state of
Bavaria, sent a letter to Prime Minister Milos Zeman, protesting
the plan for the Temelin plant.
</P>
<P>
   And for the fourth time, Austrian environmental activists
blocked virtually the whole border with the Czech Republic on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Temelin is a nuclear power plant of old Soviet design whose
construction began in 1987 under the Czechoslovak Communist regime.
After Communism fell in 1989, the Czech authorities decided to
continue the work. Its opening has been postponed several times for
financial and technical reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The latest deadline, Sept. 15, was moved back because of
recurring water leaks in the reactor's cooling circuit. Temelin
officials now say the reactor could be operational in October, at
the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   The environment ministers of Austria and Germany say the plant
will not pass the rigorous nuclear safety standards in their
countries. Czech officials say Temelin is safe according to the
standards recognized in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can argue about the technical details endlessly,'' said
David Kyd, the spokesman for the Vienna, Austria-based
International Atomic Energy Agency, the U.N. body that oversees
nuclear safety. ``The truth is, this is more a political issue than
a technical one.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyd noted that Austria's protests at new nuclear power plants in
other countries have usually fizzled once the facility is on line.
He said that although Temelin has weak spots, like loosely mounted
cooling pipes and flawed water-steam valves, the U.N. agency does
not anticipate any difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   The particular Soviet pressurized water reactor used in Temelin
has never had an accident, he added. ``Chernobyl had a completely
different technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosina Luger, a representative of the Austrian antinuclear
organization, Mothers Against Nuclear Hazard, disagrees. ``We are
sure that Temelin is not safe,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``EU countries are phasing out nuclear energy, so why should we
accept countries that are just opening new plants now?'' she said.
Josef Puehringer, the spokesman for the Upper Austrian Platform
Against Nuclear Danger, said, ``Temelin is not only Austria's
matter, it is a problem for all of Europe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
