u i BC-PERU-FUJIMORO-800&AMP;ADD     09-23 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-FUJIMORO-800&AMP;ADD(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS SKEPTICAL ABOUT FUJIMORI'S WATCHING _ AND REINING IN _
PERU'S WATCHMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ Hoping to blunt the crisis that threatens to drive
him from office, President Alberto Fujimori has promised to
dismantle the powerful National Intelligence Service.
</P>
<P>
   But the spy agency has so thoroughly penetrated Peruvian
government and society, experts and diplomats say, that a complete
purge of the state's security system will be difficult to carry out
even if Fujimori really means what he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter what name they have or what laws change,
they are going to continue to do what they want,'' said Fernando
Rospigliosi, author of ``The Art of Deceit'' and other books about
Peruvian politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a personalized dictatorship, rather than an
institutional one, in which a very corrupt elite has maintained
control through blackmail and bribes. And only if they lose power
altogether can you take the state security apparatus apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has been fighting to remain in power since the
broadcast of a video late last week that shows his national
security adviser, Vladimiro Montesinos, paying $15,000 to an
opposition congressman, apparently to get him to favor the
government. Fujimori's response was to call new elections in which,
he said, he will not be a candidate and to announce the
``deactivation'' of the intelligence agency, which Montesinos
supervises.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, though, Montesinos' whereabouts and status
continue to be a mystery. On Thursday, the armed forces announced
their support for Fujimori, ending fears of a coup. But they
conspicuously avoided any reference to Montesinos, who had a hand
in the selection of most of the members of the military high
command.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montesinos, as we understand it, is out, or is fired,'' a
diplomat here said on Wednesday. ``He is not exercising his
function any longer as national security adviser.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fujimori has also said that Montesinos still has a full
security detail to protect him and that no criminal charges have
yet been filed against him in connection with the bribery scandal,
or any other of the multitude of accusations made against him.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the government sent a bill to Congress that would
formally disband the spy agency within 15 days, and also promised
to announce Montesinos' dismissal by Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The location of an estimated 2,500 videotapes that were said to
have been in Montesinos' possession _ an electronic dossier on
leading political, business and military figures _ is also unclear.
Susana Higuchi, Fujimori's former wife and now a member of the
opposition group that released the tape showing Montesinos, said
this week that the group had other tapes but hesitated to release
them because ``the result could be chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the video scandal, the government, trying to deflect
a barrage of criticism of Montesinos, had presented legislation
that would create a new National Intelligence Center to oversee
state security affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But independent experts dismissed the government's efforts as
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montesinos has suffered a major blow and is not going to be
able to regain the position of supreme power he had,'' said Carlos
Tapia, a former lecturer at the Army Intelligence School. ``But the
apparatus he created, though weakened, remains in place, and many
of its members are simply going to transfer to the army
intelligence service, which is certain to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In fact, each of the three branches of the armed forces, as well
as the National Police, has its own intelligence service. But they
too have been implicated in human rights abuses and what Jose
Miguel Vivanco, executive director of the Americas division of
Human Rights Watch, called ``the whole system of bribes, threats,
extortion, privileges and surveillance by which this government has
preserved and accumulated power.''
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the National Intelligence Service, known by the
Spanish acronym SIN, is meant to be a supervisory body, with fewer
than 100 employees divided among three divisions: terrorism,
counternarcotics and public security. But Tapia estimates that the
agency's ranks have swelled to more than 1,200 people, not
including several thousand informants in the military and the
police.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Montesinos and his associates have infiltrated other important
institutions _ from the customs service and electoral commission to
the news media and the court system. That makes it highly unlikely,
some argue, that he will ever be held legally accountable for any
actions that violated the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there is a better chance to eventually prosecute
Pinochet in Chile than Montesinos in Peru,'' Vivanco said,
referring to Chile's former dictator. ``I don't see an independent
court or judge in a country where Montesinos, and not Fujimori, has
been able to rule the country for seven years by firing and
transferring judges, drafting legislation and changing
constitutions.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY MAY END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   The intelligence service was created during the authoritarian
military government that ruled Peru in the 1970s, when there were
fears that border disputes with Ecuador and Chile could turn to
war. The complaints about its domestic activities accelerated after
Fujimori was first elected in 1990 and set about crushing left-wing
guerrilla groups like Shining Path, and they intensified after
Fujimori shut down Congress and the courts in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone closed their eyes because it was the most difficult
period of the war against terrorism, so the attitude was that
anything that works is fine,'' Tapia said. ``But then it became a
monster.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 1990s, Montesinos and the intelligence service
also gave valuable help to the United States that resulted in a
pronounced drop in coca cultivation and trafficking here. But
experts contend that Montesinos has now finally exhausted American
patience, pointing to his apparent involvement in a
still-unresolved scandal involving the sale of arms to left-wing
guerrillas in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a Noriega situation,'' Rospigliosi said, referring
to the Panamanian dictator who after many years as an American ally
was eventually deposed in a U.S. military invasion in December
1989. ``The CIA, which has been his support, has now let him
fall.''
</P>
<P>
   But experts also say that any effort to reform the apparatus
Montesinos created is certain to run into practical obstacles. This
country, they argue, does not have the legal framework,
institutional capacity or civilian expertise that would be required
to bring the agency to heel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to any dismantling of the intelligence service is to
create mechanisms of control, and right now we don't have those,''
said Santiago Pedraglio, a political expert here. ``Even if
Montesinos and his people leave, no laws enable any entity outside
of the executive to monitor and supervise the intelligence service
by looking into its activities and accounts, and so what you are
left with is an untouchable power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
