<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NIGHT BELONGS TO GREENE; FUTURE BELONGS TO JONES
</HEADLINE>
   (Sports of The Times) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Off the track and into his new and
long-awaited life as an Olympic gold medalist, Maurice Greene made
the rounds, hammed it up with the men who had finished in his dust
and then happened to glance at the television, mounted high on the
backstage wall. There, was a scene that is likely to be repeated
several times over the following week. There, was a face that
Madison Avenue will undoubtedly soon come to love.
</P>
<P>
   There, Marion Jones was beating him to the medal stand, on her
way to becoming a transcendent American star.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of dueling sprinters and sexes, Greene did all he
could, with his flamboyant swagger, with no way to surprise people
unless he failed, which he most certainly did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got destroyed,'' said Ato Boldon, silver medalist, after
Greene powered out of the blocks, shifted into warp drive the last
50 meters and won the men's 100 meters in 9.87 seconds Saturday
night at the beautiful Olympic Stadium that holds 110,000
spectators and accommodates a fair amount of oversized moths.
</P>
<P>
   The moths were circling but Greene was flying. No doubt was left
regarding the identity of the world's fastest human, unless you
were in Lane 8, and trying to claim that title yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually thought we were even, until I saw the replay,''
Boldon said. ``But that's what peripheral vision does to you.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Boldon hit the interview area, he had come to grips
with the realization that his training partner, the 26-year-old
first-time Olympian he had taken under his wing, had ascended to
that place in time when the moon, the stars and the moths are
perfectly aligned. Too bad Greene had to stoop to all the
trash-talking and tongue-wagging. Performance is the greatest form
of intimidation, and his world-record 9.79 and his 30 sub-10-second
times coming into Sydney were enough to remind the others, at least
subliminally, that they were racing for second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely a down year for mere mortals in the 100,'' Boldon
said, a club in which Greene was not being counted as a member.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this stuff is day by day, moment by moment,'' said
the bronze medalist, Obadele Thompson. ``He puts things together
very well, day by day, moment by moment. Ergo, we don't beat him
very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Boldon of Trinidad told Thompson of Barbados, ``Two-hundred,
let's do it,'' referring to a race that will be free of Greene and
Michael Johnson, open to them and the other mere mortals. They
gratefully took their silver and bronze and left Greene to his just
rewards, including a victory lap that included a stop to sit,
remove his shoes and hurl them into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Ergo, Nike executives were cheering wildly somewhere, or merely
applauding the flawless execution of a pre-arranged plan. While
Greene maintained, ``I'm not into sport for fame and fortune,''
let's be serious. Cashing in on gold has become almost a corporate
Olympics in itself, witness the silver shoes that Jones, another
soldier of the swoosh, high-stepped in to the finish, as her face
transformed from a mask of determination to a smile that in a power
outage, could light up the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   If Michael Johnson proved one thing after Atlanta four years
ago, it is that extending Olympic celebrity beyond those
welcome-home nights on the couch next to Letterman or Leno is
getting harder and harder. Greene could have thrown Imelda Marcos'
entire collection into the stands along with his, but he'll soon
find out that only Jones, five golds or not, will step up to the
next level of stardom from these Games.
</P>
<P>
   She's got that unique and magnetic aura, the ability to enhance
a moment with a valedictory gesture, or verbal gem.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother is a native of Belize, so, along with the American
flag, Jones carried around the flag of that country, which doesn't
have a single track and whose runners train on a dusty soccer
pitch. On the subject of what her gold medal felt like, she might
have been describing herself when she said: ``No rough edges, very
smooth and glamorous.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene, naturally, was asked his opinion of Jones' attempt to do
the unfathomable, as many U.S. track stars undoubtedly will in the
coming days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish her the best because I wouldn't try it,'' he said. ``I
was very tired last year after Seville after running all the rounds
of the 100 and 200 and all the relays. I just hope her body doesn't
break down.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the trials last summer, both Greene and Johnson pulled up
lame, trying to outdo each other in the 200 meters. Everyone here
is in awe of what Marion Jones is trying to do, and that includes
the world's fastest human, still a title of renown, even when
Marion Jones was on the program, too.
</P>
<P>
   It was Greene's night, but it was also a one-night stand. With
all due respect to Cathy Freeman and Johnson, the Olympics, from
hereon out, belong to Jones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
