<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL BRIEFS: PENNSYLVANIA, FLORIDA, MONTANA, OREGON 
</HEADLINE>
   By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Democrats Gain Hope In Pennsylvania Race
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are taking heart from a Pennsylvania poll that shows
Rep. Ron Klink gaining in his effort to unseat Sen. Rick Santorum,
a freshman Republican.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the campaign, Democrats looking to regain
control of the Senate viewed Santorum as one of the most vulnerable
Republicans. They recalled that he barely squeaked into office in
1994, and since then, they noted, he had compiled an unusually
conservative record for someone representing a state with more
Democrats than Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But Santorum proved to be a formidable raiser of campaign cash,
and poll after poll showed him with a lead of 10 points or more
over Klink, a moderate from suburban Pittsburgh. Democratic hopes
began to slump, particularly when Klink proved a poor fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the new poll, released on Tuesday by the Knight Ridder
news service and Wayne State University. It indicated Klink had
closed the gap to 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, Santorum all of a sudden was pleading campaign
poverty and saying it was ``imperative'' that his supporters come
up with more money so he could continue an advertising blitz he had
been running.
</P>
<P>
   Then, within a matter of hours, Klink was on the air with his
own television blitz. How?
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, which had been
sending him mixed messages about possible help from the national
party, had finally come through with an $800,000 infusion.
</P>
<P>
   Afoul of the Law With Emery Boards  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 1976 presidential campaign, Jimmy Carter's supporters
were given a cease-and-desist order by Oregon election officials
when they started handing out Georgia peanuts to voters. State law
prohibits giving gifts of value to a voter, even a gift worth,
well, peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Boquist, a Republican businessman running for the House in
Oregon's 5th Congressional District, south of Portland, may or may
not have known about that little incident. But in any case, his
supporters were spotted the other day handing out free emery boards
_ 6,000 of them, bought for 9 cents each, including the emblazoned
``Boquist for Congress'' message.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials are investigating. Boquist, who is struggling
uphill to unseat Rep. Darlene Hooley, a two-term Democrat, could be
fined $100 if found guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing a Legend, Of the Opposing Party  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the races that could be especially important in
determining control of the House of Representatives is the race in
Florida's 22nd Congressional District. This is the Gold Coast
district, stretching from Miami Beach to Palm Beach and chock full
of retirees.
</P>
<P>
   The race, in which state Rep. Elaine Bloom, a popular Democrat,
is trying to unseat the 10-term Republican incumbent, E. Clay Shaw
Jr., looks to be close, with perhaps a slight edge going to Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   But he's taking no chances.
</P>
<P>
   In a radio ad, Shaw, a moderate, boasts of how well he has
looked after the concerns of his aging constituents, and he invokes
the name of Rep. Claude Pepper, a legend in South Florida for his
watchful legislative care of the aged.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Pepper died 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that he was a classic liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that he was a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The point, says Shaw, is that Claude Pepper cared about
America's old, and so does Clay Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was proud to call Claude Pepper my friend,'' he concludes.
</P>
<P>
   That was too much for 82-year-old Frank Pepper. He says he knew
Claude Pepper, that Claude Pepper was his brother, and that Clay
Shaw is no Claude Pepper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any animosity toward Clay Shaw,'' he said. ``I've
just known Elaine for years. I try to pray for Republicans. All I
can. If Claude were still with us, he would be devoting himself to
campaigning for Elaine Bloom.''
</P>
<P>
   Passing the Buck, In a Fashion  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a new twist on fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   In Montana, former Lt. Gov. Dennis Rehberg, a Republican running
for the state's lone House seat, is mailing 9,000 $1 bills to past
contributors, hoping the unusual approach will spur them to give
some more, including sending back the $1 bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to compete,'' his campaign manager, Alan Mikkelsen,
argues.
</P>
<P>
   Rehberg's Democratic opponent, Nancy Keenan, the state's
superintendent of public instruction, has a different take. She
says Rehberg is ``just trying to pass the buck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 1408EDT &QL; 
