<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S NEW TRAIN RUNS AT 270 MPH, INTO THE RED 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOFU, Japan _ When the invited guests had finished boarding the
gleaming new train, sitting on a custom-built test track high above
green fields growing thick with rice, a uniformed young stewardess
passed through, handing out refreshments and bowing.
</P>
<P>
   So far, all seemed familiar to train passengers in Japan, down
to the Chiclet-shaped windows and the feel of the seats. Then the
train began to move. In 90 seconds flat, without even a shudder,
the latest wonder of Japan's train developers blurred the
landscape, reaching 270 miles an hour as the director of the test
program unleashed a wicked grin.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Japan's ``bullet train'' lines, already among the
world's fastest, have been losing money for years.
</P>
<P>
   And yet money seemed like an annoying afterthought in a
demonstration that made it clear that this nation's eager railroad
developers are determined to push a new generation of
ultra-high-technology trains able to travel almost twice as fast as
today's best.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a variety of ways to consider the costs of a
train,'' said the test director, Hiroshi Suruga, who shifted
uncomfortably as a reporter sought to change the subject back to
nitty-gritty questions of development spending and operating costs
and away from magnetic levitation. That exotic technology propels
the train through a combination of expensive components cooled by
liquid helium and super-high voltage.
</P>
<P>
   If Suruga's answer resembled a fudge, it was one all too
familiar to the growing chorus of critics of Japan's huge
government-sponsored projects. Duplicate space programs spend
billions of dollars and yet are unable to successfully launch
rockets; extraordinary bridges lead to sparsely populated islands.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Japan is the world's most indebted country, with
public debt recently estimated at 130 percent of the gross national
product.
</P>
<P>
   Once, the Japanese public might have watched all this with
resignation. But the new train, the maglev (for magnetic
levitation), may turn out to be the latest in a recent string of
dubious projects that have raised the hackles of increasingly wary
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the countryside often support these kinds of
projects because they need jobs to survive in these hard times, and
it must be pointed out that our political system is heavily skewed
in favor of rural voters,'' said Akio Ogawa, a professor of policy
studies at Chuo University in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``But urban residents have completely lost their faith in this
kind of project. For them it is just runaway fantasy, and it has
been going on for 30 years or 40 years now.''
</P>
<P>
   With a bit of prodding, Sugura, the head of testing for the
train, said the maglev had cost about $3 billion to develop _ a
figure that almost certainly omitted a multitude of hidden
subsidies _ and would require about three times as much energy to
run as the country's existing bullet trains.
</P>
<P>
   And rather than build a test range for the new train in an area
of relatively flat, open spaces, the 25-mile track was built in
this heavily mountainous farmland west of Tokyo, requiring a huge
span of elevated concrete, a truss bridge and numerous long
tunnels. This has meant huge contracts for construction companies
and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   And the local government of Yamanashi put up close to $200
million to subsidize the test center to ensure that as big a piece
of the action as possible came to this prefecture of 895,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   But in the ultimate sign that this system is in crisis, even the
local residents who could once be counted on to support spending on
big public works have begun calling the projects into question. And
in an ominous foretaste of what lies ahead for planners should they
decide to introduce a magnetic levitation train from Tokyo to
Osaka, residents of the very Yamanashi Prefecture where the
project's test phase was held have begun to lodge protests against
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago only the Communist Party would have opposed a
project like this,'' said Keiji Kato, a member of a local Yamanashi
residents' group that opposes the construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there are company heads, lawyers, housewives, accountants
and students here against it. The only people who stand to profit
are a handful of construction companies and landowners, and not the
general population. We must save our money for other needs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
