<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BOX-740&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CONTROVERSY OVER JUDGING, AND A SURPRISE U.S. LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ In the Olympics, there is the quaint notion
that the fight game can be domesticated _ headgear is worn, fights
are short and savage knockouts are few _ but it is still boxing.
And that means that sooner or later there will be a judging
controversy and intrigue over scoring decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The latest dispute involved the unexpected defeat Friday of
light flyweight Brian Viloria, a gold medal favorite for the United
States. The Viloria decision left U.S. coach Tom Mustin wondering
if there was a movement afoot to limit the success of the U.S.
team, which has eight fighters alive in the 12 divisions of the
Olympic tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they want one team to come in and have nine or
10 guys progress round after round,'' said Mustin, whose fighters
have also been heartily booed at the boxing venue during the last
two days. ``Other countries want to get gold medals too, and
they're going to have to get them from somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   After Viloria lost his close fight on points, Mustin suggested
that the dozens of body punches Viloria threw at his opponent,
Brahim Asloum of France, were not counted in the scoring by the
five judges. It is a longstanding belief in international amateur
boxing that North American judges _ more influenced by professional
boxing where a premium is placed on power punching _ tend to give
fighters credit for blows to the stomach and ribs while judges from
other parts of the world do not.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of room for interpretation on whether a punch
landed or not, but it is true that neither Viloria nor Asloum
received a point for a body shot in their bout. When the judges
score a punch as a point it is registered on videotape, and of the
dozens of punches these two speedy, small fighters threw in four
rounds, the judges registered that only six punches landed for
Asloum and four punches landed for Viloria _ all blows to the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Brian's body shots had counted,'' Mustin said. ``He would
have been ahead by five points.''
</P>
<P>
   The five judges for the Viloria-Asloum fight were from South
Korea, Germany, Tahiti, the Dominican Republic and Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday, in a press conference with reporters, Loring
Baker, the general secretary of the Amateur International Boxing
Association, said he thought Viloria's punches to the body should
have counted.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been coincidental, but suddenly Saturday, during
many bouts, body shots were indeed being counted in the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   This change did not have much effect on the Americans who fought
Saturday as the U.S. team bounced back from Viloria's disheartening
defeat with two victories in three fights. Ricardo Juarez, last
year's featherweight world champion, won a tough second-round fight
with Germany's Falk Huste, 17-15. Huste and Juarez were given
credit for punches to the body.
</P>
<P>
   Light middleweight Jermain Taylor followed his knockout in a
first-round fight earlier this week with another dominating
performance. Taylor outpointed Canada's Scott MacIntosh, 23-9. The
U.S. super-heavyweight Calvin Brock, who was not considered a medal
favorite, lost his first fight of the Olympics to Paolo Vidoz of
Italy, 21-5. Vidoz built part of his early lead by punching to
Brock's body.
</P>
<P>
   But Viloria's loss was still a hot topic at ringside, even if
Mustin said the U.S. team declined to lodge a protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you protest a decision and it makes things worse,''
he said. ``We had to think of the whole team, too. We've got a lot
of guys left.''
</P>
<P>
   If the judges have adjusted their scoring philosophy after the
Viloria loss, it appeased Mustin, but not entirely. ``I do believe
the judges have consistently identified the winner of the fights,''
he said. ``It's been good. But it can be arbitrary when it comes to
what they're counting and not counting.''
</P>
<P>
   More puzzling to Mustin is how unpopular his boxers have become
inside the boxing venue at Sydney's busy Darling Harbor. As the
Olympic boxing tournament moves into the latter rounds and
attendance increases, the crowds have turned vociferous in their
disdain for the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Since the U.S. boxers are considered favorites in many
divisions, it is not unusual that the fans of boxers from other
countries are rooting against the Americans. But the many
Australian fans in attendance, whose boxers have not fared well,
have added to the anti-American cheering. And U.S. fans at the
venue are a small minority.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Taylor overwhelmed his Canadian opponent but he was hooted out
of the ring when his lopsided decision was announced. Brock's loss
Saturday night to an Italian brought about a standing ovation from
the crowd, by far the loudest fan reaction in the eight days of
boxing in the venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why there's such an anti-American crowd,'' Mustin
said. ``We're not coming out of the locker room cocky. We're trying
to be quiet and humble.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and Juarez both said they felt it was important to win
their bouts Saturday after Friday's disappointments. Before Viloria
lost, the American David Jackson also was disqualified from the
tournament because he failed to make the 132-pound lightweight
limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friday took a piece out of all of us because Brian was like
the backbone of the team,'' Taylor said. ``I'm sorry for Brian, but
the show must go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that's somebody who understands boxing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 1430EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
