<DOCNO> NYT20000923.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8925 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-BBO-NYT &LR;      09-23 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BBO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. RALLYING CRY ISN'T ENOUGH TO BEAT CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Manager Tommy Lasorda insists he was not
playing politics when he said he wanted his U.S. baseball team to
win its preliminary game Saturday night against Cuba for Cuban
exiles in Miami. He was not rattling sabers, he said; he was making
a baseball pledge to friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played there,'' he said. ``I have friends who evacuated
their homes. But it wasn't anything political, I was just thinking
about winning the game. I wanted to win the game before for my
cousin. I'll try to win one tomorrow for my brother Smokey.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda's team delivered for his cousin on Friday, beating
Italy. But Cuba beat the United States, 6-1, behind 14 strikeouts
by pitchers Jose Ibar and Pedro Luis Lazo. With their hitting in a
funk, the Americans never recovered from the Cubans' four-run first
inning off Rick Krivda, whose major-league experience did not help
him keep his pitches down in the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know one thing: We're not hitting the way we're supposed
to'' Lasorda said.
</P>
<P>
   But as ordinary as the game was, things happened to cast it in a
political light. Anything untoward between the teams of two
geopolitical enemies whose national pastimes are baseball is
destined for overinterpretation, if not as an ideological duel then
as evidence of endemic animosity.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, Ibar plunked right fielder Ernie Young on
the left shoulder. Cuba already led by 4-0, and Ibar was making
U.S. batters look like the minor-leaguers they nearly all are.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy had pinpoint control, and I get the benefit of a
94-mile-an-hour fastball on my shoulder blade,'' Young said.
``Yeah, I'm upset. I know he did it on purpose.'' As he stepped
toward the plate, Young and Cuban catcher Ariel Pestano bumped into
each other, clearing both benches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The catcher crossed paths with me, and I politely nudged him
out of the way,'' Young said. He offered no reason that Ibar would
hit him but added: ``I didn't think he'd want to fuel a fire with
us. It didn't work this time, but maybe next time it will.''
</P>
<P>
   Ibar said he intended no ill will toward Young, who was leading
the team with a .533 batting average going into the game. ``There
were no intentions,'' Ibar said through an interpreter. ``It was
badly interpreted, badly understood.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Rauch, who struck out eight Cubans in four innings of relief
for Krivda, said he contemplated retaliation, but the umpires
warned him he would be ejected if he tried. ``The thought goes
through your mind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda said, ``It's too bad that the team that gets warned
can't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   A second incident inflamed passions anew. In the eighth inning,
pinch runner Yobal Duenas scored Cuba's sixth run by sliding hard
into catcher Pat Borders, who caught a relay throw far up the third
base line. Rodriguez's left foot flew between Borders' legs and
spiked his left ankle. The ball flew out of Borders' glove. It was
a meaningless run but a meaningful episode in this pseudopolitical
drama. Borders said later that he felt the slide was designed to
injure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a strong play, but not a dirty play,'' said Servio
Borges, Cuba's manager. ``The runner has the right to go and get
the base and he was being blocked. It was a strong play and the one
who's protected is the catcher. He wears the gear to protect
himself at the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Borges said there was no political overlay to the game, nor
anything special to playing the United States. ``On our part, there
is no time for any antagonism,'' he said. ``We just go out and
play.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team will play Australia to end the preliminary round,
but with its 5-1 record it is already guaranteed a spot in the
semifinals. Cuba, also with a 5-1 record, will face Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda said he refuses to think publicly about playing Cuba
again. But after Saturday night's game, he may rethink his claim
that he has seen no better team in this tournament than his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we will play them again,'' he said. ``Do you
know for sure if we will? 'Cause I don't. I don't answer
hypotheticals. Should we face them again? That's a hypothetical.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Lasorda's trying to win the game for his Cuban exile
friends, Borges declined to involve himself in a debate about those
who have left the island since Fidel Castro became president.
``This victory is dedicated to the Cuban people, the 11 million who
saw us train and supported us,'' Borges said. ``This is for the
people of C-U-B-A.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 1434EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
