<SLUG> BC-R-OLY-RUN-ART-1,100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA FORGOTTEN, GREENE AND JONES WIN GOLD
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos OLY 4-7 and graphip are being sent to NYT photo
and graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Four years ago, the Atlanta Games played on
with them in the audience, not on the track. Marion Jones was
recovering from a broken foot, Maurice Greene from a bruised ego,
having failed to qualify for the 100 meters at the U.S. track and
field trials. Sitting in tears as Donovan Bailey of Canada won the
gold medal, Greene told himself, ``This will never happen again
without me.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Greene ran a wonderfully patient and blistering
race to win a gold medal in the 100 meters in 9.87 seconds. He did
not threaten his world record of 9.79 seconds, but his time was
superb into a head wind and he demonstrated a consistency and
technical mastery that not even Carl Lewis could equal. This was
the 31st time that Greene had run the 100 under 10 seconds, twice
as many as Lewis had during his own brilliant career.
</P>
<P>
   Moments earlier, in the women's 100 meters, Jones burst from the
starting blocks and accelerated with a bounding spring as if the
track were a trampoline. Essentially, the race was over in the
first five meters. She accelerated into her long searing stride and
skipped across the finish line in 10.75 seconds, the fastest time
in the world for a woman this year and the preamble to her attempt
to become the first female athlete in track and field to win five
gold medals in the same Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time U.S. athletes had won the men's and
women's 100-meter sprints since Lewis and Florence Griffith Joyner
were awarded first place at the 1988 Summer Games in Seoul, South
Korea. Lewis actually finished second in that race but was later
declared the winner after Ben Johnson of Canada was stripped of his
gold medal for testing positive for anabolic steroids.
</P>
<P>
   So dominant was Jones' performance Saturday night that her
margin of victory _ 37 hundredths of a second _ was the greatest in
the Olympic 100 meters since Marjorie Jackson of Australia won a
hand-timed race in 1952. Saturday night, Ekaterini Thanou of Greece
finished far behind in 11.12 seconds for the silver, and Tanya
Lawrence of Jamaica won the bronze in 11.18. This was the 35th
consecutive victory at 100 meters for Jones over the past three
years, and even before Saturday night's race began, there was no
doubt even among the competitors who would win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running only for the silver medal,'' Thanou said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones reached the finish line with an ecstatic vault but soon
broke into tears as she hugged her mother, Marion Toler, and
grabbed a flag of Belize, her mother's home country. She had been
anticipating this moment since the 1984 Summer Games in Los
Angeles. As an 8-year-old, she had traveled with her family from
their suburban Southern California home to see the torch relay.
That night, she went to her room and wrote on a chalkboard, ``I
want to be an Olympic champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at age 24, she is. Before her senior year of high
school, Jones declined a spot on the American 400-meter relay at
the 1992 Summer Games in Barcelona, Spain. Depending on who is
telling the story, Jones either wanted her first gold to come in an
individual event or her mother would not let her participate
because her grades were insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, a broken foot sustained in her second favorite
sport, basketball, prohibited her from competing in the Atlanta
Games and she had to watch as her boyfriend, now husband, C.J.
Hunter, competed in the shot put.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Jones crossed the finish line in a tangle of
emotions _ joy, relief, the shedding of her Olympic frustrations
and the expectation that four more gold medals are possible in the
200 meters, long jump, 400-meter relay and 1,600-meter relay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is 16 years of believing and dreaming about this,'' Jones
said of her emotional outburst at the finish. ``It comes down to
one moment and one race. There's a lot of pressure. To have it all
realized is a huge relief.''
</P>
<P>
   She felt the burden of expectation of her attempt at five gold
medals, and a swarm of moths bothered her at the start, but it
became clear to the 110,000 at Olympic Stadium Saturday night that
she won the race shortly after she left the starting blocks. Her
starts had been troublesome this year, but Saturday night she drove
low and hard from the blocks, hands open, chopping the air, the
exertion of breathing in her cheeks, a calm insistence in her face,
an exquisite fluidity in her stride as her knees piston-pumped her
toward the finish line in silvery spikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was beautiful,'' said Karen Dennis, coach of the U.S.
women's track team. ``Marion did what she does best _ explode out,
lift her knees, finish strong. She looked like she was having
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it appears that Jones' attempt to win five
gold medals has been seriously threatened by uncertainty in the
U.S. relays. No other U.S. woman reached the final of the 100,
compared with three from the Bahamas and two from Jamaica. And no
U.S. woman even advanced to the semifinals of the 400 meters. Inger
Miller of Los Angeles, the only real challenger to Jones in the
sprints, withdrew from the 100 with a strained hamstring, and
remains questionable for the 200 and the 400 relay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we are still going to be in the hunt,'' Dennis said.
``It takes four people to run a relay. I don't think we're going to
lead the whole way. If we can keep it close for Marion, I think we
can still win.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene, who is 26, has now demonstrated a reliability on the
track that only Lewis and Johnson had previously achieved. With a
mastery of the science of sprinting that belies his playful
behavior, Greene has now won two consecutive world championships
and an Olympic gold medal at 100 meters. He will attempt to win a
second gold by anchoring the U.S. 400-meter relay next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Greene dedicated his victory to his coach, John
Smith, with whom he began training after the Atlanta Games.
Determined to improve after sitting on the sidelines, Greene packed
his things into a sport utility vehicle and drove to Los Angeles
with his father from his hometown of Kansas City, Kan. He was a
talented but largely unknown sprinter and it was Smith who turned
him into the world's fastest man.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also coaches Ato Boldon of Trinidad and Tobago, who won
the silver medal Saturday night in 9.99 seconds. Obadele Thompson
of Barbados took the bronze in 10.04. Athletes trained by Smith
have now produced six gold medals in the sprints. The victories
serve as consolation for the fact that Smith had been a favorite at
400 meters at the 1972 Munich Olympics only to become injured
before those Games and to withdraw 80 meters into the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he has a big hole in his heart,'' Greene said. ``I
can't fill the hole he has, but I hope I can put a little back for
him. There's nothing like winning a gold medal in the Olympics. I
owe him a lot.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR; BC-R-OLY-RUN-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SYDNEY, Australia: a lot.'' &LR;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Greene has become the embodiment of Smith's coaching style. He
emerged from the blocks calmly, keeping his head down for half the
race, instead of popping up, and accelerating immediately at full
speed. The idea was to delay his top-end speed until he reached 70
meters, leaving himself a shorter distance to decelerate toward the
finish line. The cords in his neck bulging, Greene finally became
fully upright after 23 strides and he took control of the race with
tactical brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When everyone wants to get up and run, he stays down and
drives,'' said Boldon, who trains with Greene at UCLA and who won
the bronze medal at the Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
   After touching hands with Greene during the semifinals, Boldon
slowed slightly, hoping to draw an outside lane for the final. Both
sprinters tend to drift slightly, and, in an outside lane, Boldon
would avoid more contact with Greene. He drew lane 8, but, on the
outside, he did not have Greene to drag him along toward the
finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he ran tonight, he destroyed us,'' Boldon said.
</P>
<P>
   Greene wished Jones luck, saying he would not try such an
ambitious feat. He said he had grown tired after running four
rounds apiece of the 100 and 200 meters, plus the 400 relay, at the
1999 world track and field championships in Seville, Spain. Jones
won the 100 but pulled up with back spasms in the 200 in Seville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish her the best because I wouldn't try it,'' Greene said.
``She's a phenomenal athlete, and it's going to take a phenomenal
athlete to accomplish this. I think she can do it. I hope her body
holds up and doesn't break down like in Seville, so everyone can
see her reach her goals.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
