<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WPO-ART-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIA STUNS U.S. WITH A LAST-SECOND SCORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos OLY 1-3 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Under the mirror-ball effect from the sudden
flurry of flashbulbs in the aquatic center, beneath the thundering
sound of the foot-stomping Australians erupting at the buzzer, the
American Maureen O'Toole finally pulled herself out of the pool.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to let go, especially like this. Stunned by the
controversial game-winning goal that gave the 4-3 victory and the
gold medal in women's water polo to the Aussies Saturday night,
crestfallen to see her amazing career in this sport end with a
cruel twist, there was no way to disguise her sadness. A few yards
away, her 8-year-old daughter, Kelly, was empathizing with tears in
her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think she understands the full perspective of it, but
she understands that we lost and I was sad,'' said the 39-year-old
O'Toole, fidgeting with the silver medal the each U.S. team member
received after the loss. ``Losing the way we did, I think it just
makes it hurt a little bit more. It's pretty painful.''
</P>
<P>
   One moment, their spirits were soaring after Brenda Villa scored
a game-tying goal with 13 seconds left. The next moment, they were
devastated. With only 1.3 seconds left, the bizarre end unfolded.
Just after a foul was called on the American Julie Swail,
Australia's Yvette Higgins quickly whirled a shot that was
deflected outside the outstretched arms of goalkeeper Bernice
Orwig. A roar from 18,000 strong erupted. The tension-filled match
was over, time had run out.
</P>
<P>
   But for several minutes, the Americans remained bobbing in the
water like corks, unsure of what just happened. Under the
impression that the referees had called the foul inside of 7
meters, they believed the goal should have been discounted because
Higgins did not pass the ball first, which is required under the
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the chairman of the technical commission, Gianni
Lonzi, released a statement saying the foul happened outside of 7
meters. Therefore, Lonzi said Higgins was allowed ``an instant shot
and a goal was scored.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if the foul occurred outside of 7 meters, at least two
American players argued that Higgins moved forward and pump-faked,
which would also disallow the goal because the movement has to be
uninterrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an anticlimatic way for it to end,'' Swail said. ``To
have 1.3 seconds left, and to have it come down the way it did,
that's difficult to take. But I think we can leave here with our
heads held high. There were a lot of people who didn't think we'd
be here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans squeezed into the Olympics, qualifying on one last
chance in May by defeating the favored Italians in Italy. In a way,
it seemed fitting for the Americans to play for the first gold
medal in water polo against the Australians. For over a decade,
members from both teams tirelessly campaigned for the sport's
inclusion into the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Several Aussies planted themselves at the Sydney airport and
held up signs of protest when Juan Antonio Samaranch visited
several years ago. And O'Toole, who began playing the sport on
boys' teams because there were no girls' programs, had been
lobbying since the early '80s. In 1994, she retired with the belief
that women's water polo was never going to gain acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Once the unthinkable occurred, O'Toole was forced to make an
emotionally wrenching decision. While she trained with the team in
Los Angeles, she sent her daughter to live with her parents in
Northern California. For the bulk of three years, O'Toole caught a
Friday afternoon flight to see her daughter for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's painful to lose like this, but there's a lot more to
life,'' O'Toole said. ``I have an 8-year-old. That's going to be my
focus after this. I don't think any of us will forget how we lost.
It will always be in my mind. But retiring doesn't make me sad at
all. I'm definitely ready to retire. I knew this was going to be
it. It's been a hard three years of training. It will be really fun
to be a full-time mom.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   She'll get to keep up with one 8-year-old instead of a U.S. team
full of players half her age. For three years, O'Toole had to push
her body to its boundaries; and, as a leader for the U.S. team,
manufacture a positive attitude even when her energy was petering
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your body just doesn't recover as well,'' O'Toole said. ``It's
hard to snap back.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, she stood as an example of endurance. For 23
years, she has absorbed blows in a physical sport where most of the
pain is inflicted underwater, out of the referee's watch. Over that
time, the player with the whip-snap throws and keen sense on
defense has been recognized as the sport's greatest player. As much
as anyone, the Australian team appreciated what she has given to
the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Twice during the post-match interview session, members of the
Australian team applauded O'Toole as she sat at the other end of
the table. When asked why, Higgins piped up, ``She's a legend, a
living legend.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, O'Toole's daughter will understand that. Saturday
night, all she knew was that her mother was sad. The history lesson
will come later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what she understands at this point,'' O'Toole
said. ``I think when I'm back with her on a daily basis, and she
starts seeing me again, she'll understand it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 1448EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
