<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBVAN-DELAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y., N.J.)  
 ONLINE GROCER DELAYS EXPANSION PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The online grocer that was scheduled to open two large
warehouses in the the Bronx, N.Y., and Bergen County, N.J.,
bringing more than 1,900 jobs to the region, said on Friday that it
would delay its most immediate expansion plans, including the New
Jersey warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Technology industry analysts said the delay also cast doubt on
plans by the company, Webvan Group Inc., for the Bronx warehouse,
which was supposed to provide more than 900 jobs, a project that
New York City officials promoted on Thursday. Officials at Webvan
would not comment on Friday on the plans for that distribution
center.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been offered $11 million in incentives from
economic development officials in New York and more than $3 million
from New Jersey for the respective warehouses. Economic development
officials in both states said they were hopeful that Webvan would
be able continue its plans.
</P>
<P>
   George T. Shaheen, president and chief executive of Webvan,
which is based in San Francisco, said that company officials
believed ``that by focusing our key resources on bringing our
existing operations to profitability, we will be in a better
position to significantly reduce the capital needed to drive our
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Webvan officials said they would postpone the scheduled opening
of the New Jersey warehouse, already under construction in Logan
Township, for at least six months. The warehouse was to begin
operating in 2001 and create 1,000 jobs. Webvan also announced
plans to postpone the opening of a warehouse in Glen Burnie, Md. It
was supposed to serve the Baltimore and Washington markets.
</P>
<P>
   Technology analysts said that the move came after signals from
Wall Street that investors are not happy with the performance of
Webvan, a publicly traded Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   Like many business-to-customer Internet companies, Webvan has
sustained significant losses. Webvan recently acquired
HomeGrocer.com in a deal valued around $1 billion. Together, the
two companies posted losses of $103.7 million in the first quarter.
Much of those losses have come from capital investments into new
distribution centers like the $40 million warehouse the company
opened in Atlanta in May.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan's stock climbed to more than $34 per share almost
immediately after its initial public offering last November. But
the stock has dropped in recent weeks to record lows of about $2
per share. On Friday, analysts said that they were still optimistic
about Webvan's future because of its corporate leadership,
technology and the merger with HomeGrocer.com. But they were less
positive about expansion in the immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch released a bulletin on Friday on Webvan's decision
to delay its expansion plans, saying that while analysts there
supported the notion of conserving capital financing and focusing
on profitability, they were ``discouraged by the rescheduled launch
of Webvan's two newest'' distribution centers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their concerns that Webvan is operating in areas
where there are not enough families willing to spend the money
needed to make grocery deliveries profitable, Merrill Lynch
analysts have long held that they were most concerned with the
company's ability to successfully perform a national rollout and
enter new markets.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan now operates in nine markets, including San Francisco,
Chicago and Atlanta, and was expected to be in 13 metropolitan
areas by the end of 2000 and 15 by the end of 2001. ``We now expect
Webvan to be in 13 markets by the end of 2001 and believe plans to
enter Boston and New York could be permanently delayed,'' Merrill
Lynch said in its bulletin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
