<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8933 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-HARVARD-CLARE-NYT     09-23 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HARVARD-CLARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.) 
 A LINEMAN AT HARVARD FINDS NICHE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW R. TRIPALDI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Mike Clare remembers when he was not allowed
to play football.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Rutherford, N.J., it was decided that Clare was
too big to participate in the Pop Warner leagues. Turning to other
sports like basketball and soccer while growing up, Clare hoped he
would not have to wait long before his age caught up with his
imposing physical attributes.
</P>
<P>
   Although he did not start playing football until he entered high
school, time turned out to be Clare's best friend.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 6-foot-4-inch, 315-pound Clare is not only the starting
left tackle on the Harvard football team, but the senior is gaining
recognition as a national force. His coach, Tim Murphy, calls him
``the best offensive lineman in the Ivy League.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has great instincts, quickness and technique,'' Murphy
said. ``He doesn't have an easy job, because, as our left tackle,
he draws the opposing team's best pass rusher.''
</P>
<P>
   Rated as the nation's fourth-best offensive tackle by The Sports
Network, Clare is a mix of strength and athleticism, clearing space
through the opposing team's defensive line as if he were burning
weeds off a vacant lot.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Clare was named first team All-Ivy League and first
team All-New England, playing every snap of Harvard's 10 games
despite a troubling left elbow injury.
</P>
<P>
   Clare, 21, is not standing on his laurels. He is bent on
improving his pass blocking, specifically his first step, and is
working extensively with the Crimson offensive line coach, Jim
Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Clare thinks he has already made improvements in other areas.
``I am more mature than I used to be,'' Clare said. ``I don't let
the little things bother me. If I get a penalty, or the team gets a
penalty, I just move ahead instead of worrying about it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a team captain for Harvard (0-1), which opened its Ivy League
season against Brown in Providence on Saturday, Clare has added
tact to his repertory. He has learned to pick and choose his spots
with teammates who need guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a very vocal person, but I choose to lead by example,''
Clare said. ``If a player messes up, I let him know and correct
him, but I don't think yelling in his face is the right way to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   He displays the same sensitivity away from the field, working
with inner-city children in the Mission Hill Program in Boston. On
Monday afternoons, he can be found tutoring the students in the
program, helping them with their schoolwork, and humoring them on
the playground.
</P>
<P>
   And on Saturday afternoons last spring, Clare was involved in
the National Football League Flag Football Program, intended to
promote and teach the game to young people. Working directly with a
group of 9- and 10-year-olds, Clare said he was impressed with
their enthusiasm. At one point, he had them drawing plays in the
sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to teach these kids that a good education comes
first,'' said Clare, a psychology major who said he would like to
work with children if he did not succeed in professional football.
``A lot of them ask me about football, but I stress to them that if
they hit the books, then everything will fall into place.''
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the lessons Clare has learned from his parents, Tom
and Kathie. Over the last four seasons, they have never missed a
game at Harvard, making the six-hour drive from New Jersey. After
each game, instead of jumping back onto the Interstate for the long
drive home, Tom and Kathie Clare regularly hold tailgate picnics in
the parking lot, cooking more than a hundred hot dogs for the rest
of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Following the disappointing conclusion to last season, when the
Crimson lost their last three games by a combined 14 points in the
last few minutes, Clare says the team entered this season
determined to capture the Ivy League title.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team looks strong right now, but we now if we set our
goals any lower than a championship, we won't win,'' Clare said.
</P>
<P>
   Clare, who is in his third season as a starter, inherited the
left tackle position from Matt Birk before the 1998 season. Clare
and Birk, currently the starting center on the Minnesota Vikings,
have remained friends since Birk sponsored Clare during his
recruiting trip to Cambridge. ``He is the reason I came to
Harvard,'' Clare said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
