<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BKO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIANS APPEAR TO MISS THEIR BID TO AVOID THE U.S.
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Steve Nash was dribbling away as the shot
clock wound down, taking care of the basketball and _ as ridiculous
as it sounds _ unsure whether to preserve an 18-point loss to
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Nash, the Canadian point guard, had at times been spectacular
over the last week, directing his team, the most surprising of the
Olympic tournament, to three straight victories before Saturday's
77-59 loss. In the last 30 seconds at the Dome in Olympic Park, he
dribbled maybe 10 seconds off the shot clock before looking over at
the bench for instruction.
</P>
<P>
   His coaching staff told Nash to run a play, but the Canadians
were unsure whether they needed to avoid losing by more than 18
points, to maintain a point-differential advantage over Australia
for medal-round seeding purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The goal for Russia (2-2), Canada (3-1) and Australia (2-2) was
to avoid a quarterfinal matchup with the United States, which
routed New Zealand, 102-56, Saturday. With the possibility they all
might finish 3-2 in preliminary play, the Canadians at least needed
the tiebreaker over Australia.
</P>
<P>
   But then something inexplicable happened, something Team Canada
may regret for four years. Moments after coach Jay Triano explained
to the news media that the rules needed to be changed to avoid
point-shaving and admitted his players did not attack the basket in
the final moments, new math came to the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians apparently misunderstood the rules. Under the
regulations of FIBA, basketball's international governing body,
goal average, and not point differential, is used as the tiebreaker
when three teams are knotted. A team's points against the other two
teams are divided by the opposition's points, to arrive at a goal
average.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in this system, a team winning 40-20 would have the
advantage over a team winning 80-60 because they would have a
higher percentage of points scored.
</P>
<P>
   Russia won out, with a 1.10447 average. Australia nipped Canada
by the slimmest of margins, 0.9593 to 0.9581. Should the three
teams wind up with identical records, the Canadians will take no
solace in this brutal statistic: One point would have put them
ahead of Australia. A free throw. One point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit weird to find that out after the game,''
John Lee, the Canadian team trainer, said. ``If we had just made
one free throw, there would be no controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians still have a chance to win Group B if they can
upset unbeaten Yugoslavia on Monday or if Australia is upset by
Spain. But should all three teams finish 3-2, Nash and his
teammates will forever bemoan the confusing end to Saturday night's
game. The way the Yugoslavians have been playing, an upset by Spain
over Australia, which held off Angola, 86-75, is more plausible.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. men cruised past New Zealand to move to 4-0 in this
tournament. Vince Carter dunked often, ending with 18 points. Allan
Houston contributed 17 points, burying four of the five 3-pointers
he attempted.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Marks, who played in the NBA for two seasons with Toronto,
led New Zealand with 10 points. Unlike some of the more unfriendly
competitions between the U.S. men and their opponents here, a
genuine respect between the teams developed.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the game, the New Zealanders paid the Americans
the ultimate form of homage in their sporting culture. Putting
their hands on their knees in the center of the court and bending
down slightly, they suddenly broke into the Haka, a legendary war
dance used by the Maori people to show respect to their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, Kevin Garnett and the U.S. players hugged and high-fived
the New Zealand players after their baritone chant and dance was
complete. The crowd of 8,392 erupted as the two teams walked off
together toward the locker room. ``I didn't know what they were
doing,'' Garnett began, ``but I thought it was pretty cool. They
asked for the floor and for us to turn around. So I just sat back
and watched.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. men played for the first time without Alonzo Mourning,
who left Sydney on Friday to return home to Miami for the birth of
his daughter. Flying commercial to Los Angeles, Mourning was met at
the airport by a charter jet belonging to Micky Arison, the Miami
Heat owner.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived at the Miami hospital 17 minutes before his wife,
Tracy Wilson-Mourning, gave birth to the couple's daughter, Myka
Sydney. Mourning is expected to return to Sydney on Monday night
and play in the medal-round games, completing a round trip of
18,660 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the Olympic Village, the Canadians were ruing their
misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   In the final six minutes against Russia, they scored only five
points. Todd MacCulloch missed a free throw with one minute four
seconds left. Nash missed a field goal with 1:43 remaining. And
then came the final seconds, when Nash, the Dallas Mavericks' point
guard, may have unknowingly dribbled Canada's medal chances away.
</P>
<P>
   One point: Possibly the difference between leaving with a medal
and being run off the floor by Team USA in the quarterfinals.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
