<HEADER>
A8954 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-GREAT-MOMENTS-NYT     09-23 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GREAT-MOMENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID THE COMPETITION, SOME TUGGING AT THE HEARTSTRINGS
</HEADLINE>
  By NEIL AMDUR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are stories of the heart, unscripted Olympic moments of
poignancy, tenderness and sportsmanship that live for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the dead heat between two U.S. teammates, Gary Hall
Jr. and Anthony Ervin, who trained together, ate together, reached
the finish of the men's 50-meter freestyle in the same time and
stood on the same victory platform for the national anthem provided
another thread in this rich Olympic tapestry.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Hall is white and Irvin is the first swimmer of
African-American descent to win a gold medal is almost incidental
to their friendship and their ability to overcome two of the
premier names in swimming, Alexander Popov of Russia and Pieter van
den Hoogenband of the Netherlands. Hall Jr. already had his place
in another memorable moment in Olympic history. For amazingly, it
was Hall Jr. who had been carried around the pool to the medal
stand by his father during the 1976 Montreal Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics have provided the backdrop for any number of these
stories that touch the heart.
</P>
<P>
   At another Australian Olympics, 1956 in Melbourne, an American
hammer thrower, Harold Connolly, and a Czech discus thrower, Olga
Fikotova, overcame the chill of the Cold War in the Olympic
Village, won separate gold medals and then carried their
international romance to Prague, where 40,000 well-wishers attended
their wedding ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, Vera Caslavska, a Czech gymnast, survived the Soviet
invasion of her homeland earlier in the year and won four gold
medals and two silvers, including the all-around title, in Mexico
City. During the medal ceremony for the floor exercise, where
Caslavska shared first place with Larisa Petrick of the Soviet
Union, when the Soviet national anthem was being played, in a
silent moment of protest, Caslavska bowed her head and turned away.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours later, with the Games still on, Caslavska was
married in a civil ceremony at the house of the Czechoslovak
ambassador and then serenaded by a crowd of 10,000 as she and Josef
Odlozil, a runner, were married at a Roman Catholic church in
Xocalo Square.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Landon, the 1920 Olympic high jump champion, met his future
wife Alice, a diver, shipboard en route to Antwerp, Belgium. At
Helsinki, Finland, in 1952, it was a husband-wife gold-medal double
when Emil Zatopek of Czechoslovakia won the men's 5,000 meters.
After joyfully inspecting her husband's gold medal, Dana Zatopkova
followed by setting an Olympic record in the javelin.
</P>
<P>
   The saga of Derek Redmond was embraced by millions of television
viewers. The British 400-meter runner was assisted to the finish of
a semifinal heat in Barcelona, Spain, by his father, Jim, after
tearing a hamstring during the 1992 Olympic race.
</P>
<P>
   Less obvious, but equally touching, was a medal ceremony in
shooting during the Montreal Games in 1976, when Lanny Bassham and
Margaret Murdock of the United States tied for first place in the
small-bore rifle, three positions. Bassham was awarded the gold
medal on a technicality but felt that the rule was so inane that he
pulled Murdock up to the gold-medal platform, where she became the
first woman to win an Olympic shooting medal.
</P>
<P>
   Not all gold-medal stories end happily. Olga Connolly carried
the American flag during the opening ceremony in Munich, but she
and her husband were divorced the following year. Vera Caslavska is
currently an IOC member from the Czech Republic. She and her
husband were divorced in 1992. The following year, their son,
Martin, killed his father during a fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 1559EDT &QL; 
