<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8955 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-ARCH-RUNYAN0924-C     09-23 1568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARCH-RUNYAN0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Marla Runyan's inspiration is invaluable'
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ All she wanted was some steamed broccoli.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day I walked into the dining hall at the Olympic
Village, I was a little intimidated,'' she said. ``The place was
about the size of an indoor track arena and my quest was to find a
tray, some silverware and that broccoli.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a while, but I finally found something that looked
green and I had them put it on my plate, But when I got back to my
table and tasted it, it wasn't broccoli. I went back again and
again and by the fourth time, I asked someone, 'Hey, can you go
with me and find some broccoli?' ``
</P>
<P>
   She started to laugh: ``Now, I'm getting all kinds of help. I've
even got one of the cooks who comes out, reads me the menu and
gives me the fat, protein and calorie count of all the foods.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Marla Runyan's way.
</P>
<P>
   She takes a dilemma and turns it into a deli platter of
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   That 1500-meter runner for the United States Olympic track and
field team is one of the best success stories _ in all of sports,
not just these Summer Games _ that you'll find.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old Runyan is the first ever legally-blind U.S.
Olympian. And what makes her participation here even more
improbable is that until three years ago, she was a heptathlete
competing in the Paralympics. Not only did she switch disciplines,
but in no time at all, she became one of the elite metric milers in
the entire world.
</P>
<P>
   She suffers from Stargardt's Disease, a degeneration of the
retina that destroys a person's central vision. That's means she
can only see things in her periphery.
</P>
<P>
   Her sight began to fade when she was a child and continued to
worsen until she was 15. Today, she has 20/400 vision in both eyes.
With corrective contacts, her sight improves to 20/300. She
described her sight as ``very soft, unable to distinguish many
details. Like a camera with bad film.''
</P>
<P>
   On the track, she can see neither the lap clock just off the
running surface or the finish tape as she comes down the stretch.
Opponents appear in a blur of streaking color and melted feature.
Her best sensor for other runners is their breathing. She can hear
them coming, hear who's laboring and who sounds steady and strong.
</P>
<P>
   When she showed up at Olympic Park the other day to talk about
her event _ she runs her first 1500 heat Wednesday _ she felt her
way along the wall as she made her way up a small flight of stairs.
Sitting on a chair across from you, she tilted her head a bit
sideways so she could make out where you were. Even from four feet
away, she still couldn't make out facial features.
</P>
<P>
   Translated to every day life that means pressing cans to her
forehead while grocery shopping so she can see the picture on the
front. She said she can't read the messages that come up on her
cell phone screen and has trouble reading the time on her
wristwatch. Reading anything else _ from bills and birthday cards
to newspapers and E-mails _ requires a magnifying glass and a
closed circuit device that enlarges everything. Driving requires
special lenses _ ``telescopes mounted on my glasses,'' is how she
described it _ and then she can only drive during the day in
California. Her license isn't recognized in Oregon where she now
lives
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be careful _ for my safety and others,'' she said.
``A lot of my friends don't want to ride with me. We joke about it.
But my blind friends _ they think I drive just great.''
</P>
<P>
   When you press her too long on the sight issue, Runyan gets
restless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I'm trying to avoid the question,'' she said.
``I'd just rather be known as somebody who made the Olympic team in
the 1500 after coming from the heptathlon. And then, oh, by the
way, she's got a sight problem, too.''
</P>
<P>
   She'd like the storyline to be about possibilities, not
limitations. After all, that's how she's lived her life since she
was 9 and began losing her vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very slow deterioration,'' she said. ``But I remember
when I came to school for my fourth-grade year, I could no longer
see the chalkboard. I had been playing soccer, but I had to quit
because I couldn't see the ball anymore. I was so young, though
that I didn't fully understand the consequences of what was
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   As her parents came to grips with their daughter's problem, they
adopted a philosophy that could not have been better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marla was an inspiration right off,'' said Gary, her dad.
``Valerie and I didn't create barriers for her. We let her do what
she wanted. We let her find her own barriers.''
</P>
<P>
   And she found few. At her California high school, she was a
track star and graduated with a 3.98 grade-point average _ that
after her mom painstakingly had written out enlarged versions of
her reading material.
</P>
<P>
   She walked onto the track team at San Diego State, became one of
the leaders on the team and graduated cum laude. She now has a
master's degree in the education of deaf and blind children.
</P>
<P>
   During her college career, she drifted into the heptathlon, a
grueling two-day, seven- event marathon. She learned to high jump
by meticulously counting the steps to the bar. Sometimes she
trained with a piece of reflective tape on the bar so she could
guide herself on the reflections of the sun. Because she could see
none of the hurdles strung out in front of her, her coach taped
playing cards to the top of them so she'd pick up the white blur as
she approached.
</P>
<P>
   Come race time, the visual aids were removed and she was on her
own. And that's how she loved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running is one of the things I can do independently,'' she
said. ``I have a sense of strength on the track that I don't have
in other areas of my life. I've got a true freedom out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Runyan has won five gold medals at the
Paralympics, the Olympic Games for handicapped athletes. In the
Paralympics at Atlanta, she ran the fastest 800 in American women's
heptathlon history _ which includes the regular Olympics. As she
sat in a medical tent with another sight-impaired friend at the
Paralympics she told her, ``You know one day I'm going to run in
the Olympics. ``
</P>
<P>
   Runyan laughed at the memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think she believed me,''she said.
</P>
<P>
   Switching to the 1500 meters, she made great strides and
finished 10th at the World Championships in Seville, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   That race was an eye opener _ so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked into the stadium and it all hit me,'' she said. ``The
flashes of color from the uniforms. The lights around the stadium
and most of all, the roar of a big crowd. I know it sounds odd for
a person with 20/400 vision to say everything got crystal clear,
but everything was so magnified it seemed clear. I remember
thinking, 'I've been healed. I can see.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't, but I could. It helped me set my goals for
Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came a numbing setback. She suffered a knee injury six
weeks before the U.S. Track and Field Trials in Sacramento and was
sidelined until seven days before the event. She considered
dropping out, but finally realized, ``this was just one more
obstacle.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the 1500 finals _ with the top three finishers going to
Sydney _ she ran gimpily down the stretch for a dramatic
come-from-behind surge into third place at the tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just stood there with our arms around each other, hugging
and crying,'' Valerie said. ``That run pretty much captured Marla's
spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Huebner, the executive director of the United States
Association for Blind Athletes, said spirit is something others can
share: ``Marla Runyan's inspiration is invaluable. Many blind kids
aren't told how they can dream. But Marla is a tremendous role
model. She proves a person with sight problems can do well in
college, become a world class athlete and make it to the
Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Sydney, she's still not quite back to her old self on
the track. Her boyfriend and trainer Matt Lonerga estimated that in
her training regimens, she's been able to do about 50 percent of
what she's capable of. Runyan shook her head at the calculation.
``Like before, this is just another obstacle in my way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And after the response I got following the Trials, I've come
to realize there's something else at play here. There's a side
effect to what I'm doing. My race might only last four minutes or
so, but for others, hopefully, what I do out there might last a
lifetime. I never realized the impact I could have until I started
getting letters, calls and E-mails from all around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``People told me I was an inspiration and I like that. A boy
from Turkey wrote me a letter. I've gotten E-mails from Israel and
phone calls from Brazil, Argentina and South Africa. And then there
was that letter from a lady in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me her son has Stargardt's disease. He wanted to be a
skateboarder and wanted to build a ramp so he could practice. She
told him 'No, not with your condition.' Then she said she read my
story and that's when she went to her son and told him. Go ahead,
get your ramp.'''
</P>
<P>
   Marla Runyan may have trouble with her own vision, but as the
Tennessee lady learned, she sure helps the rest of us see so much
better.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
