<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buford-Bailey a deserving representative of her hometown
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Tonja Buford-Bailey, quite literally, has a captive
audience.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the Olympic hurdler's biggest fan club are the
prisoners at the Warren Correctional Institution in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom tells me a lot of the guys there are following me,''
she said as she prepared for tonight's 400-meter hurdles prelim at
Sydney's Olympic Stadium. ``She told me they always ask how I'm
doing and they follow me in the newspaper. I appreciate their
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgianna Buford is a corrections officer at the state prison
and her daughter's biggest champion. Ironically, one of her charges
at the prison is Dayton's Chris Nelloms, the former NCAA sprint
champ from Ohio State, who was an Olympic hopeful himself. In 1996,
the City of Dayton gave him $5,000 to fund his barebones training
and, hopefully, carry the city's banner onto the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   Nelloms didn't make it out of the Olympic Trials and then
earlier this year, he was convicted of repeatedly raping a young
girl and given several life sentences.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Dayton's money would have been better spent on
someone like Buford- Bailey, who's in her third straight Olympics
and already has a bronze medal from the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   Other Dayton Olympians have certainly felt the communal embrace.
Edwin Moses has a boulevard named after him. Long jumper Joe Greene
got a Riverside street. Even Wright State swimmer Leonard Ngoma _
representing Zambia at these Olympics _ has had part of his college
education funded thanks to support elicited from local charities by
City Manager Valerie Lemme.
</P>
<P>
   As for Buford-Bailey _ as with Lavonna Martin-Floreal, a Dayton
Olympian in 1988 and 1992 _ there have been no permanent honors at
home. But both women are deserving.
</P>
<P>
   Buford-Bailey is a great representative of Dayton. Even though
she now lives in Dallas with husband, Victor Bailey, a former NFL
receiver, she continues to make sure she's listed and announced as
being from Dayton when she runs in competitions.
</P>
<P>
   And if you followed the 29-year-old hurdler around Sydney, you'd
see the way people are drawn to her. That was Muhammad Ali posing
with her for a picture. And at the Opening Ceremony, that was her
marching and hobnobbing with tennis champ Lindsay Davenport and
soccer stars Mia Hamm and Brandi Chastain.
</P>
<P>
   Buford-Bailey is one of the comeback stories of these Games.
After the '96 Olympics, Buford-Bailey took off two years because of
injuries and the birth of her son VJ. When she finally did return,
she ran so poorly she considered retiring. But then came the
rousing performance at the Trials _ she surged from sixth place
with two hurdles left _ that got her to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``This experience is so much different than the others,'' she
said. ``I'm not a wide-eyed kid like I was in Barcelona and it's
not the all-business atmosphere I had as a favorite in Atlanta. I
know this is probably my last Olympics and I'm trying to soak
everything in.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it seems like each Olympics, someone else joins me. First,
it was just my mom. Then, Victor joined us at Atlanta and now,
we've got (2-year-old) VJ, though he's just along for the ride.
He's having fun and not paying real close attention to what Mom's
doing here.''
</P>
<P>
   That's OK.
</P>
<P>
   She already has a captive audience.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
