u e BC-SLEAZY-ROCK0924-COX     09-23 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEAZY-ROCK0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More sleaze, please
 &HT;    By Ron Rollins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just when we thought we'd seen and heard everything,
along comes Spin magazine, whose October cover carries the headline
(in barfy neon green, no less), ``The 100 Sleaziest Moments in
Rock.'' The mind boggles, wondering what the editors might pick
from the unspeakably vast pantheon of potential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these you know, of course. Michael Jackson's
well-publicized and unusual, um, preference for spending lots of
time alone with young boys clocks in at No. 6.
Thug-turned-rap-producer ``Suge'' Knight's business practices,
including his occasional use of a lead pipe to arrange artist
contracts, sneaks in at No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   You want groupies? Van Halen singer David Lee Roth's backstage
shenanigans with same were extremely well-organized in order to
minimize the time he had to spend between leaving stage and hopping
in bed. He rates No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   You want cradle-robbing? Jerry Lee Lewis steals No. 38 with his
13-year-old bride, while Rolling Stone Bill Wyman takes No. 12 for
marrying a 19-year-old fan at the age of 52 (he started sleeping
with her when she was 15, though).
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but it's only rock 'n' roll. Which is probably what Nico was
telling herself while shooting up, or what Keith Moon was telling
himself while running over his chauffeur, or what Tommy and Pamela
Lee were thinking while they made that silly little sex tape.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just the musicians who roll around in it, though. There
are friends nobody needs, such as the guy who helped Kurt Cobain
buy a shotgun when he knew what he might do with it (No. 34). There
are even politicians _ in this case, Richard Nixon, who in addition
to his other lapses of judgment certified Elvis (yes, that Elvis)
as an honorary DEA agent in a bid to look cool with the younger set
(No. 15).
</P>
<P>
   The entire event of Woodstock III, including the eight rapes,
10,000 injuries and countless fires, rates No. 4. Everything
Courtney Love ever did in her life crowds her into the lucky No. 13
position. Some bands we thought were kinda goody-goody, such as the
Go-Gos, turn out not to have been very nice after all. (They liked
to stop in public restrooms and play a game called ``Corner
Cleaners.'' Don't ask.) And some presumed evildoers _ such as, say,
Billy Idol, get off fairly light (Billy got busted for powder that
turned out to be nothing more than powder, alas).
</P>
<P>
   After all this, you wonder, what are the top three sleaziest
moments? Col. Tom Parker's abusive, Frankensteinish handling of
Elvis is No. 3; Sid Vicious' freakish handling of
groupie/girlfriend/co-junkie Nancy Spungen (he killed her) makes a
smashing No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Led Zeppelin takes the top spot, with an incident so
historically indecent we can't even come close to describing it
here (though a couple of people who saw the magazine said, ``Yeah,
I thought that would be No. 1'').
</P>
<P>
   It's great copy, but we all know rock provides too easy a target
_ and besides, the repellent and the grotesque have always been
part of the circus, and we all know it. We hate to admit it, but we
were more shocked by the fact that we weren't all that shocked by
any of this stuff. Not anymore, anyway. A friend suggested that the
top 100 sleaziest moments from the Supreme Court might be
interesting reading. Come to think of it, did anyone see a Coke can
around here?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
