u e BC-TORONTO-FESTIVAL0924-     09-23 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORONTO-FESTIVAL0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toronto Film Festival a moosley humorous affair
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Toronto International Film Festival celebrated its
silver anniversary in a city populated by life-size fiberglass
moose.
</P>
<P>
   The brightly painted figures, inspired by Chicago's Parade of
Cows, proved to be an appropriate symbol for this year's festival,
which ran Sept. 7-16 and presented 328 films _ including a record
178 world and North American premieres _ from 56 countries. In
contrast to the dark, premillennial angst that marked many of
1999's selections, the 25th Toronto International Film Festival was
more heavily weighted toward comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The festival opened with Denys Arcand's celebrity spoof,
``Stardom,'' and closed with Kenneth Branagh as a creatively
blocked playwright in ``How to Kill Your Neighbor's Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Other comedies that unspooled over the 10 days included Rob
Sitch's ``The Dish,'' which puts a humorous spin on events in
Australia related to the Apollo XI moon landing; David Mamet's
witty Hollywood film-industry satire, ``State and Main;'' Robert
Altman's Richard Gere-topped ensemble piece, ``Dr. T and the
Women;'' and Christopher Guest's ``mockumentary'' on eccentric dog
owners, ``Best in Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Considered the second most important film festival in the world
after France's Cannes, Toronto has become a springboard for
potential Academy Award contenders, by virtue of its position at
the start of the fall season. Last year's festival launched Oscar
winners ``American Beauty'' and ``Boys Don't Cry,'' as well as top
contender ``The Cider House Rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron Crowe's engaging cinematic memoir, ``Almost Famous,''
emerged as an early Oscar favorite. The funny and touching film,
set amid the circus-like atmosphere of the 1973 tour of an
up-and-coming rock band, opened nationwide on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Also earning Oscar buzz _ whether for the film, its screenplay
or performances _ were Rod Lurie's ``The Contender,'' Stephen
Daldry's ``Billy Elliot,'' Jonathan Glazer's ``Sexy Beast,''
Kenneth Lonergan's ``You Can Count on Me'' and E. Elias Merhige's
``Shadow of the Vampire.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the one to beat may be Ang Lee's ``Crouching Tiger,''
``Hidden Dragon.'' The astonishing martial-arts epic starring Chow
Yun-Fat, Michelle Yeoh and Zhang Ziyi won the People's Choice
Award, voted on by festival audiences, as ``American Beauty ``did
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's stunning masterpiece, an early 19th century Chinese love
story whose fight sequences were choreographed by ``The Matrix'''s
Yuen Wo-Ping, also earned enthusiastic bursts of applause from
usually reticent film critics at the press and industry screenings.
</P>
<P>
   The response no doubt comes as a relief to Sony Pictures
Classics, the film's North American distributor, which reportedly
was concerned about how well ``Crouching Tiger'' would play here
with English-language subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dish,'' which stars Sam Neill and Patrick Warburton,
placed second in the People's Choice balloting. Another Australian
film, Paul Cox's Innocence, tied with the British comedy ``Billy
Elliot `` for third place.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most unexpected standout was Joel Schumacher's
``Tigerland.'' Following his high-profile flops with Batman &AMP; Robin
and 8MM, Schumacher steps back from summer blockbusters with a
gripping story about Army recruits training for Vietnam, shot
documentary-style on a small budget with a hand-held 16mm camera.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Ebert, writing in Canada's ``National Post,'' called
``Tigerland ``the festival's best film.
</P>
<P>
   Other notable features included Darren Aronofsky's ``Requiem for
a Dream,'' Wong Kar-Wai's ``In the Mood for Love'' and Julian
Schnabel's ``Before Night Falls.''
</P>
<P>
   Many are slated to open before the end of the year for Academy
Award consideration. Some, such as ``The Dish,'' went to festival
in hopes of finding a distributor.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto attracts a galaxy of movie stars compared with other
film festivals because of both the large number of Hollywood films
shown and the city's relative proximity to New York City and Los
Angeles. Among those walking the red carpets this year were Gere,
Al Pacino, Robert De Niro, Gwyneth Paltrow, Jeff Bridges, Alec
Baldwin, Daryl Hannah, Laura Dern, Cuba Gooding Jr., Ed Harris,
Willem Dafoe, Sarah Jessica Parker and Robert Duvall.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the countless actors, directors, producers,
distributors, sales agents, exhibitors, journalists, agents and
publicists are thousands of film buffs _ many of whom plan their
vacations around the annual event. Toronto is a fan-friendly public
film festival, with two of each film's three screenings designated
for non-industry audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The public box office for the 25th Toronto International Film
Festival totaled $1.7 million (Canadian).
</P>
<P>
   Special silver-anniversary events included the commissioning of
10 short films, Preludes, from such Canadian filmmakers as David
Cronenberg, Atom Egoyan, Don McKellar and Patricia Rozema to
precede the nightly galas. Guy Madden's Fritz Lang-inspired
Prelude, ``The Heart of the World,'' was considered by many to be
among the festival's best films, despite being a 5-minute short.
</P>
<P>
   Another anniversary-related high point was the stirring
presentation of Sergei Eisenstein's 1938 masterwork, ``Alexander
Nevsky,'' with live orchestral accompaniment of Sergei Prokofiev's
``Alexander Nevsky Cantata'' by the Toronto Symphony Orchestra and
the Toronto Mendelssohn Choir. After 10 days of frantically racing
between screening rooms and interview suites, the powerful
performance was good for the soul.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, was occasionally slipping away from the serious fare to
take in a few of the offbeat features from the ``Midnight Madness''
program. My favorite was ``Wild Zero,'' a hilarious schlock-fest
from Japan that plays like a cross between ``Rock 'n' Roll High
School'' and ``Night of the Living Dead,'' with the punk trio
Guitar Wolf battling flesh-eating zombies.
</P>
<P>
   Several themes emerged over the course of the festival. A number
of films peered behind the curtain to explore the underbelly of
fame, venturing into the worlds of fashion (''Stardom''), music
(''Almost Famous''), film (''State and Main,'' ``Shadow of the
Vampire''), politics (''The Contender''), dog breeding (''Best in
Show'') and chess (''The Luzhin Defense'').
</P>
<P>
   Female empowerment was also a recurring theme in such films as
``Girlfight,'' the Sundance prize-winner that follows a female
boxer from the Bronx; ``The Contender,'' with Joan Allen as the
embattled first female appointee for vice president of the United
States; and ``Crouching Tiger,'' ``Hidden Dragon,'' where three of
the four chief warriors are female.
</P>
<P>
   Given the sheer number of films shown, the law of averages
dictates that more than a few are bound to be stinkers. That
certainly was the case with ``Duets,'' Bruce Paltrow's dreadful
karaoke road comedy starring his daughter Gwyneth, Huey Lewis and
Andre Braugher, as well as with ``Beautiful,'' Sally Field's
directorial debut about a small-town pageant queen, played by
Minnie Driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men of Honor'' _ the film biography of Carl Brashear, the
Navy's first black deep-sea diver, starring De Niro and Gooding Jr.
_ received mixed critical response, as did ``Stardom,'' ``Dr. T &AMP;
the Women'' and ``The Yards,'' a gritty crime drama with Mark
Wahlberg, Joaquin Phoenix and Charlize Theron.
</P>
<P>
   If the movies weren't to your liking, there was always the
colorful herd of moose.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
