<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLINGS ESTIMATED AT 4,000, LESS THAN HALF OF ORIGINAL FIGURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE _ War crimes investigators have found evidence that at
least 4,000 civilians were murdered in Kosovo by Serb forces last
year, less than half the original estimate, and they will end
digging next month despite their belief that there may be thousands
more bodies.
</P>
<P>
   While the final body count will be less than half the estimated
10,000 that war crimes investigators here expected to find, they
said they believe there are as many as several thousand bodies they
will never be able to account for.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview here, Graham T. Blewitt, the deputy chief
prosecutor for the International Criminal Tribunal for the former
Yugoslavia, rejected suggestions by some critics that the Western
allies, principally the United States, had exaggerated the extent
of atrocities by Serb forces to justify NATO's bombing of
Yugoslavia last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never know how many people were killed in Kosovo,''
said Blewitt, who is in charge of overseeing the massive forensic
examination of mass and individual graves in the Serbian province
of 2 million people. ``We have reliable information that bodies
were transported out of Kosovo into Serbia for incineration. How
many, we'll never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Blewitt said investigators will finish ``the forensic side'' of
their probe by the end of October. He said there are no plans to
resume digging next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Blewitt said investigators believe the Serbs learned lessons
from the war in Bosnia, where bodies yielded forensic evidence that
allowed prosecutors here to build cases against dozens of Bosnian
Serb military figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that they dug up bodies, incinerated bodies,
transported bodies so we couldn't find them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, many commentators have accused NATO officials
of having grossly exaggerated the numbers of ethnic Albanians
killed by Serb forces, and suggested the mass killings only took
place in response to the NATO bombing campaign in Serbia. Critics
have pointed to US Defense Secretary William S. Cohen's assertion,
in the middle of the war, that some 100,000 ethnic Albanian men and
boys from Kosovo were missing and may have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   Blewitt said the argument that the Serbs only began killing
ethnic Albanians in large numbers after NATO began bombing is
specious and irrelevant to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a war crime to go out and purposely murder civilians,
period,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Blewitt said the 100,000 figure of missing Kosovars was accurate
when given, but that the vast majority of that number had fled
Kosovo when Serb forces began a systematic campaign of ethnic
cleansing after the NATO bombing began. He said tens of thousands
of Kosovars had crossed over into Macedonia to stay with relatives
or friends, but that there was no reliable system to account for
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will issue a report in November with exact numbers, but I
anticipate that we will have identified between 4,000 and 5,000
bodies,'' said Blewitt. ``The discrepancy between the final figure
and the 10,000 figure that was initially used can be accounted for
by bodies being destroyed or transported into Serbia, and by the
fact that some people feared dead had managed to flee Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the discrepancy will be seized by critics of NATO who
claim the Western allies lied to justify their attack on Serbia's
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Nikola Zurovac, a spokesman for the Yugoslav government, said he
did not believe even the deflated figures, which will be officially
announced next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lie,'' he said, calling the suggestion that Serb forces
dug up and moved bodies in Serbia ``a fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   Zurovac and other Serbs believe that the Kosovo Liberation Army,
the ethnic Albanian separatists who provoked trouble with Serb
forces, murdered many Kosovars and attributed the killings to Serbs
in a cynical campaign aimed at drawing NATO into the war.
</P>
<P>
   Blewitt said war crimes investigators are probing at least five
separate cases of suspected war crimes involving the KLA, both in
1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Blewitt also said he and the chief prosecutor, Carla del Ponte,
who is scheduled to arrive in Washington Sunday night for meetings
with officials at the White House and on Capitol Hill, estimate
that prosecutors will finish issuing indictments stemming from the
Balkan wars by the end of 2004. He said trials will continue for
some time after that.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, he said, his office will have returned indictments
against most groups of combatants in the wars that took place in
Croatia, Bosnia, and Serbia during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal has been accused by Serbs and their sympathizers of
targeting only Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to judge us over the long term, and when we are done
with our work I'm confident that we will be seen to have targeted
not just Serbs, but war criminals from all the various groups in
the Balkans,'' said Blewitt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 1649EDT &QL; 
