<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK: MANAGERS COULD GET PINK SLIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Larry Dierker managed Houston to division championships in each
of his first three seasons with the Astros. In this, his fourth
season, the Astros have played badly, and Dierker is said in
baseball circles to be in danger of losing his job.
</P>
<P>
   Buck Showalter managed the Arizona Diamondbacks to a division
championship in their second season, making them the most
successful baseball expansion team in history. The Diamondbacks,
however, have not only failed to repeat, but have also played too
poorly to make the playoffs as the wild-card team, and Showalter is
said to be in danger of losing his job.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates managed the Texas Rangers to division championships
three of the past four seasons. This season, however, the Rangers
are in last place, and rumors say Oates is in danger of losing his
job.
</P>
<P>
   As the regular season begins its final week, more than half a
dozen managers, Dierker and Showalter among them, are perilously
perched on the precipice of dismissal. Oates, however, is not
teetering there. Tom Hicks, the Rangers' owner, said recently that
Oates would continue as the manager.
</P>
<P>
   Felipe Alou, the venerable manager of the Montreal Expos, is
another whose status was rumored to be in question, but Jeffrey
Loria, the team's managing partner, said that was news to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never said that,'' Loria said. ``I've never said I want
to make a change. Felipe's the manager. He's under contract, an
enormous contract. I've never entertained any other ideas other
than saying we'll take a look at everything at the end of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Loria added, ``He's not in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Dusty Baker and Lou Piniella are not in trouble, either. In
fact, they are managers in the enviable position of being free
agents after the season. Their contracts expire, and they have not
signed extensions.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco wants Baker to remain, and he most likely will
stay. He has been wise, though, to see how far the Giants go in the
postseason before signing. The farther they go, the higher his
salary figures go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dusty has made it clear he prefers to wait until the end of
the season to focus on his business issues,'' Jeff Moorad, Baker's
longtime adviser, said. ``We're acutely aware of his attraction
around the major leagues and I'm certain if he showed himself to be
available that we'd have a number of teams interested. I'm not sure
that's the intent. In fact, it's fair to say he's inclined to stay
in San Francisco as long as the terms of a deal were fair and
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The only negative aspect of continuing the relationship was
suggested by another club's executive. ``I've heard rumblings that
Dusty doesn't want to be with Barry Bonds,'' the executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella is not so certain to remain in Seattle, where he has
managed for eight years. He has not said what he prefers, but the
most popular speculation has him desiring to manage at home,
meaning Tampa Bay. The Devil Rays, however, are not the contending
team Piniella has become accustomed to managing.
</P>
<P>
   ``His focus is totally on winning the pennant and hopefully
getting to the World Series,'' said Alan Nero, Piniella's agent.
``We've all agreed not to think about it or talk about it now. Lou
has incredible loyalty to the Seattle ownership and fans. He would
like to hear what they have to say first and then decide what he's
going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's Pat Gillick sounded like a general manager who wanted
to retain his manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're grading guys on the type of season they've had,''
Gillick said, ``Lou's had a great season, not only from the
standpoint of handling players but running the games. He's had an
all-star year. I've never seen him so much under control. He has
mellowed and matured.''
</P>
<P>
   In just about every instance where a manager's position is
precarious, the team owner or general manager has said the club
will evaluate or address everything at the end of the season. That
statement covers Dierker, Showalter, Gene Lamont of Pittsburgh,
Terry Francona of Philadelphia, Larry Rothschild of Tampa Bay and
Davey Johnson of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bowden, the Cincinnati general manager, offered a variation
on the theme when asked about Jack McKeon. ``Jack's our manager,
and I have no other comment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball executives would consider it a major upset if McKeon,
Francona, Rothschild, Johnson or Lamont survived. In Lamont's case,
Kevin McClatchy, the owner, has reportedly already told him he will
not remain in the Pirates' job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll address Geno's situation at the end of the season, which
is not that far away,'' McClatchy said. ``Any discussions between
Gene and me are confidential.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Wade, general manager of the last-place Phillies, said the
club ``had high expectations coming off our offensive performance
last year,'' adding: ``Things have not developed the way we
expected. We're hugely disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Los Angeles is interesting because the apparent
desire of general manager Kevin Malone to change managers is
compounded by the possibility that Malone himself could be fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our situation is being evaluated at this time,'' Malone said.
``There's been no decisions made. We're pleased with the way we've
performed the last week or two. We find ourselves in second,
playing the best baseball we have all year with a chance for the
wild card. Unfortunately, we waited until this late date. We
thought it would have happened sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Hunsicker of Houston sounded like a general manager who
wanted to keep his manager, but Dierker's future will be determined
by the owner, Drayton McLane Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sometimes we can jump to conclusions before we know
what the real issues are,'' McLane said. ``We want to take
everything into consideration. We'll make a decision very quickly,
in the first week after the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker's position could be undermined by reports that some of
his players don't take him seriously and don't want to play for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not any different from any clubhouse,'' Hunsicker said
when asked about the reports. ``I think it's the nature of the
beast. These things surface when you lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Said a general manager of another team, ``I've never had a
manager the players liked.'' Another general manager said he had
heard that two years ago the St. Louis players were ready to revolt
against their manager, Tony La Russa. ``Now they love him,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Players do not apparently like Showalter in Arizona, even
though, like Dierker, he managed them to a first-place finish.
Jerry Colangelo, the Diamondbacks' managing partner, has said he
will wait until the end of the season before making a decision, but
the team's collapse the last five weeks can't help Showalter.
</P>
<P>
   Even the elder statesman among managers is not certain of his
status. Tom Kelly has managed the Minnesota Twins for 14 seasons,
winning the World Series in 1987 and '91, but does not know if he
will make it to 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't informed me if they want me to come back,'' said
Kelly, who is in the last year of his contract and wants to stay
with the Twins. ``Three years ago, they asked me to stay and take
on this undertaking. Now we're starting to see some light at the
end of the tunnel and I feel like I'd like to do this some more.
But we haven't heard anything. I'm hoping to hear something in the
next few days, because I have some coaches I need to take care of.
Whether we're staying or leaving, I'd like to get it resolved in
the next few days or a week. If they don't want us back, fine;
we'll get along. If they do, good; let's get going.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   No In-Season Changes Yet
</P>
<P>
   Barring an unexpected development, the season will end without
any teams changing managers. It would be the first time since 1942
such a development occurred, and there were only 16 teams then.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must be a lack of candidates,'' Pat Gillick, the Seattle
general manager, said. ``Or nobody wants the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bowden of Cincinnati attributed the novelty to baseball
economics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of it has to do with the economic disparity we
have right now,'' he said. ``The expectations for each manager are
different from what they have been. Small-market teams can't have
the same expectations for those managers as you once did. Before,
most of the teams had a chance to win, and expectations were
greater for each manager. People are more realistic now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Hunsicker of Houston said clubs might be viewing the job
more rationally than before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they're realizing that firing managers doesn't change a
whole lot of the results,'' he said. ``It's amazing how managers
become extremely smart when they have talent and extremely stupid
when they don't have talent. It transcends everyone, from Jim
Leyland to Tony La Russa to Joe Torre. They've all taken turns
managing last-place teams and coming under fire and they're still
among the most respected people in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Melvin, the Texas general manager, suggested that some
clubs might not have acted because they could not come up with
suitable replacements.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys don't want to take jobs on an interim basis,''
Melvin said. ``They want the job from Day 1 of spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   It is entirely possible that if one team had fired its manager
sometime this season, others would have followed. Often in the past
clubs wanted to make a change but did not want to be the first to
do it. When another team fired its manager, those other teams then
did likewise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
