u a BC-BEARS-MAIN0924-COX     09-23 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEARS-MAIN0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Many factors account for decrease in next year's bear population
 &HT;    By Gary Harmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Bears died in record numbers this summer
and next year's generation of cubs is likely to be thin, said the
state's top bear researcher.
</P>
<P>
   By 2002, though, the bear population likely will rebound from
the hard times of 2000, said Tom Beck, wildlife biologist for the
Colorado Division of Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``If conditions are right, within a year or two, you'll be
caught up,'' Beck said.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp spring freeze and the dry summer of 2000 forced bears to
expand their ranges for food. But what is a natural process for
bears amounted to an intrusion, as far as humans were concerned,
into the habitat in which homo sapiens is the top of the food
chain.
</P>
<P>
   When that happened, encounters between humans and bears vaulted
up as quick as a cub climbing a spruce tree.
</P>
<P>
   Bears invariably came out the losers in those encounters. They
ended up as road kill, they were blasted by landowners and wildlife
officers, they were shot with darts to tranquilize them and rushed
in metal tubes to new territory.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, a record 132 bears have been killed by law
enforcement and private citizens this year. That does not include
bears shot by hunters.
</P>
<P>
   The number and notoriety of human-bear encounters, however,
tends to obscure the fact that the bears are involved in a natural
process that poses little threat to the overall bear population,
Beck said.
</P>
<P>
   Bear distress is not unusual. In most years, eight out of 10, he
said, bears somewhere in the state suffer to some degree. People
tend to know nothing about that, though, because bears by nature
are secretive and prefer to avoid people.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, bears ``happen to be having a bad year where a lot of
people can see them, so it's a lot more apparent.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many bears will die this winter but that doesn't mean
that man should intrude deeply in the process, even though the
harsh summer will strike most heavily on the young, Beck said.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs born last January and this year's yearlings are the most
vulnerable, he said, because they have been unable to put on enough
fat for the winter, to say nothing of getting enough food for
normal skeletal and muscular development.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a significant die-off in the den,'' he said.
``They simply won't emerge from hibernation.''
</P>
<P>
   Something else will happen to reduce the number of bears that
emerge from hibernation next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Fertilized embryos in pregnant sows won't implant in the uterus,
so no cubs will be born to those bears, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, many of the young females that might otherwise be
expected to breed this spring and give birth in 2001 will be
reproductively stunted, delaying their estrous cycle by a year.
</P>
<P>
   The result of those factors could play out in the breeding
season of 2001, producing ``a big synchrony of cubs the next
year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor contributing to the likely health of the overall
bear population is that all bears haven't suffered equally in the
drought.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife officers have found bears with as little as a half-inch
of fat this year, putting them at a severe disadvantage against the
winter chill, said Steve Yamashita, area wildlife manager in the
Grand Junction office of the Colorado Division of Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Still other bears have been found packing fat layers as thick as
two inches, an ample store for the winter, Yamashita said.
</P>
<P>
   The sight of thin bears seeking food is understandably
distressing, Beck said, but not necessarily a signal that the
entire population is suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing for 1,000 square miles of bear habitat on the
Uncompahgre Plateau and figuring one square mile per bear, ``You
could have as many as 1,000 bears up there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have 20 or 30 or even 50 bears come down into town,
that still means you've got a lot of bears on the mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck said he discourages the idea of humans providing food in
natural bear habitat for a couple of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, if people mean to give food to starving bears,
putting fruit and other feed on the mountain won't help the bruins
that already are roaming elsewhere for food. It could, however,
cause conflicts among the well-fed bears that discover the food, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, older bears with established territories aren't
necessarily in danger during a lean year such as this, he said,
because their fat stores carry over from year to year.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that you can assign a bear about one square mile of
habitat isn't the same as knowing how many bears there are in a
given region, Beck said.
</P>
<P>
   Big boars, he said, can range across some 250 miles and share
territory with many bears. They tend not to gather in herds, but
they also aren't necessarily hostile to their own kind.
</P>
<P>
   Bears, Beck said, ``are solitary but social animals.''
</P>
<P>
   Bears will share food sources, such as berry patches and
acorn-laden oak brush, but they won't feed in the same places at
the same time as other bears, he said.
</P>
<P>
   They share food sources ``by time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While humans finding a food source might hoard it, bears will
eat their fill, leaving plenty for others, and move on, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After all, ``The best time to go exploring is on a full belly,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Well-traveled bears, though, are hard-to-count bears.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the fact that the black bears that populate Colorado
change color as the summer passes.
</P>
<P>
   The dark-colored bear he spots one day might be the blonde bruin
he sees a month or so later, Beck said. Their fur tends to lighten
as the summer goes along, almost as though they were getting their
hair bleached. New fur on bears tends to come in dark, lending some
a mottled appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The bears that have visited the Grand Valley have no intention
of remaining through the winter among human populations, Yamashita
said. They've already selected dens for their winter hibernation
and are on the move solely in a search for food.
</P>
<P>
   That search, though, has had dire consequences for several bears
and saddened wildlife officers used to dealing with bears and the
hard rules of nature.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle Sidener, district wildlife manager in the Division of
Wildlife, wrote in a report on a June incident where a landowner
had shot a bear.
</P>
<P>
   State law allows landowners to kill depredating bears and a bear
in a chicken coop certainly qualified. No one could know until
later, though, that the bear had no immediate interest in poultry.
</P>
<P>
   Scat discovered in the coop turned out to be ``100 percent
chicken feed,'' Sidener noted wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Sidener participated in the capture and relocation of a
250-pound bear on Road R, ``15 miles from suitable bear habitat,''
he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   For a bear, it was, Sidener wrote, ``Not a good place to be and
no place to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
