<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8972 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BEARS-REHAB0924-COX     09-23 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEARS-REHAB0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rehab center helps to insure bears' survival
 &HT;    By Ted Taylor
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SILT, Colo. _ The small rusty sign, propped against a wood fence
in the yard, tells you it's the Pauline S. Schneegas Western
Colorado Wildlife Rehabilitation and Education Center.
</P>
<P>
   But to the eight black bear cubs in pens on the other side of
the fence _ bellies full of apples, peaches and veggies _ it's the
Silt Supper Club.
</P>
<P>
   It is essentially the bears' only chance of survival through the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of them would have made it,'' said Nanci Limbach, the
woman who's been taking care of injured and starving wild animals
at her home for almost 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Limbach's property is also home to a bobcat, two golden eagles,
a dozen hawks, 11 fawns and an array of geese and ducks that soon
will be returned to their natural habitat. There are also two adult
mountain lions that can never be returned to the wild.
</P>
<P>
   But this summer, the focus has been on the bears.
</P>
<P>
   More black bear cubs than ever before are fattening up at the
rehab center thanks to virtually nonexistent food sources for them
and their parents in the high country.
</P>
<P>
   One pen for the typical bear or two Limbach might get during a
normal summer quickly became insufficient. She built another pen
earlier in the summer and remodeled a temporary pen. And on
Thursday, a new pen was built to accommodate a bear population that
could grow even bigger before fall is in full swing.
</P>
<P>
   All are orphan cubs who have either lost their mother to the
hands of hunters or have been abandoned by mothers trying to find
food to save their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   Some have wandered down into towns themselves looking for food.
</P>
<P>
   Adult bears live under the ``two strikes'' law that says that
after a bear is found in civilization and tagged, it must be killed
the next time it creates a problem for humans.
</P>
<P>
   Cubs, however, get three strikes, Limbach said, because they
aren't tagged the first time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys already have it in their heads to come down low
because that's what mom taught them,'' Limbach said. ``I've just
replaced their mother.''
</P>
<P>
   And like a mother, Limbach will push them out on their own very
soon.
</P>
<P>
   When they arrived, the cubs were well below what they should
weigh at this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   One of the cubs, who was rescued earlier this summer near Mack,
weighed only 37 pounds _ about 60 pounds underweight.
</P>
<P>
   But that's quickly changing. In Limbach's controlled habitat,
the animals get as much food as they can eat so they can build up
the fat needed to survive the winter hibernation.
</P>
<P>
   The bears eat a total of about 500 pounds of food per day and
are each gaining about 2 pounds of fat a day. When they're not
eating, they're sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   After a few weeks of seemingly perpetual eating, the cubs have
become little balls of fur and fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't play this time of year,'' Limbach said.
``Everything they eat is to build fat and they don't want to waste
any energy.''
</P>
<P>
   The bears will continue to fatten up until late November, when
Limbach will induce hibernation at the shelter. In late February or
early March, Limbach and Colorado Division of Wildlife officials
will head to the hills to build dens for the bears. The bears will
then be driven in by snowmobiles and placed in their new dens.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when they come out of hibernation in March,'' Limbach
said, ``I'm hopefully just a nightmare for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Limbach is a savior for the DOW, said John Broderick, a district
wildlife manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a real asset to the DOW and yet we don't support her
(financially) in any way,'' Broderick said. ``She's an excellent
example of a rehabilitator.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, when the rehab center had all the bears it
could hold, officials still didn't hesitate to call and ask Limbach
if she had room for just one more, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The bears at the rehab center have very little interaction with
humans, other than when Limbach or her husband, Paul, do the
feeding. The public isn't allowed to come and visit the bears like
they're at a zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Broderick said this makes it easier to release the animals into
the wild. When they need to be moved within the rehab center, say,
from pen to pen, they're drugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very wild,'' Broderick said. ``Those bears, in a
sense, are ready now to be released into the wild. They are not
tame in any manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Limbach said she is careful not to become too attached to the
bears while they're under her care. She enjoys taking care of the
animals and believes she's doing her part to get them ready for a
long and prosperous life in the Colorado backcountry.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes it's hard not to have feelings for them.
</P>
<P>
   An older bear who Limbach took care of earlier this year was
promptly shot by a hunter once it returned to the wild, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Limbach said, she's able to take something positive from
the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad; it's depressing,'' she said. ``But maybe it had at
least one happy month (here) without too much stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
