<HEADER>
A8973 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BEARS-STRIKES0924-COX     09-23 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEARS-STRIKES0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two strikes and their out
 &HT;    By Gary Harmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Only one bear captured so far this year
in Mesa County has had to be destroyed under the state's two-strike
policy.
</P>
<P>
   That bear was captured on Glade Park after it scavenged through
a kitchen, according to encounter reports filed with the Colorado
Division of Wildlife. When an officer confirmed that the bear was
tagged, he destroyed it.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, bears have one chance to cross the line into
human habitat. When they do, they're tranquilized, taken to remote
bear habitat and freed.
</P>
<P>
   If they return to human habitat, they have to be destroyed, the
law says.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as black-and-white as that, however.
</P>
<P>
   John Ellenberger, state big-game manager for the Colorado
Division of Wildlife in Grand Junction, said bears simply venturing
into town isn't necessarily something that requires immediate
action.
</P>
<P>
   When possible, wildlife officers try to make contacts with
humans as unpleasant as possible, using noisemakers, loud shouts,
even shooting them with non-lethal projectiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a bear is just wandering through and doesn't cause
problems, we don't respond with a trap or tranquilizer gun,''
Ellenberger said. If the bears don't move along by themselves,
though, or if they look to humans for food _ eating cat or dog
food, overturning barbecue grills, pawing through garbage cans _
then the division steps in.
</P>
<P>
   Captured bears are tagged and tattooed before being transported
a long distance away _ 75 airline miles is the rule of thumb,
Ellenberger said.
</P>
<P>
   A study done in southeast Colorado showed that only about 25
percent of bears that were trapped and tagged had to be destroyed
for a second strike, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The division also uncovered incidents in which relocated bears
returned to their home areas but never ran afoul of humans until
they were taken by hunters years later, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Beck, the division's top wildlife biologist, said the
two-strike policy works not so much because it changes bear
activity, but because it changes human behavior.
</P>
<P>
   People who are aware that leaving food accessible in bear
country are more likely to reconsider their actions if they know
the end result might be a first or second strike for a bear, Beck
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of the policy on bear-people conflicts is teaching
people how to live with bears,'' Ellenberger said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
