<SLUG> BC-DEL-REAL-645(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: WILMINGTON ADAPTS AFTER A MAINSTAY CUTS BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The word AT in parentheses has been used instead of the
symbol, which is nontransmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
 By MAUREEN MILFORD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ When DuPont Co. said in early 1999 that it
was selling three of its buildings, about 10 percent of the city's
office space, the announcement shook the community to its
industrial foundations. But a vibrant economy has helped smooth the
transition.
</P>
<P>
   The $25 million sale of the three headquarters buildings _ known
as the Nemours, Brandywine and Tatnall buildings _ to a development
partnership had some residents of this company town wondering
whether the mainstay citizen for almost a century was packing up.
</P>
<P>
   The sale capped a decade of real estate divestiture by E.I. du
Pont de Nemours &AMP; Co., the United States' largest chemical concern.
As the company strives to reinvent itself for the 21st century, in
part as a global life-sciences business, it does not consider real
estate investments to be the best use of corporate assets, said
William A. Sullivan, a former real estate manager at DuPont.
</P>
<P>
   All that remains in DuPont's real estate portfolio at its
headquarters complex is the DuPont Building, which was built in
stages beginning in 1906 and was one of the country's earliest
multipurpose buildings, with restaurants, theater, hotel, shops and
offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes sense from a business point of view for DuPont not to
have such a large headquarters, but for the city it's sad,'' said
Carol E. Hoffecker, a historian and the author of ``Corporate
Capital: Wilmington in the Twentieth Century.'' ``It seems like
such a dramatic symbol of the company's changing relationship with
the community.''
</P>
<P>
   But with over half of a $100 million redevelopment of the
buildings completed and DuPont leasing back a big part of the
Brandywine Building, city promoters see the divestiture as a
necessary regeneration. At a million square feet, City Center (AT)
Wilmington, as the project is called, is by far the largest
redevelopment of office space in the city's history.
</P>
<P>
   With a New Economy name, City Center will add 100,000 square
feet of retail space, 890,000 square feet of Class A office space,
75 apartments and 674 parking spaces to the city. ``It's brought in
new blood, new capital, and DuPont stayed,'' said William C. Wyer,
managing director of Wilmington Renaissance Corp., an economic
development group made up of city officials and top business
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   From a leasing standpoint, the timing could not be better.
Tenants have been having difficulty getting big blocks of space,
said Daniel R. Reeder, a senior vice president at CB Richard Ellis
in Wilmington. The city's overall downtown vacancy rate is 5
percent, but it drops to 4 percent for Class A space _ large newer
buildings with amenities and in good locations.
</P>
<P>
   Because plans call for a retail and residential mix, City Center
is expected to transform 11th Street.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, this main thoroughfare from Interstate 95 to the
downtown's Rodney Square has been without significant public spaces
other than the Hotel du Pont and the center lobby of the Nemours
Building. Office workers did not have to go outside, since the
buildings are connected by underground tunnels. This led architects
to criticize Wilmington for its lack of human scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's big, cold stuff,'' said Charles M. Weymouth, owner of
Weymouth Architects and Planners in Wilmington. ``There's no
relief, no landscaping, just the repetitiveness of windows, one
floor to the next.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding colorful awnings and flags, huge landscape planters and
lighting will make the area feel more hospitable, said Robert E.
Buccini, a partner in Wilmington's Buccini/Pollin Group, which
signed the deal with DuPont. Barrow Street Capital LLC, a private
New York real estate investment company, is providing the
financing.
</P>
<P>
   The 75 apartments in a section of the Nemours Building should
also go a long way toward making Wilmington a round-the-clock city,
Sullivan said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The 18-story Brandywine Building, built in 1972 on a triangular
plot, was the first to be renovated as offices. Kling Lindquist of
Philadelphia, the original designer of the D-shaped building, was
hired as project architect.
</P>
<P>
   City Center was given a boost at the start when DuPont agreed to
take 266,000 square feet for 10 years in the Brandywine Building,
which is still topped by DuPont's oval logo, in neon. Last month
the company moved 649 people into the renovated space. Several law
firms have signed leases on remaining space, including Young,
Conaway, Stargatt &AMP; Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   A steakhouse is expected to open this fall in space that was
formerly a bank branch. The steakhouse, to be called the Vault, is
operated by two restaurateurs who opened a Mediterranean restaurant
at Market Street Mall in Wilmington last year.
</P>
<P>
   It will have dining room seating for 115, a bar with space for
live entertainment and a mezzanine lounge with seating for 30.
There will also be tables for outdoor dining between the Brandywine
and Nemours buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in the restaurant include Charles M. Cawley, head of
MBNA America Bank, a giant credit-card bank that moved its
headquarters to Wilmington in the early 1990s, as well as two other
top MBNA executives. The investment is a message not lost on a city
accustomed to being dominated by DuPont.
</P>
<P>
   While DuPont was selling off buildings in the 1990s and cutting
its work force, MBNA put up five buildings on the northeast side of
Rodney Square, and it now employs thousands there. ``I think it
certainly has demonstrated very powerfully the transformation
Wilmington has been undergoing from a DuPont to MBNA town,''
Hoffecker said.
</P>
<P>
   The third building that DuPont sold _ the Tatnall Building on
11th Street, across from the Brandywine Building _ was demolished
to make way for a parking garage. DuPont had used the
90,000-square-foot building as a mail center.
</P>
<P>
   Tunnels will be available to Nemours and Brandywine tenants,
while a sky bridge that connects Nemours Building to the DuPont
Building will be torn down for security reasons, Buccini said.
</P>
<P>
   Now the developers have turned their attention to perhaps the
toughest part of the project, the 14-story Nemours Building, built
in stages from 1935 to 1942. Earlier this month Buccini/Pollin
Group began gutting the 600,000-square-foot building.
</P>
<P>
   Juniper Financial Corp., a 4-month-old Internet
financial-services company founded by several former executives at
Bank One Corp., has already leased 65,000 square feet. The
traditional hallways lined with marble and individual office doors
will give way to open floors that characterize the information age.
</P>
<P>
   An apartment wing will be carved out of 124,000 square feet on
the corner facing 10th and Orange streets. It will have its own
entrance lobby separate from the office lobby. Up to half of the 75
apartments could be leased for corporate use, with DuPont agreeing
to lease eight apartments.
</P>
<P>
   The floor plans call for studios to two-bedroom units. Rents for
the apartments will be decided nearer the opening in 2001, but a
one-bedroom apartment is expected to cost about $1,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the plan is to have the Hotel du Pont supply room
service, dry-cleaning pickup and other amenities for apartment
dwellers.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel will also cater to office tenants. A small auditorium
in Nemours could be converted to a movie theater, Buccini said.
Negotiations are under way for a first-floor restaurant in Nemours.
</P>
<P>
   The developers decided not to rename the buildings, believing
their DuPont heritage was an important part of the city's history.
Indeed, three du Pont cousins _ Alfred I., Pierre S. and T. Coleman
_ single-handedly transformed the city from an aging industrial hub
to an office center when they made the decision in 1904 to build
the company headquarters in Wilmington rather than in New York or
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   As the major shipbuilding and railroad-car manufacturing
industries waned, the du Pont cousins built a new business that
earned Wilmington the name Chemical Capital of the World.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilmington has been fortunate that when one of its Old Economy
businesses has been on the rocks, something new comes along,''
Hoffecker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000923.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8978 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BLACKS-STOCKS0924-COX     09-23 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-STOCKS0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Photo not available with this story.
 &HT;    Black investors losing wariness about stocks
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Black investors are getting less suspicious of the
stock market, says mutual fund executive Mellody Hobson.
</P>
<P>
   That's a major change, and one that should bring benefits to a
traditionally conservative group of investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individuals need to understand that over the long term, wealth
is created through the stock market,'' said Hobson, president of
Chicago-based Ariel Capital Management.
</P>
<P>
   The company's most recent survey of households with $50,000-plus
income shows that increasing percentages of African-American
households own stocks or plan to start buying them.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the study showed that blacks are more likely than
whites to save and invest for emergencies and college expenses or
to pass wealth along to their heirs. Whites are more likely to save
for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Hobson talked during a recent interview about insights provided
by the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why have African-Americans held back from the stock market?
</P>
<P>
   A: One of the key issues is knowledge. We have said, ``We have
not invested because we don't feel that we know enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason is exposure. We don't typically grow up in homes
where investing is discussed. We don't know people who work in the
field. The major Wall Street firms don't hire many
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we tend to be very conservative. We're talking about
people who are making money for the very first time. They are very
risk-averse. They are therefore picking what they perceive as the
safest investments. Bonds, insurance products. There is a real bias
toward real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why real estate?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's because you can see it. It's tangible; you can get
income from it, or borrow against it, or leave it to your heirs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a mistrust of the stock market?
</P>
<P>
   A: No question about it. This has a lot to do with exposure,
with the lack of diversity on Wall Street. We have felt the stock
market is intangible. Many say the stock market is like gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But your surveys show more African-Americans are investing in
stocks. Why is that?
</P>
<P>
   A: One reason is the continuing American fascination with the
stock market, which is certainly an offshoot of the market's strong
performance in the 1980s and '90s. The last 20 years have had the
strongest returns in the history of the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Second, I think the growing coverage of the stock market in the
press has made a difference. That has been driven by the increasing
incidence of 401(k) retirement plans. Before, the workplace would
take care of your retirement. Now you're making your own decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do rising incomes make a difference?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some. We looked at families with incomes of $50,000 and
higher. When we cut the data at a very high income level, over
$100,000, we saw very similar issues. Income was not as big a
driver as education was.
</P>
<P>
   The media are making a big difference, but there are a few
things that still need to be done. One is that investing should be
taught in schools. It amazes me that we have courses in auto repair
but not investing.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing is that Wall Street needs to help educate those
who have not typically invested in the stock market. To the extent
we can increase minority participation, that helps them. Everyone
wins.
</P>
<P>
   Also, corporations have to be attuned to their own
communications and enrollment policies for their investment plans.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can people get started in the stock market?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are terrific mutual funds out there. You don't have to
be an expert. You can find professional money managers who reflect
your own investment interests. Reading is another way to learn. Or
you can go to investment professionals, brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you find the best advisers?
</P>
<P>
   A: You ask people you know for the advisers they are comfortable
with. You want to find someone you trust and who will help educate
you along the way. Then you can check their references. That's very
important.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
