<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-POETRY-FESTIVAL-41     09-23 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-POETRY-FESTIVAL-415&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POETRY FESTIVAL INSPIRES THOUSANDS OF RHYME SCHEMES 
</HEADLINE>
   By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANHOPE, N.J. _ The attire ranged from athletic-coach casual to
the flowing-skirts-with-hiking-boots look, with an occasional beret
and silk scarf sighted. Grandmothers and pierced eyebrows were in
equal abundance. There were blind poets with guide dogs, slouching
young poets with infants asleep on their breasts, and everywhere,
under almost every tree, someone writing in a hard-bound notebook _
poets in their natural habitat.
</P>
<P>
   From as far away as Hawaii, thousands of people came to the
Geraldine R. Dodge Poetry Festival, which began on Thursday and
runs through Sunday, to hear some of the nation's and world's
better-known poets.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, nicknamed Wordstock by its fans, was expected to
attract 15,000 people to Waterloo Village, a restored colonial
enclave in Sussex County complete with a canal, a gristmill, and a
temporary Borders bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the weekend, Yusef Komunyakaa, Mark Doty, Lucille
Clifton, Chinua Achebe and Stanley Kunitz, among others, were
scheduled to read.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been anywhere where there are so many happy people
in one place for so many days,'' said Betty Lies, a poet from
Princeton who works with the Geraldine R. Dodge Foundation, the
festival's sponsor. ``People are happy, relaxed, and high on
poetry. It's not a frantic high, it's kind of a mellow high.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a circus tent, where mourning doves destined to appear in
someone's volume of Personal Reflections in the near future flew
through two at a time, capacity crowds of about 2,400 gathered to
hear Stanley Kunitz, 95, the national poet laureate, and Gwendolyn
Brooks, who won the Pulitzer Prize for poetry in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, an every-other-year gathering since 1986, is known
for attracting poets who, like their work, are accessible. James
Haba, the festival director, has brought together writers from a
variety of disciplines and cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to invite people who are really interested in a living
audience, who are not afraid to encounter that audience, and who
think there is some value to being in a room with people and giving
their words directly, at the moment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an afternoon discussion about teaching poetry, Billy Collins,
who has published six books, poked fun at the academy's infatuation
with obscure poems. ``It can't be good if it's clear,'' he said.
``I think we still have that masochism, in a way _ we need to see a
certain level of difficulty before we recognize it as literature.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As evidenced by the abundant yucks under the big top during his
reading, Collins draws people into his work by making them laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Heather McHugh, a chancellor of the Academy of American Poets,
displayed her trademark wordplay in her reading, sharing her
favorite anagrams (the letters of Dylan Thomas' name, for example,
can be rearranged into ``hot lady's man,'' ``Russian poetry'' can
be transformed into ``syrup into ears,'' and ``English poetry''
turns into ``nightly repose.'')
</P>
<P>
   After explaining her love for the counties of Pennsylvania, she
read a poem about a would-be seduction that ended, ``It was just
for Lackawanna that I didn't take him home,'' and she concluded
with a harrowing piece defining poetry as what could not be said by
the martyr who was burned alive in an iron mask that kept him from
speaking.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that writing poetry was something one owned up to
sheepishly _ an eccentric, somewhat suspect hobby, like a
predilection for collecting Mason jars. But after facing an
audience of 2,400 eager listeners, the poet Edward Hirsch, author
of ``How to Read a Poem and Fall in Love with Poetry'' (Harcourt
Brace, 1999), felt a quicker pulse in the art form.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were something like this in every state, the state of
American poetry would be completely changed,'' he said. ``It's so
powerful. People come with so many questions about poetry. The
enthusiasm about it is tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sander Zulauf, a poet who teaches at the County College of
Morris in Morris County and edits The Journal of New Jersey Poets,
the festival serves as a family reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see each other so rarely, because we work alone,'' he said.
``I just love the extraordinary poets, their responsibility to
language and their responsibility to humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Wesol, an English major at Brown University who had
driven from her campus in Providence, R.I., is used to listening
carefully at poetry readings, but enjoyed this weekend's
opportunities for interactions with writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just great to be at a place where poetry is celebrated
and emphasized,'' she said. ``You can be waiting in line for a
hamburger, talking about Lucille Clifton.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodge Foundation, based in Morristown, has chosen poetry and
the teaching of it as priorities. The foundation invited high
school students and teachers to the festival free on Thursday, when
6,500 people attended. Friday was devoted to teachers at all
levels, with 3,000 people showing up, twice as many as in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
