u i BC-EURO-INTERVENE-NYT &LR;      09-23 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-INTERVENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESCUE ATTEMPT FOR THE EURO FALLS SHORT OF BANKERS' HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE &UR; ,  &LR; Czech Republic _ One day after the world's major
central banks announced an unusual rescue attempt for the euro,
Europe's struggling currency, the effort showed signs on Saturday
of being more modest and tentative than it first appeared.
</P>
<P>
   To the disappointment of many European bankers, American
officials refrained from speaking out strongly in support of a
stronger euro and raised doubts about their willingness to
intervene forcefully in currency markets by selling dollars or
buying euros.
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting here on Saturday of central bankers and finance
ministers from the Group of Seven industrialized nations, the
president of the European Central Bank said the intervention, which
stunned money markets on Friday, was already over, at least for the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   And that was the case even though the euro rose to only 88 cents
against the dollar and is still far below what European bankers
want to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no strategy to continue and continue,'' the Central
Bank president, Wim Duisenberg, said here on Saturday night.
``Intervention will take place when we deem it appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the central banks are trying to have as much impact
on the market with the signals they send to investors as with the
money they spend buying up euros.
</P>
<P>
   And by all accounts, European finance ministers and the European
Central Bank scored a surprising coup by persuading the U.S.
Treasury to cooperate in a rescue attempt at all.
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday, the Treasury Department had consistently given the
impression of its strong skepticism about attempts at buoying up
other currencies at the expense of the dollar, and they continue to
repeat their conviction that a strong dollar is good for the
American economy.
</P>
<P>
   But American officials seemed more intent on lending the name of
the United States _ but not necessarily much American money _ to an
effort on behalf of the euro.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be bucks behind it,'' said Klaus Friedrich, chief
economist of Dresdner Bank AG in Germany, who was here for the
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Though Friedrich was happy that European officials were able to
orchestrate an effort that included the United States, Japan,
Canada and Britain _ the most significant European Union member
country still outside the euro network _ he remained unconvinced by
the American commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market badly needs a statement from the Americans that the
euro is substantially undervalued and the dollar is substantially
overvalued,'' Friedrich said.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not coming. In a communique issued by the Group of
Seven, the finance ministers merely repeated their ``shared
concern'' about the ``potential implications of recent movements in
the euro for the world economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, first signs indicate that the amount of money used to
intervene in the currency markets on Friday was very modest. The
European Central Bank gave no clue about the magnitude of its
campaign to buy euros or sell other currencies, but currency
experts and traders have estimated that the amount was about $6
billion or $7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That estimate may in fact be generous. Dow Jones Newswires,
quoting an anonymous official at the European Central Bank, said
the actual amount of the intervention was in the ``low single
digits,'' perhaps $2 billion or $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That is not insignificant, but it is not enough to have a
long-term effect given the trillions of dollars that sweep through
the global financial system every week.
</P>
<P>
   Psychology and timing may ultimately be more important to the
future of the euro than the amounts of money used by the world's
central banks on its behalf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
