<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9003 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-OPTIONS0924-COX     09-23 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPTIONS0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: PHOTO AVAILABLE.
 &HT;    Stock options spread wealth to all workers
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Stock options _ once a get-rich perk of white-collar
executives and technology whizzes _ have gotten democratized.
</P>
<P>
   One out of five American workers now have the opportunity to buy
shares in the company he or she works for, hopefully at a bargain
price.
</P>
<P>
   That comes to more than 10 million employees, including grocery
clerks, secretaries and factory workers.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is a major benefit for people like Cara Hoffhien, a
21-year-old who started as a counter clerk at Starbucks four years
ago. ``I really am going to do something with this company,'' she
said. ``This investment makes me feel like I'm really part of it. I
don't want to be just a worker bee.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest share of stock options still goes to top corporate
officers. But a new survey from the National Center for Employee
Ownership indicates that about a third goes down the line, to
middle managers as well as salaried, sales and hourly workers.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of companies now grant options to all employees. Among
them are Starbucks, along with Aetna, DeVry Institute, First Union,
Kodak, Pfizer, Procter &AMP; Gamble and Whole Foods.
</P>
<P>
   Even part-time workers can qualify at Starbucks and some other
companies.
</P>
<P>
   A stock option gives a worker the right to buy a given number of
shares, at a fixed price, for a stated number of years.
</P>
<P>
   The buying price often is the value of the stock at the time the
option is granted. Employees hope the share price will go up,
giving them an opportunity to buy company stock at a bargain price.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, deciding what to do with options can be
challenging. To start with, options can be either incentive or
non-qualified, and the tax treatment of them is different.
</P>
<P>
   The trend to providing more employees with options is driven by
business necessities, including a tight labor market and fierce
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies don't want to compete by raising wages because of
global competition issues,'' said Corey Rosen, director of the
Oakland, Calif.-based NCEO. Instead, companies sweeten the pot by
offering an ownership stake to employees.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is the changing nature of work. ``Most business
organizations, particularly in technology, have adopted a flatter,
more participatory work environment,'' Rosen said. ``If they give
employees more decision-making power, they want them to have more
of an interest in the decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Tax and accounting rules also encourage corporations to use
options, rather than base salary increases, to reward employees,
said consultant Laura Sejen of Watson Wyatt Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of stock options is not accounted for as an employee
expense, which makes earnings statements look better each quarter.
The impact of options expenses must be disclosed in a footnote,
however.
</P>
<P>
   For employees, the main attraction is the money to be made.
Hugely successful technology companies like Microsoft are famous
for rewards reaped from stock options.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Home Depot claims to have turned 2,000 employees _
secretaries and store managers included _ into stockholding
millionaires. That includes options recipients and employees who
bought stock at a discount.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey from Oppenheimer Funds found that 46 percent of
workers who receive options believe they will be able to retire as
much as five years earlier than expected.
</P>
<P>
   There are disadvantages. The value of the option is obviously
tied to the price of the stock. If employees concentrate too much
of their investments in their employers' shares, a down market
could have a significant impact.
</P>
<P>
   The young and hopeful, like Starbucks' Hoffhien, are not
discouraged. Option grants run 10 percent to 14 percent of base
salary, and Hoffhien buys more shares each payday through payroll
deduction. She now owns almost 200 shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really confident about where this company is going,''
she said. ``None of the fluctuations have scared me.''
</P>
<P>
   Her plan? She's getting married next year. Two or three years
from now she'll sell her shares to help buy a house _ if the share
price is high enough.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
