<HEADLINE>
SLUMP ENDS AS YANKEES BLAST AWAY IN RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ During the six games without a victory, their longest
drought in three years, the Yankees had withered from postseason
favorites to doubting shadows of their former selves. Lunging at
the plate, the Yankees could not find a way to break through their
futility.
</P>
<P>
   But they emerged on Saturday from the fog of their own failure
with an electric 13-8 comeback victory over the Detroit Tigers
before 40,029 on a rainy afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had 18 hits and delivered four home runs, including
three-run drives by Derek Jeter in the sixth inning and David
Justice in the eighth, his second homer of the game and 40th of the
season, tying his career high.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez broke his 0-for-28 hitless streak in the third
inning, following back-to-back home runs with a single. Scott
Brosius, who had two hits in his previous 20 at-bats, had two
singles and scored two runs on Saturday. And Paul O'Neill, who had
four strikeouts Friday, singled in two runs in the fourth inning,
reaching the 100 runs batted in mark for the fourth straight
season.
</P>
<P>
   But Roger Clemens struggled, giving up seven runs, six of them
in the fifth inning. Jeff Nelson allowed a single that led to
Detroit's eighth run in the seventh, but got the victory. Mariano
Rivera retired the side in the eighth inning and pitched the ninth
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson began the seventh by giving up a single to Juan
Encarnacion with the Yankees ahead, 9-7. The left-hander Mike
Stanton came in and gave up a broken-bat single to Bobby Higginson,
whose pop-up landed over Jeter's shoulder in short left field.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton struck out Billy McMillon, who had deflated the Yankees
with a grand slam in his previous at-bat. But with two men on,
Deivi Cruz hit a ball sharply to Jeter and it skimmed off the top
of his glove, allowing Encarnacion to score to shave the Yankees'
lead to 9-8. But that was as close as the Tigers would get.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees down by 7-5 in the sixth inning, Luis Sojo
singled off the reliever Willie Blair. Brosius followed with
another single and then Chuck Knoblauch singled to score Sojo.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter then hit a three-run home run to right field that put the
Yankees ahead, 9-7, and saved Roger Clemens from his second
straight loss.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who only 10 days ago was penciled in as the No. 1
starter in the division series, stumbled after he took a 5-1 lead
into the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   But his difficulties began in the third inning when he gave up a
leadoff home run to Damion Easley. The next batter, Brad Ausmus,
lined a pitch back to Clemens, hitting him in the leg. Clemens
threw to first in time, but the trainer Gene Monahan came out to
look at the pitcher. He retired the next two batters to get out of
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, Clemens plunked McMillon, the designated
hitter, on the foot with two outs, but got Cruz to ground back to
him.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth inning degenerated into a debacle reminiscent of Denny
Neagle's fifth-inning unraveling Friday night. Clemens gave up a
leadoff single to Hal Morris, then walked Easley. Ausmus doubled to
the wall in center field, scoring Morris. Again, Clemens struggled
with his control, trying to pitch inside on Jose Macias and hitting
him instead, and then walking Encarnacion, which brought in another
run, making it 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens struck out Bobby Higginson and got Dean Palmer to pop-up
to shortstop. Mike Stanton was warming up in the bullpen, but Torre
kept Clemens in. McMillon, the designated hitter, battled Clemens
to a 2-2 count, then blistered the next pitch to the upper deck in
right field for a grand slam and Yankee Stadium fell into a stunned
silence as the Tigers took a 7-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth major league homer for McMillion, the Tigers'
minor league player of the year, who was called up July 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had opened the scoring in the second inning when the
leadoff batter David Justice blasted his 39th home run of the
season, giving the Yankees their first lead in six games. Jorge
Posada followed, hitting his 27th home run to right field, his
first homer since the Yankees' last victory, on Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, the next batter and the emblem for that frustration,
broke out of his slump by singling to right. In the fourth inning,
the Yankees added to their lead with a rally.
</P>
<P>
   After Martinez led off and flied out to deep right, Luis Sojo
reached base on a bloop single. Then Brosius laced a single to
left. Knoblauch fouled out, but Jeter cracked a single that scored
Sojo.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill then got his first hit in seven at-bats, singling in
Brosius and Jeter. That also knocked out Mlicki with the Yankees
holding a 5-1 lead. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
