<DOCNO> NYT20000923.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9018 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CUSTODY-BATTLE0924-CO     09-23 1966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTODY-BATTLE0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Child caught in middle of affluent parents court battle
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Ask to see Case No. 95-7096, and
courthouse clerks roll their eyes and shake their heads. They don't
have to look it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ohhh,'' they groan. ``Keitel. You want the whole thing?''
</P>
<P>
   That would be 10 boxes of files, 40 volumes and growing, a giant
hairball of a divorce and custody battle that demonstrates how one
case with the right ingredients _ money, legal savvy and an endless
supply of animosity _ can choke a court system.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, it escalated into a no-holds-barred brawl,
with the ex-husband _ Palm Beach lawyer and real estate investor
Frederick J. ``Rick'' Keitel III _ accusing Circuit Judge Mary Lupo
of negligence, incompetence, prejudice and unethical conduct, and
Lupo _ the latest of eight judges saddled with the case _ giving
him a verbal horsewhipping and threatening to ban him from the
courtroom unless he gets another lawyer to speak for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This court is obliged to try to protect Mr. Keitel from having
a 'fool for a client' by continued self-representation,'' Lupo
wrote in a scathing Sept. 8 order.
</P>
<P>
   ``(T)his judge is so prejudicial, angry and hateful towards
(Keitel) that he has no chance of getting a fair and impartial
hearing,'' Keitel fired back. Last week, he moved that Lupo take
herself off the case and transfer it out of Palm Beach County or he
would ask the 4th District Court of Appeal to remove her.
</P>
<P>
   Keitel v. Keitel has amassed more than 2,100 docket entries,
spawned at least 10 appeals, spun off a handful of other suits and
been through two hearing officers and eight Circuit Court judges _
six who recused themselves and one whom Keitel accused of bias
before he was even appointed to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Keitel, 48, owns office buildings in Palm Beach and once put
together a deal to buy 27 Wendy's restaurants in South Florida. The
venture fell through in 1992, and the resulting legal tangle is
also still in court.
</P>
<P>
   Keitel and Diane de LaBegassiere, 44, both tall and attractive,
met at a party in Palm Beach and married in 1992. She had the
social pedigree: fourth generation oil royalty, descendant of the
founders of both Texaco and Exxon, French upbringing, net worth
more than $20 million. Possibly a lot more, since the financial
disclosures were filed before the stock market boom.
</P>
<P>
   Her ex-husband, who listed his own income at $500,000 a year,
grew up in a middle-class home in New Jersey where his father owned
a motel, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   The two have been at war over their 5-year-old son, Sebastian,
since before he was born. Keitel left his wife when she was
pregnant, he said in court documents, because she continued to
smoke and drink during the pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The court record is not flattering to either of the parents, who
have splattered each other with the sort of allegations that are
practically de rigueur in Palm Beach divorces: alcoholism,
psychotic behavior, marijuana and cocaine abuse, party sex,
three-way sex, same-sex sex, kidnapping _ even child abuse, though
no judge has believed it.
</P>
<P>
   Psychological reports and custody evaluations in the record say
that both parents, despite their ``selfish vendettas,'' appear to
love the child they use as a weapon against each other.
</P>
<P>
   Both are battling for sole custody of Sebastian, who lives with
his mother in New York and is enrolled in the French American
School in Larchmont. Keitel claims he spends $150,000 to $200,000 a
year in travel and living expenses to exercise his weekly
visitation, because De LaBegassiere moved to New York in violation
of court orders.
</P>
<P>
   The visitations have routinely turned into angry encounters
between the parents, according to the court record, leading to
allegations of kidnapping, assault and obstruction and involving
police on several occasions.
</P>
<P>
   The Keitel case has consumed more time, paperwork, lawyers and
judges than even the most notorious disunions played out in Palm
Beach County Circuit Court. Roxanne and publishing heir Herbert
Pulitzer required only 835 docket filings to split the sheets in
1982, and Ruth and auto mogul Roger Dean's notably nasty 1992
breakup ended with No. 1,635.
</P>
<P>
   Keitel and De LeBegassiere both declined to comment on the
record for this story. But in court documents, each side blames the
other for the size and ferocity of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Keitel contends he has to keep filing motions for contempt _
more than 30 are outstanding _ because his ex-wife continually
ignores orders to share Sebastian's medical and school records,
thwarts his visitation and tries to get it reduced, and that judges
won't do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   De LaBegassiere claims Keitel harasses her with multiple daily
telephone calls, interferes with Sebastian's schooling and medical
needs, is obsessed with tape-recording the child's conversations
and makes false statements about her, including that she is a
continuing alcohol abuser.
</P>
<P>
   Keitel has had eight lawyers, including his brother, represent
him off and on since the case began. He sued his original attorney,
Robert Shalhoub, alleging he was in cahoots with his ex-wife's
lawyers and a previous judge on the case. But he has been his own
client much of the time, and in that role has clashed with a long
line of judges over his legal maneuvers and courtroom behavior.
</P>
<P>
   De LaBegassiere has spent more than $1 million on legal fees and
costs, in the estimation of West Palm Beach attorney Joel Weissman,
who represents her along with his partner, Doreen Yaffa, and
Melinda Gamot. She also has hired lawyers in New York, plus several
therapists for Sebastian, including Dr. Paulina Kernberg, the
Cornell University psychiatrist retained by the federal government
to evaluate Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Hearings and motions are laced with vitriolic exchanges between
the pugnacious Weissman and Keitel, who has accused his ex-wife's
lawyers repeatedly of lying, concealing records, conspiring to get
friendly judges assigned to the case and having hearings without
properly notifying him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it has reached that point,'' Weissman said. ``It has
degenerated to where he has to put the focus on somebody else, and
. . . I have never been one to sit idly by or not speak my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have filed grievances against each other with the
Florida Bar. Keitel's motion to remove Lupo says the bar complaint
against him contains 33 allegations, and that he has filed a
459-count complaint against Weissman, Gamot and Yaffa. A Bar
spokesman said the complaints are under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Keitel declined to say whether he has complained about any of
the judges, including Lupo, to the Judicial Qualifications
Commission. A JQC spokeswoman said she couldn't confirm or deny
complaints unless they result in formal charges, and no charges had
been filed as of last week.
</P>
<P>
   Each side has taken aim at various judges _ sometimes the same
one. Trial Judge Kathleen Kroll stepped down after De
LaBegassiere's lawyers complained that she was biased against the
heiress because of her wealth, though Keitel later complained that
the judge was biased against him.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Roger Colton, who ordered De LaBegassiere to move back to
Palm Beach County, also recused himself after a bias complaint that
Keitel alleged was orchestrated by her lawyers, but signed by her
because they didn't want their names on it.
</P>
<P>
   Keitel accused Kroll and Judge Stephen Rapp of ``criminal,
illegal and unethical behavior'' because of actions and inactions
of theirs that he felt were detrimental to him and asked the state
attorney and chief judge to investigate. Neither office pursued the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   He alleged his ex-wife's attorneys persuaded her to hire a
lawyer from Judge Thomas Barkdull's former law firm, to create a
conflict of interest so he could be removed.
</P>
<P>
   The last judge to throw in the towel was Gary Vonhof, who took
himself off the case last December after nearly two years. Vonhof
said in his recusal order that he had stayed on because he felt one
judge should hear the case for a reasonable length of time to
protect the interests of Sebastian.
</P>
<P>
   ``However,'' the order said, ``because of the personalities of
the parties, the motions for contempt and petitions for
modification and the endless acrimonious hearings have not ended.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the last things Vonhof dealt with was Keitel's allegation
that his ex-wife was sexually abusing Sebastian by dressing him in
girls' clothing and allowing him to sleep in her bed, both of which
the mother denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was simply nothing presented to the court that even
remotely resembled proof of any sexual abuse,'' the judge said in
denying Keitel's request for custody.
</P>
<P>
   Vonhof directed the court clerk to reassign the case to some
other family division judge _ except for those who'd already
stepped down or been subpoenaed by Keitel as witnesses, like Judge
Timothy McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   So the case landed with Lupo, long noted for a sharp tongue and
short patience with litigants or lawyers she perceives as
unreasonable or wasting the court's time.
</P>
<P>
   In a July 31 order, Lupo lashed Keitel for ``persistent filing
of frivolous, immaterial, irrelevant, impertinent, scandalous and
repetitive motions and pleadings.'' She said he consistently
disrupted the court with ``endless rambling arguments, by his
outbursts, and by other activity which is clearly designed to
impede and obstruct the administration of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   That order has become an exhibit in the Bar investigation of him
and means Lupo will be a witness against him, Keitel said in his
removal motion. Five other judges _ Vonhof, Kroll, Rapp, Colton and
McCarthy _ have been interviewed by the Bar in conjunction with his
complaint against his ex-wife's lawyers, according to Keitel's
motion.
</P>
<P>
   At a brief scheduling hearing on Thursday, Lupo gave no
indication she intends to recuse herself. She told Weissman, Gamot
and Palm Beach attorney T. Westray Battle, who said he was making a
``limited appearance'' for Keitel and trying to find him a
permanent lawyer, that she will try in October to set the custody
issues for trial by March.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court should not be micromanaging this family or any
other,'' Lupo said. ``But it's better than bloodletting on the
streets . . . and these matters are obviously important to little
Sebastian.''
</P>
<P>
   Lupo cited a previous hearing in which she had worked through a
calendar by weeks, days and hours to divide up the child's time
with each parent for the summer. The session had the guarded and
painstaking tone of hostage negotiations, with each side referring
to the ``pickup,'' the ``dropoff'' and the ``exchange.''
</P>
<P>
   Sebastian's life, according to court reports, consists of
nannies, school, French and drama lessons, double sets of clothes
and toys and rooms, Dunkin' Donuts _ his favorite snack _ and
constantly being handed back and forth across the borders of the
alien worlds of his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sebastian seems to be a droll, fairly articulate
five-year-old,'' says a report by Toby Pilsner, a New York lawyer
engaged to do home studies for a custody evaluation. But the little
boy is ``very angry,'' Pilsner wrote, and ``knows much too much
about the situation from both parents because they cannot control
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is evident that both parents manipulate this situation to
play out their own unresolved battles with each other,'' the report
says. ``Sebastian clearly loves both his parents, who are tearing
him apart as they wage their war against each other, with the
heaviest casualty being the damage done to their son.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
