<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9021 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-FLIGHT-SERV0924-COX     09-23 2111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLIGHT-SERV0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flightserv relied upon an ancestor company for launch
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Todd Bottorff was brought in to help pull
Flightserv.com out of its dive in late May, he faced some
Internet-sized challenges.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta company's stock had dropped 90 percent from its
52-week high, after ranking as Georgia's best-performing stock last
year.
</P>
<P>
   A New York money manager had canceled the second half of a $10
million investment. Few business travelers were using Flightserv's
Web site, www.flightserv.com., which offers individual seats on
private jet flights between Atlanta and New York. And the company
was running out of cash.
</P>
<P>
   So over the next several weeks, Flightserv's new president and
chief operating officer cut the staff and marketing budget. Its
sporadic flights waned to nothing. Bottorff also plunged into
retooling Flightserv's business model and rounding up new investors
and business partners.
</P>
<P>
   Such problems and countermeasures are by now familiar to
managers of once high-flying Internet companies. But unlike with
most Internet firms, Bottorff had an extra set of challenges to
deal with. The reason: Flightserv is at least the fourth
incarnation of a so-called public shell corporation that has passed
through bankruptcy court three times.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most Internet companies that sold shares in the past few
years through initial public offerings, Flightserv hadn't recently
been scrutinized by an investment banking firm, or filed lengthy
registration statements with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, before selling shares.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Flightserv is one of a growing number of small
companies that gained instant access to a stock exchange by buying
a public shell, usually a defunct company with shares listed on a
stock exchange but little in the way of assets or operations.
</P>
<P>
   With shells, ``people do not go through the IPO process. That
means that the discipline has to come from the management and the
shareholders,'' says Bottorff.
</P>
<P>
   But in today's post Internet-boom market, he adds, ``I think
that any investor that is putting money in the Internet right now
has a high level of scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the collapse in Internet shares, Flightserv has
completed a private stock placement totaling $2.6 million. Two
stock-swap acquisitions added a start-up air charter service with a
$9 million contract to fly passengers to Cancun, Mexico, and a call
center service with annual sales of $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bottorff was named interim chief executive officer after
Flightserv's former CEO, C. Beverly Lance, resigned in August from
his executive and director positions. Lance, the son of former
Carter administration budget chief Bert Lance, couldn't be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Flightserv needed new management that is ``significantly more
experienced in areas that are directly related to the success of
the model,'' says Bottorff. With his wife, he co-founded
HeliosHealth.com, an Atlanta firm that wires doctors' offices to
provide online information to patients. His wife still runs the
company.
</P>
<P>
   With the changes that have been made, Flightserv now has a
``very compelling model'' in place, says Bottorff. ``This strategy
lowers the risk while keeping the upside'' of Flightserv's nascent
Internet flight booking service alive, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Bigger changes are coming to Flightserv in about three weeks,
but Bottorff won't elaborate. ``The story's going to change
dramatically,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Change, it turns out, is one thing Flightserv's ancestor company
has gone though quite a bit of itself.
</P>
<P>
   The shell company's former lives include a Maryland drug testing
company, Keystone Medical Corp., that went bankrupt around 1988,
according to a former executive, Joel Holt. The company passed
through bankruptcy court in Tulsa, Okla., twice more in 1992 and
1995.
</P>
<P>
   A Tallahassee real estate developer bought the shell company
next. But after a failed attempt to take over a developer of an
Atlanta-area golf course community, the shell was once again sold
at the end of 1998 to Flightserv's founders.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, many investors' holdings were wiped out or reduced
to penny-stock levels before the next round of new owners took
over.
</P>
<P>
   Isser Elishis, whose New York firm pulled the plug on its
Flightserv stake, says this is the first and probably the last time
his company will invest in a company that used a public shell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just chalk it up to Murphy's Law that what can go wrong will
go wrong,'' says Elishis, senior portfolio manager for Acqua
Wellington Asset Management. He says the company's $5 million
investment in Flightserv is currently worthless because its
unregistered Flightserv shares can't be sold on a stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the shares were registered, Acqua Wellington's stake
would currently be worth about $1 million at Friday's closing price
of $1.25 on the American Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one just didn't work for us,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Sam Brown, a retired construction company
owner from Newnan, says he had likewise written off his Flightserv
investment of just under $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   But he has now bought more shares, he says, since Bottorff
announced several recent changes in Flightserv's operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm cautiously optimistic,'' he says. ``If they will go ahead
and execute now, I think they've got a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   From Wall Street to Main Street, Elishis, Brown and other
Flightserv investors have plenty of company in their experience
with shell companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, so-called reverse mergers combining a
shell company with a new owner made a big comeback as entrepreneurs
rushed to cash in on the Internet mania. The volume of announced
reverse mergers more than quadrupled in 1998 to $86.8 billion from
about $18.6 billion the previous year, according to Thompson
Financial Securities Data. Reverse mergers fell slightly in 1999,
to $62 billion, and are down to about $8 billion so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   There are legitimate reasons to use publicly traded shell
companies, including raising capital more cheaply and passing a
company on to employees or heirs, says Eric Stevenson, president of
Axiom Capital, a Phoenix consulting firm that advises clients on
reverse mergers. Ted Turner launched Turner Broadcasting System
that way, and shells were used by Occidental Petroleum and
Blockbuster Video, he says.
</P>
<P>
   But there are inherent risks. First, says Stevenson, there's the
risk of hidden liabilities that surfaces after the new owners
arrive. ``What you're really doing is taking over someone else's
failure. There's liabilities with that. Buyer beware,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Second, he says, ``the people that sell shells these days are
into it to profit off your story. ... They're looking for something
that's exciting and easily explained.''
</P>
<P>
   And shell companies are ``the typical type of vehicle those
people have used,'' for a stock manipulation scheme known as a
``pump and dump,'' he says, often without the knowledge of the
entrepreneurs who bought the shell company. To drive up the stock's
price, unscrupulous stock promoters artificially pump up the
trading volume by selling shares back and forth. At the same time,
they hype the stock through a combination of press releases and
e-mails to Internet stock chat rooms. After they sell the stock to
investors at a big profit, the stock price plunges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that (shell companies are) bad things,'' says
Stevenson. ''It's more that they're used badly. They're a license
to print money, and there's a responsibility with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottorff says he's seen no signs that Flightserv's stock was
caught up in a pump-and-dump manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the skyrocket trajectory of Flightserv's stock during
the past year mirrored that of many similar companies caught up in
the feeding frenzy for Internet stocks, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that if you look at the charts of Internet companies
over the past six months, many of them look the same,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   `A STORY STOCK'
</P>
<P>
   Flightserv evolved from the public shell bought by Arthur
``Buddy'' Weiss and C. Beverly Lance. When Weiss and Lance acquired
Proactive Technologies last year, its shares traded well below $1,
and daily volumes were usually in the thousands or tens of
thousands of shares.
</P>
<P>
   But daily trading volume began topping 100,000 shares within a
few months of the acquisition, and Proactive Technologies' stock
started slowly climbing.
</P>
<P>
   By October last year, after Proactive Technologies had announced
that it was in the Internet aviation services business, had changed
its name to ``flightserv.com'' and had hired the first of four
former Delta Air Line executives, daily volume swelled sometimes to
700,000 shares. The stock price approached $6.
</P>
<P>
   It would nearly double that price during the next two months. By
the end of 1999, Flightserv was the top-performing stock in
Georgia, up 3,450 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what happened is, in the Internet chat rooms, this
became a story stock,'' says Ben Branch, a University of
Massachusetts finance professor and former director of the shell
company. ``I never understood at that point what they were going to
do in aviation service.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, hundreds of messages about Flightserv were being posted
on Silicon Investor, Raging Bull and other popular Internet stock
chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stock will go up, it has risen 150% in the last month. .
. . When the web sight gets going, Flight Serve will fly!''
declared ``aaabond'' on Raging Bull's site on July 15 of last year,
when the stock traded at $2.75. The investor posted several more
bullish messages on the site until Oct. 12, when Flightserv's stock
closed at $7.44, before dropping from the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Silicon Investor, a handful of investors were selling
Flightserv's stock short, or selling borrowed shares in hopes of
profiting from a later price decline. They suspected that
Flightserv's stock, whose stock ticker symbol is FSW, was being
manipulated.
</P>
<P>
   ``FSW getting pumped again today by (another Web site),'' wrote
``Harpo'' in a Dec. 7 message to another trader. ``Could be in
shortable territory again. What do you think? The last quarterly
filing is, um, interesting to say the least.''
</P>
<P>
   Flightserv's stock peaked at $12 on March 9, the same day it
answered Branch's and other investors' questions by activating its
Web site and announcing it would sell seats on private jets to
business travelers between Atlanta and New York. The company, which
by then had a market value of $397 million but little revenue, said
it expected to have 100 routes by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume topped more than 1 million shares that day.
</P>
<P>
   But the party was drawing to a close for Flightserv's investors,
as it would for many other investors in Internet stocks. By the end
of April, Flightserv shares were back to $2.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Coggin, a former Delta executive vice president who was
the first Delta alumnus Flightserv hired, has since left his job as
senior strategic adviser.
</P>
<P>
   He had recommended that the company use a combination of direct
mail, direct sales and advertising in The Wall Street Journal and
other national publications ``to reach out to the business
traveler.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never got around to implementing the marketing strategy
that we recommended,'' he says, but ``I don't understand why
(Flightserv) hasn't been more successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottorff says the other three former Delta executives have since
departed as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got here, the guys from Delta were frustrated by the
delays in implementing the company strategy,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some uncertainty about what the company wanted to be
when it grew up. The company needed a very detailed, thoughtful
strategy,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Acqua Wellington, concerned about its investment, was
balking at forking over its second $5 million installment.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Flightserv hit its downdraft last spring with many
other tech stocks, Branch, the former Proactive Technologies
director and shareholder, had already sold off his Flightserv
shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed to me that if (Flightserv's business plan) was such
a great idea, it would have been done long ago,'' he says. Plus,
the company only had ``maybe $4 million in hard assets, maybe,'' he
adds, compared to a market value of almost $400 million at its
peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``That said to me, get out of your stock, which I did. I just
didn't see that the value was there for the company,'' he says. ``I
made money. I was lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
