<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shell company has taken different shapes
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before it became Flightserv.com, the shell company
that launched the Atlanta dot-com had at least two previous
reincarnations.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which had started as a Maryland drug-testing firm
in the 1980s, had already gone through bankruptcy twice by the time
Tulsa, Okla., entrepreneur Bill Davis bought the shell in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Stock of the shell company, then called Keystone Medical,
doubled to $10 in a few months after Davis announced a new company
name and business direction.
</P>
<P>
   Davis says he did a reverse merger of his start-up business
software firm into the defunct drug testing company's shell, once
again stripped of its liabilities and most of its assets in
bankruptcy court, as a way to quickly list his company on a stock
exchange. He wanted to raise capital at a time when initial public
offerings were getting a cold reception, he says. He renamed the
merged company Proactive Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   But the stock had dropped to about $1 by the time the shell
landed again in bankruptcy nine months later. The company' gyrating
stock price drew the attention of the Securities and Exchange
Commission, says Davis. No formal action was taken in the case,
according to an SEC spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got an education in shells,'' says Davis.
</P>
<P>
   In bankruptcy court, he accused three individuals, who had
retained a stake in his company after selling the shell, of fraud
and conflict of interest. They countersued. The parties eventually
settled and split the software and drug-testing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Next, a Tallahassee real estate developer, Mark A. Conner,
bought Proactive Technologies' shell company out of bankruptcy
court in 1996. In the two years following the reverse merger, he
rapidly expanded his small real estate empire, reaching as far as
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Florida developer tried unsuccessfully to take over
Killearn Properties Inc., a publicly traded Georgia developer of a
golf course community in Henry County. Struggling under debt after
the failed attempt, Conner quickly sold off assets _ including
Proactive Technologies' public company status.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about that time that Buddy Weiss and Beverly Lance came
on the scene,'' recalls Ben Branch, a University of Massachusetts
finance professor who served on Conner's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur ``Buddy'' Weiss and Lance combined a couple of Atlanta
shopping centers and a start-up company called Stratos Inns with
Proactive. Weiss and Lance became chairman and CEO, respectively,
of Proactive Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Branch, whose investment in Proactive Technologies was
underwater by hundreds of thousands of dollars by then, says he
gladly departed the board in February 1999, when he and another
director were replaced by Lance and a Nashville investment manager.
</P>
<P>
   Branch was also glad to see that his Proactive Technology
shares, once worth as little as a quarter a share, started taking
off within a few months. A little over a year later, the company's
shares would briefly reach $12 _ a 4,700 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   The new owners first sold Conner's surviving real estate units
back to the developer and cleaned up some unforeseen liabilities.
Weiss told the Tallahassee Democrat those surprises included a
$105,265 lien from the IRS for unpaid payroll taxes and $90,000 in
unpaid interest on a $2.1 million loan that Proactive Technologies
had defaulted on without his knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Weiss said the idea for the private jet
service was conceived after he and Lance acquired Proactive
Technologies as a real estate business.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
