u s BC-FBN-KURTWARNER0924-CO     09-23 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KURTWARNER0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Warner-led offense is a defense's nightmare
 &HT;    By Ken Sugiura
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To sleep, perchance to dream.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Brown only wishes. Not this week, not with Kurt Warner and
his passing chaos coming to town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not been sleeping,'' said Brown, coach of the Falcons'
defensive backs. ``I have not slept a wink, and neither has our
secondary.''
</P>
<P>
   Every fan is familiar now with Warner, the conductor of the
high-speed train that will come blowing through the Georgia Dome
this afternoon. Unwanted out of college, he kicked around the Arena
Football League and NFL Europe before an injury to another player
made him the Rams starting quarterback. Then he became just the
second player in league history to throw 40 touchdown passes in a
season, and he led St. Louis to perhaps the most improbable Super
Bowl season in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the Rams offense looks even better. The Rams have
scored a league-high 119 points. Their NFL-record streak of most
games in a row with 30 or morepoints has run to nine. Running back
Marshall Faulk is on pace to surpass his NFL record for yards from
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, to be honest with you, if I've ever seen a
better offense than this one,'' Fox NFL analyst John Madden said.
</P>
<P>
   And Warner, who went from stocking shelves in a supermarket to
throwing touchdowns in the Super Bowl, is hot. He threw for 441
yards against Denver in the first game and has gone over 300 yards
in all three games. He leads or is close to the lead in every major
statistical category.
</P>
<P>
   Some people might have thought him a fluke last year. Not too
many think that way now. Those around him say he's more confident
and has a better grasp of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so on top of the stuff that, whatever you put in or
insert that week, he understands immediately what you're trying to
do,'' Rams coach Mike Martz said. ``Absolutely, he's better than he
was a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   During the offseason, the Falcons and every other team tried to
dissect the Rams attack and find a way to slow it down. No one has
succeeded yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams are doing the same thing as last year _ spreading fast
wide receivers all over the field and creating mismatches. Except
they are doing it even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me put it to you this way,'' Brown said. ``When the Rams
are on offense, it looks like you let a bunch of greyhounds on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   With copious help from blazing wide receivers Isaac Bruce, Torry
Holt and Az-Zahir Hakim and running back Marshall Faulk, Warner is
on pace to take a swipe at many of the single-season passing
records. He is on track to break Dan Marino's record for yards
(record _ 5,084, pace _ 6,512), Warren Moon's mark for completions
(404, 442) and Ken Anderson's record for completion percentage
(70.55, 71.55). If he throws for 300 yards in the next three games
_ against the Falcons, the Chargers and then the Falcons again _ he
will tie Steve Young for most consecutive 300-yard games.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams defense, ironically, gets more credit than it wants.
Last year, the defense was sixth in the league and held up the
offense's leads. In 11 of the Rams' 13 wins, they held at least a
10-point lead at halftime. As a result, the offense could cool down
after the half. Warner threw only 12 of his 41 touchdowns in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   But the defense has been so poor this season, next to last, that
the team has needed Warner's heroics all game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like it's a different thing this year, where they're
so desperate, they have to throw,'' said Hall of Fame quarterback
and ABC analyst Dan Fouts. ``Which is not a bad deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner and his pals are ready for anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just kind of the standard that we've set,'' he said.
``We don't have any problem living up to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
