<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AIMS DIRECTLY AT GORE ON CHARACTER AND ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ At the end of a campaign swing that was intended
to focus on issues, Gov. George W. Bush stepped up his personal
criticisms of Vice President Al Gore on Saturday, accusing him of
``misleading Americans'' through a ``pattern of embellishments and
sudden reversals.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush assailed Gore in a speech he delivered by satellite to the
state committee of the Pennsylvania Republican Party. He cited a
series of incidents involving the Gore campaign last week that he
said provided telling insights into the vice president's character.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent has unfortunately spent the week misleading
Americans,'' Bush said. ``His misrepresentations are serious
business _ not the legitimate debate of political disagreements.
They are a disturbing pattern of embellishments and sudden
reversals.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also took aim again at President Clinton's decision to
release oil from the nation's emergency reserves, portraying the
move as political opportunism. The reserve, Bush said, ``was
created for America's national security, not for the vice
president's political security.'' Gore had called for the reserve
to be tapped just a day before Clinton acted.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seized on Gore's assertion at a news conference that he had
been involved in discussions about the strategic oil reserve in the
days since it was first established.
</P>
<P>
   ``He claimed he was involved in the very invention of the
Strategic Petroleum Reserve,'' Bush said. ``The problem is the
reserve was first established in 1975, two years before Al Gore
even went to the United States Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, Bush tied together a week's worth of examples to
ridicule Gore. He brought up matters as varied as Gore's attendance
at a Hollywood fund-raiser, at which the vice president muted his
previous criticism of the entertainment industry, to his quip to a
union group that ``Look for the Union Label'' had been one of his
childhood lullabies. The song was not written until years after
Gore's childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Bush made a similar mistake earlier in the campaign when he
named as one of his favorite childhood books one that had not been
written until he was a student at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   Gore responded to Bush through his own campaign telephone call
to a union representing electrical workers. ``The other side said
they wanted to talk about the issues, but that didn't seem to last
very long,'' Gore said to the group, which was meeting in
Cleveland. ``With our whole future at stake this is no time for
personal attacks, which is why I'll never make any.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of Gore's, Douglas Hattaway, immediately pointed to the
ties that Bush and his running mate, Dick Cheney, have both had to
the oil industry. ``The Texas oil ticket is on the defensive
because they've been making excuses for the oil industry while Al
Gore is fighting to cut oil prices,'' Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   Hattaway stood by Gore's assertion that he had been involved in
discussions about the oil reserve since its first days. He said
that while it was authorized by law in 1975, the reserve was in its
early days of creation in 1977, when Gore was serving on a House
subcommittee on energy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has called for more domestic oil exploration, sought
on Saturday to turn the focus to the country's increased dependence
on foreign oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about big foreign oil. I'm worried that under the
vice president's policies America is more dependent on foreign oil,
and domestic production is at its lowest level in almost 50 years _
since 1954.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign also responded sharply to an Associated Press
report that law enforcement officials were investigating whether it
had been a Bush official who mailed materials about Bush's debate
preparations to an associate of Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, Bush' communications director, said that Bush's
campaign manager, Joseph Allbaugh, was calling the Federal Bureau
of Investigation to complain. ``If they have identified a suspect,
Gov. Bush would like to know,'' Hughes said.``It is completely
inappropriate and wrong for the Justice Department to play politics
by leaking information in the midst of a presidential campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI was called in when a Gore adviser, Tom Downey, a former
member of Congress, alerted law enforcement officials that he had
been sent the package of materials anonymously. Downey, who had
been helping Gore in debate preparations, recused himself from
further sessions.
</P>
</TEXT>
