<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9028 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-SPORTSCASTER0924-     09-23 2158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SPORTSCASTER0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Announcer is Braves' `professor' of telecasts
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Her name was Mrs. Balcolm. She taught social studies
at Charlotte Junior High in Rochester, N.Y., and her lesson plan
always included a career project. Her eighth-graders were to pick a
career that piqued their interest, research the profession and
write a report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put down, `baseball announcer,' '' Pete Van Wieren said. The
next morning that fall of 1957, Mrs. Balcolm summoned the
eighth-grader to class and said, ``That's very nice, but it's not
realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Balcolm checked her handy list of professions and picked
one out for the young Van Wieren. ``Here,'' she said. ``Nobody has
picked optician.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't want to do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Mrs. Balcolm insisted. ``Take optician.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the young geek's eyeglasses. Who knows?
Nevertheless, Van Wieren did what he's always done. He dutifully
did his job. Learned all he could about the wonderful world of
opticians, then handed in his report. And just what did he learn?
</P>
<P>
   ``Only that I knew I didn't want to be an optician,'' Van Wieren
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Balcolm should see her young visionary now. Nearly five
decades later, he is celebrating his 25th season of broadcasting
Atlanta Braves baseball. The kid that Ernie Johnson helped hire,
then nicknamed ``The Professor,'' has become just that: one of the
most respected professionals in his profession, and as
knowledgeable a baseball historian as you'll find.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best play-by-play man in America,'' says Don Sutton, the
Hall of Fame pitcher and now Van Wieren's on-air partner. ``I watch
40 games a week. There are a lot of guys who can do a lot of
different things. But if you want to watch a ballgame, and be
entertained by a game, there's not a better guy in America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a guy who wasn't a player, he has very good instincts for
what's about to happen, a very good feel for the game,'' said Joe
Simpson, the former outfielder-turned-Braves broadcaster. ``That
comes from loving the game and having a passion for something you
want to learn about as much as you can. And as good as he is in
decades later, he is celebrating his 25th season of broadcasting
Atlanta Braves baseball. The kid that Ernie Johnson helped hire,
then nicknamed ``The Professor,'' has become just that: one of the
most respected professionals in his profession, and as
knowledgeable a baseball historian as you'll find.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best play-by-play man in America,'' says Don Sutton, the
Hall of Fame pitcher and now Van Wieren's on-air partner. ``I watch
40 games a week. There are a lot of guys who can do a lot of
different things. But if you want to watch a ballgame, and be
entertained by a game, there's not a better guy in America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a guy who wasn't a player, he has very good instincts for
what's about to happen, a very good feel for the game,'' said Joe
Simpson, the former outfielder-turned-Braves broadcaster. ``That
comes from loving the game and having a passion for something you
want to learn about as much as you can. And as good as he is in the
booth, as easy as he is to listen to, he's one of the nicest men
I've ever known.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate the s.o.b.,'' said Skip Caray, Van Wieren's
silver-anniversary broadcast partner. ``He's a hell of an
announcer. He should have been a network announcer full time. He
can do football, and has. Baseball, and has. Basketball, and has.
He has the perfect network style, and he's totally unflappable. If
a piece of equipment breaks down in the truck and you've got to
cover for that, he does it as well as anybody in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a fan of the game, a baseball historian and very
knowledgeable about the game without overdoing it,'' pitcher Tom
Glavine said. ``He comes up with very interesting facts that are
pertinent to the game. It's not like he's getting this information
to show you he's smarter than you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, you hear announcers trying to be funny, or
trying to degrade players. Pete doesn't do any of that. He doesn't
get into criticizing players a lot, if at all. It's not his style.
But when he does, it means something.''
</P>
<P>
   It meant everything in May, when the Braves began a West Coast
trip in San Diego and the John Rocker Show first hit the road.
After Rocker had a Friday night confrontation with a photographer,
Van Wieren ripped the reliever on the air the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That coming from Pete, it means something,'' Glavine said.
``It was like, 'Hey, E.F. Hutton's talking. Let's listen.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I had to say something,'' Van Wieren said. ``It was a
very upsetting time on the club, and everybody was tiptoeing around
it. Maybe as a manager or player you couldn't say anything, but I
felt I could. I was disturbed we had the biggest story of the
baseball season so far _ the winning streak _ and you had to go to
page three in the paper to find out about it. The focus needed to
get back where it belonged: the performance on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where it's always been for Van Wieren. For him, the
playing's the thing. The preparation and professionalism, too.
There's no ``we'' in Pete. He never refers to the Braves as such,
even if he lives and dies with the club more than any of the other
broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's out of respect for those in the audience who aren't a
fan of that club,'' Van Wieren said. ``You owe them that courtesy
and nonpartisanship. It's the fan's job to react and root, the
broadcaster's job to describe.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a job Van Wieren has done spectacularly well for more than
three decades, and with the care and philosophy he had since first
working Binghamton Triplets Eastern League games in upstate New
York in the late '60s. ``My philosophy's always been pretty much
the same,'' he said. ``I knew I wasn't coming in with a 20-year
career as a player. I didn't have a big name that people recognize.
So I always felt I had to do as accurate and honest a job as I
could do.''
</P>
<P>
   When Van Wieren called Triplets' games, he would stop by the
sports department at the Binghamton Evening Press on his way to the
ballpark to check ``Pete's peg.'' John Fox, the sports editor,
would leave box scores from the previous night's Eastern League
games. Van Wieren used them to update his personal stats on every
team and was prepared when each hit town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God, there were only six teams in the league,'' he said.
Years later in Atlanta, long before there were personal computers,
Van Wieren kept a day book _ a daily statistical update _ on every
Braves player. ``I still feel what got me here was preparation and
being as thorough as I could,'' he said. ``And have fun with it. No
reason you can't.''
</P>
<P>
   No reason you couldn't be a broadcaster and not an optician.
Even if your father left your mother while you were still in the
womb. ``I never met my dad,'' Van Wieren said. ``Never knew what
happened to him 'til about five years ago. He died in 1974.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, his son had come a long way from Greece, the Rochester
suburb where he was raised in his maternal grandparents' house by
his mother, Ruth, grandparents Wilbur and Eunice Jardine, and an
extended family that loved baseball. An only child, Van Wieren had
three aunts and scads of cousins who all were crazy about the game.
</P>
<P>
   He saw his first Rochester Red Wings game by age 4 and by 8
never missed a game, either on radio, listening to Jack Buck call
games, or in the ballpark on weekends. Each summer, the entire
family took a road trip to see the Red Wings play in Toronto,
Montreal, Buffalo or Syracuse. There was an annual trip to
Cooperstown, to the Baseball Hall of Fame. And every day, all day
in Swansea Park, the kids played ball in the street.
</P>
<P>
   Pete loved baseball. Loved bowling, too, and would later host
the popular weekly king-of-the-hill ``Challenge Bowling'' TV show
each Sunday at noon in Binghamton. The extra $30 each week was well
worth it, even if it meant interviewing one champion who had no
teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd ask him a question, and he'd give me an answer,'' Van
Wieren said. ``To this day, I have absolutely no idea what he
said.''
</P>
<P>
   It helped prepare Van Wieren for the wonders of live TV, though.
His passion for broadcasting never waned, though, not even when he
went to precisely the wrong upstate New York college for an
aspiring sportscaster. Instead of Syracuse, which spawned such
talents as Bob Costas and Marv Albert, Van Wieren went to Cornell.
There, he wrote sports for the campus Daily Sun and majored in
English and _ drumming.
</P>
<P>
   They called themselves The Hustlers, from the Paul Newman-Jackie
Gleason movie ``The Hustler.'' They were five fraternity brothers
from the Alpha Delta Phi house who played frat parties on weekends
and Wednesday gigs at the Closer Club in Ithaca. ``We all had
crewcuts and we all wore sunglasses,'' Van Wieren said. ``That was
our look.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, they opened for big acts passing through town, or even
accompanied them while students danced the ``Mashed Potatoes'' or
the ``Locomotion.'' Dion. Freddie Cannon. The guy who now provides
the soundtrack for Glavine and Greg Maddux once laid down the
backbeat for Chubby Checker, if not Bo Diddley. ``We opened for
him,'' Van Wieren said, ``but Bo brought his own band.''
</P>
<P>
   His future was in broadcasting, though, not percussion. At the
urging of a Braves scout named Harry Dorish, Van Wieren called a
Cornell baseball game one day when the play-by-play announcer was
late. Van Wieren felt comfortable, did well and got hooked.
</P>
<P>
   His first job after college was announcing high school football
in Warrenton, Va., home of the Fauquier Falcons. ``If you ever get
a job like that,'' he said, ``you'll learn how important
pronunciation is.''
</P>
<P>
   At WNBF in Binghamton in 1966, Van Wieren wondered why Triplets'
games weren't aired. Told that no one could sell air time, Van
Wieren did, with the help of the team's general manager, in
exchange for doing the play-by-play job himself. He began sending
out audition tapes, worked briefly in Toledo and got his first big
break in 1974 with the Class AAA Tidewater Tides in Norfolk, Va.
</P>
<P>
   When Milo Hamilton was fired by the Braves after the 1975
season, Van Wieren applied for the job. Ernie Johnson and Wayne
Long, the Braves' vice president of marketing and broadcasting,
were very impressed with Van Wieren's tapes, even more with the
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to like his voice, and he was a very studious type
of guy,'' Johnson said. ``He had everything in order. Always
well-prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   A week after Van Wieren was hired, the Braves were sold to Ted
Turner. That meant several years of outrageous ostrich races and
cow-chip-throwing contests involving announcers and owner. It also
meant more work for Van Wieren after Turner fired long-time
traveling secretary Donald Davidson and replaced him with the first
guy Turner saw walking down the hall _ Van Wieren.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, he doubled as a broadcaster and traveling
secretary, fretting over travel plans even while calling a game.
``The seventh or eighth inning, Pete would get paged and turn white
in the press box,'' Caray said. ``The bus was late, or the plane's
late, and he had to get up and leave: `Here's the windup and the
pitch, and here's Skip.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He had moments of even higher anxiety. Such as the West Coast
trip when Van Wieren forget to bring the $5,000 in meal money. He
also had to do the uneasy balancing act between being privy to
inside information about players and having to go on the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of times, I had to get players out of jail,'' he
said. ``And I couldn't say anything about it the next day. That was
hard to do.'' Finally, Van Wieren got the nerve to approach Turner
and ask out. ``And he said, `OK,' '' he recalled. ``I said, `Geez,
if I'd have known that, I'd have done it years ago.' ''
</P>
<P>
   If he would have known all that has ensued over the last
quarter-century, he never would have written that optician's report
years ago for Mrs. Balcolm. The 13-0 start in 1982, climaxed by
winning the NL West. The bad, bad years of the late '80s. The
wonder of worst to first in 1991, when the Braves boarded the team
charter from Pittsburgh to Minneapolis after winning the NLCS and
Van Wieren saw the National League championship trophy propped in a
first-row seat and told TBS producer Glenn Diamond, ``We're going
to the World Series!''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the world championship in '95, the heartbreak of
'96 and now another chance to put a World Series exclamation point
on a decade of unparalleled greatness. Through it all, Pete Van
Wieren, who turns 56 on Oct. 7, has been there. Has been himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not trying to be anybody else,'' he said. ``You can't copy
anybody else's style. That never works.''
</P>
<P>
   That's never been necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
