<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9029 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-ARCH-MARION0924-C     09-23 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARCH-MARION0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marion Jones is 'grace under pressure'
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ They were lying next to each other in the darkness _
the clock next to them burning through the night _ and neither
could doze off.
</P>
<P>
   ``C.J. kept telling me, 'Close your eyes,''' she was saying. ``I
told him I was trying to keep them closed, but I just couldn't fall
asleep. It was a very difficult night. In my mind, I just kept
going over my race.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, no wonder Marion Jones is sleepless in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The race she was visualizing _ Saturday night's women's 100
meter final _ was the ultimate eye opener.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first chapter of ``Marion Jones Superwoman'' and it
brought the crowd of 110,000 to its feet cheering, screaming and
knowing very well it could be witnessing the coronation of one of
the great athletes to ever pass through the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is trying to do what no other woman has ever done. In a
marathon session that will tax the mind and the body, the
27-year-old American sprinter, long jumper _ and former NCAA
champion basketball player _ is trying to win five gold track and
field medals at a single Games. The great Jesse Owens and Carl
Lewis both managed four, but you'd have to go all the way back to
1924 to find Paavo Nurmi _ The Flying Fin _ who won five golds in
one Olympic track an field session.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was Jones' debut and after a fitful night of insomnia,
she proved that sleep may well be an over-rated commodity.
</P>
<P>
   She is not.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-9 running machine _ a seemingly perfect specimen of
power, efficiency and grace _ turned the 100-meter final into Tiger
Woods winning the U.S. Open, Secretariat dominating the Belmont.
Enduring a chilly evening and a noticeable headwind, she still blew
away the field to win by almost three full strides. She finished in
10.75 seconds. Ekaterini Thanou of Greece was second at 11.12 and
Tanya Lawrence of Jamaica was third at 11.18.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' winning margin _ .37 seconds _ was the greatest in the
history of the women's Olympic 100 meters. Only one men's 100 final
has had a wider gap between gold and silver.
</P>
<P>
   Although U.S. teammate Maurice Greene would win the men's 100
meters in 9.87 seconds, it was obvious from the time Jones stepped
onto the track in her shiny silver shoes, she owned Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   As she was introduced to the crowd _ and the seven other women
in the race tensely waited the call to the starting blocks _ she
waved her arms to the adoring masses, flashed that megawatt smile
and then blew kisses to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Watching her on what had to be one of the most intense moments
of her life, you started to understand what makes her to special.
It's her grace under pressure. Later when someone asked her if _
like Carl Lewis once said _ it was a relief to get the first race
out of the way, she thought a moment and shook her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it like that at all, `` she said. ``I wouldn't
call it a relief. It's not a stressful time for me. It's a happy
time. I'm having a ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Her 330-pound husband C.J. couldn't say the same. He stood near
the finish line and said he felt ``physically sick. I was so worked
up, all I did was scream and worry. I don't remember seeing much of
the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what he missed:
</P>
<P>
   After giving herself a quick verbal pep talk and exhaling
mightily, Jones marched to the start and lowered herself into
position She wore small pearl earrings and a thin gold necklace
about her neck. After closing her eyes for a moment's meditation,
she awaited the gun.
</P>
<P>
   Enduring two false starts by other runners, she burst from the
blocks in a flush of muscle and adrenaline, her head down, her arms
quickly picking up their piston-like rhythm. Some 16 strides into
the mad dash, she finally looked up and eyed the ever-closing
finish line.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Olympic Games,'' she said. ``You don't save
anything. You don't leave a thing out there (on the track).''
</P>
<P>
   As she crossed the finish line, her arms flew open toward the
heavens, she let out a scream and then, in that endearing
little-girl manner, she gave a joyful hop. As she realized what had
happened, her hands were drawn to her heart, then her eyes which
began to leak tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of Olympic Games, seen how other runners cross
the line and start to cry,'' she said later, her eyes again
brimming with tears. ``I'd thought I'd be a cool cat and celebrate,
but then you cross the line and everything goes out the window. It
hits you that you now can be described as an Olympic champion. That
was really emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   When she spied her mother and brother along the rail, she ran
over to them and gave her mom a kiss. Someone handed her a Belize
flag in honor of her mom, who comes from the Central American
country. Soon Jones had an American flag too and she carried them
with her around the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right then, everything was just so overwhelming,'' she said.
``For 19 years I had been living and dreaming this and then it all
came down to one race. It turned out to be everything I'd dreamed
of...and so much more.''
</P>
<P>
   When the gold medal was finally draped around her neck, she held
it in her hand and studied it intensely as Thanou and Lawrence
joined her on the platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just really wanted to inspect it,'' she said. ``I've seen
other athletes glance at it, but I really looked at it close. It
has no rough edges. It's very smooth. It was very glamorous
looking.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounded as if she had looked into that medal and seen her own
golden reflection.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
