<DOCNO> NYT20000923.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9031 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-OLY-FOOD0924-COX     09-23 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-FOOD0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A roo awakening
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Possibly it was an emu swing.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't tapping on the table, but I must have been shifting in
my chair. The waitress had come by to assure me. ``It will be ready
in one minute,'' she said. ``I didn't know where it was, so I had
to chase it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase it?
</P>
<P>
   Since the dish in question was a plate of kangaroo, I couldn't
help but smile. If I'd been quick enough, I might have said,
``Well, tell the kitchen to hop to it.'' Or: ``When I say roo it,
jump to it.''
</P>
<P>
   But no worries. This was turning into one of those magical
Sydney days. On a mission to check out the native flavors and
ingredients of Australia, I had traveled seven miles by ferry
across the harbor to get to this restaurant, a place called Red Gum
in the little town of Manly. And yet I was never bored. At the
ferry station, a chattery group of old Russian women resembled a
pile of hats and coats blown in by the wind from Moscow. And
because the Olympic regatta was under way, the boat had to dodge an
ensemble of dancing sails, making for a slow ride to Manly.
</P>
<P>
   I had eaten kangaroo once before, but this was superb _ rare,
tender and without a trace of the gaminess that some people find.
Sliced and piled high on a bed of garlic mashed potatoes and
ensconced in a little puddle of quandong sauce (more on that in a
