memory. It was no roo awakening, but a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   Australia is like that. From lemon myrtle to quandong (the tart
peachlike fruit of the native sandalwood tree), from wattleseed to
emu, there's a palette of exotic flavors here that you won't find
anywhere else in the world. Paired with the region's wealth of
seafood, and the techniques and traditions of Sydney's Asian
population, it's a culinary arrival. Here, then, is quick survey of
foods that are unique to Australia:
</P>
<P>
   Lemon myrtle: An aromatic leaf from a luxurious rainforest tree,
it is suffused with the scent of lemon. It reminds me of Kaffir
lime leaves. You don't know whether to eat it, or polish your
furniture with it. Chef Raymond Kersh of Edna's Table uses lemon
myrtle to infuse olive oil, and puts it on the table with a basket
of bread, crushed black pepper, shards of salt and grindings of
akudjura (or bush tomato). I think they should put the fragrant
branches in the Olympians' bouquets.
</P>
<P>
   Akudjura (bush tomato): I only had it dried and crushed, as
above, but it was a wonderful combination of earth and smoke _ like
a very mild chili pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Emu: Would you believe emu carpaccio? Sliced thin like the
Italian classic, this klutzy big bird had been transformed into a
delicate-tasting nibble.
</P>
<P>
   The chef at Red Gum had barely seared it on the edges, then
plated the garnet ribbons in starfish pattern. The emu had a
faintly wild taste, like venison only very subtle, but the bulgur
wheat and tomato salad on the side washed it clean.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney rock oysters: They are small, with beautiful clawlike
shells. Served raw, need nothing more than a squeeze of lemon. Then
they become astringent, slightly zincy and sing out best with a
glass of crisp white wine. They are also being prepared all over
town in the Chinese style, steamed with ginger and long thin
strands of scallion. I could eat a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Quandong: This makes a beautiful ruby sauce and works well in
desserts. Kersh and his sister Jennice have opened a temporary
restaurant at the Olympics' Main Press Centre, where I tried a wild
lime tart topped with the fruit, which looks like bleached apricots
and has a slightly bittersweet taste. I liked the pungent little
limes even better.
</P>
<P>
   Crocodile: I'm still trying to find out the true flavor, but
served tempura style and rolled in a nori wrapper by the Edna's
Table folks, it was quite good. Nothing like the chewy, jerky
texture you'd expect.
</P>
<P>
   Vegemite: Made by Kraft since 1926, this weird vegetable spread
is Australia's answer to peanut butter. One wag wrote in the Sydney
Morning Herald the other day that the salty, foul-smelling black
stuff was originally made from brewery waste. He also advised that
you apply the thinnest possible layer to toast with lots of butter.
I tried it, sans butter, as I wrote this piece. Concentrated yeast
extract? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Vegemite nights. Give me days of wine and roos'es.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
