<HEADER>
A9041 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-SENATE-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      09-23 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO FINDS HIS DEFINING ISSUE AND POUNDS AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rep &UR; . &LR;  Rick Lazio made no mention of campaign finance
reform in his speech accepting the nomination as the Republican
Senate candidate on May 30. In eight years in Congress, he was
never closely identified with the issue, although he did vote on
House bills advocating it. And he barely mentioned the subject
until August, after two months of aggressive and fruitful
fund-raising showed him catching up to his rival.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last few weeks, he began talking like a crusader
about rooting out soft money, which political parties and interest
groups use to allow candidates to skirt legal limits on political
fund-raising. It is, Lazio said, ``the kind of money that has
distorted the political process, the kind of money that has kept
young people from having more confidence in the political system,
the kind of money that is unregulated, unlimited and creates a
great deal of cynicism for the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks before Election Day, Lazio's advisers believe they
have finally found the issue that gives their candidate a
recognizable public profile.
</P>
<P>
   The advisers, and some outside strategists, say Lazio's embrace
of campaign finance reform has given him a way to stand toe-to-toe
with his opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton, to put her on the
defensive and show, despite his obscurity as a little-known Long
Island congressman, he can play in big league politics. There is
also a practical side; Lazio is outraising her in strictly
regulated hard-money contributions and so stands to benefit
financially from such an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But he also gains from no agreement, said Zenia Mucha, the
senior adviser to Gov. George Pataki, a patron of Lazio's
candidacy. Merely raising the issue plays into Lazio's line of
attack that Clinton, any Clinton, cannot be trusted. Lazio's
advisers say polling, their own and by independent organizations,
shows that a key weakness for Clinton is her trustworthiness, not
only stemming from association with White House scandals but also
from the belief she is in this race more out of self-interest than
out of concern about New York.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also true Lazio has made his boldest strokes on the
issue at times he or his campaign came under scrutiny. His one and
only appearance with Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who has
championed campaign finance reform, came Aug. 4, a few days after
Lazio's brief appearance at the Republican National Convention fed
a round of ``Where's Rick?'' articles.
</P>
<P>
   He initiated his soft-money pact at a news conference at Planet
Hollywood in Manhattan 10 days later _ the day Clinton appeared at
the Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles, where Hollywood
fund-raisers were held on her behalf.
</P>
<P>
   And he brandished the pact again a month later at the
candidates' first debate, on Sept. 13 in Buffalo, with his actions
seen as a pivotal opportunity to make a stamp on voters' minds
after Republican murmurs about a lethargic campaign had grown
worrisome. From that point on, Lazio has pushed the issue
relentlessly, frequently raising it to deflect questions about
whether he was too aggressive in dealing with Clinton during the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe that whatever the motive, Lazio has
finally demonstrated an ability to stand up to Clinton, to cast off
questions over whether he belongs in the same arena as the first
lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is showing he is as big as she is,'' said Rick Wilson, a
Republican consultant who advised Mayor Rudolph Giuliani on his
aborted Senate bid. ``He is showing he can take on a national issue
and be a national player. He has not been able to score on her with
anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   But few see Lazio as morphing into McCain, who reserved judgment
on how this issue might affect Lazio's standing. ``I can't make the
argument if this helps or hurts his political campaign, although I
am a supporter of his,'' McCain said Friday in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   A number of people from McCain's staff joined Lazio's campaign,
most notably Michael Murphy, Lazio's senior strategist. He has
copied some elements from McCain, employing a campaign bus with the
name ``Mainstream Express'' (as opposed to McCain's ``Straight Talk
Express'').
</P>
<P>
   Whether the theatrics of confrontation will help sway voters, or
whether the issue itself is a touchstone issue for voters, is
debatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is for cleaner campaigns. And so it is kind of a
no-lose issue for Lazio,'' said James E. Campbell, a professor of
political science at the State University of New York at Buffalo.
``It's going to be an extremely close election, so anything that
puts a dent in Clinton's public image is helpful to Lazio.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
