<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9051 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0924-COX     09-23 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Networks shrug off debates in favor of ball
coverage
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two of the four biggest broadcast networks said Saturday that
they would not carry the first presidential debate between Texas
Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore. NBC will broadcast
a first-round baseball playoff game instead of the Oct. 3 debate;
Fox has decided to show entertainment programming that night,
network executives said. Fox's corporate partner, the Fox News
Channel, will carry the debate. Television contracts with Major
League Baseball require networks to broadcast games despite debate
conflicts, NBC News spokeswoman Barbara Levin said. This was
brought up with the presidential commission organizing the debates,
she said, adding: ``We have no choice.'' The debates are expected
to run on ABC, CBS, public broadcasting stations and the three
cable news networks _ CNN, Fox News Channel and MSNBC. Fox also is
scheduled to run baseball during the Oct. 5 vice presidential
debate and the second Bush-Gore challenge on Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   POLL FINDS GORE AHEAD OF BUSH IN BATTLEGROUNDS STATES
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore appears to have a clear lead over George W. Bush among
voters in the key battleground states of Illinois, New Jersey and
Pennsylvania largely due to Gore's favor among women voters, a
Chicago Tribune Poll out today shows. Gore is seen as more
personable and thoughtful than Bush and respondents favor his
policies, according to the survey, which also polled Michigan and
Ohio voters. The poll found Gore is most popular among suburban
women _ a crucial block of voters. Married women who do not work
outside the home seem to favor Bush.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN-USA Today-Gallup national tracking poll released Saturday
found 48 percent of voters favor Gore, 45 percent are for Bush _
within the poll's 4 percentage point margin of error. A Newsweek
poll out Saturday also showed the race within the margins, at 47
percent for Gore to 45 percent for Bush. Gore had been up 10 points
in the CNN-USA Today-Gallup tracking poll earlier in the week and
was up by 8 points in the last Newsweek poll, both among likely
voters.
</P>
<P>
   GAY GROUPS TO STEP UP CAMPAIGNS
</P>
<P>
   Several activists for gay and lesbian groups said that their
organizations plan to step up political efforts over the next seven
weeks to influence voting in November. ``Gay, lesbian and bisexual
voters make up 5 percent of the national electorate,'' said
Elizabeth Toledo of the National Gay and Lesbian Task Force. ``We
have the power to swing close elections, specifically closely
contested congressional and state elections and even the race for
the White House.'' Groups plan to use grass-roots campaigns in
every state to register gay and lesbian voters and help get them to
the polls.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON BRINGS IN BUCKS FOR DNC
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton drew out high spending donors in California on
Saturday who paid $10,000 each to attend a Democratic fund-raiser
in Silicon Valley. The president helped raise $400,000 at the
Democratic National Committee luncheon, one of eight events
scheduled over three days in California and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   NADER DRAWS RECORD CROWD
</P>
<P>
   Green Party presidential candidate Ralph Nader drew a record
crowd of 12,000 people in Minneapolis, Minn., on Friday, who paid
$7 each to hear him denounce the major party candidates. ``This is
the largest gathering of paying citizens of the entire year,''
Nader told the raucous, whistling crowd. Nader's running mate,
Winona LaDuke _ who lives on the White Earth Reservation in
northern Minnesota _ spoke about generational justice and the
environment
</P>
<P>
   BUSH SR. HOLDS TONGUE NO MORE
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush, who had vowed to keep a civil
tongue while his son campaigns, verged as close as he has ever been
to endorsing the House vote to impeach Clinton. At a fund-raising
luncheon in Miami on Friday for Rep. Bill McCollum, who is running
for the Senate, Bush seemed to support McCollum's vote to impeach
by saying: ``I'm not in the issue business any more . . . But I'm
in the character business. And I know a man of character when I see
one. I saw him take a lot of heat a few months ago in the House,
held his head up high, and did what he felt was right. And whether
you agree or not _ and I 100 percent agree _ I think people
respect'' his decision. The father of George W. Bush added that if
his son is elected president ``we will restore the respect, honor
and decency that the White House deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   BAYLOR WANTS TO HOST PRESIDENTIAL LIBRARY
</P>
<P>
   Baylor University says it is the place to host a presidential
library for Bush _ assuming he wins in November. Baylor President
Robert Sloan Jr. told the Waco Tribune-Herald on Friday that
consultants are helping to look into landing a library to house the
mementos of a Bush presidency. ``You have to take a few risks in
life to be on the cutting edge,'' Sloan told the Tribune-Herald.
Baylor regents have not yet approved a library project, but Sloan
said they seem willing. If Bush loses, the university also would be
interested in hosting a gubernatorial library for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   _Compiled by Sandra Sanchez from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
