<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9055 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-SWIM0924-COX     09-23 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. depth dominates fastest meet
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ The 2000 Olympic swimming competition ended Saturday
the same way it began a week earlier: exceeding all expectations
with inspired performances by national heroes and sudden stars.
</P>
<P>
   And in the final analysis, Gary Hall Jr. was right and Mark
Spitz was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The meet was the fastest in history, with 15 world records and
38 Olympic records. The United States continued its domination,
winning 33 medals, including 14 gold. However, the rest of the
world isn't treading water _ 17 other countries won medals, with
seven earning golds.
</P>
<P>
   As Hall predicted, the U.S. smashed Australia like guitars. The
Aussies, who had hoped to knock the Yanks off their pedestal, won
18 total medals, their best result since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're faced with a worthy opponent, it really forces you
to get your act together and step up,'' said Hall, who won two gold
and has been nothing but complimentary of the Aussies since his
good-natured jibe. ``We were able to use that threat of being
dethroned as the best swimming nation as motivation to reach a
level that otherwise we might not have reached.''
</P>
<P>
   The legendary Spitz provided some motivation himself. He said
that the U.S. women wouldn't win any gold medals, then saw them win
seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mark should have known better,'' said Jenny Thompson,
who won a record eighth career gold medal _ all in relays _
Saturday as the U.S. women's 400-meter medley relay demolished the
world record. ``We had a lot of heart and swam with tremendous
spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Spitz can still point to his own meet in Munich in
1972 as the greatest ever, since 30 world records were broken.
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney medal haul was the fourth-highest in American
history. The U.S. won 52 medals in 1968 and 43 in 1972, but in
those days the team had three entrants in each event, compared to
two today. The U.S. also won 33 medals in the boycott-marred 1984
Olympics which had 29 events, three fewer than in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy medal winners were four-time Olympian Dara Torres, 33,
who after a seven-year layoff won two gold and three bronze for a
career total of nine; Thompson, who won three golds and a bronze
for a career total of 10; backstroker Lenny Krayzelburg, who won
three golds; Hall, who won two golds, a silver and a bronze, for a
career total of eight; and Brooke Bennett, Megan Quann and Anthony
Ervin, who won two golds apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The most astonishing winner was Misty Hyman of the U.S., who
upset Australia's Susie O'Neill in the 200-meter butterfly by going
more than three seconds faster than she ever had before.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta four years ago, the U.S. won 26 medals (13 gold), and
only four world records fell, all in men's events.
</P>
<P>
   From the first day here, when five world records were set in
four events, the fast pool contributed to some of the exceptional
swims. The competitors were also carried on a wave of support from
the Australian crowd, which treats swimming the way Americans treat
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 17,500 was packed into the upper reaches of the
aquatics center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the times (it was) scary, other times pretty
awesome,'' said O'Neill, the most adored swimmer in Australia. ``It
gave me goose bumps every time I went out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The final day of the meet had predictable moments, as well as
some surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Inge de Bruijn of the Netherlands won her third gold medal of
the Games in the 50-meter freestyle. She and teammate Pieter van
den Hoogenband single-handedly won five gold medals, tying
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The Flying Dutchman and Dutchwoman also set or equalled six
world records.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all going bananas back in the Netherlands,'' said de
Bruijn. ``They're even letting children out of school to watch the
Olympics. It's getting crazy over there.''
</P>
<P>
   However, both have had to fend off queries about the use of
performance-enhancing drugs, which they vehemently deny. ``I want
to enjoy every moment of this and no one is going to take that away
from me,'' de Bruijn said. ``I'm in the history books. The sky is
the limit.''
</P>
<P>
   As expected, an Australian won the 1,500-meter freestyle, but it
was Grant Hackett, not Kieren Perkins. Chris Thompson of the U.S.
won the bronze. For the first time in history, four swimmers went
under 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women's medley relay then became the first to go under
four minutes, obliterating the old world record of 4:01.67 with a
time of 3:58.50. B.J. Bedford, Quann, Thompson and Torres each had
the fastest split for their stroke in the race, while Quann's
1:06.29 breaststroke leg was the fastest ever, as was Thompson's
57.25 butterfly split.
</P>
<P>
   The men's medley relay also broke the world record to close out
the meet.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Moses became the first man under one minute in the
breaststroke at 59.24 while Ian Crocker's butterfly split (52.10)
was the fastest by an American. Krayzelburg and Hall swam the other
legs.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins admired the U.S. team's tremendous depth. ``Invariably
every time there's a race,'' he said, ``if you blokes don't win,
there's sombody picking up second or third. If we're really going
to challenge for that No. 1 spot, we need to be able to pick up the
minor placings.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres, who now will retire again, cried on both the medal stand
and during the press conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess,'' she said, ``I'm just bummed that it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
