<HEADER>
A9056 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-TRACK0924-COX     09-23 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones, Greene golden in 100
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ At the end, they were right where they started out to
be. When they crossed the finish line on ``Super Saturday,'' Marion
Jones and Maurice Greene validated themselves as Olympic 100-meter
champions, the fastest sprinters in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Jones needed a leg up on her quest for five gold medals.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, the world record-holder, needed just one last thing to
put his sprint dominance in a class with Carl Lewis _ an Olympic
gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried not to cry,'' said Greene, after the medal ceremony.
``It's overwhelming. I put a lot of pressure on myself to come out
and put on a great Olympic show.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years earlier, on a muggy Atlanta night, Greene cried as he
sat watching the 100-meter final. Half a world away, the
26-year-old from Kansas City shed a few tears of joy after becoming
the first American to win the Olympic sprint since Lewis at the
1988 Seoul Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Greene put his stamp on the Games, impressively running 9.87
seconds into a slight wind for his 35th sub-10-second race _ the
most in history. Now, he'll duck away from the NBC cameras until
the closing 400-meter relay.
</P>
<P>
   Not so Ms. Jones, whose TV time is only beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``One down, four to go,'' said C.J. Hunter, her husband.
</P>
<P>
   But for a night, Jones basked in her glory.
</P>
<P>
   Almost playfully, she broke into a skip one stride from the
finish line, and kept at it until landing in the arms of her
mother, Marion Toler. The former North Carolina point guard circled
the track with the American and Belize flags _ her mother's
birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   One moment she flashed her trademark gap-tooth smile. The next,
she was sobbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of the Olympic Games, and seen people cross
the (finish) line,'' Jones said. ``I'm thinking, `I'm going to
cross that line and be a cool cat.' All of a sudden it hits you.
It's real emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marion Jones Show began with her racing down the middle of
the track, the Olympic cauldron over her left shoulder, destroying
an Olympic final field like few women ever before. The outcome was
history by 50 meters. Her only challenge, avoiding the pesky moths
that fill the evening air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I couldn't win it,'' said silver medalist Ekaterini
Thanou of Greece. ``I was only running for second.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta silver medalist Merlene Ottey came home fourth. Former
University of Georgia star Debbie Ferguson, running for the
Bahamas, made the final _ but finished a distant eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Coming in, this was the surest thing in Jones' ambitious quest.
Her victory was the 35th consecutive dating to 1997. Her 10.75
clocking proved the fastest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But if it was a cinch, Jones wasn't convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a very difficult night sleeping,'' she said. ``I slept
very little. C.J. would say, `Close your eyes, close your eyes.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I am, I'm just not sleeping.'''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, she dreamed of her 100-meter final.
</P>
<P>
   But as Jones tells it, she already was dreaming Olympic glory as
a child growing up in southern California.
</P>
<P>
   The summer of 1984 brought the Games to Los Angeles, and Jones,
her brother, mother and step-father made the short drive into the
city for a pre-Olympic parade. She clicked on the TV every day to
watch the Games. On a chalkboard in her bedroom, she remembers
scribbling her newfound ambition: gold medalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is (16) years of believing and dreaming,'' Jones said.
``This is an incredible experience. It's everything I dreamed of
and more.''
</P>
<P>
   On the podium, Jones inspected her medal, describing it as
having ``no rough edges, very glamorous.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Greene was in awe of the medal, too. But equally so the
quest Jones finds herself in the midst of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish her the best, cause I wouldn't try it,'' offered the
world's fastest man.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
