u s BC-OLY-BASE0924-COX     09-23 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BASE0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anticipated duel turns one-sided
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ The man wore a Cuba baseball shirt and a strained
expression, like he either had an upset stomach or was about to
cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean?'' he said to the man holding his ticket.
``What's the problem?''
</P>
<P>
   The man had entered the most anticipated baseball game of the
Olympics, but left to find a cousin. Upon his attempt to return, he
was told there were no re-entries allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I've got to go back in,'' the man said. Three people
manning the entrance huddled with the distraught man, explaining
the policy over and over.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't understand,'' he said. ``I have to go back in. This
is Cuba playing the United States. I have to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   This went on for about two minutes before, finally, he was told
by a woman who had come over: ``OK, sir, you can go back in. But,
please, don't come back out until the game is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Relieved, the man charged into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe they want to keep me out. I bought a ticket,''
Juan Valdez said. ``This is the game no one wants to miss. America
invented baseball, but we play the game better in Cuba. You see.
You see.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside Homebush Stadium, the atmosphere was a mixture of
major-league baseball and WWF. Kids donning big-league hats chasing
foul balls; kids with faces painted eating french fries smothered
in sour cream. Quality play on the field; rock 'n' roll music
between innings. The wave; sound effects after foul balls.
</P>
<P>
   A weird mix, but it worked.
</P>
<P>
   If only the game had matched the anticipation. Cuba scored four
runs in the first and was never threatened the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cu-ba, Cu-ba'' went the chant, and it was a familiar refrain
by the time the 6-1 mauling was complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't in the game after the first inning,'' U.S. manager
Tommy Lasorda said.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides insisted there was no contention between the teams,
but that was hard to believe. There was a feel of antagonism from
the start, and it carried throughout the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``On our part, there is no antagonism,'' Cuba manager Servio
Borges said. ``It's a sport. We just go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   By the top of the fourth inning, the animosity between the teams
reared its head. Ernie Young, the former major-league player, was
hit by a pitch from Jose Ibar, who was throwing a perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   The catcher, Ariel Pestano hurried between the batter and
pitcher, and Young pushed him out of the way. Words were exchanged
and both benches immediately emptied.
</P>
<P>
   It did not escalate into a brawl, but sentiments were laid out
for all to see. Immediately, the large Cuba contingent started
waving its country's flag. Then there were the chants in Spanish
that, it's safe to say, were not promoting harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy (Ibar) had pinpoint control and I get to be the
beneficiary of a 94-mile-an-hour fastball in my shoulder,'' Young
said. ``I was upset because I knew he hit me on purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. fans were no less enthusiastic. They expressed their
displeasure with boos. And throughout the game, even if it was an
anticlimactic finish, the U.S. red, white and blue flags waved in
the pleasant night air.
</P>
<P>
   When Miguel Caldes was called safe after running over first
baseman Doug Mientkiewicz, it was reason for fans on both sides to
get loud. But not as loud as the song ``We Will Rock You'' that
blared through the sound system; the fans rocked along with the
beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where else can you get this,'' said John Ziomek, a high school
football coach from Fairlawn, N.J. Ziomek wore jeans, no shirt,
with ``USA'' painted on his chest, with a U.S. flag around his neck
like a cape.
</P>
<P>
   He looked up at a group of Cuba fans and yelled to them in
Spanish. Security came over, thinking Ziomek had said something
nasty. ``All I said was, `Listen to me. We've spotted you five
runs, but the United States is still going to win.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to seven baseball games, but this is the one I
really looked forward to. I came here having little expectations
from the U.S. But these guys have done us proud, beating
professional players from the other countries. As far as this game
against Cuba goes, it's a blast win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``What an atmosphere. Regardless of the outcome, how great is it
to have people from all around the world in the same place,
enjoying baseball and getting along? There are not many places in
the world where that can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
