<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9059 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-TV0924-COX     09-23 0233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TV0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OLYTV Here's what you'll see on TV tonight.
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Although there will be a Michael Johnson sighting in
the men's 400 meters in track and field, the main attraction on
tonight's telecast will be the men's and women's individual event
finals in gymnastics. About the only sure thing is that the height
of the vault will be accurate. The Americans have had a rough time
in Sydney, but Elise Ray on the balance beam, Morgan Hamm on floor
exercise and Blaine Wilson on the vault will each get one more shot
at coming home with a medal. NBC is also showing the men's and
women's eights final in rowing, where the U.S. men's eight has won
the last three world championships, but hasn't claimed Olympic gold
since 1964. During the afternoon segment, Mia Hamm and Brandi
Chastain will lead the U.S. against Brazil in what should be an
entertaining match in women's soccer. The women's marathon is also
on the slate. MSNBC (TV 33) is offering the U.S. women in
basketball and volleyball against Poland and Brazil, respectively,
along with manager Tommy Lasorda leading his U.S. team against
Australia in baseball. Tennis is scheduled for CNBC, which usually
means air time for one or both of the Williams sisters, Venus and
Serena.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
