<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9061 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-G7-U.S.-ECON-2NDLD-WR     09-23 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-G7-U.S.-ECON-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 U.S. VOWS TO BATTLE RISE IN OIL PRICES, VOICES CONCERN ON EURO'S
WEAKNESS  (SUBS to add new info on communique; expands by about 300
words) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ The top financial officials of the
United States, fresh from an unprecedented synchronized plunge into
world oil and currency markets, joined other rich nations on
Saturday in vowing to fight what they described as double jeopardy
for the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   In a communique issued after Group of 7 financial leaders met
here, ministers said they would monitor currency markets to see if
they needed to follow Friday's coordinated central bank action to
shore up the euro, Europe's battered common currency, with further
interventions. But they used stronger language on oil prices,
saying it was ``crucial for the world economy'' that oil-producing
nations take steps to reduce prices, which have tripled since early
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oil prices are the largest dark cloud in the blue sky of the
global economy,'' Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said after
the G-7 meetings, speaking of a recent run-up in the price of crude
oil to a 10-year high of more than $30 a barrel. ``Prices need to
return to a more historical range.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's decision on Friday to tap the
Strategic Petroleum Reserve to help dampen oil prices won praise in
the G-7 communique. Other G-7 nations are also considering
releasing oil from their reserves, and ministers discussed ways of
breaking oil distribution bottlenecks and ways of putting
diplomatic pressure on the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, officials said in describing the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The attempts to correct currency and oil prices cast the United
States, which often argues that such markets should take care of
themselves, as an aggressive interventionist, evoking expressions
of surprise from other G-7 ministers. Several said Friday's
concerted buying of euros and selling of dollars, yen and other
currencies had gone smoothly, though some traders expressed doubts
that the American, British, European, Canadian and Japanese central
banks would continue to do whatever it takes to push the euro up
against the dollar if sentiment turns negative again. ``It was
surprising how well the action went,'' Germany's finance minister,
Hans Eichel, said. ``Especially before the U.S. election, it was
surprising the U.S. even participated.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-level talks on how best to corral market prices
underscored how officials had come to view the euro's weakness and
oil's strength as major inflationary threats that pose an immediate
and largely unanticipated danger to global growth, which according
to recent forecasts was keeping the fastest annual pace in more
than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Broad political considerations also played a role. The
relentless decline of the euro challenged the concept of European
integration generally, especially as Denmark prepares to vote on
Thursday on whether to join the euro zone.
</P>
<P>
   Longer term, Europe faces a paradox: Its drive to expand both
the geographical and political reach of the European Union depends
in good measure on the euro, the showpiece of the region's economic
common interest. But currency traders increasingly lost faith in
the euro, European Central Bank officials argued to their G-7
counterparts, because they saw insufficient political weight behind
the currency, which was introduced 21 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   American officials largely accepted those arguments when
discussing whether to join the European Central Bank in defending
the currency in the open market, a decision that Summers and Alan
Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, recently made. It
was the first such intervention the United States has undertaken
since it helped Japan raise the value of the yen in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has long lent its support to European
integration because it is seen as a way of ensuring stability in a
region where America has fought two world wars.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt to rescue the euro was closely intertwined with the
Clinton administration's decision to tap the Strategic Petroleum
Reserve. Several European nations, including Britain and France,
have had sustained protests by truck drivers and others hurt by oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Prices at the pump, already far higher in Europe than the United
States because of heavy taxes, have risen even more sharply here
than across the Atlantic because oil is bought and sold in dollars,
which have been rising in value against the euro almost in tandem
with the oil price spike. American officials were counting on an
uptick in European growth rates to extend the American-led economic
expansion of recent years, something that seems less likely if
Europe is hit by an inflationary shock.
</P>
<P>
   There was also growing trans-Atlantic concern that the weakness
of the European currency and the inflationary impact of high-priced
oil gave Saddam Hussein, the Iraqi leader, his best opportunity
since the Persian Gulf war to wreak havoc on his Western
adversaries. With oil supplies already short, the Western world
depends on Iraq continuing crude production, something he could cut
off at any time.
</P>
<P>
   G-7 ministers in effect dismissed a French proposal to organize
a summit meeting between the Western powers and OPEC. But they
agreed to pursue bilateral contacts with OPEC counterparts,
including a coming French session with Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Summers said he hoped that the United States decision to provide
30 million barrels of oil from its reserves would persuade traders
to stop snapping up forward contracts for oil in anticipation of
severe winter shortages, a key factor behind the rising price.
</P>
<P>
   In comments the currency markets will have to decipher this
coming week, Summers also stressed that there was ``no
contradiction'' between his decision to sell dollars to buy euros
and his oft-repeated view that a strong dollar is vital to American
interests. His insistence that America has not changed its currency
policy suggests that Summers does not foresee the euro's rising
sharply against the dollar _ and, further, that any continued
United States intervention in currency markets would be limited
unless the euro resumes its plunge.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as the G-7 ministers met in private sessions,
President Vaclav Havel of the Czech Republic invited about 100
people representing charity and pressure groups concerned about
globalization to debate the heads of the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund at Prague Castle. The officials and
protesters have gathered here for the annual meetings of the
Washington-based lending agencies, which will continue for several
days.
</P>
<P>
   During the two-hour session, followed by a walk through the
gardens of the sprawling Prague Castle, many environmental and
social activists peppered the World Bank president, James D.
Wolfensohn, and the International Monetary Fund managing director,
Horst Koehler, with an extensive list of demands.
</P>
<P>
   Several called for the complete abolition of the two
Washington-based lending agencies, which were founded just after
World War II to finance the reconstruction of Europe and stabilize
world currencies. They have recently been under heavy pressure to
improve the economic performance of poor and middle-income nations
that receive most of their loans.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets, where protest organizers have vowed to stage
major demonstrations beginning on Sunday, the biggest march
Saturday was by some 500 anarchists, many dressed in black with
black masks.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd briefly blocked a highway. There was also a skirmish
between anarchists and neo-Nazi skinheads, who were staging a rival
demonstration near Prague's main railway station. At least one
person was injured before the police arrived.
</P>
</TEXT>
