<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NDAME-MICHST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN STATE BEATS NOTRE DAME, 27-21 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST LANSING, Mich. _ He had been sacked six times, fumbled the
ball once and threw an interception inside his own 5-yard line.
What's a freshman to do? Well, with a little less than two minutes
left in the game, Michigan State quarterback Jeff Smoker got the
kind of luck that usually blesses the Fighting Irish.
</P>
<P>
   On fourth-and-10 on his own 32-yard line, Smoker stood strong in
the pocket and rifled a pass between the hash marks at midfield and
into the arms of a streaking Herb Haygood. Haygood, a junior wide
receiver, never broke stride as he galloped through the Notre Dame
secondary and into the end zone for a 68-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   It was only Smoker's 12th completion in 24 tries but it was the
one the 74,714 at Spartan Stadium will remember as the one that
beat the Fighting Irish, 27-21, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The loss extended two dubious streaks by the No. 16 Irish (2-2).
They have not won a road game since November 1998 (over Navy) and
now have lost four consecutive games to the Spartans. The last time
a team beat Notre dame four consecutive times was Miami in 1983,
'84, '85 and '87.
</P>
<P>
   When Smoker arced a 10-yard swing pass to fullback Travis Wilson
in the end zone in the final minutes of the third quarter, the
Spartans had a 20-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Gary Godsey, the 6-foot-7-inch former tight end who
led the Irish to a 21-20 upset of Purdue last week, had problems
Saturday. When Godsey was intercepted by Cedrick Henry early in the
third quarter, Notre Dame Coach Bob Davie made a change. Godsey's
turnover led to a 36-yard field goal by David Schaefer and a 13-7
Michigan State lead. From that moment on, Davie turned the offense
over to the freshman Matt LoVecchio who, at 6-4 and fleeter of
foot, returned the Irish to option football.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening minutes of the fourth quarter, LoVecchio, the
former Bergen Catholic star, crossed everybody up, however, when he
launched a 42-yard pass to Javin Hunter for a first down at the
Michigan State 2-yard line. Two plays later, Julius Jones punched
in the end zone to pull Notre Dame to 20-14.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 23 Spartans (3-0), too, had quarterback woes. Junior
starter Ryan Van Dyke hasn't played since injuring the thumb on his
throwing arm in the season opener against Marshall. He warmed up
before the game Saturday, but was not fully recovered and. For the
second week in a row the Spartans had to play Smoker, who was 10 of
24 for 157 yards last week in a 13-10 victory over Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Smoker had looked like the better of the backups until two
costly fourth-quarter mistakes. On third-and-7 on his own 28,
Smoker was in the shotgun when Irish linebacker Tyreo Harrison
burst through and knocked the ball loose. By the time defensive
tackle Darrell Campbell smothered the ball the Irish were on the
Michigan State 12-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Three runs moved the ball to the Michigan State 3-yard line and,
facing fourth-and-1, Davie decided to go for it. This time,
LoVecchio kept on the option, but Michigan State tackle Josh Shaw
stopped him short of the first down.
</P>
<P>
   Smoker and the Spartans weren't so fortunate moments later. On
third-and-15 at his own 11-yard line, Smoker hurried a screen pass
that was intended for tailback Little John Flowers. The Irish's
Anthony Weaver intercepted and was caught by Flowers on the
2-yard-line. Jones carried it in on the next play, giving the Irish
a 21-20 lead with 7:59 to play.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, both teams came out running and, as Michigan
State's 10-7 halftime lead reflected, the Spartans were able to
gobble up the most ground _ especially the sophomore T.J. Duckett,
a powerful 6-2, 252-pound tailback whom the Irish were unable to
tackle. He gained 107 yards in the half and on the Spartans'
touchdown drive carried the ball 6 times for 47 yards and rolled
over three members of the Irish secondary on a 6-yard touchdown
run. Over all, he ran for 141 yards and one touchdown on 26
carries.
</P>
<P>
   Smoker, however, settled down enough to complete passes to
Hagood and wide receiver Marcus Waters and move the Spartans into
Irish territory. When the drive stalled junior David Schaefer, who
had missed a 50-yard field goal earlier in the quarter, gave the
Spartans a 10-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish, meanwhile, leaned on the sophomore tailback Jones who
rushed for 93 first-half yards. Jones finished with 126 yards and
two touchdowns on 26 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Godsey was 4 of 8 for 20 yards in the first half and threw the
first touchdown of his Notre Dame career _ a six yard swing pass to
reserve fullback Jason Murray early in the first half. But it was
Jones who set up the touchdown when he popped inside the right
tackle and then angled outside and 56 yards up the sideline down to
the Spartans 4-yard-line. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
