<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9065 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-PERU-ANALYSIS-HNS &LR;      09-23 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUJIMORI'S FUTURE LINKED TO AIDE MONTESINOS' FATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ If President Alberto Fujimori's rapid reversal of
fortune were made into a Hollywood thriller, it might be called
``Gone in 60 Seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how long it took for a grainy videotape, which shows
Fujimori's most trusted aide apparently bribing a congressman, to
shock and disgust Peruvians.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the minute-long video was broadcast on national
television, Fujimori, Latin America's longest-serving elected
leader, suddenly announced last weekend that he would call early
elections and leave office.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, the Fujimori government has been accused
of far more serious misdeeds, ranging from electoral fraud and
human rights abuses to selling weapons to Colombian guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say the videotape showing Vladimiro Montesinos, the
president's shadowy spy chief, handing an envelope stuffed with
cash to an opposition legislator captured the public's imagination
and quickly came to symbolize all that has gone sour in Peru under
Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peruvians can see for themselves,'' said Alberto Borea, a
lawyer and a political activist in Lima. ``Other accusations (of
wrongdoing) did not have the same impact as these images.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's bombshell announcement Sept. 16 of new elections
threw the nation into disarray. As Peruvians contemplated the vote,
Montesinos remained holed up at army headquarters in Lima after
refusing Fujimori's order to resign from the government.
</P>
<P>
   What does seem clear, analysts say, is that the Fujimori era is
at last coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Montesinos, Fujimori has very little power,'' said
Joanna Drzewieniecki, an independent political analyst and human
rights consultant in Lima.
</P>
<P>
   Montesinos, the de facto head of the state intelligence agency,
has played a behind-the-scenes role at critical junctures during
Fujimori's rule, exercising wide control over the military, the
judiciary and electoral institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Montesinos is thought to have served as a CIA informant and has
won praise from U.S. officials for his role in Peru's fight against
drug traffickers. At the same time, he has been accused, though
never convicted, of graft, spying on government opponents and
receiving payoffs from drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts here think Montesinos finally went too far and took
part in an arms-smuggling ring that sent thousands of Russian
assault rifles purchased in Jordan to Marxist guerrillas in
neighboring Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The smuggling ring involved Montesinos as well as retired
Peruvian military officers, the local media reported, adding that
the intelligence service protected the officers.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government, which recently approved a $1.3 billion aid
package for the war against drugs in the Andean region, was enraged
and pressured Fujimori to dump Montesinos, observers said. Most of
the U.S. assistance is earmarked to help the Colombian government
battle Marxist guerrillas who earn millions of dollars annually in
the narcotics trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sending arms to the Colombian guerrillas was too much. It
caused profound anger in the United States and Colombia,'' said
Fernando Rospigliosi, who writes about military affairs for the
Lima news magazine Caretas. ``Montesinos didn't calculate the
effects this could have. This was fatal.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori often shrugs off criticism, but his room to maneuver
has greatly diminished. Following last May's fraud-tainted
elections, Fujimori has faced growing domestic opposition and
stepped-up international pressure to restore full democracy to
Peru.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he may have felt compelled to respond to the arms
scandal, Borea said.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next is a matter of speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts think Fujimori used the compromising videotape of
Montesinos as an excuse to fire him Sept. 16. Montesinos apparently
responded by rallying the support of the military high command,
which threatened to launch a coup against Fujimori, according to
Francisco Loayza, a respected Peruvian military analyst who has
written a book about Montesinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montesinos had decided that this was the only way to paralyze
the country and win enough time to negotiate his own exit,'' Loayza
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Fujimori backed down, Loayza said, and the coup was called
off.
</P>
<P>
   That same night, Fujimori broadcast a message to the nation
calling for new elections and saying that he would not be a
candidate. He also announced that he was dismantling the
intelligence service.
</P>
<P>
   It now appears that Fujimori, Montesinos and military commanders
might be negotiating some way for the spy chief and the nation's
top generals to avoid prosecution. Some analysts believe Montesinos
eventually will be allowed to flee.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be the easiest solution. But he has too much
baggage, with all of the accusations against him,'' Rospigliosi
said. ``What country would take him?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Panama rejected a request Saturday to give him asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders have made the investigation and prosecution
of Montesinos a key demand in ongoing negotiations with the
Fujimori government over next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a great opportunity for the reconciliation
among Peruvians, a great opportunity to make democratic reforms,''
said Cesar Gaviria, secretary-general of the Organization of
American States, the regional body sponsoring the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the Fujimori government has often run roughshod over
the nation's democractic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   First elected in 1990, Fujimori closed the congress and the
courts two years later in a so-called ``self-coup.'' His government
was hailed, however, for taming hyperinflation and for largely
defeating the fanatical Shining Path terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori was easily re-elected in 1995. He devoted much of his
second term to dubious legal maneuvers that allowed him to run for
a third term.
</P>
<P>
   International observers say that widespread irregularities and a
government dirty-tricks campaign against opposition candidates
marred last spring's elections. In the May 28 presidential runoff,
Fujimori won an unprecedented third consecutive five-year term. His
opponent, Alejandro Toledo, claimed the process was rigged and
pulled out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, rival politicians claim the current administration
cannot be trusted to run a clean election.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the opposition is badly divided. Toledo, who wants to run
for the presidency again, held a campaign rally last week. But some
critics of Fujimori said the opposition's first task should be to
pressure the government to run a fair election and to prosecute
Montesinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opposition was furious with Toledo,'' Drzewieniecki said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference last week, Fujimori rejected calls that he
step down immediately and allow a transition government to organize
next year's balloting. He insisted that he would campaign for his
party and even hinted that he would run for president again.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will happen in 2006? I am going to offer a surprise,''
Fujimori said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have closely followed Fujimori's career predict that
he will attempt to paint himself as a victim of Montesinos'
maneuvers, then attempt to stage-manage next year's balloting and
later launch a political comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, he is trying to survive, to arrange for a soft
landing, and then return in 2006,'' said Carlos Ivan Degregori, a
political scientist at the Institute of Peruvian Studies.
</P>
<P>
   But others contend that, without Montesinos, Fujimori's
political career is all but finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a huge defeat'' for Fujimori, Rospigliosi said.
``He knows he can never come back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
