<SLUG> BC-OLY-SOCCM0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. soars on day of shockers
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Compared with the shocking results taking place at the
same time Saturday night, the penalty-kick victory by the U.S.
men's soccer team over Japan couldn't be called an upset.
</P>
<P>
   But for an American team enjoying its first trip to the Olympic
quarterfinals, its come-from-behind 2-2 thriller (5-4 on penalties)
over a determined Japanese squad in Adelaide was the stuff of their
wildest imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Twice the U.S. fell behind and twice it equalized, the second
time in drawing a penalty kick in the final minute of regulation.
After 30 minutes of scoreless extra time, a fortuitous misfire off
the post by Japan's star player, Hidetoshi Nakata, propelled the
Americans into a Tuesday semifinal match in Sydney against Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Stone Mountain's Josh Wolff scored the first goal of the game
for the U.S. and set up the dramatic spot kick in the 90th minute,
when he was taken down in the penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   Spain got an 86th-minute goal from Gabri to send Italy, the
pre-Olympic gold-medal favorite, crashing out of the tournament.
Brazil, which has never won Olympic gold, is out, too. Modeste
Mbami lashed a wicked shot in the 113th minute as Cameroon took a
2-1 extra-time victory. Nigeria, which won the 1996 gold medal in
Athens, was thrashed 4-1 by Chile.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, also making its best showing in the Olympics, had the
better run of play until late in the second half, when the U.S.
used its three substitutions to inject pace and some fresh legs.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff's goal, on a rebound from 16 yards out, knotted the match
at 1-1 in the 68th minute. But four minutes later, Japan retook the
lead when Naohiro Takahara smashed a point-blank shot at U.S.
goalkeeper Brad Friedel, who parried it away.
</P>
<P>
   But he couldn't stop the rebound, and the Americans were playing
on their heels again. In the 89th minute, Friedel unleashed a long
free kick just outside his box and ahead to Wolff, who drew a beat
five feet away from Japanese keeper Seigo Narazaki. Wolff and
defender Tomoyuki Sakai got tangled up, and Peter Vagenas easily
made the conversion.
</P>
<P>
   In the penalty-kick round, all five Americans scored. In the
fourth round, Nakata, a Japanese sporting icon who plays for AS
Roma in Italy, hooked his right-footed shot off the left post.
Friedel, badly beaten, pumped his fists while sitting on the
ground. Then the U.S. bench engaged in a group pile-on near the
sideline after Sasha Victorine put home the winning spot kick.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
