<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9070 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-HUMMER0924-COX     09-23 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HUMMER0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drive for 5
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ This was a moment as full of portent as a second,
separate lighting of the Olympic flame.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing her first Olympic finish line as alone as any soloist,
Marion Jones freed the most radiant smile yet loosed on these
Games. That smile _ toothy and total _ is her second greatest gift.
It beamed the beginning of 2000's second Olympics, the one she'll
call her own.
</P>
<P>
   Let the Games of the first Mariad begin.
</P>
<P>
   Her emotions would swerve much more than her feet. From the
smile that preceded her across the 100-meter finish, to the tears
that quickly followed her right turn toward the stands. Both were
in reaction to finally getting her audacious pentathlon under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is 19 years of believing and dreaming about the gold
medal,'' Jones said. ``Then it comes down to one moment, one race.
That's a lot of pressure. What a huge relief. It's wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Like so much else about her quest, the finish to the 100 meters
was carefully planned. ``I vowed I was going to play it cool,''
Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the best parts of life, though, her reaction could not be
scripted. ``Once I crossed the line, all that went out the
window,'' she said, explaining the brief salty flood.
</P>
<P>
   But remember that smile, for it was the signal that Jones can
handle the weight of the next week and have enough energy left to
fleetingly enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of 7-year-old kids do things like write, ``I want to be
Olympic champion'' on a blackboard, and Marion Jones said she was
one of them.
</P>
<P>
   But only one in millions can live up to such childish notions.
Only the rarest sort can come to that single apex of time, stare
down an empty stretch of track at the end of which a life's purpose
is fulfilled or crushed, and not be overwhelmed. To those we build
cavernous stadiums and dedicate them with worshipful roars.
</P>
<P>
   Jones described a sleepless night on the eve of becoming,
officially, the world's fastest femme. And yet she had them from,
``Take your mark.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones jumped on the field from the start, and glided
increasingly beyond their reach. They were just not the Marion
kind.
</P>
<P>
   Her time of 10.75 was not a record, but with silver-medal winner
Ekaterini Thanou of Greece .37 of a second behind, Jones' margin of
victory was the second-widest in the history of the women's Olympic
100 meters.
</P>
<P>
   This was a victory that excluded no one. While Jones and mother
Marion Toler have had their Jones and mother Marion Toler have had
their differences, the two warmly embraced at the other end of the
100. Along with the U.S. flag, Jones included a small flag of
Belize on her victory lap _ a tribute to mom's native land.
</P>
<P>
   At the medal ceremony, Jones savored the texture of the first of
her collection. This one deserved a long, loving inspection. ``I
wondered for the longest time what (an Olympic medal) would be
like,'' she said. ``There are no rough edges, it's very smooth and
glamorous. It's beautiful.'' The medal could return the same
compliment to its owner.
</P>
<P>
   But only the ``easy'' part of Jones' five-step plan toward
becoming Olympic lore is done. The 200 meters may not be a much
more competitive race, but it is longer. The long jump is not her
specialty. And considering the loss of Inger Miller, America's
second best sprinter, to injury and the awful showing of America's
400-meter runners (none advanced past preliminary rounds), the
strength of the 4x100 and 4x400 relay teams are questionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish her the best, but I wouldn't try it,'' men's 100-meter
silver medalist Ato Boldon said. ``I hope her body holds up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't I just enjoy this for a couple of minutes?'' Jones
wondered after gold No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not much more than that. She set the rules with her
own ambition. And the truth is, we are hooked. We need another fix
of that smile as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
