<HEADER>
A9075 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FERTILITY0924-COX     09-23 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERTILITY0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The costs of infertility
 &HT;    By Jenna Hunt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Tina and Gary Nix wanted another baby, but
after two unsuccessful years they turned to fertility treatments.
The Goldsboro couple enlisted the help of Dr. Lynn Borchert, a
Greenville fertility specialist, who spent months testing the
couple to rule out fixable difficulties before recommending an oral
fertility drug.
</P>
<P>
   It took about 14 months using the drug for the couple to
successfully become pregnant with their son, who is now 3 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really wanted another child _ we didn't want our oldest to
grow up alone,'' Tina Nix, 34, said. ``We were really blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Visiting the clinic each month or talking with women who
couldn't conceive made Tina feel guilty because she already had a
child, she said.
</P>
<P>
   One out of six couples experience infertility problems in the
United States, and more couples are turning to medicine to become
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   The Nixes' success story is not the rule when it comes to
fertility treatments. Most attempts fail to lead to pregnancy, and
a few result in twins, triplets, quadruplets or more babies.
Multiple births _ including the
</P>
<P>
   recent sextuplet birth in Greenville, septuplets in Iowa and
octuplets in Italy _ can often be prevented by careful monitoring
before conception, doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   A healthy woman without fertility problems has about a 25
percent chance of getting pregnant each month. A couple is
considered infertile if they can't become pregnant in a 12-month
period, doctors said. The chances of getting pregnant with
fertility treatments range from 10 to 40 percent, doctors said.
ECU's fertility center averages about 80 patients a year with a
live-birth rate of 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last five to 10 years there has been an increase in
using fertility treatments,'' said Dr. Cal Hayslip, director of
East Carolina University's Assisted Reproductive Technology
Laboratory Center and director of the Brody School of Medicine's
Reproductive Endrocrinology and Infertility Division. Desperation
to have one baby can often lead to fertilization treatments that
produce multiple births, what some doctors refer to as tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think personally, as a fertility specialist, if treatments
produce five or six babies, I consider that to be a failure,''
Borchert said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nix family knew they didn't want to have more than twins at
the very most, but felt confident with Borchert's experience that
they wouldn't face a multiple birth. Borchert has never had more
than twin births in his 30 years of practice, he said.
</P>
<P>
   All most couples want is one healthy baby when they seek
fertility treatments, Gary Nix said. But the waiting game can be
agony, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Month after month you're still not pregnant and . . . you
start to question everything,'' he said. ``People take getting
pregnant naturally for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Multiple births occur because couples proceed with fertilization
attempts after drugs produce two or more viable eggs. Couples could
choose to abstain or use birth control when tests reveal several
viable eggs exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The five- and six-birth kids have put a bad wrap on fertility
treatments,'' said Nix, 35. ``I don't care if you're Superman _ you
can't take care of five kids. There is no one on earth who would
want to have five kids at one
</P>
<P>
   time.''
</P>
<P>
   Multiple births can place physical and emotional burdens on the
mother and children, in addition to taxing family and community
resources, Borchert said.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Nix said she can relate to the desperation of having
children at any cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted another baby so bad that at times, if it was a chance
to have twins or triplets, I would have said, 'Go for it,' `` she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Borchert's care the Nixes were advised to be cautious and
patient. Each month, the couple visited the medical practice to see
how many follicles _ or unfertilized eggs _ had developed on Tina's
ovaries. Numerous eggs could develop into multiple fetuses if
fertilized, her doctor said. He said he never recommends a couple
try to get pregnant with three or more mature follicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wouldn't have been a chance at multiple births _ if I
had four, six or eight follicles we wouldn't have even tried to get
pregnant,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some medical professionals and families are willing to take the
risks of having large multiple births. In some cases, couples opt
for injection fertility treatments, which are stronger than oral
drugs like the Nixes used.
</P>
<P>
   For them, a successful fertilization may result in a choice
between multiple births or selective reduction of fetuses after
conception, doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past six years, Hayslip has had two couples become
pregnant with quadruplets. Both decided to have selective fetal
reduction and each delivered healthy twins. He said he understands
this decision involves moral, ethical and religious choices for
couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe before women take fertility drugs they should be
counseled on fetal reduction,'' he said. ``On average, a woman will
have a better chance of having healthy babies if she reduces to
twins.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayslip is the only doctor in eastern North Carolina and one of
about 500 certified reproductive endrocrinologists in the country
providing in vitro fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have much more control over multiple births with in vitro
fertilization _ most of the time only two or three embryos are
placed back inside the uterus,'' Hayslip said.
</P>
<P>
   Medical experts agreed the million-dollar price tags attached to
having large multiple births can often place a weighty financial
strain on communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society has to bear responsibilities for the care of these
babies,'' Hayslip said. ``But does society have a right to limit
choices that an individual can make as far as fertility
treatment?''
</P>
<P>
   In England and some other European countries, it is illegal to
place more than three fertilized embryos back inside a woman's
uterus, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple births can easily occur with more embryos, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It can cost millions to care for tiny infants in their first
year of life depending on complications and hospitalizations, said
Hayslip. The cost of fertility can also be a determining factor for
couples trying to conceive since the average cost for each in vitro
fertilization cycle is at least $7,000. Most couples try at least
twice, with some repeating the process three or four times without
success, Hayslip said.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs and injections are less expensive but still costly. ``It's
definitely not cheap _ it's very expensive,'' Gary Nix said.
</P>
<P>
   He estimated that they spent more than $3,000, but he said you
can't put a price on the birth of a child.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000923.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9076 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOOD0924-COX     09-23 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD0924-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keeping up the neighborhood
 &HT;    By T. Scott Batchelor
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ The city of Greenville is on the verge of
enforcing a high-grass ordinance for homes whose owners were driven
away from their property by Hurricane Floyd flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Johnson, neighborhood services coordinator, sent a letter
to displaced property owners in the federal buyout program asking
them to cut their grass and secure abandoned structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become quite apparent that the time is fast approaching
that we must begin enforcement actions in these flooded areas,''
Johnson wrote in the letter dated Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are requesting that you secure (board up) your
</P>
<P>
   structure and keep the grass on your lot cut,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please keep in mind that you are currently the owner of the
flooded property and are responsible for its condition,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The letter also called for the removal of abandoned vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the residents who have moved back into their
previously flooded homes have complained about nearby lots growing
wild, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems they should have some strategy to do something,''
Johnson said of the absentee property owners. ``They can't just let
it stay out there without making a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The ordinance prohibits owners from letting grass get more than
1 foot high. Houses that aren't occupied have to be locked and the
windows boarded up, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   He said tall grass and overgrown vegetation can harbor rats and
other pests. The ordinance is currently not being enforced for the
properties in the buyout program, Johnson said. Officials will
decide at a later date when to
</P>
<P>
   hold property owners responsible.
</P>
<P>
   He wants property owners ``to understand that there are people
living in close proximity to these lots,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Li and Bob Bunger received the letter right around the time they
accepted a cash offer for their flooded Warren Street home, which
is flanked by vacant dwellings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we had listened to (city officials) and gone out there
with plywood and paid for someone to mow the lawn, it would just
have been one house between two that would have been done,'' Li
Bunger said.
</P>
<P>
   And, her husband added, ``What's the point of doing landscaping
or even boarding it up when it's just waiting for the bulldozer?''
</P>
<P>
   Debra Parks moved back into a new mobile home in the midst of
overgrown lots and abandoned homes on Mill Street, and she doesn't
like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to hurry up and get that right,'' Parks said of the
property owners. ``When are they ever going to do anything about
it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``There ain't no telling what's up there in all that grass,''
she said, pointing to tall vegetation bordering her lot. ``I'm
scared of snakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention rats and other vermin, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're definitely going to be coming up out of that when it
gets cold,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
