<HEADLINE>
ONLY REAL RACE LEFT IS IN NL EAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While Arizona and the Dodgers consider their
playoff hopes alive because they haven't been mathematically
eliminated, it'll take something more extraordinary than another
Mets collapse in September to give the Dodgers and Diamondbacks a
real chance.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, the only playoff drama remains in the National League
East, where the Mets and the Braves have a few meaningful games to
play.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the schedule-makers got it right as the Mets and Braves
conclude the season with three games at Shea Stadium, and the East
Division title should be decided then. The Braves entered Saturday
with a 3-game lead over the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a division is to be decided it should be decided within the
division,'' Braves third baseman Chipper Jones said. ``This gives
whoever plays the best the best opportunity to win. ... It can
create a little better rivalry, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamenting Lieberthal: Phillies catcher Mike Lieberthal may be
injured, but it hasn't kept the Westlake High product from talking
about the direction of the Phillies, who average a last-place
finish once every 4.4 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to have a new stadium and I can't see the
Phillies spending a whole lot of money,'' Lieberthal said. ``We
have to have a miracle season to compete with the Braves and Mets.
... Look at the Mets' and Braves' payroll, and look at ours. How
can we beat the Braves and Mets? We don't have a closer. We don't
have a No. 1 starter. Look up the middle. There are concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at how many question marks we have and how many the
Braves and Mets have. I'm sure they have some question marks, but
we have a lot more. And the only way to fill them is by spending
money. And even by spending, it's hard to get players to come here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing is playing here, at this stadium. You might
not have said that a few years ago. But now, everyone has a nice,
new stadium, or at least a nice revised one, like St. Louis. You
see the difference in fan attendance, the turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't get a new stadium for five years, put some money
into this one - just for the fans. If I was a fan, the only reason
I'd come to a game is to see a few of the Phillies players I liked.
They aren't coming here for the food and the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   King(man) of losing: Former A's pitcher Brian Kingman flew to
Philadelphia to watch Phillies lefty Omar Daal attempt to lose his
20th game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But Daal didn't figure in the decision in Thursday's win against
the Mets, which is fine with Kingman. He'd prefer not to be knocked
into anonymity if Daal were lose 20 games. Kingman was the last to
do it, dropping 20 in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, if we had scored more runs, I might have went 14-13,''
said Kingman, CEO of a financial services group. ``But then, who
would be talking to me? I'm proud of losing 20. Cy Young did it
three times. Steve Carlton did it. I'm proud to be associated with
those guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing 20 is actually quite an accomplishment, sad as that
sounds. When you factor in that you could be taken out of the
rotation or sent to the minors, someone has to think you're a good
pitcher to give you the opportunity to lose 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey joins group: Reds center fielder Ken Griffey Jr. became
the fourth player to hit at least 40 homers seven times, joining
Babe Ruth (11), Henry Aaron (eight) and Harmon Killebrew (eight).
Griffey also topped the 40-homer mark for the fifth straight
season, joining Ruth (seven), Ralph Kiner (five) and Duke Snider
(five) as the only players to accomplish that.
</P>
</TEXT>
