<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KARROS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARROS: DODGERS' WOES NOT FOR LACK OF CARING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Eric Karros is used to discussing what's wrong
with the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   That's part of being on the team longer than any of his Dodgers
teammates and seeing the team underachieve each year since enduring
a Los Angeles-record 99 losses in his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   The problems vary from year to year and Karros can identify more
than he'd care to list, noting that, ``It's a combination of
things, not anything specific.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to figure out what went wrong has been frequent again
this year as the Dodgers failed to win the division title for which
they were expected to contend. However, contrary to popular belief,
Karros says a lack of desire is not one of those problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not winning, you're gonna look lethargic and like
you don't care,'' Karros said. ``But that's so far from the truth.
No matter what our record is, we're out there trying as hard as we
can.''
</P>
<P>
   The claim of what's right with the team is supported by a surge
that saw the Dodgers climb back into the National League wild-card
race last week by gaining three and a half games from Sunday
through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not perfect, but we're moving in the right direction,''
manager Davey Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we spend all offseason, all spring training
for,'' Karros said. ``We aren't doing this from February to October
- pretty much year-round - just for the hell of it. It's because we
have pride and we enjoy the game. Our heart's in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's anything I have a hard time understanding, it's for
the fans to feel upset like we don't care. That's just so far from
the truth, it's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Karros backed up his words by arriving hours before a recent
afternoon game in which there was no batting practice and therefore
no requirement to be there so early. He'd rather show how much he
cares that way instead of using outbursts after disappointing
performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go throw my helmet and bang the bat against the cooler or
something, does that mean I care more?'' Karros said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From February until October, the No. 1 priority is this team,
this organization - not family, not anything else. So what is it?
Do you want somebody to just go out and throw their helmet and do
their thing? Well, that's another thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Karros' patience has been tested through the years. The Dodgers
have qualified for the playoffs twice since his first full season
in 1992, but the 32-year-old first baseman from UCLA has yet to
experience a playoff win.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were leading the National League West in 1994, but a
strike ended season. They won the division the next year and made
the playoffs as the wild-card team in 1996, but both times were
quickly eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Despite high expectations and one of the highest payrolls in
baseball, the Dodgers finished third in the division the past two
seasons, last year 23 games out of first.
</P>
<P>
   This year's inconsistent play that has been blamed on everything
from instability in the lower portion of the pitching rotation to
team-chemistry problems dropped the Dodgers out of the division
race long ago, leaving Karros and his teammates with a familiar
feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans think they're upset and they're mad,'' Karros said.
``This is our livelihood, this is what we do. You think somebody on
the street is more discouraged than any person here? We're
frustrated. ...The perception from the outside looking is never
completely accurate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
