<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS GIRD FOR A BATTLE AGAINST THE BUCS' DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was facetiously suggested at some point during the
cacophonous past week that the real fun would be if Keyshawn
Johnson played defense, too, so that he could spend Sunday trying
to jam Wayne Chrebet all the way into the grass of Raymond James
Stadium in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   As if Tampa Bay's defense was not scary enough. The dirty little
secret of Sunday's game between the undefeated Jets and Buccaneers
is that while Johnson may present a huge challenge to audio
technicians everywhere, he is not, by far, the greatest threat to
the Jets' chances of going 4-0. Johnson may have provided the
oratorical background dissonance, but it is the Tampa Bay defense,
which Jets Coach Al Groh compared last week to Pittsburgh's Steel
Curtain of the 1970s, that will surely decide this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been tough to score against Tampa Bay,'' Groh said.
``There has been only one true offensive touchdown scored against
them.''
</P>
<P>
   That came in the game against New England. Two other touchdowns
scored against the Bucs this season came on a punt return by New
England and a desperation pass by Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers' defense will swarm to the ball today with all of
the ferocity of the microphones encircling Johnson. Though ranked
third in the league, it is the most feared unit in the game. The
Bucs have the defending defensive player of the year in lineman
Warren Sapp, who has a league-leading five-and-a-half sacks, and
they have cornered the market on the league's defensive player of
the week award, winning it all three weeks this season.
</P>
<P>
   The unit has 18 sacks in three games, putting it on pace for 96
this season; that would obliterate the record of 72, set by the
1984 Chicago Bears. And the defense has allowed the Bucs' offense,
considered the weak link of the team, to outscore opponents by
93-26, the second-fewest points allowed in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay defense says that if the offense scores just 17
points a game, it can do the rest. Seventeen points is 11 fewer
than the 1985 Bears gave their vaunted defense to work with. It is
8 fewer than the Steel Curtain got in the 1970s, as the Steelers
won four Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Jets center Kevin Mawae said Tampa Bay had the best defense in
the league. Groh went further.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team certainly has the look of a Super Bowl team,'' Groh
said. ``The team looks in style similar to the Pittsburgh teams
when they were on their championship runs. The cornerstone of the
team is defense built on speed and explosiveness and disruption.
You see some of the same type of players, whether it was Jack Ham
playing outside linebacker and now it's Derrick Brooks. Whether it
was Mean Joe Greene disrupting things in the middle and now it's
Warren Sapp. Whether it was the hard-hitting guys in the secondary,
be it Mel Blount and now it's John Lynch and Ronde Barber as the
blitzer.''
</P>
<P>
   This all comes at a time when the Jets' offense continues to
start and stall like a balky car. Fourteen of the Jets' points
against Buffalo _ the best defense the Jets have faced this season
_ were a result of a desperation pass at the end of the first half
and a kickoff return by Kevin Williams. And quarterback Vinny
Testaverde admitted recently that he was having trouble reading
some defenses, particularly corner and safety blitz packages that
are being disguised in ways different from what he was used to
seeing in 1998. That could play right into the Bucs' plans: Barber,
a cornerback, has three and a half sacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets discovered the formula for facing a great defense when
they played Buffalo, which finished last season ranked No.1. The
secret: do not fall far behind and establish the run. That means
blocking Sapp, who has exceptional mobility for someone so large.
</P>
<P>
   Jets running back Curtis Martin, the league's second-leading
rusher, carved out 84 yards against the Bills' defense, which had
been giving up just 46.5 rushing yards a game. Martin said he would
prefer to run right at Sapp, rather than around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that's better or not,'' Martin said. ``He can
disrupt the entire offense. They run around and they all get to the
ball. You need just one guy making the tackle. There's always two,
three, four, five, six guys on one tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   If Tampa Bay gets a quick lead, it will force the Jets to start
throwing the ball more and relying on Martin less. That would give
the Bucs the freedom to rush the passer continually. Ask the Lions'
Charlie Batch what that was like. The Bucs led Detroit by 11 points
in the second half, so he was forced to throw on all but two
second-half plays. The result: he was sacked six times in the
second half. The Jets have given up only two sacks so far this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a line that's going to back down from anyone,'' Jets
guard Randy Thomas said. ``We work too hard to go out there and
make guys look real good.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay's defense looks just fine on its own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
