<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASECOL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYSTEM ERRORS IN MINORS LIMIT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The conclusion to fire Los Angeles Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson seems foregone, though anything is possible
considering the way the Dodgers have operated since ownership was
transferred from the O'Malleys to Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Despite management's complaints about Johnson's managerial
style, one thing keeps popping into mind:
</P>
<P>
   From the moment the current front office took over, it has
preached the importance of the minor-league system. From general
manager Kevin Malone down, it has said a team can't win a
championship unless it has a healthy feeder system.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Dodgers' system is a step above sickly, yet Johnson
was supposed to win this season. Because the Dodgers haven't won,
Johnson could be gone.
</P>
<P>
   Something doesn't seem right.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, it's another example of Johnson feeling the brunt of
a payroll that borders on being out of control. Just because the
Dodgers spent $98 million this season doesn't mean it was spent
correctly.
</P>
<P>
   If, indeed, a team can't win with a poor minor-league system -
and the Yankees, Braves and Cardinals have proven it - why, then,
were the Dodgers expected to win?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing sums up this morass more than last year's outfield woes,
which would have been amplified had the team been involved in a
tight playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   With rosters expanded to 40 players in September, the Dodgers'
starting outfield has consisted of journeyman infielder Chris
Donnels, catcher Paul LoDuca and even pinch-hitter/infielder Dave
Hansen. Injuries to Devon White, Gary Sheffield and Bruce Aven made
it necessary, but the alignment also shows the Dodgers' limited
resources.
</P>
<P>
   This was, after all, an organization so thin that when Eric
Gagne faltered in the back of the pitching rotation, the only
answer was Carlos Perez. Gagne was rushed into a starting spot
despite having no Triple-A experience. The only other choice at the
minor-league level was right-hander Mike Judd.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of viable options is much of the reason Perez lasted the
season with the Dodgers. The club also re-acquired right-hander
Ismael Valdes because it had no candidate as a fifth starter, let
alone a fourth.
</P>
<P>
   When third baseman Adrian Beltre was injured in June, veteran
shortstop Kevin Elster was the answer because no one existed in the
minor- league system to replace him. Not even in a platoon role.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy with the way Todd Hollandsworth and White were playing
in center field and producing in the leadoff spot, the Dodgers
traded for Tom Goodwin. He's under contract for the next two
seasons, but it's not as though he's taking a job from a younger
player.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers thought they had a center fielder in their
minor-league system, they wouldn't have signed White to a
three-year deal after the 1998 season and they wouldn't have
acquired Goodwin for this and the next two seasons. Again, a
shortcoming in the system.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers boast about a 100-game turnaround and five
postseason appearances among its minor-league affiliates. That's
wonderful, especially at the lower levels where the new regime's
draft picks are learning the game as professionals.
</P>
<P>
   But those wins, those playoff berths, meant nothing when it came
to helping the major-league club this season. Albuquerque did it
with a bundle of veteran minor-leaguers and fringe major-leaguers
who will never help the Dodgers. Double-A San Antonio missed the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   When rosters were expanded Sept. 1, the Dodgers called up two
players from Albuquerque. A week later they added three more
players, but only Gagne has seen action from that group.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Johnson could communicate better with his players. Perhaps
jockeying for that big inning most of the time isn't the way to go.
But those are subjective views.
</P>
<P>
   What stinks in this whole mess is how management has maintained
its belief that in order to win, there must be a flourishing
minor-league system. That's not the case with the Dodgers, and, not
only do they know it, they talk about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
