<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL MARINERS FOOT A-ROD'S PRICE TAG?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez will be the
market's hottest free agent this offseason, perhaps commanding as
much as $200 million in a long-term deal. But he refuses to
speculate about his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have me written in as the next Dodgers shortstop, as
the next Mets shortstop,'' Rodriguez told Seattle beat writers last
week. ``They can say what they want, they can write what they want.
What I'll tell you now is that I still consider Seattle No.1.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I really was dead set against returning, I would have done
what Griff (Ken Griffey Jr.) did and just come out and say it. But
I don't feel that way. If Pat (Gillick, GM) and Howard (Lincoln,
CEO) do what they should, there's a good chance that I will stay
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, what Rodriguez thinks Gillick and Lincoln ``should''
do is not only offer enough money, but also convince Rodriguez they
will do what it takes to be an annual contender. Here's the
contradiction: If the Mariners commit $200 million to Rodriguez,
how much money will be left to spend on other quality players?
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be in an environment year-in and year-out like my
buddy Derek (Jeter of the Yankees),'' Rodriguez said. ``It's not
that he knows he's going to the World Series every year. But he
knows his team is going to be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Long dreams: Oakland A's rookie center fielder Terrence Long
wants to be in the playoffs. But he also has another goal: to win
the AL rookie of the year award, and the balance for him is to not
try to do too much while impressing the voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I try not to think about it, but it's hard not to,''
Long said Friday. ``Getting to the playoffs is the thing I want,
but yes, it would be great to win the award.''
</P>
<P>
   Long is putting on an impressive campaign. He scored a run in
the first inning, giving him 98 to break Mark McGwire's team rookie
record.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was in the minors for the A's first 19 games,
Long could finish at .300 with 100 runs, 20 homers and 80 RBIs. He
is hitting .298 in 129 games and leads all rookies in average,
runs, hits, doubles, total bases, extra-base hits and multiple-hit
games.
</P>
<P>
   Long also is hitting .370 with runners in scoring position and
.558 with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Record quest: The Angels' Darin Erstad went into Saturday's game
with 97 RBI, one short of the all-time single-season record by a
leadoff hitter. Boston's Nomar Garciaparra had 98 RBI for the Red
Sox from the leadoff spot in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad also is nearing one of the greatest single-season hit
totals. Going into Saturday's game, he had 227 hits in 153 games, a
pace for 240. No one has reached 240 in a season since Wade Boggs
did it in 1985 for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   And if Erstad can reach 241, he would be the first to get that
many since 1930, when Bill Terry (254), Chuck Klein (250) and Babe
Herman (241) all did. Only 11 players in history have reached 241.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, Rickey: Seattle's Rickey Henderson entered
Saturday's game five walks short of Babe Ruth's all-time record of
2,062. Henderson, though, would have already broken the record if
not for a recent change to Ruth's record.
</P>
<P>
   After research by Elias Sports Bureau and long-time sports
writer/baseball historian Jerome Holtzman, the commissioner's
office added six walks to Ruth's total last year, upping it from
2,056.
</P>
<P>
   Short hops: Even though they don't know who their opponent will
be, the White Sox already have announced their starting pitcher for
the first game of the Division Series - Mike Sirotka. ... With
Derrick Turnbow starting Saturday's game, the Angels have used 15
different starters this season. ... Kansas City's Mike Sweeney has
set a club record with 139 RBI. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
