r a BC-DEADMAN-BACKSBUSH-TEX     09-23 0237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEADMAN-BACKS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBIT ASKS FOR BUSH VOTES IN LIEU OF FLOWERS
</HEADLINE>
 BUSH-TEX  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MELODY McDONALD 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was an unconventional request, but in keeping with their
father's outspoken character.
</P>
<P>
   When James E. Fete Sr. of Canton, Ohio, died of natural causes
Sept. 19 at age 71, his adult sons and daughter ran an obituary in
the ``Canton Repository.'' The obit listed the retired telephone
repairman's accomplishments: Korean War service and 39 years with
Ohio Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing out of the ordinary, until the last line:
</P>
<P>
   ``In lieu of flowers, Vote Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Fete (pronounced FATE), once a staunch Democrat, became a
diehard Republican 40 years ago. He never let the readers of the
``Repository's'' letters-to-the-editor column forget his strong
political views.
</P>
<P>
   Fete was ``anti-Gore and really anti-Clinton,'' said his eldest
son, James E. Fete Jr., explaining his father's support of Gov.
George W. Bush, the Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   So when Fete's survivors composed his obituary, the political
appeal was a natural choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of bouquet of flowers, he would rather have a vote for
Bush,'' the son said Saturday, speaking by telephone from Canton.
``He would have also liked to have got the last word _ and he
did.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
