<HEADER>
A9092 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-SOFTMONEY-N     09-23 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-SOFTMONEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES BACK `SOFT MONEY' BAN IN NEW YORK RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DEAN E. MURPHY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rep. Rick Lazio reached a
tentative agreement on Saturday to forgo the use of soft money for
advertising in the New York Senate race, but the deal included
several conditions and provisions that could derail it and came
just a day after talks on another proposal collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an agreement _ it appears,'' Lazio said at his
headquarters Saturday night. ``I said that yesterday, I know.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate statement Saturday night after Lazio's acceptance
of Clinton's proposal, her spokesman, Howard Wolfson, said: ``Nine
months ago, Hillary Clinton called for the elimination of soft
money issue advertising and independent expenditures from this
race. We hope that today we have finally achieved her goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Under an offer made by Clinton during a campaign appearance in
Manhattan, both sides would place a ban on television and radio
advertisements paid for by political parties with so-called soft
money _ largely unregulated contributions that enable candidates to
circumvent legal limits on fund-raising. Clinton and Lazio would
also appeal to independent groups supporting them to refrain from
broadcasting ads on their behalf, leaving the campaign committees
as the only advertisers in the contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is simple,'' Clinton said. ``We will keep soft-money issue
ads off the air if they keep theirs off the air. Just the two
campaign committees should be on the air advertising their
campaigns. If any supporters of either candidate should violate
this, the other side could respond proportionately.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said she had secured the commitments of the various
Democratic Party organizations that would be affected by the
prohibition, as well as the Working Families Party and Liberal
Party, which have also endorsed her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   She said Lazio needed to do the same among Republicans and
Conservatives by Monday, a deadline Lazio said he could and would
meet.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would not take effect until Wednesday, Clinton said,
because the state Democratic Party has already bought television
ads on her behalf that run through Wednesday. Lazio's campaign
initially objected to the Wednesday deadline, saying the state ads
must be withdrawn by Monday, but Lazio backed off that demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the ads that she is airing right now should come
down by Monday; I think that would show good faith,'' the
congressman said Saturday night. ``But what is important here is
that it appears we have an agreement in principle to ban soft money
from both campaigns and keep all outside groups out. But it is
important, in the words of former President Ronald Reagan, that we
must trust and verify.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's campaign said it liked Saturday's offer better than
Clinton's previous proposals because it dropped the requirements
that Lazio stop advertisements by groups that support him.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Clinton suggested that Lazio should get written
assurances from those groups, but insisted she did not need to do
the same from groups that support her. She said Saturday that she
still believed there was a difference between groups that back her
candidacy and those that support his, but added that it was more
important to focus on the political parties' involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Berger, a prominent Democratic election lawyer in New York
City, said enforcing the deal could prove to be its downfall.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has always maintained that she does not have the power
to stop independent groups from advertising on her behalf, and it
is unclear whether they will heed her call to stay out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plus is that it is a first step that may limit soft money
expenditures; it may in fact work,'' Berger said. ``The downside
is, if the advocacy groups simply don't go along with it, it may
break down.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger said the ban may also have come too late to have a big
effect on the race. ``It is very late. It is sort of like trying to
turn the Queen Mary around.''
</P>
<P>
   Soft money, which is raised by party committees for
get-out-the-vote and other party-building activities, is separate
from the so-called hard money raised directly by political
campaigns. Hard money is subject to federal limits _ $1,000 per
person _ while soft money can be collected in unlimited amounts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has relied heavily on soft-money contributions to pay
for advertisements on her behalf; Lazio has not raised soft money
for his Senate campaign, in part because he has been able to
collect large sums of hard money from people across the country
opposed to Mrs. Clinton and her husband.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
