<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUNNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE TACKLES PROBLEMS OF TURNOVERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ True to his word, Cal State Northridge football
coach Jeff Kearin is taking measures to prevent turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past week, the Matadors were given the green light to
tackle to the ground in practice - something they usually don't do
to avoid injuries. However, a change was in order since CSUN is
averaging four turnovers a game.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of players - including running back Bruce Molock and
defensive back Steve Paysinger - sustained crushing hits and had to
be walked off the field by trainers. Both are OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've certainly picked up the intensity,'' Kearin said.
``We've had more live periods where we're working on our execution
in a live situation and testing our toughness.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times we're not sure (about our toughness) and at times
we're the toughest team I've seen. We need the consistency over
time. We have to perform at that toughness and level of execution
over time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors had the luxury of withstanding hard hits since they
had a bye Saturday. But the week off also meant CSUN had to deal
with its disappointing 49-26 loss to Northern Arizona a little
longer. The Matadors (1-2, 0-1) aren't out of contention for the
Big Sky Conference title but they must figure out a way to get back
on track - and fast.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN and NAU were tied 21-21 at halftime, but three second-half
turnovers and miscues by the Matadors defense led to the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think where NAU beat us is heart and toughness,'' senior
receiver Gil Rodriguez said. ``They outplayed us in the second half
and outhit us. We can't play two quarters. We have to play four
full quarters - four full quarters of hitting and four full
quarters of holding on to the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting rush: The CSUN coaching staff blanketed the area from
San Diego to Fresno on Friday and Saturday in an effort to attract
its recruiting class for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Northridge, it's as important for us to see as to be
seen,'' Kearin said. ``A lot of these kids don't want to think in
terms of I-AA football now. The vast majority of these kids that
sign believe they're I-A scholarship guys. We'll be gathering as
much information as we can as far as our needs and scholarships.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury report: Wide receiver Drew Amerson is ahead of schedule
with rehabilitation on his bruised knee - an injury he suffered
Sept. 9. Amerson started riding the exercise bike on Wednesday.
There's a chance Amerson could play in Saturday's home game against
Idaho State but the Oct. 5 game at Weber State is a more likely
return date. ... Linebacker Ben Lorier (ankle), Jamaal Perry
(ankle) and D.J. Hackett (knee) are expected to be OK for Idaho
State.
</P>
<P>
   Bulletin board material: Rodriguez and offensive lineman Keith
Kincaid plastered players' lockers with the Weekly Buzz, which runs
in The Daily Sundial - CSUN's student newspaper. Four students were
asked what they thought about the CSUN football team and the
responses were not good.
</P>
<P>
   ``(We) put it in their lockers to get the guys fired up,''
Rodriguez said. ``This is not high school football - it's college
football. It kind of motivated me. I don't want to lose anymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
