<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAYPHONES-RARE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISUSE DOOMING PAY PHONES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DONNA HUFFAKER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Once a fixture on many corners, the pay phone has
become as rare as a rotary dial.
</P>
<P>
   Competition from wireless phones and long-distance calling cards
has driven down the number of public telephones by more than
300,000 since 1998, from 2.4 million to 2.1 million nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   And while the average pay phone produced a little more than $200
a month two years ago, revenues today have dwindled to $150 a month
or less.
</P>
<P>
   Even Martin Mattes, counsel to the California Payphone
Association, said he doesn't use pay phones as much now as before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use a cell phone. You might be paying more money for that
call, but it's worth it for the convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Cellular Telecommunications Industry
Association, there are 101,985,390 worldwide wireless subscribers -
a number that will skyrocket to 1 billion over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones might pose the largest threat to their coin-operated
counterpart, but other factors also chip away at the pay phone's
time left on the streets, including service carriers failing to pay
the required amount to the pay phone providers, Mattes said. Plus,
he added, when the cost of maintaining the phone surpasses the
amount of money it is making, there's no point keeping it
connected.
</P>
<P>
   Not that everyone is sounding the death knell for pay phones.
``There's always going to be a need for a pay phone,'' said Vince
Sandusky, president of the American Public Communications Council,
a national association of independent pay phone providers that
keeps track of how the pay phone is faring in a fast-growing world
of wireless technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``There won't be a market for 2 million of them, but I don't see
this as the demise of the pay phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting across the street from a public telephone, Julia Blythe
pulled her cell phone from her purse, checked her messages and
lined up evening plans without ever getting up from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-year-old became a wireless user six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just too lazy to go and look for one,'' she said of pay
phones. ``And this is so convenient. I mean, it's right here.''
</P>
<P>
   The only bummer?
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless phones, and their attractive packages offering
``buckets of minutes'' for nominal rates, have helped reduce pay
phone revenues, said Steve Getzug, spokesman for Pacific Bell.
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications, the parent company of Pacific Bell, isn't
worried, though, he said. Officials believe pay and wireless phones
complement each other and that there's room for both in the market.
Besides, not everyone has a wireless phone, he said, noting there
are places where pay phones are preferred - airports, shopping
malls, schools and the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 35 cents, a pay phone is still a bargain in some people's
books. You can talk until your voice runs dry on a local call, and
that's a pretty good deal,'' Getzug said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Public Communications Council, 95
percent of homes in the United States have telephone service.
Roughly 25 percent of the rural poor do not, Sandusky said. For
them, the only way to call friends, to dial 911, to make a doctor's
appointment or call for a job interview is to use the pay phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Demographics suggest they'll put a phone in their home before
they'll buy a wireless,'' Sandusky said. ``There are a bunch of
people who still don't have wireless and probably never will. The
pay phone still has legs.''
</P>
<P>
   The two main lines of revenue for a pay phone are the coin box
and the compensation the provider receives from the carrier. An
example of compensation is when a caller uses 1-800 COLLECT or
1-800-CALL ATT, Mattes said, explaining that the latter is called
``dial-around compensation'' guaranteed by the Telecommunications
Act passed by Congress in 1996 and regulated by the Federal
Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers must pay 24 cents to pay phone providers for
dial-around calls, but the providers do not always receive that
money, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, two-thirds of a pay phone's revenue stems from coins
and one-third is generated from noncoin means. But pay phones at
airports and convention centers, where callers zip a credit card
through more technologically advanced systems, see higher profits
than phones stationed outside a convenience store or a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   And, Mattes added, the providers must pay fees to the owners of
the land where the phone is located.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated revenue a phone needs to produce to be profitable
is $200 to $300 a month. Installing a phone costs at least $500,
and that's with a simple enclosure. Add $1,000 in other fees, plus
$100 in labor, and the phone must net at least $200 a month just to
show a profit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dropping coins into a pay phone, Delbert Gleason wanted to call
his son and ask what he wanted for dinner. He doesn't have a cell
phone and said he uses public phones about six times a year.
</P>
<P>
   Not for much longer, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting a cell phone. I go to the desert a lot. There's no
pay phones out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
