<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BCEAGLES-DEWALT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEWALT WINS THE PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston College junior wide receiver Dedrick Dewalt really loves
playing against the military academies. Two weeks ago at Army, he
had three catches for 122 yards and two touchowns.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, in the Eagles' 48-7 victory against visiting Navy, the
5-foot-9-inch Dewalt (who says he feels like ``I'm 6-3 and that the
ball's mine'') collected six catches for 111 yards and two
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm older now than I was a year ago, and I know what to expect
for the games,'' said Dewalt. ``I know how to approach games. I
know how to prepare for them, with my confidence helping me from
last year, and it's been a steady building.''
</P>
<P>
   Dewalt, who had 38 catches last season, has 11 receptions for
261 yards and a 23.7-yards-per-catch average. Dewalt, who clocks
the 40 in 4.4, is the veteran the Eagles are looking for to spark
the passing game.
</P>
<P>
   He has been patiently working with quarterback Tim Hasselbeck to
build a solid passing combination. ``We worked real hard during the
summer, during the offseason, ever since I've been here,'' said
Dewalt. ``Having man-to-man against me surprised me (and gave) me a
lot of room on the flank. And then along the sidelines, we gave
each other the eye, to let him know that I will probably be right
there on the pass, with Navy giving me the outside, but I was
always able to be inside the coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   His first TD came on a 30-yard pass with 1:08 remaining in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a post-route move, moving to the middle; the guy came
back underneath me,'' Dewalt said. ``And then on my second
touchdown catch for 37 yards, I just put on the move to make the
catch.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, Dewalt thought he had a 40-yard catch but
it was ruled incomplete. ``The ref said I caught it and the other
game official said it fell incomplete,'' said Dewalt, who did well
on a punt return, too (37 yards). ``It's something I've been
working hard on all of last week. I was kept back there, and I
improved with my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Dewalt likes what Boston College has done the last two games,
with the 55-17 victory at Army and Saturday's triumph after a 34-14
setback at West Virginia to open the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our last two games got our confidence going again, reaching
back,'' he said. ``We've taken the last two games to heart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
