</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ONBALL-SOXOWNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNER OF THIS MESS MUST ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Mr. Harrington (it's been so long since I've talked to you,
I feel a little awkward calling you John):
</P>
<P>
   I know you've had a rough summer, spending long hours on winning
support for your field of dreams. Personally, and I mean this
sincerely, I hope you succeed in your venture.
</P>
<P>
   But Mr. Harrington, I think you need to put the fund-raising on
hold for a little while. Maybe you've been too busy to notice, sir,
but your ball club has gone to hell the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   Missing the playoffs is the least of your worries. Your general
manager, Dan Duquette, has sold out your manager, Jimy Williams,
one of the most honorable and respected men in the game, in order
to pander to your center fielder, Carl Everett, a guy who doesn't
even care that his own teammates have little respect for him.
</P>
<P>
   It may just be urban legend, sir, but one of your fans swears
that he was sitting in the bleachers Friday night and saw one of
your relief pitchers clapping when Everett struck out as a pinch
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that's true or not,'' another player said
Saturday, ``but you know what? There probably are some other guys
in here who would have liked to have clapped, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Strictly from a business perspective, I don't think that's the
best way for you to drum up $650 million for your new playpen,
sacrificing Williams on the altar of Everett, who somehow has
become more important around here, at least to your general
manager, than Nomar Garciaparra and Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   You may not know this, but Nomar has been playing hurt for
weeks. And Pedro's legacy may forever be coming out of the bullpen
in Cleveland last October with a bad shoulder and pitching no-hit
ball for six innings. You won the American League Division Series
that night.
</P>
<P>
   Everett's legacy? Well, he's going to have a hard time living
down what he did Thursday, showing up an hour before a
make-or-break doubleheader with the Indians, erupting in anger when
he saw his name in the lineup, announcing that he couldn't play,
cursing your manager to anyone within earshot, then nearly coming
to blows with Darren Lewis, who dared to question Everett's
commitment to the team to his face.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette would have you believe it's a tardiness issue, sir. But
that's just the beginning of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about winning,'' one of your players said Saturday.
``This guy shows up an hour before one of our most important games
of the season and says he can't play. He didn't come in for
treatment, he didn't even try to see if he could play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can find stars around the game who show up late, but I
have never, ever seen that, a guy who showed his teammates he
didn't even care.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, as class a guy as you'll ever find in this or any other
clubhouse, won't say exactly what it was he told Everett, but I can
you assure you, that was the essential message. Everett's response?
Lewis was disrespecting him.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't surprise Williams that Lewis said something to
Everett. ``Darren Lewis is a winner,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   What does that make Everett? I don't know. All I know is that
for all his wonderful talent, which far eclipses the gifts Lewis
has, your team is staying home this October. Lewis played on two
teams that went to the postseason for you.
</P>
<P>
   And now Williams isn't taking it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was general manager, I certainly would back the
manager,'' Williams said Saturday after making a phone call to
Duquette's office and leaving a message that he was going to say
his piece. ``Now if you can't back the manager, then you probably
need to get rid of him. That's what you need to do, and get
somebody you can back.
</P>
<P>
   ``You separate a team with one player, and it's basically going
against the thoughts of the manager and the focus of the team in
trying to win. It becomes very difficult. So, with the statements
that have been made, I feel like I'm kind of backed into a
corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, you may disagree, but to me that sounds like definitive
evidence that there's a problem between your manager and your GM.
Duquette would have you think that the media made it all up. That's
something Duquette and Everett have in common. The minute they're
held accountable for their actions, they blame it all on the media.
</P>
<P>
   You remember that sports management consultant you hired back in
1996 to meet with Duquette and your manager at the time, Kevin
Kennedy, in an effort to iron out their problems? I hope you saved
his phone number, because the problems between Duquette and
Williams make the Kennedy-Duke spat look like batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   I might be wrong, but when the consultant delivered his report
to you four years ago, he told you your GM was a big part of the
problem. But you backed your GM when he fired Kennedy, just as you
backed him when Roger Clemens and Mo Vaughn left.
</P>
<P>
   Remember what Duquette said back then? Let me jog your memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This catering to stars doesn't work. We're trying to change.
The formula for winning isn't one star and the rest of the Red Sox.
Boston has always catered to the stars, always. And that's not the
best way for success. We're trying to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said that in 1997. I don't know, sir, but it seems to
me he was either lying then, or is a hypocrite now.
</P>
<P>
   Let me remind you of another statement that came from your
organization. When Tomo Ohka and Sunny Kim, your two gifted Asian
pitchers, came to blows this summer in Pawtucket, they were both
suspended. Your organization issued a high-minded press release
that stated the Sox have ``zero tolerance for conduct that includes
hostility between co-workers on or off the field. The organization
makes every effort to foster a workplace where each individual
treats each other with dignity and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet on a night when Everett curses your manager and nearly comes
to blows with a teammate, Duquette stands in front of the media and
says no disciplinary action will be taken.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Harrington, your players are weary of talking about this.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a problem, obviously,'' catcher Scott Hatteberg said.
``It's not a big thing, but yes, the last incident, yeah there are
things that need to be worked out. Whether or not they can be, I
don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get a guy like Darren Lewis, who I respect as much as
anybody I've ever met in the game, upset, there's something that is
wrong. Whether it's reparable, I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   The rift between Williams and Duquette creates its own problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that there's so many hands in the pot here,''
Hatteberg said. ``You don't know who is making calls or doing what.
Guys need to play on the field, but they also need to get along.
There are too many of us who are working too hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo Vaughn was as good as anybody on the field and I didn't
think he was that bad around here, but that seemed to be the reason
they got rid of him. I understand being a superstar like (Everett)
is, Pedro is, Nomar is, we know there will be extra demands on
their time. But there are rules that are in place, not only for us
but for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where it has gotten in the clubhouse with Everett: ``We
look at it as there are 24 of us,'' one player said, ``and if he
wants to play, great.''
</P>
<P>
   I assure you, Mr. Harrington, Williams isn't going to quit. He's
no fool. He understands that Duquette would like nothing better
than for him to quit, regardless of what he might say. How can you
any longer attach any credibility to what Duquette says, when he
still went on TV Saturday and said there were no problems between
Williams and himself?
</P>
<P>
   Here's how much respect Duquette has for Williams. According to
the manager Saturday, Duquette had not discussed the Everett matter
with him, two days after it happened. That is shameful.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette claims that Everett will cease to be a problem once he
learns to report on time. He doesn't even realize how ridiculous
that sounds, coming at the end of the season. If Everett hasn't
figured that out by now, what makes anyone think he's going to
figure it out later?
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Everett stood in front of his locker and said he owes
no one an apology. Not his manager, not his teammates, surely not
the reporters he has cursed, nor the umpire he bumped. Everett has
to apologize to no man. He sits in the back of the plane on team
flights and talks about how the whole world disrespects him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk to him, you're talking to a guy who thinks he's
always right,'' one teammate said, ``when the reality is he is
almost never right.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is going to make Duquette fire him. And as much as
people might gripe about some of the moves Williams makes in the
dugout, they know him to be a man of unassailable integrity. And
Duquette now knows he will be barbecued if he fires Williams.
</P>
<P>
   When Duquette was defending Everett Thursday night, one of the
things he mentioned was that ``the fans like him.'' But fans still
believe in some of the old-fashioned values, too, like having some
respect for your boss and your teammates. It was no accident Friday
night that when Everett pinch hit, the fans booed him.
</P>
<P>
   Would they have cheered if he had hit a home run instead of
striking out? Sure. But will they ever feel about him the way they
do about Nomar or Pedro or even Mo? Not a chance. And it won't be
because of anything the media reports. Everett prides himself on
being his own man. Well, his own actions, unfiltered by the media,
will speak for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Harrington, I know we have had our differences. I admit
there have been times you may have been justified in feeling that I
have been unfair to you.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm suggesting that you need to intercede now, sir, and try
to salvage some dignity out of this sorry mess, because I was born
a New Englander, and for good or for bad, I _ like you _ was raised
to care about the Olde Towne Team.
</P>
<P>
   I hope to see you at the ballpark, sir. In case you've been too
busy to notice, Sunday is the last time this season the Sox will
play at Fenway Park, the place that brings you to tears when you
talk about someday having to tear it down. This place can't be
spared a wrecking ball. But maybe it's not too late to save your
team.
</P>
<P>
   Sincerely, &QL; 
Gordon Edes
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
