<HEADLINE>
EAGLES' AIR ATTACK TOO MUCH FOR NAVY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Boston College shellacked Army. Saturday, the
Eagles bombarded Navy. Is there any chance of getting Air Force on
the schedule?
</P>
<P>
   With a tough Big East game looming Saturday against a
well-rested Virginia Tech team that enjoyed an open date Saturday,
BC improved its record to 2-1 after scoring its second consecutive
victory in three weeks against a service academy opponent. After
blasting Army, 55-17, two weeks ago at Michie Stadium, the Eagles
came back from a week off to execute a 48-7 aerial bombardment of
Navy in Saturday's home opener before an Alumni Stadium crowd of
42,681.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're in the big leagues next week and we have to
improve a lot,'' BC coach Tom O'Brien said about the fifth-ranked
Hokies.
</P>
<P>
   Senior quarterback Tim Hasselbeck completed 20 of 28 passes for
a career-high 355 yards Saturday, connecting with junior Dedrick
Dewalt on six passes for 111 yards, including touchdown plays of 30
and 37 yards that helped the Eagles build a 24-7 lead in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   Senior running back Cedric Washington recorded his second
consecutive 100-yard effort and the seventh of his career, carrying
24 times for 107 yards, including a 5-yard TD run. William Green
added 58 yards on 12 carries, scoring on runs of 1 and 3 yards.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Eagles sandwiched 14-point quarters in the first and
fourth around 10-point eruptions in the second and third to run 80
offensive plays for a season-high 625 yards total offense. It was
BC's biggest offensive output since a 610-yard effort in a 32-31
home loss to Navy two years ago. In its games with Army and Navy,
BC has put up a gaudy aggregate of 158 plays, 1,212 yards total
offense, 103 points.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Hasselbeck intoned, that should be kept in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two teams we beat don't have any wins between them, so
that kind of brings you down to reality a little bit,'' said
Hasselbeck, who has connected on 47 of 73 passes for 730 yards and
six touchdowns this season. ``You have to understand that, but at
the same time, you can walk away with some confidence and some
experience, and guys are getting a feel of what it's like to make
plays out there, and that's important.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the offense was buoyed by its production of late, the
young and inexperienced Eagles defense only seemed to become more
challenged with the loss of starting linebackers Scott Bradley and
Ryan Burch to knee injuries, forcing redshirt freshman J.D. Schmidt
to step in as the only middle linebacker left on the BC sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably going to lose Bradley and Burch a couple of
weeks,'' said O'Brien. ``Both of them have to have MRIs.''
</P>
<P>
   Things were tough already as junior linebacker Andy Romanowsky,
Burch's backup, suffered an ankle sprain in Thursday's practice and
was not available and senior cornerback D.J. Sutton was also out
after falling ill earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing threes now,'' O'Brien said. ``Someone was
yelling at me to put the subs in and they were in. They were
starting.''
</P>
<P>
   And O'Brien was pleased with the way his defense responded. The
Eagles held Navy to 223 yards total offense, forced three fumbles
(with Lenny Walls and Frank Misurelli each making a recovery), and
completely dominated the Midshipmen in the third quarter by
allowing six plays for 8 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles took 6 minutes 6 seconds to build a 17-0 lead on
Green's 1-yard run, Dewalt's brilliant 30-yard grab (despite
defensive interference by Navy cornerback Marcus Jackson), and Mike
Sutphin's 39-yard field goal, before Navy scored its only TD of the
game on a 12-yard run by Rashad Jamal with 6:28 left in the half.
Dewalt's second TD rallied the Eagles to a 24-7 lead at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Sutphin added a 24-yard field goal, and Washington followed with
a 5-yard TD run in the third before the Eagles closed out the
scoring with Green's 3-yard TD and Brian St. Pierre's 6-yard TD
pass to Josh Cervi with 8:31 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speed of (Navy's spread option offense) caught us
off-guard, which it was going to do after not playing for two
weeks,'' said O'Brien. ``Once we caught up to it, we did a better
job.''
</P>
<P>
   But the survivors of BC's injury-riddled defense will have to do
a much better job if they expect to contain Michael Vick, the
mercurial quarterback of Virginia Tech's explosive offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of challenges coming up,'' said senior free
safety RaMon Johnson. ``But we've got a lot of young talent on this
team and hopefully we'll play as hard as we did today.'' If not
harder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
