<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-WEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER IS POINTING TO THE WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here at the Globe, we jokingly refer to ourselves as the junior
varsity in the presence of our esteemed colleagues from the mother
ship, The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the majority of teams in the NBA also should feel now
that Patrick Ewing has gone to Seattle to make a tough division and
conference even more powerful. That tilt you may have just felt was
the top-heavy West getting stronger and the JV East getting, well,
more JV.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the NBA might consider adopting the Italian League
format, adding the Spurs and Heat to the Pacific Division, throwing
out the Warriors and Clippers, and letting everyone else battle for
scraps. You'd have seven teams in A1 and everyone else in A2. That
includes Indiana and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Put yourself in the shoes of Golden State general manager Garry
St. Jean. He can look at the Eastern Conference and figure his
team, if healthy, would be a viable playoff contender. He can look
at his team in the Western Conference and book nonrefundable
airfare to the Cape for the weekend of April 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we're going to be better,'' said St. Jean, going out on
a limb after last year's glittering 19-63 submission. But he's
right. They will be better. It just won't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our division,'' St. Jean continued, ``is as good as any
division in, what, the last 15 years? And our conference is as deep
as I can ever remember. Night in and night out, there are going to
be great games. The power is in the West.''
</P>
<P>
   That has been the case in the post-Jordan era, and it sure
doesn't look like anything has changed. The two best teams in the
league last year, the Lakers and Portland, both improved. The 1999
NBA champion, San Antonio, improved. The Sonics have improved with
the addition of Ewing. The Suns feel they are better after last
week's megatrade simply because they replaced a slug (Luc Longley)
with a stiff (Chris Dudley).
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected more of Luc, and we didn't have very high
expectations,'' said Suns boss Jerry Colangelo in a real show of
support for his ex-center. ``But I think we're a better team now
than we were before the deal. Dudley, warts and all, still gives
you toughness, rebounding, and shot-blocking capabilities. And I
like what Seattle did. I like a team that's willing to take risks.
But that's what you have to do out here. It's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   We haven't even gotten to Utah, Sacramento, or Houston, the
latter of which can throw Steve Francis and Maurice Taylor at you
and still will have a hard time making the playoffs. Dallas could
win a division title in the Central and still not crack the top
eight in the West. Minnesota? Its team slogan should be ``the
writing's on the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, you have the JV East, in which the Celtics will be
pressed to crack the not-so-great eight.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana, last year's JV entrant in the Finals, is not as strong
and may be further weakened if Rik Smits hangs 'em up. Did the
Knicks bring a laugh track to accompany the remarks that they were
going to war with their new roster, featuring Longley and Glen
Rice? Philadelphia may be better simply because it did nothing (a
strange feat given Larry Brown's historically itchy trigger finger)
and Orlando is better, but by how much?
</P>
<P>
   Miami is, right now, in a class by itself, although it remains
to be seen whether Brian Grant can survive Pat Riley's boot camp.
Grant has never averaged 32 minutes a game; Riles wants him to play
35.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, he may only need to go 20. After all, he'll be
playing most of his games against the junior varsity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Packing his bags?
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pack never wanted to be included in the four-way trade
last month that landed him and the disabled Hot Rod Williams in
Boston. There was considerable discussion during negotiations about
Pack's situation, including, but not limited to, his apparent
tendency to be tardy for practice with the Nets. There's also his
contract situation: He'll be a free agent, and even if he delivers
a boffo season, he has come to a team that won't re-sign him.
That's why there's still talk of sending Pack to Denver. Dan Issel,
the Nuggets coach/GM, remains one of the few people in the league
who still think Pack can play. In addition, Pack would have a
better chance of playing in Denver as Nick Van Exel's backup and,
by extension, of re-signing there . . . The NBA actually approved
Joe Smith's one-year contract with the Timberwolves, but did so
knowing that the deal will get voided in arbitration. The league
did the same thing with Dudley's wink-wink deal with Portland a few
years back, but lost that one in arbitration. That won't happen
this time. Smith, meanwhile, is said to be all but signed, sealed,
and delivered to Dallas once the arbitration decision makes him a
free agent . . . As the Celtics had hoped, Kris Clack decided to
play this season in Italy. The Celtics retain his rights. Clack
played well during the summer but still faced long odds to make the
team . . . The comeback story of Bobby Hurley, which looked
promising, probably won't happen at all. Hurley was scheduled to
play for the Celtics' summer league entry in July with an eye
toward getting into someone's veterans camp. But Hurley wasn't fit
enough to play and he still isn't. His agent, Mike Higgins, reports
that his client will now consider retirement and try to catch on in
the coaching business . . . I thought last year's first-round NBA
playoff schedule was ridiculous (and it was) and then I saw the
grueling Major League Soccer postseason schedule. The Revolution
and Fire needed eight days to play three games . . . It has become
fashionable to point out David Falk's tough summer (which was even
tougher until the Rice/Ewing deal went down). Cited as one example
is Taylor's settling for the mid-level exception ($2.25 million) in
Houston when the Rockets had a valid trade exception of $4.5
million. ``I wanted to use the exception and I told David that we
could do a sign-and-trade with Elgin (Baylor, the Clippers' general
manager),'' said Carroll Dawson, the Rockets' executive vice
president of basketball operations. ``David said he didn't want it.
He said he'd prefer to roll the dice and see what happens next
summer when we have some cap room. A lot of people were after
(Taylor). I think we were lucky to get him.'' Houston still has its
trade exception, which expires Oct. 3. Dawson said the Rockets will
not use it unless they can obtain a ``building block'' for the
future. (The exception has to be used in a trade.) ``Also, we've
got to get under the cap to retain the guys we have now,'' he said,
referring to Taylor and Shandon Anderson, both of whom will be
looking for big paydays after coming to Houston for short money
(NBA currency). There's also the matter of Hakeem Olajuwon, who is
in the final year of his contract. ``Dream is looking forward to
the season,'' Dawson said. ``He just has to find a way to whip the
asthma he had last year. That really slowed him down last year.'' .
. . You have to wonder why the Hawks are so hesitant to deal
Dikembe Mutombo to the Knicks (unless, of course, they don't want
to help a conference foe). Or, let's put it another way. Why would
Mutombo want to stay? The Hawks have blown it up and are starting
over. They are going to be bad this year with or without Mutombo,
and have already said they are pointing to next summer when they
plan to have cap room to pursue free agents. But that cap room
disappears in a hurry with Mutombo's weighty contract on the books,
unless he is quickly re-signed before the Hawks pursue any free
agents. Until he is re-signed, his cap hold for the 2001-02 season
will be an astronomical $21.6 million. That's more than half of the
projected $42.7 million cap. Throw in Alan Henderson, Lorenzen
Wright, and some of the young kids and there goes the cap room.
However, if Mutombo were traded, the Hawks' cap room would reemerge
in that the salaries of the players coming aboard likely would be
much less than his cap hold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Greece is slippery
</P>
<P>
   What did the NBA know and when did they know it? That's what
lawyers for the Greek team AEK asked at last Thursday's arbitration
proceeding in London pertaining to the future of center Iakovos
``Jake'' Tsakalidis. Is he 23 or 21? The NBA says it doesn't
matter, even though, in its own arbitration brief, it lists
Tsakalidis as 23, which, under NBA rules, would have made him
ineligible for last June's draft. (Phoenix took him in the first
round.) The reason it doesn't matter is that Tsakalidis, the NBA,
and the Players Association all met before the draft and agreed he
was 21 and thus eligible. OK. But AEK has what sure looks like a
league memo from six weeks before the draft, which dealt with an
anonymous letter questioning Tsakalidis's age and background. A
copy was sent to then-operations chief Rod Thorn, who forwarded it
to the legal department. Also cut in for a copy of the anonymous
letter (which was addressed to New York Post columnist Peter
Vecsey) was union head Billy Hunter. The league's arbitration
brief, meanwhile, had all the ingredients of a LeCarre novel,
mentioning that Tsakalidis was plucked out of Soviet Georgia by a
greedy Greek agent, supplied with false passports and other bogus
data, and then, magically, became a Greek citizen. He then was told
to sign a contract he had not read, nor could read, because it was
in Greek and he couldn't speak or understand the language. But he
was listed as a Greek national on the AEK roster. The NBA contends
that the contract Tsakalidis has with AEK is invalid because the
center didn't know what he was signing and that it violated FIBA
regulations regarding the number of ``foreigners'' (non-Greeks in
this case) allowed on one team. Thursday's arbitration lasted about
10 hours and both sides have until Tuesday to submit further
information. A decision is due Friday, but the Suns remain hopeful
something can be worked out before then. Colangelo said the Suns
have tried to be accommodating, offering exhibitions and clinics in
Greece (where Scott Skiles coached) as well as the league-allowed
maximum of $350,000 to settle the issue. He said AEK has been
obstinate. ``Their requests were ludicrous,'' Colangelo said,
preferring not to elaborate. ``There were things they wanted that
we could not do. Hopefully, we can get it settled. We think Jake is
a terrific prospect.''
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in compiling
this report.
</P>
