<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-OLYMPICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO BURNING REASON TO ADD GOLF TO GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No, we don't need to add golf to the Olympics. This bad idea has
been talked about for years, and talk was rekindled this past week
when David Fay, executive director of the US Golf Association,
threw his support behind the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, people have looked at the notion of Olympic
golf and said, `Why should we do it?' '' Fay said after attending a
meeting of the World Amateur Golf Council. ``That frustrates me. I
ask, `Why shouldn't we do it?' I haven't come up with one reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, this is a guy whose extravagantly rich organization
saw fit to restructure the US Public Links Championship so that
less money was available for travel, meaning fewer players _ many
of whom are at the heart of this game _ got to play. Yet he's
willing to get involved with a group that spends lavishly on
pampered athletes.
</P>
<P>
   But that is straying somewhat from the point, which is Fay's
search for a reason. He wants one; let's give him three.
</P>
<P>
   1. Patriotism in soft spikes? Golf already stuffs a ton of it
into cups of all shapes, sizes, and names. Ryder Cup, Presidents
Cup, Solheim Cup, Walker Cup, Curtis Cup, Palmer Cup, PGA Cup,
World Cup, Dunhill Cup, Junior Ryder Cup _ here a cup, there a cup,
everyhere a cup, cup. Then there's the World Junior and the recent
World Team Amateur, which offered a glimpse of the drama Olympic
golf would deliver: Team Slovakia took 1,052 strokes over 16 rounds
to finish last among 59 teams, a mere 211 shots behind the winners,
the Americans. Radoslav Sip and Peter Wieger posted Slovakia's best
score _ 85s. You want to rush right out, wave the flag, and sing
``God Bless America'' when you slap around Slovakia, Estonia,
Croatia, Latvia, Greece, Luxembourg, Costa Rica et al on the golf
course.
</P>
<P>
   2. Who's going to play? The touring pros? Sure, they'll line up
to skip the British Open for a chance to beat up on some Tunisian,
10 and 8. (This year is an aberration; the Summer Olympics are
normally in the dead of summer, right when players are gearing up
for the British and the PGA.) The BUY.com stars? The minitour guys?
Club pros? Does anyone feel a pulse of excitement? What about
amateurs? OK, go with them and what happens when the US loses?
Typical of us, there'd be a huge outcry to fix this catastrophe and
before you know it, we'd steal away childhoods _ just as they do in
gymnastics and figure skating _ all in the name of winning.
</P>
<P>
   3. Golf is, at its very core, a sport of honor and integrity,
and there isn't an ounce of honor or integrity left in the
Olympics. Bribes, scandals, drugs, and a sort of media extortion
(cover our trials if you want credentials) are the norm. Do you
want to associate with people like that?
</P>
<P>
   Golf leaders in recent years have tackled issues that are far
more crucial to the sport than whether or not to march alongside
some synchronized swimmer. Why are people leaving the game at such
a high rate? How do you get kids into the game? Where do they play?
Why isn't equipment more affordable?
</P>
<P>
   Golf in the Olympics? Not ahead of ballroom dancing. And when
ballroom dancing gets in, golf takes a back seat to dominoes, kite
flying, and bungee jumping.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Solheim time
</P>
<P>
   The Solheim Cup approaches. While it's not the Ryder Cup, it's
intense stuff for the women, and the US team will be finalized this
weekend. The top eight _ Juli Inkster, Meg Mallon, Rosie Jones,
Dottie Pepper, Sherri Steinhauer, Pat Hurst, Kelly Robbins, and
Michele Redman _ are locks, leaving Nancy Scranton (ninth) and
Becky Iverson (10th) looking over their shoulders at Cristie Kerr
(11th), Kelli Kuehne (12th), Beth Daniel (13th), and Betsy King
(14th). After the final round of the Safeway LPGA Golf Championship
Sunday, Pat Bradley will name her two captain's picks for the Oct.
6-8 competition in Scotland . . . It's early, of course, but Nick
Faldo's publicized vow to challenge for an automatic berth on next
year's Ryder Cup team is off to a strong start. After two events
he's in fifth place, though he's not playing in this week's
Belgacom Open . . . Ron Philo Jr. of the Country Club of Vermont
fell two shots shy of making it through the first stage at European
Tour Qualifying School . . . You want a week of highs and lows?
Consider Roger Wessels of South Africa. Last week he opened with a
63 at the Trophee Lancome, then missed the cut with an 81. This
week he shot 70 to start the Belgacom Open, then followed it up
with a 64.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Summertime blues
</P>
<P>
   You can't blame Laura Torrisi for wanting school to start.
Things just didn't go well for the 1999 WGAM Player of the Year,
now a senior at Campbell College in North Carolina. ``It just
didn't seem like a great summer, tournamentwise,'' said the
21-year-old lefthander from Lunenberg, who plays out of Sterling.
She hurt her wrist early in the summer, missed some competition,
then seemed to be getting into the swing of things when she was
sidelined again, this time with a cyst. ``I had just started
swinging pretty well, so it was frustrating. I worked with my pro
(Jacques Panet-Raymond of Stow Acres) on my connection _ I tend to
clear my hips a little before my hands _ and was just getting it
when I had to stop playing.'' Feeling better, Torrisi was tied for
eighth in Campbell's first tournament of the year, shooting
72-79_151 to help her squad finish second. Torrisi will graduate
with a degree in sports management, then tackle a heavy golf
schedule next summer. If things go well, LPGA Tour Qualifying
School would be in her plans in the fall of 2001, ``but if my game
is not where I think it should be,'' Torrisi said, she would hold
off on a pro attempt for another year . . . On the men's collegiate
front, the University of Rhode Island was seventh out of 12 teams
at an event hosted by the University of Minnesota. ``We got some
kids some experience and I got a chance to see how we stack up
against national competition,'' said Tom Drennan, coach of New
England's perennial golf power. Newcomers Tom Giles (74-75-75) of
Stow, a transfer from Liberty, and David Spitz of Norwell
(80-75-74), a freshman, finished T-11 and T-24, respectively, and
gave Drennan plenty of reasons for optimism. Michael Carbone of
Brewster, a sophomore who played regularly last year, did not make
the trip, but he figures prominently in Drennan's plans this year .
. . In Wake Forest's first tournament of the year, sophomore Brent
Wanner of Chatham shot 74-71-75 to finish in the middle of the pack
as the Deacons were tied for seventh in the 14-team field . . . Joe
Cunningham, a sophomore from Manchester, is playing for the
University of Richmond, which won the Navy Fall Classic recently.
Cunningham shot 74-78. Rollins College, with Rob Oppenheim of
Andover contributing a 2-over 73 on the second day, finished third.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crowd control
</P>
<P>
   Fall golf? There's plenty of it, starting with Monday's 47th
annual Boston Globe Tournament of Club Champions at Brae Burn CC in
West Newton. When it began in 1954 and for most of the ensuing
years, the process was simple _ secure a venue, make tee times, and
honor the lowest scorer. Ah, but times have changed, and like most
competitive events on the calendar, the T of CC has become heavily
oversubscribed. Paring the field has become a nightmare (some 200
entries for 129 spots this year), what with so many players walking
around with handicaps that look like temperature readings for a
cold winter's night, and while we struggle with solutions, that
still leaves dozens of guys who aren't happy as they sit outside
looking in. The MGA, WGAM, and just about every quality local event
_ from the Cronin Memorial to the Hornblower to the Norfolk County
Classic _ have faced the same problem at one time or another: too
few spots for too many players. Enemies are easily made, but
golfers being golfers, they rarely blame themselves even though
many of them are a tad out of line with their handicaps. At the
heart of any golf competition is the USGA index, and that can be an
accurate reflection only when a golfer uses the handicap system the
way it was meant to work _ which is to hand in all scores, even if
they are high tournament numbers. Gentlemen, let's curb the egos
and reintroduce humility and honor to the game _ even if it means a
handicap going up . . . Also on tap Monday is Round 1 of the Cape
Cod Senior Open at Cape Cod CC. The second and final round will be
Tuesday at Hyannis GC, and the field includes defending champ Bob
Green, the head pro at Tedesco CC; Paul Parajeckas of Woburn CC;
Tom Cavicchi of Wollaston GC; longtime force Paul Barkhouse; the
legendary Bob Crowley of Pine Brook; Tom Sullivan of Wyantenuck,
who lost in a playoff last year; four-time NEPGA Wogan Award winner
Jeff Bailey; and two-time State Open champ Charlie Volpone . . .
After four qualifiers, a field of 120 was finalized for the State
Mid-Am Championship, which will be held Wednesday and Thursday at
Sterling CC. On those same days, the New England PGA Individual
Match Play Championship will take place at Prouts GC in
Scarborough, Maine. The 16 competitors qualified via the recent New
England Open . . . Finally, at Wollaston GC in Milton, members are
putting together plans for an Oct. 28-29 tournament that will be a
challenge to their emotions yet a tribute to their spirit. The Carl
E. Leone Trophy Competition will honor the longtime club member who
was tragically killed last January in a motorcycle accident. Notice
about tournaments of this nature come across the desk all the time,
each one a wonderful cause, none more important than the other, but
this one hit home. Leone was a high school classmate of mine (North
Quincy, 1974). His sport was football, mine was baseball, but here
we were 25 years later crossing paths because our passion had
turned to golf. They say you meet the greatest people in golf and
in the case of Leone, that is a correct assessment, even if it more
accurately was a reintroduction.
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and other sources was used in compiling this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
