<SLUG> BC-OLY-DRUMMOND-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD RACE BUT THE WRONG ROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Everything about Jon Drummond's race was
perfect. Everything except his timing.
</P>
<P>
   In the semifinals of the Olympic 100 meters Saturday, the
32-year-old Los Angeles resident clocked 10.10 seconds to finish
between training partners Maurice Greene (10.06) and Ato Boldon
(10.13).
</P>
<P>
   If it had been the finals, it would have been a clean sweep of
the medals for the UCLA-based HSI team. The way Drummond bolted out
of the blocks and beamed at the finish, it boded well for the
would-be Broom Brigade.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the semifinal that Jon Drummond had, I thought he had a
very good chance,'' Boldon said.
</P>
<P>
   To win, he meant.
</P>
<P>
   Only Drummond's legs remained noncommittal. In the 90 minutes
between the semifinal heat and the finals, they lost their
resilience. The best Drummond could drum up in the finals was a
10.09 that felt a whole lot harder than his semifinal effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could do it all again, I'd run like I did in the
semifinals. But I can't so I've just got to get over it,'' said
Drummond, who wound up fifth, behind Greene (9.87), Boldon (9.99),
Obadele Thompson of Barbados (10.04) and Great Britain's Dwain
Chambers (10.08).
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the race, Drummond's body language spoke of
his disappointment at missing out on a medal by .05-seconds. He
slowed to a walk with his head drooping and stopped a few feet from
where Greene and Boldon were locked in a hug.
</P>
<P>
   Drummond stood frozen for a few seconds. At length he dropped to
his knees and then to the track where he lay staring vacantly at
the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw Jon just kind of standing there,'' Boldon said, ``I
went up and hugged him and said, 'You know what? You showed me the
way, I showed Maurice the way and you are an inspiration to us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Drummond could be a hurdler for all the obstacles he has
overcome on the road here. He was born with spina bifida and over
the past few years has been sidelined with everything from leg
cramps to viral meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   In the grand scheme of things, he guessed, a fifth-place finish
wasn't worth singing the blues over (although Drummond could do it
beautifully; he has sung with the gospel group Kirk Kranklin and
the Family).
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't look at what happened to me and be sad,'' said the
two-time Olympian, who didn't make it out of the semifinals in the
100 in Atlanta in 1996. ``Jon Drummond was in an Olympic final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy. I'm healthy. God gets the glory because I gave it
all I had. I gave Maurice the best race I could give him. Jon
Drummond put his best foot forward. I can walk away with my head
held high.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 2218EDT &QL; 
