<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-RAHAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAHAL SHIFTING GEARS TO FORMULA ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest development this past week at Indianapolis
Motor Speedway wasn't the much-anticipated arrival of Formula One
stars Michael Schumacher, Mika Hakkinen, and David Coulthard for
Sunday's inaugural US Grand Prix at the fabled Brickyard.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it seemed to be the news that Bobby Rahal, who for
several months has held the dual role of car owner and interim
chief executive officer of Championship Auto Racing Teams, had
agreed to a three-year deal to become CEO and team principal of the
Jaguar Racing Formula One team.
</P>
<P>
   Rahal, 47, will continue to fields cars for CART drivers Max
Papis and Kenny Brack, leaving the day-to-day operation of Team
Rahal to general manager Scott Roembke, who took over supervision
when Rahal was tabbed this year to succeed Andrew Craig as CART's
CEO on an interim basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I always said it was interim,'' said Rahal when asked
what his departure to Formula One would mean to CART's future. ``I
don't think I ever conveyed in any way, shape, or form to anyone
that it was anything but that. I also said at times that no man is
more important than the sport. And to say that by my changing from
not being the CEO that somehow everything is going to come to a
grinding halt I think is ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that there is an executive search going on right now.
The level of interest in the position is extremely high. I think
probably better than at any time in the past. I view my position in
the last several months as nothing more than getting the company
ready for a permanent CEO, and that's happening. So I think that,
as I said, I'd take a very different look than some people.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are saying this is a great thing. There are
some naysayers out there, but I believe that ultimately in the long
term CART is going to be stronger for it and I think certainly Team
Rahal, Bobby Rahal is going to be stronger for it. If I do my job,
Jaguar Formula One will be stronger for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Indy 500 winner, who won three championships and 24
races as a driver on the CART circuit, will take on the new
challenge of heading up Jaguar Racing's Formula One enterprise,
which will field cars for drivers Eddie Irvine and rookie Luciano
Burti next season. The switch from CART to F1 represents something
of a dream realized for Rahal, who competed in Formula 3 and
Formula 2 early in his racing career and aspired to drive on the F1
circuit but managed to compete in only two Grand Prix races in 1978
(US and Canada) for Wolf Racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I certainly loved living in Europe and racing over there
many, many moons ago,'' said Rahal, who will move his family to
England to be closer to Jaguar's racing headquarters. ``There's no
question that, as a boy growing up, I aspired to Formula One. I did
make it briefly, but at least I made it. But there's no question
that coming back now, maybe in some respects vicariously I'm
achieving that goal that I had or that dream I had 30-35 years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does Rahal intend to bring to the table, especially
after being away for so long from the political backbiting and
heated competition of the F1 circuit?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, first off, I'm sure some people might say, well, what
do I know about Formula One? And obviously I think that that really
misses the point to a large degree,'' he said. ``I think this is a
company whose main task is to enter motor racing events and to win
them and to represent in this case Jaguar cars in the manner in
which Jaguar would wish to be represented.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I'm creating the race setup. We've got engineers
to do that. But my task is to take the organization, work with the
various components within the organization to assist in turning it
into a winning team because I can't do it myself. This has to be a
team effort. So my job is to create that team with the help of the
many people that are there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I have no illusion about the immensity of this
task. Irrespective of whether I had Formula One experience in the
last several years or not, this is a huge task; and yet I'm moving
there, I'll be living in England, and I'm there because I'm ready
to take on that challenge. Eddie has certainly proven that he's
capable of winning races. My job is to help him do so in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Giving it a spin
</P>
<P>
   Heinz Harald-Frentzen, driver for the F1 Jordan team, was the
first to tour the recently completed 2.6-mile, 13-turn circuit at
Indianapolis Motor Speedway. Frentzen did so in a rental car back
in June when he stopped for a visit while on his way to Montreal
for the Canadian Grand Prix, the only other North American stop on
the F1 circuit. ``The only circuit that comes close to resembling
this is Hockeheim,'' Frentzen said, referring to the site of the
German Grand Prix. ``But this track is more complex, and finding
the correct aerodynamic setup will be a huge challenge for all the
F1 teams.'' Drivers will find the Brickyard's circuit to be
particularly challenging because of the second and first turns and
the high-speed front straightaway, where speeds are expected to
reach as high as 220 miles per hour, making it one of the fastest
F1 races. ``That could make it a little more difficult to get
totally comfortable,'' said Schumacher. ``Usually, at a new track,
you get into a sort of rhythm within a couple of laps and then you
just develop the setup and adapt it until the final moment of
qualifying and the race. That is what I expect here.'' . . . Mario
Andretti's victory in the 1977 US Grand Prix was recently voted
``MasterCard Priceless Moment of the US Grand Prix'' in a poll of
40 US F1 historians and journalists. Driving Colin Chapman's Lotus
78, Andretti outdueled Niki Lauda and Jody Sheckter to win the 1977
US Grand Prix at Long Beach, thus becoming the first _ and, so far,
only _ American driver to win a US Grand Prix event.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's territory
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart will try to make it a clean sweep when he goes for
his second NASCAR Winston Cup victory of the season at Dover, Del.,
in Sunday's MBNA.com 400. In just three career starts at Dover
Downs International Speedway, Stewart has recorded a fourth, a
second, and a victory in June's MBNA Platinum 400. ``It's
definitely important for us,'' said Stewart, who is seventh in the
driver standings with 3,447 points, 484 behind Joe Gibbs teammate
Bobby Labonte. ``We need to take every one of the tracks where we
feel we're strong, and we need to be able to capitalize on those
days and gain as many points as possible.'' . . . After putting one
controversy behind them in last weekend's Dura Lube/Kmart 300 at
New Hampshire International Speedway, where carburetor-restrictor
plates were implemented, NASCAR officials braced for another
firestorm after considering rule changes for the Winston 500 at
Talladega next month. Among the changes: a rear spoiler alteration
for the Chevrolet Monte Carlo, which would be reduced in width from
57 to 55 inches, while Ford and Pontiac would be required to run a
57-inch spoiler width. The changes were considered a means of
reducing speeds aerodynamically at the last restrictor-plate race
of the season. ``What they're proposing is not a good deal,'' said
car owner Robert Yates, who fields Ford Tauruses for Ricky Rudd and
Dale Jarrett. ``We all want the best of both worlds _ to have high
downforce cars on the smaller tracks and low drag cars on the plate
tracks. Chevy's got a high downforce car. But that gives them more
drag on the plate tracks and that's the choice they made. It looks
like they've learned to make it work by how they ran in April (at
Talladega, where Chevys finished 1-2-3-4). I don't like to get in
this line of bitching, but I'm in the bitching line. I'm not happy
to be on that side of the fence.''
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, race teams, and sanctioning bodies was used in
compiling this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
