<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-MCCLEARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE OUTSIDE RINK OK WITH MCCLEARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He spent his short time in the NHL as a natural-born instigator,
a constant pain in the neck for opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Off the ice, he was gleeful, ever the kid in the proverbial
candy store. For wiry former Bruins forward Trent McCleary, the
glass was always half-full. He was a positive presence everywhere
he went.
</P>
<P>
   Then came that terrifying afternoon last Jan. 29 when McCleary,
playing for the Montreal Canadiens, was struck in the throat while
blocking a shot by Flyers defenseman Chris Therien. His face turned
an ominous shade of blue because his larynx was fractured and he
couldn't breathe. Looking back, he figures he was two minutes away
from death.
</P>
<P>
   Because of some lucky factors _ having team doctors on hand in
the Molson Centre and Montreal General Hospital nearby, the medical
team already on duty because it was an afternoon game _ McCleary's
life was saved.
</P>
<P>
   After a valiant attempt at a comeback, McCleary announced his
retirement Wednesday at the age of 28. He tried to play in last
Sunday's exhibition game against the Bruins but had trouble
breathing because of a 10-15 percent reduction in the size of his
airway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two minutes, two more minutes, that's all,'' said McCleary.
``They told me later that they checked my blood gases when I
arrived at the hospital. Two more minutes, they told me, and I was
a dead man.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the heroic work of doctors David Mulder and Vincent
Lacroix that made all the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that went through my mind was: `I'm in
trouble. This isn't the way I'm supposed to feel.' It hurt,'' said
McCleary. ``I remember getting to my knees, and now I'm not
breathing right. I thought: `Why can't I breathe? Oh my God, why
can't I breathe? Why?' My mouth guard is out, my chinstrap's off,
but all I'm thinking is: `I can't breathe. I'm choking. Why? Why?'
''
</P>
<P>
   He said he felt as if he were breathing through a straw, and he
panicked. He said he could taste his own blood and was fearful of
choking to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the doctors were there, they're always there,'' he
said. ``I knew where they were sitting. I was out of air and I
wanted the doctors to help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, McCleary was transported to the hospital.
Lacroix estimated it was 12 minutes from the time McCleary was
struck to the time he was wheeled into surgery.
</P>
<P>
   He made a remarkable recovery and spent seven months getting
back into shape. But his airway was just too narrow, as a result of
the incident, to permit him to play NHL hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 15 seconds of skating, I was looking for the bench,
looking for a place to get off the ice,'' he said. ``I was
wheezing. After 20 seconds, I couldn't catch anybody. It's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   So pro hockey is over for Trent McCleary. But it isn't the end
by any means. McCleary, who had to fight so hard to make it to the
NHL and fight even harder to stay there, knows it's only the
beginning. He's counting his blessings, not bitter as some would be
about what's been taken away. He is newly married and has another
chance at a healthy, happy life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finding their place
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis Blues left wing Tyson Nash has continued his effective
role as team agitator. Judging by the first couple of weeks of
camp, it appears Jay Henderson could play a similar role in Boston,
which is sorely needed. Nash has proven to be a big asset for the
Blues in helping get opponents off their games. ``He found a way to
put himself in the NHL,'' said Blues general manager Larry Pleau.
``He figured out his role. A lot of guys don't figure that out.
They try to do too much or they think they can do more. Nash is a
perfect example of a guy who'd rather make $800,000 than $70,000 in
the minors. He said, `This is what I'm going to do to stay here.'
He got a nice contract because he deserved it.'' . . . Sincere
apologies to Bruins defenseman Darren Van Impe for neglecting to
include him in a recent story on the club's blue line corps. As
amazingly quiet as Van Impe is, I'm sure I'll be hearing about it
all season, which is fair enough . . . The retooled Islanders are
expecting even better things from former Bruins right wing Mariusz
Czerkawski, who had a career-high 35 goals and 70 points last
season. Coach Butch Goring said of the 28-year-old Czerkawski,
``I'd obviously like to see him score no less than 35 and see if he
can't get to the 40 range. I think he's finally starting to
understand what his game is about. He's been criticized in the past
for being basically a one-way hockey player. But I think he's
finally understanding that he can score goals and still be a
complete hockey player.'' . . . Look for Rangers winger Theo Fleury
to begin the season on a line with Mark Messier and Adam Graves.
Fleury, who was booed unmercifully in New York last year because of
a disappointing season, is expecting this one to be completely
different. ``I've got a chance to make it right this year and
that's what I want to do,'' said Fleury. His experience in Gotham,
much removed from his native Calgary, ran the gamut of emotions.
``It was hilarious,'' said Fleury. ``First you get mad. Then you
try harder and that doesn't work. Then, you nonchalant it, trying
to ease off and hope things come naturally. Then, you go see a
shrink and talk to him and he gives you some support and even that
didn't work. It was just one of those years.'' . . . Early in
training camp, feisty Capitals defenseman Brendan Witt said he was
strongly weighing retirement at 25 despite having his best year as
a pro in 1999-2000. Seems Witt was upset by an arbitrator's
decision to give him no raise this year on his $1 million salary.
He will get a $75,000 raise for 2001-02. ``I just expressed how I
felt at the time and I needed to get that off my chest,'' said
Witt. ``It's nice to say I get to come to the hockey rink for work
instead of working somewhere 9 to 5. I appreciate that.'' Chances
are Witt also appreciates there's no other job, 9-5 or otherwise,
where he could pocket $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Light on his skates
</P>
<P>
   Blackhawks center Josef Marha, who was left unprotected in the
June expansion draft but was passed over by both Minnesota and
Columbus, came into training camp with a renewed commitment. The
24-year-old lost 13 pounds and is down to 192, the lightest he's
been in his career. ``I feel quicker,'' said Marha. ``We'll see if
these changes make a difference. I hope so.'' Marha suffered a
setback when he injured his thigh, but he isn't expected to be
sidelined long . . . As much as that team is looking for
improvement from Marha, they need a huge year from 25-year-old
goalie Jocelyn Thibault. Thibault was pulled from three games early
in the season last fall, including opening night, and said his
psyche was a mess. ``That first month was awful,'' he said. ``I've
never been through a slump like that in my life. I lost my
confidence for a couple of weeks. And as a goalie, you need
confidence.'' Thibault is scheduled to become a restricted free
agent next summer. ``This is an important year for Jocelyn,'' said
Mike Smith, manager of hockey operations . . . Look for Sabres
center Doug Gilmour to rebound strongly after a disappointing end
to last season. Gilmour, who was traded to the Sabres from the
Blackhawks March 10, suffered mightily at the end of the regular
season and through the playoffs because of a stomach virus.
Gilmour, who is not exactly beefy to begin with, lost 10 pounds and
had zero energy in five playoff games against Philadelphia. ``Four
or five days afterward, I was fine,'' said Gilmour. ``I started
putting the weight back on, and my stomach felt good. In hindsight,
maybe if I would have taken four or five days off right away, (the
virus) could have left me. I'm more excited than I have been in a
long time to get back here and start the season.'' . . . Amid much
ballyhoo last Monday, Senators center Alexei Yashin played his
first game at the Corel Centre since April 23, 1999. Yashin, who
sat out all of last season in a contract dispute, was booed every
time he touched the puck, but he also had a good amount of
supporters who seemed to forgive him for refusing to honor the
final year of his contract. ``I can't control what people think and
I tried to concentrate on playing the game,'' said Yashin, who had
two goals in the game against Calgary. ``I'm just going to keep
doing the best I can.'' . . . Incoming Coyotes co-owner Wayne
Gretzky is getting a much better reception from Team Canada than he
is from the outgoing Phoenix owner, Richard Burke. Burke banned the
Great One from the team's locker room as well as workouts at the
Scottsdale practice rink because the sale of the club hasn't been
completed. GM Bobby Smith supported the move. Startlingly, Burke
felt Gretzky, his partner Steve Ellman, and incoming executive vice
president Cliff Fletcher were disruptive and hungry for photo
opportunities. Meanwhile, Team Canada is hoping Gretzky will accept
its GM job for the 2002 Olympics in Salt Lake City . . . Our
prayers and sincere condolences go to the family and friends of
Quincy Police officer Larry Kelly, who died last week at 61.
Kelly's son, Larry Jr., is director of media relations for the
Dallas Stars, and it was he who made arrangements to bring the
Stanley Cup to Quincy after the Stars won it in '99, largely so his
father would have a chance to enjoy it . . . 11 days to opening
night.
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in this report.
</P>
