<HEADER>
A9297 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-BLEDSOE-     09-23 2902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-BLEDSOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS QB NOT ABOUT TO TAKE A HIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Unless you've come to the conclusion that Bob Kraft is
an idiot who never learns from his mistakes _ which there is ample
evidence is not the case _ please forget this idea that Drew
Bledsoe will be traded to Seattle or somehow be allowed to walk
away from New England when his contract expires in two years.
</P>
<P>
   If you recall, and I'm sure Kraft does, the Patriots let that
happen with running back Curtis Martin three years ago, and they
haven't found a replacement yet and they're not going to soon.
Knowing that quarterbacks of NFL caliber are even harder to find
than running backs of Martin's caliber, Kraft has the common sense
not to repeat his folly of a few years back, when he listened to
his football men and continued not to pay Martin anywhere near his
market value until the team's back was against the wall. When that
happened, Martin walked after the Jets delivered a poison pill to
the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft has a history of not renegotiating contracts that have two
years to run, which is a wise course in the NFL. The exception he
made in Bledsoe's case came with a gun to his head because his
young quarterback was in position to void the final years of his
deal and become a free agent. Other than that, he has pretty much
waited until a player was entering his last year before working out
a new deal.
</P>
<P>
   Any salary cap relief Bledsoe would supply now by an extension
would be worthless until next February, so why not wait until this
season is over and see how things stand? In fact, the way it's
going, wait and see whether Bledsoe can still stand.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that's the case, Kraft still holds the cards, including
the franchise tag if he has to play it. He is not about to let
anyone persuade him that the Patriots are better off without
Bledsoe unless someone can show him they have a better quarterback
already under contract; that situation did not exist among his
running backs when he let Martin leave.
</P>
<P>
   The simple fact is they don't have such a quarterback and they
won't unless they play so badly this season that they can draft
Michael Vick with the No. 1 pick. If they do that, though, it
probably means Bledsoe has finished this season in traction, which
would reduce his allure considerably anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Barring such an unfortunate circumstance, forget about the
MetroWest Daily News's unnamed sources close to Patriots management
saying Bledsoe is on his way to Seattle or anywhere else or that
Kraft has lost faith in him. There's a better chance that St.
Louis's Trent Green ends up in Seattle, and if Kraft has lost faith
in Bledsoe, he should listen to people like Miami Dolphin defenders
Trace Armstrong and Jason Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's impressed me with his toughness,'' said Armstrong, who
will be pursuing Bledsoe Sunday in passing situations. ``He's taken
a lot of hits and he's still not afraid to stand in the pocket.
He's not looking to slide out. I see little to fault him about.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff you used to hear about his character or not caring,
I don't know where it comes from. If you see him this year, he's
doing all he can for that team. He' standing in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Taylor, who will try to use his speed rushes to get by
Bruce Armstrong and into Bledsoe's mind as well as his body, ``The
guy has gotten hit a ton and taken some sacks to avoid
interceptions. Anyone who says he isn't tough must be watching a
different game than I've watched. He's a tough kid with a great
arm. He deserves a lot of respect.''
</P>
<P>
   That issue out of the way, let us consider one other in the
matter of rumors about Bledsoe. Just what is a source ``close to''
Patriots management? A driver? The cleaning lady? A secretary? Bill
Belichick's wife? Give me someone in Patriot management threatening
to dump Bledsoe or quoting the boss as saying he's tired of him and
I'll bet you this: He won't be even close to being in Patriot
management the next day.
</P>
<P>
   As for the idea of gathering a host of draft picks for Bledsoe,
don't think Kraft doesn't now understand the difficulty of the
drafting process. He got six high picks for Bill Parcells and
Martin, including two No. 1s, and not a one of those players is a
regular starter, while half are flipping hamburgers in Houston or
slinging chili in Chicago at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   So get used to seeing Bledsoe in a Patriot uniform unless the
worst of all possibilities happens: He decides he wants out to
preserve both his health and his chance of getting back to the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, you can bet on this: You won't hear it from any
sources close to Patriot management.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scary stats
</P>
<P>
   Here's the sad sack Patriot stat of the week. Since opening last
season 6-2, the Patriots have gone 2-9. The only team with a worse
record is the 49ers, at 1-10. The Patriots also haven't scored more
than 20 points since last Halloween . . . Keyshawn Johnson
continues to show both his immaturity and his pettiness by bashing
former teammate Wayne Chrebet. He also seems to be showing that he
can't count. In the days leading up to Sunday afternoon's showdown
between Chrebet's Jets and Johnson's Buccaneers, Johnson claimed
Dedric Ward was New York's best receiver while Chrebet was just the
media's pet. This is the same Chrebet of whom Belichick said, ``We
doubled the guy the whole game and he still beat us.'' Johnson went
on to say, ``You're comparing a flashlight to a star. Flashlights
only last so long. A star is in the sky forever.'' Well, at least
until it goes into nova or disappears in Tampa's ball-control
offense. For the record, Johnson has 14 catches for 180 yards and a
touchdown this season, while Chrebet has 13 for 154 and two scores.
Unlike Johnson, Chrebet did not even make an appearance in the
locker room all week during the time the media had access, making
sure to avoid the controversy as best he could. The same was not
true of Jets center Kevin Mawae, who said this of Johnson: ``I just
think if you're going to be a professional athlete, act like a
professional athlete and just go about your business. Wayne
continues to make plays and he continues to get dogged. I don't
know if it's a sense of jealousy or insecurity. We're 3-0 and he's
not here. Go tell that to Keyshawn.'' Many theorize that is what is
really eating at Johnson. His absence has not led to the Jets'
collapse but rather to their best start (albeit a bit lucky) in
decades . . . That hot start has come despite the fact that
quarterback Vinny Testaverde is not yet fully recovered from the
Achilles' injury of a year ago. Tampa Bay coach Tony Dungy said as
much in a shocking bit of candor by NFL coaching standards when he
said, ``Vinny is not playing as sharp as he did in 1998 before he
got hurt. He was just deadly that year, throwing 65 percent
completions.'' Dungy went on to counter that by adding that
Testaverde continues to avoid sacks and has made big plays late in
games when the Jets needed them most. Statistics back up the
dropoff in Testaverde's play. In 1998, he led New York to
touchdowns 28.3 percent of the time. This year it's 19.4. And he
completed 61.5 percent of his throws that season. This year it's
48.7 percent. Still, in the stat that counts most, he's 15-2 as a
regular-season starter in New York . . . Up in Buffalo, linebacker
Sam Cowart continues to be a marvel. Buffalo coaches credited him
with 23 tackles against the Jets last week, giving him 53 in three
games. If he continues that pace, he'll shatter the club record of
206 set by Chris Spielman. He'll probably end up needing shoulder
surgery, too, if he has to make that many stops.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Backfield in motion
</P>
<P>
   All is not settled with the Bills, though. Quarterback Rob
Johnson is the team's leading rusher, with 109 yards on 16
scrambles, and that is not what head coach Wade Phillips is looking
for. That's why Phillips decided to bench running back Antowain
Smith Sunday and replace him with Jonathan Linton, who has yet to
carry the ball this season as he is coming off a rib injury. Smith
has not returned to the form of his rookie year, 1998, when he
rushed for 1,124 yards. Injuries plagued him last year and thus far
this season he has 72 yards on 34 carries . . . You may not believe
this, but the Dolphins respect the Patriots' anemic offense. Head
coach Dave Wannstedt insisted that New England was one play away
from being 3-0. I guess he meant one play a game . . . While Smith
struggles in Buffalo, old reliable Thurman Thomas is continuing to
show he has plenty left in Miami. Exiled to the beach (which isn't
that bad a fate when you've spent more than a decade in Buffalo),
Thomas is now a third-down specialist and an effective one. Last
week he had three carries for 25 yards and three catches for 31
more; all six were third-down plays he converted to first downs.
But in Miami's loss to Minnesota, the Vikings blitzed nearly every
time Thomas was in the backfield, forcing him to stay in on pass
protection. He ended up with one catch for 2 yards and the Dolphins
were 3 of 13 on third down. Look for the Patriots to try a similar
tactic . . . Thomas needs 149 yards to pass Franco Harris for
eighth on the all-time NFL rushing list and 341 to pass the great
Jim Brown's 12,312 yards, which is now sixth. Thomas, with 11,972
yards, is capable of gaining those yards but he has only six
carries for 34 yards this season . . . The Colts gave the Jaguars
something to think about Sunday when they ran the no-huddle offense
on nine of their 11 offensive series last week. The key to that set
is Marcus Pollard, who is so versatile he can play fullback, tight
end, or slot receiver, thus allowing the Colts to run their offense
without substitutions . . . Don't want to say old friend Tom
Coughlin is a little intense, but he was angry at the Jaguars fans
who did not show up for last Sunday's game with Cincinnati. There
were 45,653 on hand but there were another 20,000 missing, which
led Coughlin to remark, ``I can't for the life of me understand
where the others were.'' Probably boarding up their homes, since
there was a hurricane hitting at game time . . . They're trying to
raise $250,000 to fund the building of a statue of Johnny Unitas in
front of PSINet Stadium in Baltimore. The statue is going to be 19
feet tall, which is no coincidence. Unitas wore number 19 to glory
in Baltimore . . . Apparently, sign language is not allowed in the
NFL. After Cleveland punter Chris Gardocki was cheap shotted by
Pittsburgh's Joey Porter and knocked flat, he got up and gave
Porter half a peace sign to show his unhappiness. The NFL fined
Gardocki $5,000. Porter wasn't assessed a nickel, which shows where
the NFL is at. It cares less about free speech than the rule book.
A lot less, as a matter of fact . . . Here's Tennessee offensive
coordinator Mike Heimerdinger's opinion of how tough the Bills'
defense is to beat: ``Anybody that wins against the Bills will have
to win ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sticky fingers
</P>
<P>
   Steelers quarterback Kent Graham found a new use for super glue.
He used it to hold his injured right thumb together in practice.
The trainers punctured two holes in Graham's nail to release blood
that was beneath it and causing him pain. Then they covered the
holes with super glue and Graham was able to finish the practice
and throw without problems. This is not considered holistic
medicine but it worked . . . Latest evidence that end zone
celebrations should be banned: The Browns lost starting left guard
Jim Pyne for the year when he tore the anterior cruciate ligament
in his right knee while jumping up to celebrate a touchdown pass to
tight end Mark Campbell. Pyne later claimed he'd injured the knee
earlier. Sure he did . . . The Bengals hosted a six-hour hearing
with an arbitrator a week ago at their team offices over their
insistence that players sign a loyalty clause pledging not to
overly criticize the team's coaches or management or face a loss of
bonus money. The clause is being challenged by the players' union,
which brought in agents Marvin Demoff, Jim Steiner, and Terry Bolar
to testify on their behalf. Each has had veteran players who had
problems with the Bengals' front office. Six of the team's seven
draft picks signed the loyalty pledge this spring. The only one to
refuse was first-round choice Peter Warrick. Now there's a surprise
. . . For a guy who's not talking, Bryan Cox moves his lips a lot.
Not only did the Jets linebacker break his self-imposed silence to
speak to both ABC and ESPN before the Monday night game with the
Patriots, he sat down a week later to explain his silence to the
print media in New York. ``I don't want my kids going to school and
getting teased about something their father said,'' the often
outspoken Cox claimed. ``It was a time for me to shut up. My go-to
days (for quotes) are over.'' . . . Cox apparently would love
Cleveland defensive back Corey Fuller. After the Browns crushed the
Bengals in Cincinnati's new stadium, Fuller threatened young safety
Earl Little with a fine if he answered a reporter's question about
his interception. Little declined to comment, but three days later,
Fuller was running off at the mouth about how little respect the
Browns got for beating the lowly Bengals. Who asked him? . . . The
Chiefs' defense has an interesting streak going. It has knocked the
last two starting quarterbacks it faced out of the game. First it
was Tennessee's Steve McNair, who is still suffering with a bruised
sternum, and then it was Moses Moreno, who is out of the lineup
Sunday for San Diego. Kansas City has 10 sacks in the last two
games . . . Moreno will be replaced by affable Ryan Leaf, who spent
the week acting weird, as usual. He kept claiming he didn't care
whether he played or not, but he'd do whatever the Chargers asked.
That's what happens when you bench a guy two games into the season
and then have to go back to him a week later even though he's 3-8
as a starter and has thrown two touchdown passes while turning the
ball over 26 times. Leaf's ascension didn't seem to set well with
linebacker Junior Seau, whose disgust with Leaf is well documented.
``A guy got hurt, and you know he's the next in line,'' said Seau.
``You don't have to love each other, you've got to respect each
other. And right now, we've got to respect the next guy in line.''
Somebody should tell Junior the next guy he has to respect has a
name.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Busted Bronco
</P>
<P>
   Limping Terrell Davis was reduced to playing on the Broncos'
scout team last week, wearing number 49 to play the role of Chiefs
fullback Tony Richardson. Davis won't start Sunday, so Mike
Anderson has a chance to become the first rookie back to gain 100
yards rushing in each of his first three games. Anderson leads the
NFL with 318 yards. He turned 27 this week, making him the oldest
rookie in the league . . . The fallout from the fall of Broncos
linebacker Bill Romanowski continued when the doctor who gave him
illegal prescriptions for the drug Phentermine was forced to close
his practice because Medicare and Medicaid cut off payments to his
practice. Dr. Randall L. Snook pleaded guilty to unlawful
dispensing of a controlled substance, but Romanowski is fighting
the charges of illegally acquiring the drug . . . The Rams defense
continues to struggle, and it spilled over last week when unhappy
All-Pro defensive end Kevin Carter did not show for Wednesday's
practice after the birth of his first child Tuesday morning. The
Rams claim Carter got carried away with the moment and was too
exhausted to show up but admit he never called to ask for the day
off. This comes only weeks after negotiations on a contract
extension collapsed when he turned down a $49 million deal that
included a $12.5 million signing bonus. Carter has been unhappy
ever since, and now he has another reason to be. His 83-game streak
as a starter will be snapped Sunday because head coach Mike Martz
said he will put Sean Moran in Carter's place and not just for a
series or two. Carter has only one sack, but he's not the only one
struggling. A year ago, St. Louis's defense was sixth in the NFL.
At the moment, it's 30th, trailing only feeble San Francisco. The
Rams are giving up 387.7 yards a game and 31.3 points; they even
allowed the Niners to hit them with eight plays of 15 yards or
longer. What is saving them is that their offense is playing as if
it's still 1999, averaging 506 yards and 39.7 points a game.
Unbelievably, Marshall Faulk is ahead of his pace of a year ago
with 530 total yards. He averaged 112.7 total yards a game in 1999
and is at 176.7 a game this year, a pace that would net him 2,827
and break the record he set a year ago of 2,429 . . . If you want
to bet a hunch, go to Vegas and bet the Rams, Bucs, Vikings, and
Giants to win the Super Bowl. All are 3-0, as are the Jets. In the
last five years, 22 of the 28 teams that started 3-0 made the
playoffs and every year the Super Bowl winner was a team that had
started 3-0. Since the only four 3-0 teams in the NFC are the
above, go with that, and it's not betting, it's science.
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in compiling
this report.
</P>
