<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9298 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-SEASON     09-23 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-SEASONENDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION UNDERWENT EVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The theme of recent Revolution seasons has been to avoid the
mistakes of the past. The team did so this season, finally shedding
its losing reputation and actually reaching the MLS playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Revolution's 6-0 loss at Chicago Saturday night was a
bit of a reality check, it should not dim the accomplishments of
the season: New England's first .500 record and first playoff
victory, over the Fire in Game 2 of the first-round series.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, coach Fernando Clavijo and director of soccer Sunil
Gulati must plan for the future. Past regimes have overhauled the
team and, usually, produced a similar but no more effective version
of the previous group.
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo and Gulati will not likely make sweeping changes, but
the ones they do effect will involve high-profile performers.
</P>
<P>
   They will likely concentrate on making the important moves where
they count _ through the center of the field. The goalkeeping
position is set with Juergen Sommer and Jeff Causey. Mauricio
Wright will require an experienced accomplice in central defense.
Joe Franchino proved he can fill the defensive midfield role. But
the Revolution will bring in a midfield choreographer to replace
Mauricio Ramos, who seldom played in the final six weeks of the
season. And another striker will be added to join leading scorer
Wolde Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo proved to be adept at optimizing New England's talent.
The Revolution won 14 games without ever dominating an opponent;
only thrice did they win by more than one goal.
</P>
<P>
   And the six-goal defeat in the final game indicated they had
been overachieving. The Revolution prevented such blowouts during
the season, but they collapsed against the Fire, a team that
matched their intensity but far surpassed them in offensive
firepower and creativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just a bad night,'' midfielder Leonel Alvarez said.
``To fall behind, 3-0, after 20 minutes, even if you have a big
heart and the willingness to fight, it is very tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six goals is a lot to give up. But we were not playing 100
percent and, unfortunately, this is tough for the young players to
take.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, at the same time, we had a lot of good results this
season and the young players got a lot of experience. A game like
this is not any one player's fault. You just have to accept it and
go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez, though, favors the MetroStars over the Fire in the
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is a more solid team, with more variety,'' Alvarez
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fire and MetroStars used different formulas to reach
this stage. The Fire retained their style of play and key players
since starting as an expansion team in 1998. The MetroStars
revamped and went from last place to the Eastern Division title.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teams that have had success have all had continuity,''
Alvarez said. ``You can't change 50 percent of your players every
year. You have to build on your team and allow the young players
who are gaining confidence to keep improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to have the opportunity to return. It's important
to keep this group together, to learn from our mistakes. I'd like
to stay, to correct a few details that need correcting, to provide
continuity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
