<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9299 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GLENN-BO     09-23 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GLENN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN HOPES PATRIOTS CAN CATCH A BREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ He was looking at the schedule recently, shaking his
head as he pointed at each opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tampa Bay, New York, Minnesota, Miami . . . look at this
schedule,'' said Terry Glenn. ``We have a schedule like we just won
the Super Bowl by 30 points.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know something? That's no excuse. You play them and
you have to win them. If we don't get it together soon . . . I
can't believe we're 0-3. I've never seen 0-3 in all my life and I
never want to see 0-4.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots go down that path Sunday against the Dolphins,
there won't be much reason to look at the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn is one player taking it upon himself to forge a new
beginning for the New England offense. He knows he and Drew Bledsoe
are targeted by opponents as the players who must be shut down. He
knows that can't happen. One thing he knows for sure: The bad start
isn't Bledsoe's fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tip my cap to him,'' said Glenn. ``I have so much
respect for that man. Look at the hits he's taken and he gets up
and he never flinches. He never complains. This year he's even
scrambling around better than ever. He made himself improve in that
area. Now we have to repay him. We have to make some plays for him.
I get sick and tired of hearing all the crap that comes his way.
We're all responsible. He gets much too much blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn hopes the frustration goes away Sunday. He knows it's
another week when the opponent will put seven men in the box and
come at the Patriots' offensive line like there's no tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, someway the Patriots need to break the pattern of
Bledsoe being pressured and Glenn being blanketed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get it together as an offense,'' said Glenn.
``We're trying, we really are. This team works as hard as any team
I've ever been with. Our offensive coordinator (Charlie Weis) is
trying everything out there to spread the offense and use multiple
formations. But we haven't executed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just Drew. We've had problems as receivers, the
offensive line has had problems. I think we've run the ball well.
Kevin (Faulk) has been very impressive. He's very talented. Maybe
if we keep running it'll open up the passing. Something's got to
give.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe what they need is a long bomb to Glenn. He caught a
39-yard touchdown pass in the opener against Tampa Bay on what he
called a ``courageous throw'' by Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hit just as he threw it,'' said Glenn, ``but we got it
down the field and we made the play. It's going to take more like
that. We'll take our shots down the field. I think you always have
to keep the defense honest. Miami wants you to throw those
rinky-dink passes of 2 or 3 yards. Our hope is that we can spring
loose and make big yardage, but they're waiting for us. It's hard
to get away.''
</P>
<P>
   Every year, Glenn said, there's a lot of attention paid to him,
but what he's saying is that in time he hopes his offensive
teammates can make plays around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about respect sometimes,'' said Glenn. ``When we go into
a town, you hear, `If they can stop Bledsoe, if they can stop Glenn
. . .' It used to be, `If they can stop Ben Coates, Shawn
Jefferson, Curtis Martin . . .'
</P>
<P>
   ``We have talented players. Troy (Brown) is an excellent
receiver. Tony (Simmons) is so fast. Shockmain (Davis) is really
going to be a good one. Eric (Bjornson) runs good routes and can
catch the ball. Sometimes it's hard to get that respect unless
you've had the big years to earn it. Ben had it because he was one
of the greatest to ever play the game. Same with Shawn. Teams knew
he could beat them deep.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenses, Glenn said, ``have been blitzing us hard. They're all
doing it to us. We have to find a way to make a play off a blitz.
We've done it a couple of times, but we have to do it more.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn says there is concern on the team about when it'll all
come together but ``as long as there isn't doubt. We're a better
team than what we've showed so far.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching film of the first three games, Glenn felt he did
everything he could to get open. Bledsoe often has eaten the ball
or had to get rid of it short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had a big play,'' said Glenn. ``We have to have
that. We have to get teams to respect that capability.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he knows it can't be one player alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be a collective thing,'' said Glenn. ``We have to
have everyone working together. Maybe our offensive line can begin
to jell. Maybe Drew can buy an extra second. Maybe we can sustain
long drives with our running game.''
</P>
<P>
   What he's sure of is that they can't fall behind the way they
did against the Vikings and expect to come back against that
caliber of team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get down like that,'' said Glenn. ``Minnesota had a
great defense. Miami has a great defense.''
</P>
<P>
   In last year's matchups with Miami, Glenn was shut out in the
first game and caught three passes in the second. He credits the
Dolphins' front seven more than the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put so much pressure on us and then they press us at the
line,'' he said. ``It's not so much that I get double-covered _
although they run that at you from time to time _ it's just that
they pressure Drew so much it's hard for him to get rid of the
ball. If I can get one-on-one with someone with a little time to
make a move, that would make a huge difference for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Something, someone has to make a difference. It may have to be
Bledsoe-to-Glenn after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
