<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9301 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-THOMAS-B     09-23 1458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-THOMAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI'S THOMAS A ONE-MAN WORK FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ Zach Thomas was standing by his locker, speaking
of the Patriots, describing a threatening offense that might be
unfamiliar to New England fans up North.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriots throw so many gadgets at you, trying to keep you
off-balance with screens and reverses,'' said the Dolphins inside
linebacker, whose team faces the winless Patriots Sunday in Miami.
``They're doing a lot of different things this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Except score points, came one thought. But that thought was
immediately pushed out of mind by another. My gosh, this linebacker
is so small.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a defense that hopefully won't get rattled,'' Thomas
went on. ``The Patriots are going to have a couple of big plays.
(Drew Bledsoe) has a strong arm and can go deep at any time. We
just can't give up the big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was describing a New England offense that once might have
been, but clearly isn't, came another thought. But that thought,
too, was quickly pushed sideways by another: This linebacker is a
throwback to a past era. A ``fiercely small'' linebacker or,
perhaps, a ``small, fierce'' linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas kept going through the midweek ritual in NFL locker rooms
across America, the ritual of puffing up the next opponent. But the
eyes were paying more attention than the ears, the eyes focusing on
Thomas's size (an officially generous 5 feet 11 inches and 235
pounds) and marveling at what that small-by-NFL-standards body can
accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells, as usual, had the right words after a
Jets-Dolphins game last year when the teams were walking off the
field. Parcells, then the Jets coach, went up to Thomas and said,
``I love to watch you play.''
</P>
<P>
   So would any true football fan. Miami has one of the better
defenses in the league, and while no one player can star without a
complete defensive unit around him, Thomas time and again makes
plays that raise eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he is swooping back in coverage, like a defensive back,
and picking off a pass (``I feel I can cover any tight end or
running back in the league'') or making jarring tackles on running
backs foolish enough to run over the middle, Thomas seems to be
near the ball so often. It is the rare, rare inside linebacker who
can both cover passes and punish running backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriots are going to be dangerous,'' Thomas kept on in
that Texas twang of his. ``We've got to start fast against them.
Hopefully we'll jump on 'em quick. They're coming to our place, so
we definitely have got to get this win.''
</P>
<P>
   And Thomas will do his all to get it. Just as he did last Sunday
night, when he was flying everywhere, leading the Dolphins with 13
tackles in their 19-6 win over Baltimore, and helping hold Ravens
tight ends Shannon Sharpe and Ben Coates to only seven catches.
That might seem like a lot, but on a night that brought a driving
monsoon, Baltimore quarterback Tony Banks's only real passing
options were short tosses to his tight ends or backs.
</P>
<P>
   Pure football fans should focus on Sunday's battle between New
England center Damien Woody and Thomas, as a gauge to see how much
progress Woody has made in his second year and how devastating
Thomas can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be on me a lot,'' said Thomas, ``and he's a
great center.''
</P>
<P>
   An unusual pedigree
</P>
<P>
   Thomas often has won such battles since he came out of Texas
Tech five years ago, so unheralded that Miami used its fifth-round
pick merely hoping that Thomas might be a decent special teams
player someday.
</P>
<P>
   Hard work and a demanding family _ ``family values'' in the
political lexicon of the day _ explain so much of Thomas's success.
So much so that the second shock after the eyes catch the small
size of Thomas is the news that Thomas is the son of a millionaire
oilman from Texas. Sons of millionaires are seldom found in the
National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas's father, Steve, felt he should pass on more than
money to his son. When the younger Thomas wanted a car, he had to
work to purchase a beat-up 1975 Chevy. The younger Thomas once
explained his father's thinking by saying, ``He made me work
because that's the way he had to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Thomas seems the prototypical football player out of
Texas. Ask him what he fires up on a typical barbecue and he
replies, ``Steaks . . . burgers . . . basically everything. Hot
dogs . . . and beer, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas's mother, Bobbi, would send him newspaper clippings when
he was at Texas Tech, ones that said Thomas had ``pedestrian''
speed, that he was so small he couldn't see over the line of
scrimmage or that offensive linemen could push him around at will.
Thomas would read the words and take his usual approach _ prove all
of them wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Another home experience factors into his huge success. When he
was 3 years old, Thomas was playing near the North Fork of the Red
River when a pickup truck ran over him. Then the panicked driver
backed up and ran over him again.
</P>
<P>
   Tire tracks were on the T-shirt of the unconscious boy, who
suffered a broken arm and permanently damaged hearing. His parents,
according to various accounts over the years, thought they had lost
him.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas survived, and clearly has shown he wants to make the
most of his life. He acknowledges that he does not have Lawrence
Taylor's prototype linebacker body but is sensitive to the
implication that his size precludes athletic prowess. Indeed, he
has said he would have made it to the Pro Bowl before last season
if the voters were not prejudiced by the ``overachiever'' label
that has been pasted on his forehead.
</P>
<P>
   Reapplying himself
</P>
<P>
   Above all, though, hard work and preparation are the key to
Thomas's success. He spent hours and hours this past week, extra
hours, studying tape of the Patriots, knowing that New England's
offensive coordinator, Charlie Weis, with Parcells's help, often
baffled Miami when Weis was the Jets' offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``They definitely scheme teams,'' said Thomas. ``That was the
same with the Jets; they get you out of position and keep you off
balance and they don't go by what their tendencies are. They want
to get your mind rattled on defense, throw a bunch of gadgets at
you to get you confused. Then, at the start of the second half and
stuff, they go back to their normal tendencies and then the next
thing you know, you can't even play that right because you're so
rattled.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is worried about what the Patriots will throw at him and
his mates ``because it has bothered me in the past and I hope it
won't bother me Sunday,'' he said. ``But it definitely is a problem
when I'm thinking something and they throw some other things at
you, such as new plays. I mean, I can understand new plays, but
when they break their consistencies and things like that, that
rattles you a little bit. And you start doubting yourself on your
reads. And when you start to read slower, you can't make plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas's answer to subterfuge is work and more work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stay at least 2 1/2-3 hours after practice every day to
watch tape,'' said Thomas. ``I'm usually out of here late. What I
do when I look at the tape is I'm looking at the linemen to see if
they're giving away things by their bodies, and looking at the
formations and the tendencies (of the entire offense). If you can
just get one little thing that can help you from studying the
linemen, it's definitely a help. Even if I have to spend a lot of
hours after practice.''
</P>
<P>
   To Thomas, such work is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the mental edge over people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas's hard work is not limited to just watching tapes
during the season. Stories are legion around the Dolphins of former
coach Jimmy Johnson telling Thomas to get out of the team facility
and go home and ``take a break.'' And there was the time Miami
coaches called up Thomas's agent to see if he could convince Thomas
to take a break and go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, nah, nah . . . (Johnson) never threw me out of here,''
replied Thomas when asked about the tales. The truth, said a
Dolphins official with a laugh, ``is that Zach threw Jimmy out of
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, though, the truth came out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy told me to take a break . . . they told me in the
offseason to get out of here,'' he said. ``I was doing physical
stuff, lifting and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   When was this?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ahhh . . . it was probably February,'' said Thomas. ``Early
February.''
</P>
<P>
   When the team had not been asked to work out until March. But
Zach Thomas, the season just over, still was looking for that edge.
</P>
<P>
   As always.
</P>
<P>
   With more hard work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
