u s BC-BBA-JIMYWILLIAMS-DUQU     09-23 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-JIMYWILLIAMS-DUQUETTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS REBUKES GM FOR LACK OF BACKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stung by Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette backing a star,
Carl Everett, to his detriment, manager Jimy Williams Saturday all
but challenged Duquette to fire him.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the 1999 American League Manager of the Year, made the
extraordinary move three days after Duquette apparently undermined
his authority by refusing to discipline Everett for arriving late
to the park, becoming embroiled in an altercation with Darren
Lewis, and profanely berating Williams in front of players and
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was general manager, I certainly would back the
manager,'' Williams told reporters before Saturday's game against
the Orioles at Fenway. ``If you can't back the manager, then you
probably need to get rid of him. That's what you need to do, and
get somebody you can back.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is under contract to manage the Sox next year for about
$1 million. Asked if he planned to honor the deal, he declined to
give a definitive answer, saying only, ``I have a contract next
year for more money than I've ever made in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter suggested Williams might value his
``self-respect and dignity more than money,'' he said emphatically,
``You're right. But I'm not saying I'm leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor would he say he is staying. And with his rebuke of Duquette
Saturday, Williams left that issue squarely in the lap of the Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also said he would not resign before the season ends
Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never do that,'' he said. ``That's wrong. You finish
what you start. I've tried to preach that to my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette, explaining his decision not to discipline Everett, has
said the slugger's contributions on the field weighed more heavily
than his actions off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the bottom line is how you perform on the field,''
Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a highly productive player for the Red Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   The GM said in his pregame show on WEEI Saturday, ``When you
have a dysfunctional family, you don't throw out any members.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said Friday he looks forward to working with Williams
next year. He was not available Saturday for an interview on the
subject. Team spokesman Kevin Shea told reporters, ``We're not
going to get into a tennis match.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett, meanwhile, said he has done nothing to warrant being
disciplined by the Sox. And he reiterated his belief, first uttered
after he was suspended for 10 games for bumping umpire Ron Kulpa,
that he has been inaccurately portrayed by the media.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he said reporters have chosen to wrongly attack him
because the team's other two stars _ Pedro Martinez and Nomar
Garciaparra _ are sacred cows.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I've done wrong and hurt someone, I apologize in their
face,'' Everett said. ``And if I don't feel like I've done anything
wrong, I'm not going to say anything to you.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's home run leader believes publicly cursing Williams,
among other things, was not wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one to apologize to,'' Everett said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said Duquette told him he would not suspend Everett or
trade him. And no other disciplinary action has been taken against
the slugger, contributing to the perception that Everett is immune
from the manager's authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to support each other through thick and thin,''
Williams said. ``You can't single out any individual and make the
others a separate entity. You have to be one. One unit.''
</P>
<P>
   By Duquette publicly backing Everett over him, Williams said,
``I feel like I'm backed into a corner.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he spoke out ``because of self-pride and the principles
I believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he left a phone message for Duquette to tell him
he was publicly responding to the general manager's statements. He
said he made the call ``so he is not surprised, like I was
surprised (by Duquette's remarks.)''
</P>
<P>
   He also said Duquette has yet to explain to him why he backed
Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who commands intense loyalty from most of his players,
suggested Duquette's special treatment of Everett has hurt the
team's cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you separate a team with one player,'' he said, ``it's
basically going against the thoughts of the manager and the focus
of the team in trying to win. It becomes very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Sox players said they were troubled both by Duquette's
refusal to back Williams and the apparent double standard in the
general manager's treatment of Everett.
</P>
<P>
   ``What (Williams) says, we agree with because he is as loyal a
manager as they come,'' said reliever Derek Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe added: ``When you're a team, No. 1 and No. 25 should be
treated the same. That's the way I believe it should be. When you
see that some type of conduct is going to be OK that we've been
told all along is not OK, you know, hopefully it doesn't lead to
anything, but it easily could because now the groundwork has been
set.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe and Williams both said the Everett situation has affected
the team, if not seriously distracted it. The Sox have yet to be
mathematically eliminated from the race for the playoffs, though
their chances are slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to knock anybody,'' Williams said. ``I have
nothing against Carl Everett. I want him to be the best player he
can be. But with these games remaining, our clubhouse should be
better than what it is right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett, asked whether the episode has become a distraction to
his teammates, said, ``You'd have to ask them whether it's a
distraction or not. I'm going to play regardless.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not. Since Everett started the commotion by arriving late
last Wednesday and announcing he would not play because of an
injured left quadriceps, Williams has used Everett only sparingly,
as a pinch hitter.
</P>
<P>
   And Everett, who is earning $5 million this year, spent all of
Saturday's game on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The benching may not please Duquette. But Williams did not
appear concerned. Asked if there was any way to repair his
relationship with the general manager, he said, ``You'd have to ask
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Shira Springer of the Globe staff contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
