<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9311 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     09-23 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF ONLY THE WORLD COULD FOLLOW OLYMPICS' EXAMPLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, AUSTRALIA _ The weather has been matchless, the Aussies
have been warm and cooperative and the Games themselves have gone
on without any major incident.
</P>
<P>
   If these trends continue, XXVII Olympiad could go down as the
greatest ever staged.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it might already rate such an exalted status because
of the incredible feel-good atmosphere that has pervaded the Games
in this city that has been overflowing with a United Nations
contingent of tourists.
</P>
<P>
   If only the world could exist as smoothly as Sydney has the past
eight days, we'd have everlasting peace.
</P>
<P>
   Those zealots who insist that culturally diverse people can't
live alongside one another without conflict should see what's been
unfolding in these parts. Their petty perceptions would be
exploded.
</P>
<P>
   I agree with a growing sentiment being voiced among the
international press---the IOC should anchor the Games here
permanently instead of rotating them every four years to logistical
nightmares like Atlanta and to sweltering summer saunas like
Athens.
</P>
<P>
   The Aussies have done everything right. Their athletic venues
are modern and roomy. Their vast transportation system of trains
and buses is terrific. Their support system---the 40,000
volunteers---is unparalleled.
</P>
<P>
   I missed a bus to the Ryde Aquatic Centre the other night, and
was in a panic.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the kindly volunteers at the Press Village gate, a
Mr. Mark Wheeler, offered to give me a ride me over in his
car---and even repeated the favor a couple days later!
</P>
<P>
   Stories of such kindness by the locals abound.
</P>
<P>
   And Sydney itself, with its galaxy of beaches, coves, inlets and
islands, is a picturesque paradise aesthetically pleasing to one's
senses. . .
</P>
<P>
   -- The good burghers around here treat swimming with greater
attention than the Americans do football, baseball and basketball,
or the British do soccer.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think a day has gone by without reading something about
Dawn Fraser, and Saturday's 1,500 meter duel between a couple of
Aussies, Grant Hackett and Kieren Perkins, turned out to be the
most watched sporting event in Australian history.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, more than 8.5 million people were glued to their TV
sets for a race I'd watch only under threat of imprisonment. . .
</P>
<P>
   -- There isn't anyone savoring these Olympics more than Tom
Lasorda, reveling almost obscenely in all the adulation. Leave it
to ol' Tommy to start an international incident with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, my one-time friend should go back on that Slim-Fast diet.
He's put on many unflattering pounds, not good for someone with a
history of heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   But he has done a terrific job with his collection of minor
league players, and it won't surprise me if Lasorda adds a silver
medal to his trophy case. . .
</P>
<P>
   -- France's reclusive 400-meter star Marie-Jose Perec has
received more publicity in the local papers for lamming it back to
Paris than she would have had she remained and competed tonight
against national hero Cathy Freeman. . .
</P>
<P>
   -- Freeman figures to emerge victorious, but she's fortunate
that Marion Jones didn't decide to go for six gold medals and add
the 400 to her busy schedule. I don't think anyone alive can beat
Wonder Woman up to 400 meters. . .
</P>
<P>
   -- I spoke to Misty May this morning, and she spent Saturday
afternoon visiting the local zoo with her family and friends after
she and her partner, Holly McPeak, had been eliminated by the
Brazilians in beach volleyball earlier in the day at Bondi.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those days,'' said May, who returns to
America on Tuesday and will participate in the Queen of the Beach
tournament in Las Vegas on Oct. 5-8.
</P>
<P>
   She and other extraordinary Long Beach State alums like Daniele
Scott and Tara Cross-Battle will play against Brian Gimmillaro's
49ers on Oct. 3 at the Pyramid. . .
</P>
<P>
   -- I think the United States women's water polo team would be
celebrating a gold medal triumph today instead of mourning that
final-second, 4-3 loss Saturday night to the Australians had they
seen to it that their best shooter, Brenda Villa, taken more than
four shots during the 28-minute match.
</P>
<P>
   Villa drilled two of them for goals, including a clutch one with
13 seconds left that deadlocked the game, and she might have had a
couple of more goals had she been set up for more shots. But what
do I know about women's water polo?
</P>
<P>
   The team's coach, Guy Baker, did a remarkable job building the
Americans into one of the world's most formidable outfits . . .
</P>
<P>
   -- If I never hear ``Oi! Oi! Oi!'' again, it will be far too
soon. I swear I hear that more from the Aussi fans than even
``Waltzing Matilda,'' a song I actually enjoy listening to. . .
</P>
<P>
   -- Ticket scalpers have invaded this city from all over the
world---with the greatest contingent from Great Britain---but the
biggest ticket scalpers apparently are the Olympic committee
members from the United States, Switzerland, Spain, Russia and
Venezuela, who allegedly have sold thousands of leftover tickets to
the brokers. . .
</P>
<P>
   -- Maurice Greene is one guy who backs up his swagger. . .
</P>
<P>
   -- American swimming diva Amy Van Dyken hasn't hid her disdain
for Holland's three-gold medal winner Inge de Bruijn, hinting
Bruijn has enhanced her performances with drug usage. Yet, Amy's
maid of honor at her upcoming wedding to Denver Bronco punter Tom
Rouen is Julie Romanowski, Bill Romanowski's wife who recently has
been indicted for possession of illegal drugs. . .
</P>
<P>
   -- I seriously doubt anyone in weightlifting from Eastern
European countries is clean. . .
</P>
<P>
   -- Those love birds, Australian Russell Crowe and American Meg
Ryan, are getting big play in the media here. . .
</P>
<P>
   -- Look for Cuba's two-time gold-medal winning heavyweight Felix
Savon to easily beat America's Michael Bennett in their showdown
Tuesday. . .
</P>
<P>
   -- The Australian press is about as provincial as it can get.
One of the headlines today in the Sunday Telegraph's sports section
was, ``Toughest Test For Our Brave Women,'' in reference to women's
marathon. The local writers use words like ``we'' and ``ours'' a
lot when talking about the Australian athletes. . .
</P>
<P>
   -- I never knew I'd know so much about one-time rock and roll
groupie Paula Yates, the former Boomtown Rats lead singer Sir Bob
Geldof, the late INXS frontman Michael Hutchence and Tiger Lilly,
the daughter of Hutchence and Yates, found dead in a London
apartment early last week. The coverage of this saga here has
almost equaled that of the Olympics. . .
</P>
<P>
   -- Now I understand why so many millions around the world
immigrated to Australia during the final four decades of the 20th
century. It's a terrific place. . .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
