<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RUN-WOMENS-MARATHON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARATHON: A FIRST RUNNING GOLD FOR JAPANESE WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ With a keen sense of her place in running
history and a legendary appetite for food and success, Naoko
Takahashi won the first gold medal ever for a Japanese woman in
track and field Sunday by setting an Olympic record in the
marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Her compact stride suited perfectly to the difficult, undulating
course, Takahashi built a lead of 28 seconds with less than a mile
and a half remaining in the 26.2-mile race. Then she had to fend
off a furious kick in the final quarter-mile in Olympic Stadium
from Lidia Simon of Romania to win in 2 hours 23 minutes 14
seconds. Simon took the silver medal in 2:23:22, and Joyce
Chepchumba of Kenya won the bronze in 2:24.45.
</P>
<P>
   All three medalists finished below the previous Olympic record
of 2:24:52, set by Joan Benoit Samuelson in 1984. Had this been a
cooler, less humid day and had the course been flatter, Takahashi
might have challenged the world record of 2:20:43, held by Tegla
Loroupe of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way she did it, going at 19K, just blowing the field away,
I think it has to be one of the greatest performances ever,'' said
Chris Wardlaw, the head coach of the Australian track team. ``A
2:23 in these conditions. This course is very, very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The race began in temperatures of 57 degrees, with 91 percent
humidity, and the weather steadily grew hotter. These were perfect
conditions for Takahashi, who has been brilliant in steamy weather.
Her arms swinging lightly at her side, she drew away from Simon at
about 21{ miles as the course roller-coastered from uphill to
downhill. Feeling confident, Takahashi tossed away the sunglasses
she had been wearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to speed the pace, and slow the pace, to shake
her,'' Takahashi said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunched over, her wet hair plastered to her head, bothered by
menstrual cramps, Simon appeared to be in trouble. However,
Takahashi's legs began to grow heavy, and just before she entered
the stadium, she looked over her shoulder to see Simon gaining on
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to put my legs forward,'' Takahashi said.
</P>
<P>
   Revived, Simon began to sprint after Takahashi as nearly 100,000
people in the stadium realized that the outcome was still in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd find the force to overtake her, but it was not
meant to be,'' Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   Not until 30 meters from the finish did Takahashi finally feel
confident that she would win.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the hardest of the five marathons that I have done,''
said the 28-year-old Takahashi, who is 5-feet-4-inches tall and
weighs 104 pounds. She became the first marathoner to win a gold
medal for Japan. Sohn Kee-chung's marathon victory at the 1936
Berlin Games was credited to Japan. Sohn was actually Korean,
however, and his country was occupied by Japan at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't swallow what I've done,'' Takahashi said.
</P>
<P>
   Chepchumba's medal was the first won by a Kenyan woman in the
marathon. Loroupe had been the favorite, but she grew sick and
vomited before the race. By 6.2 miles, she was already 30 seconds
off the pace. She kept running and finished 13th in 2:29:45.
</P>
<P>
   Fatuma Roba of Ethiopia, the defending Olympic champion,
struggled in the heat and finished ninth in 2:27:38. Christine
Clark of Anchorage, Alaska, the lone American entry, set a personal
best of 2:31:35 and crossed the line in 19th place.
</P>
<P>
   At 15{ miles, Takahashi broke the lead pack that had once
contained 20 runners down to three _ herself, her teammate Ari
Ichihashi and Simon _ and she was clearly intent on winning. At the
1998 Asian Games in Bangkok, Takahashi ran one of the most stunning
marathons of all time. In temperatures that reached 82 degrees,
with 90 percent humidity, she won in 2:21.47, the sixth-fastest
time in history and the fastest in a women's only race.
</P>
<P>
   She visited Olympic Stadium here in August and said: ``I must
win the gold medal in the Olympics and set the best time in the
world to etch my name in history. I want to leave proof that I
existed in this era.''
</P>
<P>
   Since May, she had trained at high altitude in Boulder, Colo.,
and Sunday she was still breathing lightly at 22 miles. ``I was
able to enjoy the fruits of that practice,'' Takahashi said.
</P>
<P>
   After the race, she said she planned to enjoy her other passion
_ eating.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Japanese track magazine, Takahashi can consume 40
pieces of sushi, or a four-pound steak, at one meal.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how she would celebrate her victory, Takahashi said, ``I
want to eat some nice food.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
