<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PENNST-OHIOST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN STATE IS DEMORALIZED BY OHIO STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By   JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio, Sept. 23 _ Penn State's early-season slump
descended into something worse on Saturday: an appalling defeat
that established the start of the 2000 schedule as the worst in Joe
Paterno's 35 years as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   After losing by 45-6 to Ohio State in the wet gloom of Ohio
Stadium in their Big Ten conference opener, the Nittany Lions are
1-4. Unless they sweep their final seven games and qualify for the
Rose Bowl as conference champions _ an unlikely event _ the Lions
will probably need to win six of seven to qualify for a trip to
even a second-tier bowl game. That, too, does not seem promising
after what transpired on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But things were encouraging for the Buckeyes, who are 1-0 in the
conference and 4-0 over all. They scored touchdowns in a variety of
ways, including a fumble recovery, a double deflection on a pass
play and short-yardage runs.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth consecutive time the Buckeyes have defeated
the Lions in this stadium. Penn State has now lost seven of its
last eight regular-season games. The Nittany Lions have not started
1-4 since 1964, two years before Paterno replaced Rip Engle as head
coach. Penn State plays host to Purdue on Saturday. No Penn State
team has started 1-5 since 1931, and the Lions have not had a
losing record since they went 5-6 in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Paterno began the season with 317 victories. He still needs five
in his final seven of the regular schedule to tie Bear Bryant's
record of 323, the most ever for a head coach in Division I-A.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State held Penn State to 93 yards rushing and 120 yards
passing, and forced three turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, the Buckeyes retired the No. 31 of the late Vic
Janowicz, their 1950 Heisman trophy winner. It is only the second
number retired in the long history of a school where football has
been played since 1890. The other is the 45 of Archie Griffin, who
won the Heisman twice.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, nasty weather raged through the early minutes, and
the play-calling of John Cooper helped the Buckeyes storm to a 17-0
lead at halftime. They scored on their first possession with Jamar
Martin getting the touchdown on a carry from the 1-yard line to
complete a 92-yard drive that mixed running and passing plays. They
scored again on their second possession when Darnell Sanders caught
a pass in the end zone after it was deflected twice, once by each
team. It ended a 50-yard drive with the scoring play of 18 yards on
a pass by Buckeye quarterback Steve Bellisari, who was 10-of-17 for
203 yards.
</P>
<P>
   After Dan Stultz kicked a 31-yard field goal to put the Buckeyes
up by 17-0, Ohio State had a chance to increase its lead when a
fumble by Tony Stewart of the Nittany Lions gave Ohio State the
ball at Penn State's 32-yard line. But Bellisari tried to pass into
thick coverage and the ball was intercepted by Penn State's James
Boyd with 1 minute 2 seconds remaining in the half.
</P>
<P>
   At intermission, Penn State quarterback Rashard Casey had 6
completions in 14 attempts. His leading rusher, Eric McCoo, had
only 19 yards. For the Buckeyes, Bellisari had 139 passing yards
and tailback Derek Combs had 49 yards on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State, which had been shut out by Pitt the week before, got
on the scoreboard with 9:56 remaining in the third quarter on a
2-yard run by McCoo, who swept to the right to complete a 33-yard
drive that began with a short Ohio State punt. But the Lions missed
the extra point and the score was 17-6.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State's Combs scored on the next possession, a 1-yard run,
to give the Buckeyes a 24-6 lead. His run ended a methodical drive
of 73 yards in 11 plays. The highlight was a gain of 26 yards on a
pass by Bellisari to Chad Cacchio, who ran 20 yards after catching
the ball 6 yards past the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   After Casey's long pass was intercepted by Nate Clements, the
Buckeyes drove again. This time the touchdown was scored by Jerry
Westbrooks on one of those plays that seem to sum up a game.
</P>
<P>
   Running wide to the left, Westbrooks was hit by cornerback Bryan
Scott at about the 5-yard line. But Westbrooks kept pushing
forward, dragging the tackler with him until he crossed the goal
line at the corner flag. When Matt Senneca replaced Casey for the
next Lions possession, he fumbled when trying to pass and the ball
was recovered by nose guard Mike Collins, who ran it into the end
zone to make the score 38-6 for the Buckeyes at the end of the
third quarter. Ohio State scored another touchdown in the fourth
quarter for the final margin. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 2301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
