<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARMY-MEMPHIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMPHIS BEATS ARMY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, N.Y. _ Four straight losses at the end of last
college football season cost Bob Sutton his coaching job at Army.
Sutton's firing also marked the end of the run-oriented wishbone
offense that Army had used for 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although the new head coach, Todd Berry, has instituted a
wide-open passing offense, the result has not changed. Army lost,
26-16, to Memphis in a Conference USA game before a crowd of 38,375
at Michie Stadium. With the loss, the Black Knights matched their
season-ending streak of four in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   With Memphis leading in the fourth quarter, 20-14, quarterback
Curtis Zervic's pass into the end zone was picked off in the left
corner by defensive back Idrees Bashir, who ran the ball back 105
yards for a touchdown with 3 minutes 49 seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was it the longest pass interception run back in the
76-year history of Michie Stadium, but it also sealed Memphis'
third victory in four games.
</P>
<P>
   That put a damper on an otherwise superb performance by Zervic,
a third-string quarterback who a year ago was the manager of the
Army men's lacrosse team after quitting the football team after his
freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   Zervic entered Saturday's game after quarterback Joe Gerena
injured his right shoulder. The team's first-string quarterback,
Chad Jenkins, has been sidelined since injuring an ankle against
Boston College two weeks ago. Zervic completed 28 passes for 246
yards to tie a record set by Leamon Hall in 1976. He had four
completions on Army's ill-fated drive. Army was on the Memphis
14-yard line when Bashir ended the Black Knights' hopes with his
interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had Bryan Bowdish open when I threw the pass, but
the safety made a great play,'' said Zervic, who also threw two
other interceptions while connecting on 28 of 38 passes. ``Maybe I
should have thrown the ball a bit shorter than I did.''
</P>
<P>
   That drive was just one of Army's many missed opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Memphis led at halftime, 14-7, because the Black Knights did not
score on two goal-line situations.
</P>
<P>
   Memphis tailback Sugar Sanders opened the scoring by sprinting
62 yards for a touchdown on the Tigers' first possession. Army, on
its third possession, drove from its 19-yard line to the Tigers' 2.
But the Black Knights came away empty when Brendan Mullen's 24-yard
field-goal attempt sailed wide to the left.
</P>
<P>
   Army then squandered another scoring opportunity when, on the
ensuing Memphis possession, Randy Mitchell blocked the punt by Ben
Graves and Anthony Miller recovered the ball at the Tigers' 30.
</P>
<P>
   With Zervic connecting on four straight passes, the Black
Knights advanced to the Memphis 1. Zervic was stopped for no gain
on a quarterback sneak on fourth down.
</P>
<P>
   Army finally tied the score, 7-7, when the 5-foot-7-inch Omari
Thompson, who is used as a wide receiver, running back and
kick-return specialist, took a punt at the Army 28-yard line and
raced 72 yards down the left sideline just under six minutes into
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But Memphis soon regained the lead. Aided by a 15-yard
roughing-the-passer penalty, Memphis followed with a 15-play,
78-yard drive that consumed almost seven minutes and ended with a
1-yard touchdown run by fullback Darche Epting with 3:03 left in
the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made too many mistakes today, and didn't play up to our
capabilities,'' Berry said of Army, which duplicated a feat of the
1973 team. That group lost its first four games and dropped all 10
games it played that season. The eight-game losing streak is the
longest that Army has endured since the 1975 team lost its final
nine games after winning its first two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
