</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALK KEEPS SOX IN THE RUNNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By BOB HOHLER 
c.2000 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was conflict in the management ranks; the star slugger was
in the doghouse; and the Red Sox harbored only the most slender
hope of surviving into the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   But the Comeback Kids of Yawkey Way did it again Saturday night,
engineering a dramatic come-from-behind victory over the Orioles,
8-7, in the bottom of the 10th inning at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   With the Sox trailing, 7-6, entering the bottom of the 10th,
Nomar Garciaparra made a brilliant slide into home on Troy
O'Leary's double to tie the score. And after Baltimore reliever
Ryan Kohlmeier intentionally walked the bases loaded, Trot Nixon
came up with two outs and worked Kohlmeier to a 3-2 count before
drawing a walk to force in O'Leary with the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no quit in this team,'' Nixon said. ``A lot of teams
may look at us as having a few problems here and there. But we just
battle back.''
</P>
<P>
   A few problems, indeed. Starting with a rift between general
manager Dan Duquette and manager Jimy Williams, who was irked that
Duquette failed to discipline Everett for showing up late for
practice and publicly using expletives to deride him.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Everett's apparent good standing with Duquette, the
slugger was nowhere to be seen as Williams sent out three pinch
hitters in crucial situations late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manager's decision'' was all Williams would say about passing
over Everett. But he did say Everett was available to hit if he
chose to call on him.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Everett, who did not go out onto the field to
congratulate his teammates after the victory, was actually on the
bench in the late innings, Williams said, ``I don't go around and
check off who is there and who's not there. All I know is I want to
be there so I'm there.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Sox used 20 players other than Everett in the
overtime game. But the formula worked.
</P>
<P>
   And though the stakes were not great _ the magic number for the
Sox to be officially eliminated from postseason contention is 3
with seven games to play _ the spirit was alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the chance we've got,'' said Dante Bichette, who
singled in the third inning and scored on Garciaparra's two-run
homer. ``We have to hope for a miracle, a real big miracle. But
we're going to play to win until the season is over.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles had gone ahead in the top of the 10th after Chris
Richard singled to right off Sox reliever Rheal Cormier to open the
inning. Richard moved to second on Melvin Mora's ground out and
took third on Brook Fordyce's ground out off reliever Hector
Carrasco.
</P>
<P>
   And after Brady Anderson drew an intentional walk, Carrasco gave
up a single to Luis Matos that put Baltimore ahead, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Carrasco, who posted his first win with the Sox as the pitcher
of record in the bottom of the 10th, was the team's seventh pitcher
of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still not back where we want to be with these
pitchers,'' Williams said. ``But maybe we'll get there by the end
of next week'' when the season ends.
</P>
<P>
   The game was a major test for Rolando Arrojo, who failed
miserably last Thursday when he was pounded by the Indians for
seven runs in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo bounced back admirably, giving up two runs on five hits
in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox led, 6-2, when Arrojo left the game. But the Orioles
scored two runs off reliever Hipolito Pichardo in the sixth on a
walk, a double by Chris Richard, and Mora's single.
</P>
<P>
   Worse for the Sox, the Orioles tied the score in the seventh on
two unearned runs. With two outs and Jeff Fassero pitching in
relief of Pichardo, Eugene Kingsale drew a walk and took second on
Jerry Hairston's single.
</P>
<P>
   On came Rod Beck to relieve Fassero. And he induced a grounder
by Delino DeShields to Garciaparra. But the shortstop booted it,
allowing Kingsale to score. Cal Ripken then singled in Hairston to
tie it.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sox came through in the 10th, although they nearly were
foiled when left fielder DeShields, summoned with the bases loaded
to serve as a fifth infielder, made a lunging grab near second base
to rob Jason Varitek of a game-winning hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done that before,'' Garciaparra said of the
five-infielder defense. ``I was like, oh, are they taking one out
of Jimy's book?''
</P>
<P>
   No problem, thanks to Nixon's eventual walk. And Williams
appreciated that his players persevered amid adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a special game, coming back like that,'' he said. ``It
was a credit to all of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
