</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-LOWE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOWE SAYS TEAM NEEDS A LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The temper and tardiness of center fielder Carl Everett, the
inaction of general manager Dan Duquette, and the disappointment of
manager Jimy Williams promise to remain hot topics in the Red Sox
clubhouse for the remainder of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday's game against the Orioles, reliever Derek Lowe
spoke at length about the possible long-term effects of recent
incidents, the lack of vocal leadership in the clubhouse, and the
loyalty Williams inspires in players.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe said all the talk about Everett's behavior has distracted
the team. The reliever noted that, unlike the past two seasons when
the team won more than 90 games each time, they were ``maybe not on
the same page.'' After learning that Williams had
uncharacteristically spoken out about a lack of backing from the
front office in the wake of Everett's tardiness, Lowe sympathized
with his manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be tough if you want to do one thing but you don't
have the power to do it,'' said Lowe. ``I just hope he comes back
and everything settles down. It could lead to a lot of bad
incidents, meaning if one person can do it, why can't all of us?
That's the kind of message you don't want to send. We have a bunch
of classy guys and I don't think anything's going to happen, but on
the flip side, if one guy can do it, why can't we all?
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we're told as long as we can produce on the field, we can
do anything we want. That makes it tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a team, No. 1 and No. 25 should be treated the
same. That's the way I believe it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Nomar Garciaparra, who declined to speak about Everett but
praised Williams for his leadership, ``I have the utmost respect
for (Williams). He takes the brunt of everything. He's always
positive. We play a lot of games, a lot of things happen out there
and a lot of stuff goes on, a lot of question marks. People want to
point fingers. I've never seen him do that. If there's any
finger-pointing, it goes right back to him. That takes a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   When told that Everett was unapologetic, Lowe was not surprised.
He reasoned that if a general manager condones a player's actions,
the player would not see any need to apologize or clarify possible
misunderstandings.
</P>
<P>
   Although the clubhouse may be filled with ``classy guys,'' it
lacks a strong, vocal leader, someone who could prevail upon a
problematic teammate. Mo Vaughn, Mike Stanley, and to some extent
Jeff Frye assumed such leadership roles in the recent past. But
during Duquette's tenure, Vaughn (lost to free agency), Stanley
(released), and Frye (traded) have unhappily left the Hub.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if a teammate should have dealt with the Everett
situation before it festered, Lowe said, ``Yeah, but you can't
force that upon anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the one great thing about Mo Vaughn. If he was
here, things may have been different because this guy was what you
want to call a true leader. There's not many guys out there, as you
can see. People figured, `Aw, Mo will leave, someone else will take
over.' There was talk of certain guys doing it, but it's not in
some people's nature to be a vocal leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot guys that are leaders on the field, Nomar,
Pedro. There's more guys than that, but we don't have a vocal
leader. Mo was fantastic at that. This guy, if you did something
wrong, he let you know it. It didn't matter who you were. Even if
he saw something starting, he stopped it right before it got to be
anything big. Maybe, if he was here, it wouldn't have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has one hard and fast rule: Be on time. If a player is
going to be late, the manager expects a phone call and an
explanation. If the only rule set by Williams apparently doesn't
matter, what type of behavior will follow, wondered Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just hope that it won't snowball to where there's no rules
at all,'' he said. ``Bottom line, we all get paid to play the game
of baseball and produce on the field, but there's a lot more that
comes with that. If you were to ask me, I would rather have a bunch
of guys that get the best out of their ability day in and day out,
that abide by the rules and respect everybody, than tremendous
players who kind of do their own thing.''
</P>
<P>
   With the season winding down, Lowe hopes the team can regroup
and get back on the same page. By the time spring training starts,
he would like to see the recent events well behind the Red Sox.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
