<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-EVERETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERETT CALLS HIMSELF A TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An unapologetic Carl Everett broke his two-day silence Saturday
in the Red Sox clubhouse. Dressing while most of his teammates were
on the field for batting practice, Everett blamed the media for the
recent problems, alleging the press has continually misrepresented
him and made him a target.
</P>
<P>
   Everett called reports that he and Darren Lewis argued about
showing respect ``incorrect.'' He said he had done nothing to
``disrespect'' his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   When Lewis was asked about Thursday's heated exchange with
Everett, he said, ``I have no comment on that. You can pretty much
read between the lines on what was said.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett said that, rather than set reporters straight on the
recent events, he would let them ``soak in your own lies.'' He
spoke calmly and at times used disjointed biblical diction to make
his point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can accept truth and negativity,'' said Everett. ``But when
it's a lie and negative, there's a different thinking. So, those
whom have lied on me cannot say anything else to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Fan reaction, he said, ``actually doesn't bother me. That's what
they want _ those reporters want those fans to be negative to me.
That's their only goal in life because they're miserable already.
The fans don't report the negativity. It doesn't bother me. You
look at what I do on the field. No reporter can take that away,
just can't do it. The fans react to the ignorance of the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett said media scrutiny and negative fallout are the price
of performing well. And because he possesses exceptional athletic
talent, he has become tolerant of the attention that follows him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been talked about all my life,'' said Everett, who has 34
home runs, 108 RBIs, and a .302 average.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still hasn't stopped me. I don't have any shield. It's just
when you disrespect me, I'm done with you. I can deal with true
negative. It don't surprise me.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I made $100,000 you guys wouldn't be standing here in front
of me. It's that simple. Every team has their target. On this team,
no matter what happens, you're going to look at Pedro (Martinez),
Nomar (Garciaparra), and myself. Maybe Dante (Bichette) now that
he's here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's going to mess with Nomar? He owns this town. Who's going
to mess with Pedro? He owns this town. You've got to find someone.
I'm the new guy and basically I speak my mind. I'm not afraid to
say what's on my mind, so there's a target right there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 2335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000923.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-23 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9344 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-RICHARDSON-LADN     09-23 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RICHARDSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHARDSON IS BACK WITH RELISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All those hung up by logic, take a hike. All those restricted by
normal laws of physical possibilities, bound by traditional human
limitations, make for the exit.
</P>
<P>
   This is not about any mortal realm of endeavor, but of Dr. Dot
Richardson, the mystifying one-woman bundle of energy who remains
the envy of every electric company on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Understand, Richardson is going again, throttle fully opened,
the only way she goes anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   She will be 39 during these Olympic Games, but age gave up
trying to slow her years ago. So she is back, back with her
defending gold-medal-winning U.S. softball team, back trying to
recapture that magic of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   There is absolutely no logical reason for her to be back in the
Olympic Games, to have sweated under the hot sun just north of the
Mexican border at the U.S. training camp in Chula Vista. To have
pushed herself through drills, exhorting her teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson already had it all. She has been named the country's
top softball player seven times. She is the woman who ripped the
game-winning home run in the gold-medal game in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   She's written books, made instructional videos, become a
national speaker, set up foundations, picked up a dozen sponsors,
appeared on numerous national television shows - all while becoming
an orthopedic surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Why would anyone who has accomplished everything in their sport,
is financially secure, has a promising medical career waiting ...
still be out there?
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, it's very simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy it, I ``love it,'' Richardson said. ``And as long that
love is still there, I'll continue to be on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe all of us are given incredible talents, and these
talents that are a gift meant to be expressed and shared with
others. I feel that very strongly in my passion for softball and my
passion for medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   The real truth is, though, Richardson seems to feel strongly
about anything she does or discusses. Her quotes should
automatically be equipped with exclamation marks. Everything is all
out, full commitment, pedal slammed to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson recently completed a sports-medicine fellowship at
the Kerlan-Jobe Orthopedic Clinic in Los Angeles. When Dr. Frank
Jobe, the internationally renowned orthopedic surgeon, was asked to
speak at a local high school, he quickly witnessed the zeal with
which Richardson attacks all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made up a talk about injuries and how to prevent them, the
things a high schooler ought to know,'' Jobe said. ``Then at the
last moment I thought, 'You know, I really ought to take Dot with
me and just let them see an Olympic star. I thought that might be
worth a minute or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have not even gone. As we walked down the aisle from
the back to the front, the students all stood up and gave her
high-fives. We got on the platform and I gave my little talk. They
were tolerating me so they could get to her. And she just revved
them up something special. Gave them a really heart-warming talk
about the possibilities in life, what you can do if you have
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Jobe said they stayed another hour after the assembly ended, as
students from the depressed neighborhood crushed toward Richardson,
wanting their picture taken with her, looking at her gold medal,
and asking, ``Do you really think I could be a doctor, too?''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson has big plans for her medical career, but then those
are the only kinds of plans she has for anything.
</P>
<P>
   Her immediate goal is to help lead the U.S. back to the Olympic
medal platform.
</P>
<P>
   The memory of Richardson in Atlanta seems fresh - the doctor who
helped the American softball team become the unexpected darlings of
the Olympics, in the sports' Olympic debut, in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that I think about from 1996 - and it feels
like it just happened yesterday - is the roar of the crowd, a
standing-room-only packed stadium of over 10,000 people,'' she
said.'' A roar with a sense like they realized they had lived in a
moment of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that we had won a gold medal, it was like we had
made a mark in history. I'm getting chills just thinking about it.
The inspiration in knowing that everyone who experienced it,
everyone who watched, everyone following us, would never be the
same because we were inspired by living in that moment. It's so
hard to really describe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson immediately returned to medical school and national
celebrity. Maybe the U.S. team figured she was through with
softball, or it was just time for everyone to move on. Richardson
wasn't invited to be on the team for the next 2 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling of rejection was there,'' she said. ``The feeling
they wanted me to retire. That loneliness and disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Even her own team might have underestimated her resolve. And
Richardson figures it might have been noticed the U.S. lost to
archrival Australia three times while she was out. After she
returned, the U.S. was 5-0 against Australia going into the
Olympics at Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   So she is back, if at a different position. Richardson has been
moved from shortstop to second base, which seems less a recognition
of the years than of the impact of Crystl Bustos.
</P>
<P>
   Bustos, the former Canyon Country high school standout who
joined the U.S. team only last year, bats cleanup and is considered
the most powerful hitter on the team. Bustos and Richardson room
together on the road.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. coach Ralph Raymond said Richardson - who still bats
leadoff at age 38 - made the switch smoothly and again is like a
coach on the field, still going when most had countered her out.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really relishes the thought of participating on the
softball field,'' Raymond said. ``She's like a 10-year-old kid who
just got her first ice cream cone.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just does a tremendous job. She's like a catalyst. The way
she goes, it seems the club just goes the same way and it spurs
them on. In that respect, she still maintains a lot of the things
that she did 10, 20 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond, however, acknowledges Richardson ``may have slowed down
a little,'' but makes up for it with her great baserunning sense.
That her bat is no longer one of the most feared in the game but is
still close.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a big kid a heart,'' he said. ``Just enjoys the
competition. If at any time I would see her slowing down to the
point where she couldn't do the job, I would definitely have to sit
her down. But thus far, she has done a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom McCarthy, her longtime agent, said Richardson's confidence
is unshaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going to be interesting is to see how she responds in
big competition,'' McCarthy said. ``There are a lot of players who
do well on the tour but who have never done anything in a major
competition. She still believes she's going to produce and help the
team win. There are just certain players who respond to big-time
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Those high school students of Jobe's knew Richardson was all
about setting goals to achieve dreams. And with her, there is
always another goal to chase down. Like a second gold medal at age
39.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson has no fears of a letdown after '96 and calls this
Olympics a competitive athlete's dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we are going to meet our No. 1 competitor - Australia - in
their backyard,'' she said. ``For any athlete to not want to be
there - oh, never, never, never.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why this is so exciting, because they want it so badly.
Everyone wants to knock you off, and that's the way it's always
been and that's the way you want it to be. To win a gold medal
again, is like part two of living the dream.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-23-00 2340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
