<HEADER>
A9345 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN     09-23 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA MISSED MANY CHANCES ON FIRST DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ There was no deceptive advertising on the part of
the Oregon defense. The Ducks, just as UCLA expected - and just as
Fresno State and Michigan had done - loaded eight or nine men near
the line of scrimmage and dared Ryan McCann to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on first down, when the Bruins might have best taken
advantage of Oregon's defense, they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA passed the ball on first down just eight times in 23
chances until it was down 12 points with three minutes to play.
Foster carried the ball 15 times on first down and netted just 28
yards. Overall, he rushed 19 times for 49 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Such a trend was in stark contrast to the Bruins' play selection
on their first 20 first downs in the second half against Michigan.
UCLA split the plays evenly between the run and pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I called it much different than against
Michigan,'' offensive coordinator Al Borges said. ``I may have been
more conservative (with the inexperienced McCann), but there comes
a point where you get the ball kicked back at you. If you're too
conservative, you'll face second-and-10 all day.''
</P>
<P>
   It's gotta be the shoes: UCLA had trouble with footing in the
first half. McCann slipped as he dropped back to pass and Foster
lost his feet on an 18-yard run that might have gone for 41 more
and a touchdown. Several players switched shoes at halftime and
didn't seem to have any noticeable problems.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated Freddie: Receiver Freddie Mitchell caught six passes
for 158 yards and one touchdown and might have had another if an
official had seen his left foot come down in the end zone. But
Mitchell also had a ball deflect off his hands and into the arms of
Oregon cornerback Rashad Bauman, whom he battled most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell and Bauman could be seen jawing at each other most of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Said Mitchell: ``He's the easiest cornerback I've played against
all this year. And I felt that he was so easy to beat but he talks
too much. It's so disrespectful for him to talk so much.''
</P>
<P>
   From Bauman: ``I had fun watching Freddie Mitchell talking on
ESPN (Saturday morning) about how this was going to be a big
breakout game for him. It was funny. We went out there and pretty
much ruined his plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett's bomb: Drew Bennett, the quarterback-turned-receiver,
faked an option on third-and-2 and threw a 54-yard touchdown pass
to Mitchell. Bennett became the fifth UCLA player to complete a
pass this season and third to throw a touchdown, joining McCann and
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Knight shirt: Nike chairman Phil Knight, who withdrew his $30
million pledge to help expand Autzen Stadium this year because of
the school's affiliation with a worker's rights organization, was
the object of pleas from Oregon students on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them wore T-shirts that read, ``Phil, Phone Home,
1-800-Be A Duck.''
</P>
<P>
   The back of the shirt read: ``Just Do It!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
