<HEADER>
A9353 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-McHALE-COLUMN-LAD     09-23 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS CAN AVOID A HUGE MISTAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAKERSFIELD, Calif. _ Philip Anschutz must have forgotten those
empty yellow seats.
</P>
<P>
   In the final year of the Forum, they glowed like neon at the
television cameras. You didn't need to check the standings to see
how the Kings were doing. Those empty seats said it all.
</P>
<P>
   Anschutz, the Kings' billionaire owner, must have forgotten
there used to be a guy in this town named Chase Carey, who puffed
out his chest and traded Mike Piazza because that's what Fox people
do when they don't get what they want. The Dodgers haven't been
heard from since.
</P>
<P>
   Anschutz now is faced with the same situation, overpaying his
best player Rob Blake or trading him. He should let history be his
guide.
</P>
<P>
   Anschutz was smart to outfit the new Staples Center in deep
purple, which is much less revealing. He was smart last year to
upgrade his team with Ziggy Palffy and a new contract for
undervalued Matty Norstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Now he needs to be smart again. The Kings made some great
strides last year, recording 94 points and reaching the playoffs
for just the second time in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   This season is all about keeping the momentum. Everyone has been
to the Staples Center now. It's no longer a novelty. Winning is the
only thing that matters.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are a fixture here, drawing three million this year
in the face of abject failure. The Kings don't have that luxury.
Sharing the winter with the Lakers means they can disappear without
a trace.
</P>
<P>
   The club says it has an obligation to the NHL to keep salaries
down and keep small market clubs like Calgary, Edmonton and even
Montreal alive.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have a bigger obligation to their fans, who have
waited so long to root for a consistent winner.
</P>
<P>
   The team can do both, but it has to act quickly before the
momentum is gone.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Dave Taylor is offering $7.5 million a year for
three seasons and is technically right in not going a penny more.
And if you want to get even more technical, how much is your
cornerstone worth on a team that hasn't won a playoff game in seven
years?
</P>
<P>
   Plenty if the team doesn't want to start from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Players live a fragile existence. Not too many people have to
play out their failure in front of 18,000 fans. By not coming to
terms with Blake, the Kings already have given their players their
out clause for this season.
</P>
<P>
   The players disagree, saying they won't be distracted even
though their top center, Jozef Stumpel, is holding out and best
player, Blake, has resigned his captaincy.
</P>
<P>
   Those will not be rallying cries when the weather gets cold and
playoff races get hot.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza repeatedly has said he regrets the hard line he took with
the Dodgers. Like Blake, he thought it was part of the
negotiations. Although he signed with the New York Mets for seven
years and $91 million, Piazza would not have agreed to less than
$100 million with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Former club owner Peter O'Malley never cultivated a good
relationship with Piazza. He always thought players were Dodgers
first, individuals second. He didn't realize the times had changed.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it appeared Blake had a great relationship with
the Kings. He and his wife, Brandy, have lived in Manhattan Beach
year round and could shame Jerry Lewis with all their charity work.
Blake pushed for Andy Murray to be hired as coach last year and the
results were terrific except for their blowout in the playoffs. If
that wasn't enough, Blake's agent, Ron Salcer, used to represent
Taylor when he was a player. This deal should have been done over a
couple of beers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Kings have drawn a line in the ice. Anschutz, known
as a ``bottom-line guy,'' is trying to build stability in an
organization that has known years of financial disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Standing firm on Blake is not the way. Even if the Kings record
another 94 points this year and win a playoff round, they are not
going to the Stanley Cup finals. Next season will be their big push
and it will cost big money to get a center like Alexei Yashin or a
goaltender like Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   The payroll will rise, even if the NHL does not have the TV
contract to grow as fast as baseball. But without the Kings signing
their best player, why would those players come to a place so
uncommitted unless they were thrown obscene amounts of money? The
Dodgers gave Kevin Brown almost $40 million more than the next
highest bidder - plus a Lear Jet.
</P>
<P>
   Blake hasn't helped. The NHL Players Association wants him to
hang tough so others can enjoy the trickle-down salary bumps. Blake
really hasn't given the Kings a dollar amount, but somewhere
between Detroit's Nicklas Lidsrom and the New York Rangers' Brian
Leetch is $8 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Blake actually is doing the club a favor asking for only three
years. A player in his prime - with a history of knee injuries -
wanting a contract that short is absurd. Blake thinks the market
will be that much higher in three years. He should remember how it
felt to get out of bed at the end of last season.
</P>
<P>
   Payroll flexibility are the two most important words to a
franchise these days. Fans hoping for a quick Dodgers turnaround
should remember the club is beholden to Brown and Shawn Green five
more years, four more for Eric Karros and three for Gary Sheffield.
Pitchers Darren Dreifort and Chan Ho Park also are in position to
command long term deals at $10 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Anschutz should look at all that and remember Piazza. And the
yellow seats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
